<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH-CARE INDUSTRY'S Y2K ACTIONS CALLED `WOEFULLY INADEQUATE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES and FINN BULLERS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prepare for Y2K as you would an oncoming tornado, experts tell
us. But no one needs to remind Oklahoma nursing home administrator
Randy Musick of that.
</P>
<P>
   On May 3, tornadoes cut a deadly swath across Oklahoma and into
Kansas, leaving 42 persons dead and millions of dollars in damage.
The storm put the small rural care facility and its residents
through the ultimate Y2K drill.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the hospital, the emergency backup generator, phones,
cell phones and heating, ventilating and air-conditioning systems
all failed. Outside, there was no electricity, natural gas, phones
or emergency services.
</P>
<P>
   Lessons learned?
</P>
<P>
   Heavy loads on a backup generator caused it to fail after three
days. Have power backups for the backups. Don't rely on cell phones
because the lines overloaded and failed. Instead, install a battery
backup to the existing phone system. Also, create contingency
contracts with alternative suppliers and buy more blankets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter whether it's an F-5 tornado or the year
2000,'' Musick testified this week before the Senate Special Y2K
committee examining hospital emergency plans and medical device
compliance. ``We need to be equally prepared for both.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by other witnesses, however, the health-care industry
simply isn't ready.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Willemssen, the General Accounting Office's Y2K expert,
said the number of noncompliant biomedical devices reported on
manufacturers' Web sites, 4,445, is much larger than the number of
noncompliant devices they report to government regulators at the
Food and Drug Administration, 897.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the status of biomedical equipment is unknown because a
significant number of care providers do not respond to requests for
information, Willemssen said.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to crack down, the FDA has said it will publish a
list of high-risk equipment. A draft list now contains about 70
devices, including a powered emergency ventilator, an infusion
pump, a blood-sugar test system and a fetal cardiac monitor.
</P>
<P>
   The federal agency also may issue public warnings or suggest
voluntary recalls if it finds medical devices that could
malfunction on Jan. 1, 2000, said Kevin Thurm, the Health and Human
Services deputy secretary.
</P>
<P>
   In extreme cases, Thurm said, dangerous devices will be seized.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: The health-care industry is ``woefully inadequate''
in its year 2000 preparations, said Senate Y2K committee spokesman
Don Meyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those rare industries that we've poked and
prodded and held hearings on and studied. And still, they are at
the same lack of readiness as they were six months ago,'' he said.
``It's rather dumbfounding.''
Drug supplies
</P>
<P>
   The President's Year 2000 Conversion Council and a host of
pharmaceutical officials will release guidelines on Monday
addressing whether consumers should stockpile prescription drugs
before Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, there has been no common ground for consumer
advocates and drug-supply manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Reports recommends up to a two-month supply of
life-sustaining drugs. Drug suppliers say that's excessive and will
only create a self-fulfilling prophecy of shortages. They recommend
a two-week supply of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Guidelines will appear on the White House Y2K Web site _
{www.y2k.gov} _ early in the week.
No limits yet
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has again postponed a vote on a bill that would limit
class-action lawsuits from consumers or businesses whose computers
have Y2K breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the measure say the nation's high-tech companies
need legislative protection to avoid a flurry of lawsuits caused by
software or computers that malfunction after the first of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The measure has been pushed by large corporations and the
high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has threatened to veto the measure, which was
supposed to come to a vote on Friday. Opponents contend the bill
would stop consumers and small businesses from recovering economic
losses in court.
</P>
<P>
   Citing unnamed congressional aides, /{The Washington Post/} said
holding the vote Tuesday, when Microsoft Corp. Chairman Bill Gates
and other CEOs are in Washington, will make it more difficult for
President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore to continue their
opposition to the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Joint Economic Committee of Congress and the Business
Software Alliance are planning a joint meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   John Czwartacki, spokesman for Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott
of Mississippi, said the postponement was not aimed at putting
pressure on Clinton and Gore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
