<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS LEARN ABOUT THE CIVIL WAR IN A CAMP, NOT A CLASSROOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY BERRIOS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Unlike the soldiers who attacked the Jesse
James Farm near Kearney, Mo., in 1863, the ones Friday were
friendly visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in heavy wool jackets, long-sleeve wool shirts, denim
pants, wool hats and military-style boots, six cadets from
Wentworth Military Academy's Civil War Living History Camp gave a
two-hour demonstration to about 50 onlookers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not every day you get to start a fire, shoot muskets and
learn about the 1800s,'' said 17-year-old cadet Capt. Robert
Teachenor as he stirred bacon and onions in a cast-iron skillet.
</P>
<P>
   Hibberd V.B. Kline, Wentworth's vice president of
administration, said the Living History Camp at the academy in
Lexington, Mo., represented a mythical military academy like
Virginia Military Institute in Lexington, Va., in 1860.
</P>
<P>
   Students learn drill and tactics. They also study ``current
events'' from the time period, such as the Kansas-Nebraska Act.
</P>
<P>
   The program, in its first year, started June 5 and ends July 7.
It is open to boys ages 14-18, and not limited to Wentworth
students. The group will participate in a re-enactment of the
Battle of Gettysburg in Pennsylvania July 2-4.
</P>
<P>
   The James farm, the site of Friday's demonstration, once was
attacked by Union soldiers in the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Teachenor, a Wentworth senior, made ``cush,'' a
mixture of bacon, onions, zucchini, cornmeal and seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Prosser, 17 of Riverside, Calif., abstained from the meal
because he was a vegetarian. Prosser, a Wentworth junior, munched
on a carrot and a biscuit the soldiers called hardtack.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of the camp, Prosser said, was making friends and
learning about the Civil War. The worst part was the uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets pretty hot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the cadets agreed that shooting the muskets was the
``coolest'' part of the program.
</P>
<P>
   Tracey Alexander, a 15-year-old high school sophomore visiting
from San Antonio, said she was impressed that the participants were
the same age as many Civil War soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a lot better to see it re-enacted than read it in a
history book,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
