</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGE IN ORDER AGREES WITH O'NEILL AS YANKS TOP MARLINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ How is Albert Belle hitting? Paul O'Neill asked before
Friday's game. When told Belle's average was sinking below .250,
O'Neill thought about this.
</P>
<P>
   ``See?'' he said, grinning. ``I'm not the only one who's not
hitting.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill may soon escape Belle's hell. Since being dropped from
the No. 3 spot to No. 5 in the New York Yankees' order, O'Neill has
begun spraying hits all over the place.
</P>
<P>
   He had a double, two singles and a walk, Jorge Posada drove in
five runs, and Orlando Hernandez, pitching his first game in South
Florida since his defection from Cuba, pitched 6 2/3 innings as the
Yankees beat the Florida Marlins, 8-4.
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, was here to
watch and tell tales of the team's visit to the White House on
Thursday. When Steinbrenner and President Clinton descended the
steps together and ``Hail to the Chief'' was played, the president
turned to Steinbrenner and said, ``Don't get any ideas, it's not
for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Not in the White House, anyway. But Steinbrenner reigns in the
Yankees' organization, and for now, he is projecting a patient
look, in spite of the team's relative mediocrity over the last
month. Because Joe Torre is the manager, Steinbrenner said, he is
sure the Yankees will play better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried,'' Steinbrenner said. ``We're in first place,
playing the way we are. We're going to get turned around, and we're
getting close. Yeah, we're on the right track.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner agrees with Torre's recent lineup changes, the
demotion of O'Neill and Chuck Knoblauch's two-day assignment near
the bottom of the batting order. (Knoblauch returned to the top of
the Yankees' lineup Friday night.)
</P>
<P>
   ``He's shaking them up a little,'' said Steinbrenner, referring
to Torre. ``You take a guy like O'Neill. He's my supreme warrior,
he's the ultimate warrior, and he's having trouble. A little change
might not hurt. Knoblauch is another warrior. We've got a team full
of warriors. I think they proved that last year.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as O'Neill said this week, this year is not last year and
the Yankees are not overwhelming. Florida's Brian Meadows, a
right-hander with a 5.07 ERA, had never allowed fewer than two runs
in his first 12 starts of the year, and yet he held the Yankees
hitless through the first three innings. Derek Jeter was the first
Yankee to reach base, with a one-out single in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees tied the score at 1-1 in the fifth, after O'Neill
pulled a double that skipped off the wall in right, took third on a
wild pitch and scored on Posada's groundout. Tino Martinez walked
to open the seventh inning against Meadows. With the Marlins' Kevin
Millar holding Martinez at first, O'Neill bounded a single through
the right side of the infield, Martinez taking third base.
</P>
<P>
   Meadows got ahead of Posada, no balls and two strikes, and like
other pitchers have done so successfully against Posada this year,
Meadows attempted to finish Posada with soft stuff, a change-up _
but left it high in the strike zone. Posada crushed a three-run
homer, giving Hernandez (7-5) a hefty advantage.
</P>
<P>
   El Duque, as Hernandez is known, walked into a restaurant with
his brother Livan here early Friday morning, and even past
midnight, the arrival of the Hernandez brothers _ Livan pitches for
the Marlins _ created a scene. They shook hands with restaurant
patrons, who recognized them instantly, Orlando grinning and
greeting.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, he had signed a ball for a fan in another
city: Clinton asked for an autograph from Hernandez, and he
presented a jersey to the president. This is Hernandez's life in
the United States, just 18 months after defecting from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The Hernandez brothers sat together for an interview with ESPN,
and Livan _ who will throw against the Yankees on Saturday _ was
asked what he thought about El Duque's defection from Cuba in a
boat. ``Lunacy,'' Livan answered. ``Just lunacy.''
</P>
<P>
   But he's here, and thriving. Hernandez, who always seems to
pitch well in the spotlight, allowed just two unearned runs,
changing speeds and throwing strikes. He also got his first hit, a
bunt single in the seventh inning. When he was relieved with two
out in the bottom of the inning, the fans stood and roared for him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
