<SLUG> BC-VIRUS-COMPUTER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLY COMPUTER BUG CATCHES SOME UNAWARES, BUT MOST AVOID IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREG HACK  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Worm.Explore.Zip computer bug has been
sneaky and mean, fooling some pretty savvy computer users and
devouring files on tens of thousands of computers this week.
</P>
<P>
   There was a flurry of Worm sightings Thursday at such big-name
companies as General Electric, AT&AMP;T, Boeing, Compaq and even
Microsoft. But it appeared Friday that the bug, which disguises
itself as friendly e-mail, was being contained by computer
administrators across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Worm was tricky enough to claim a few victims who
probably should have known better, such as Steve Lunceford of
Sprint Corp.
</P>
<P>
   When Lunceford tapped into Sprint's intranet, he read:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, Steve! I got your email. I'll get back to you ASAP. In the
meantime, check out these documents.''
</P>
<P>
   When he did, his computer went kaput.
</P>
<P>
   ``It totally destroyed my drive,'' said Lunceford, who works at
a Sprint office in Washington but was in Kansas City Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost about two weeks of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Lunceford did catch the Worm fast enough to keep it from
spreading to other computers, which it does by sending a copy of
itself as a reply to any incoming e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Companywide, Sprint's network security staff caught the virus
early. Lunceford was one of only four Sprint employees affected.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the security staff at Cerner Corp., the North Kansas
City software maker, detected the virus early Thursday morning and
moved quickly to protect files and hard drives, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, about 5 percent of Cerner's computer files were
deleted, but all critical documents among them were recalled from
backup systems, said Jerry Smith, Cerner's business systems
director.
</P>
<P>
   Other heavy computer users in the Kansas City area appeared to
have ducked the virus, thanks in part to a combination of prompt
warnings and protective software.
</P>
<P>
   No one involved with the Silicon Prairie Technology Association
had reported any problems as of midafternoon Friday, said Susan E.
Catts, the organization's president.
</P>
<P>
   Spot checks Friday turned up no problems at such institutions as
Hallmark Cards, the Kansas City Board of Trade and Kansas City
Power &AMP; Light. The Greater Kansas City Chamber of Commerce hadn't
heard of any troubles among its members as of midafternoon Friday,
said Dick Gibson, an executive there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most businesses are being very wise and warning employees not
to open any e-mail that looks suspicious,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;R Block Inc. learned of the problem early in the day and was
able to provide descriptions of the potentially damaging messages,
said Todd Ransom, a company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri and Kansas state government offices also reported no
problems, as did most area municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri uses antivirus software aggressively, ``and in fact
we've even seen a drop in problems during the last month,'' said
Kay Dinolfo, a spokeswoman in Jefferson City.
</P>
<P>
   The bug did show up on three or four government computers in
Overland Park, Kan., but anti-virus software stopped users from
opening the e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
