<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISIT-CLINTON-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HAILS B-2 AND ITS CREWS AT WHITEMAN AIR FORCE BASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOB NOSTER, Mo. _ Basking in military victory over Yugoslavia,
President Clinton on Friday visited the home of the B-2 stealth
bomber to thank the crews of a ``truly remarkable aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton toured Whiteman Air Force Base east of Kansas City,
where the batlike B-2s took off and landed for their 30-hour,
round-trip sorties to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told airmen and their families in a crowded hangar: ``I
want you to know that we are very proud of you. Thanks to you, the
century is ending not with helpless indignation over such
unspeakable cruelty, but with its opposite, a ringing affirmation
by a free people of human dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
accepted terms of a peace agreement because of the B-2's ability to
wreak havoc.
</P>
<P>
   ``You made him do it,'' Clinton said, stressing each word.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was a day for warm embraces between the commander in
chief and some of the men he ordered into combat. The Whiteman
crowd cheered the president often.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what he said was beautiful,'' said Staff Sgt. Vurtis
Cunningham. ``I loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Before speaking, the president inspected the enormous B-2s.
Guided by two pilots, he climbed into the plane's cramped cockpit
and peered out a window.
</P>
<P>
   The sophisticated $2 billion bombers, designed for their quiet
flight and ability to avoid radar detection, proved remarkably
effective, the president said. The jets were among the first allied
planes to fly into hostile territory, where they dumped loads of
satellite-guided ``smart bombs'' on heavily guarded targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we know, (the Serbs) still don't know you were
there,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He drew a rousing cheer when he added that the 50 missions the
B-2s flew represented less than 1 percent of the total number of
missions flown in the conflict. But the B-2s dropped 11 percent of
the bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit was a moment of vindication _ for him and the
aircraft. The president was criticized for not defining the war's
objectives more clearly and for stipulating early on that he would
not use ground troops. Critics said that admission gave Milosevic a
strategic advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know,'' he said, ``everybody in America was free to
tell me I was wrong about this from the get-go.''
</P>
<P>
   The B-2, meanwhile, was questioned for its enormous expense and
criticized that it would never live up to its billing. The first
B-2 was publicly displayed in 1988, but was not used in the Persian
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an I-told-you-so day,'' said U.S. Rep. Ike Skelton of
Lexington, Mo., a Democrat who pushed hard for the money to build
the aircraft. ``The B-2 has modernized modern warfare.''
</P>
<P>
   Whiteman is home to 10 of the aircraft, but only six were used
in eastern Europe. The others were either not ready for combat,
were undergoing maintenance or were being used for training, said
Brig. Gen. Leroy Barnidge.
</P>
<P>
   The president's visit to Whiteman included three segments: He
toured the plane, visited with about 50 crew members and family
members and delivered a speech.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Clinton reminded the crowd that allied forces
achieved victory by the force of their bombs as well as the power
of their example. By fielding a diverse military, the forces
provided a ``stern rebuke on a daily basis'' to ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   ``His whole justification for power has been to tell the Serbian
people that...their country can only be great when everybody's just
like everybody else,'' the president said of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, look around here,'' Clinton said, his gaze sweeping the
room. ``You put the lie to that by the power of your example. And
make no mistake about that, it is even more powerful than the power
of our bombs.''
</P>
<P>
   On his flight from Washington, Clinton met for about an hour
with an 11-member congressional delegation that included five
members from Missouri and one from Kansas. Their discussion ranged
from Kosovo to China to Russia and the Mideast and, at one point,
turned to home health care.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton visited the base, a handful of protesters stood
outside the gates challenging the decision to bomb Serbia. They
held signs saying, ``Let's try setting a peaceful example (for the
kids)'' and ``Bombs do not produce peace or freedom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
