<SLUG> BC-PLUMBERS-STRIKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLUMBERS BACK TO WORK AS UNION, COMPANIES REACH AGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Striking plumbers in the Kansas City area
returned to work Friday, ending a 10-day walkout. Roofers, however,
remained off the job with more talks set for next week.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Plumbers Local 8 ratified a new three-year contract
in a meeting Thursday evening, said Rick Wallace, Local 8's
business manager.
</P>
<P>
   About 650 area union plumbers will receive a $6.09 increase in
hourly wages and benefits over three years under the new agreement.
However, the economic package was not the issue that led to the
strike last week.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said the plumbing companies, represented by the
Mechanical Contractors Association, were seeking to create a
pre-apprenticeship position that would pay less than what other
union plumbers earn.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what was the big stumbling block for us,'' he said.
``Our members and the local were concerned that the language the
association wanted would undermine our apprenticeship program.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said the association agreed to contract language that
satisfied the union.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Brandon, president of A.D. Jacobson &AMP; Co. and leader of
the association's negotiating committee, said no more than one or
two workers in the pre-apprenticeship position would be working on
any single project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame we were out of work for eight (work) days, but
we'll try to make up for the lost time and get things going
again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the plumbers union's first strike in 32 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a strike-happy bunch,'' Wallace said. ``But that's
how seriously our members took the issue over the apprenticeship
program.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Dunn, president and chief executive officer of J.E. Dunn
Construction Co., said many plumbers were back to work Friday and
that virtually all of them should return by Monday.
</P>
<P>
   However, Dunn remained concerned about the strike by Roofers
Local 20, which has about 400 members off the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``That situation remains tenuous,'' he said. ``We're still
monitoring that one closely.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hadel, Local 20's business manager, said a meeting between
the union and the Associated Roofers was scheduled for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The roofers are seeking wage and benefits gains as well as a
reversal of some work-rule concessions made in the 1980s, when the
construction market was depressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think both parties might present something new,'' he said.
``We'll have to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, work by other unionized construction workers
continues at various commercial projects because Local 20 has not
picketed those sites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
