<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN CENTURY LOSES FOUR PEOPLE FROM FUND TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK DAVIS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Four of the five persons running the American
Century Select Fund resigned Thursday to join another mutual fund
family, Kansas City-based American Century said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Fund co-managers Jean Ledford and Richard Welsh and two of the
three analysts assigned to the fund resigned late in the afternoon,
said Chris Doyle, an American Century spokesman. He said they have
been hired by First Union Corp., the Charlotte, N.C.-based banking
company that owns the Evergreen Funds.
</P>
<P>
   A First Union spokesman declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle said the departing American Century managers and analysts
were not commenting Friday, pending an announcement from First
Union.
</P>
<P>
   Select, with $7 billion in assets, is American Century's
third-largest fund.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle said Jim Stowers III would step into the manager's seat at
Select. Stowers, American Century's chief executive officer,
already oversees the management of Select and the other growth
stock funds in the company's Twentieth Century group of funds.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Terry Foster, who joined the Select team in 1997,
remains to work with Stowers, Doyle said. He said they would be
able to tap analysts of the company's other growth funds, too.
</P>
<P>
   The two Select Fund analysts who resigned are Rick Petran and
John Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   The manager shake-up is the second at Select in three years.
Ledford joined American Century in January 1997 to co-manage the
fund with Chuck Duboc. Duboc left in mid-1997 and was replaced by
Welsh.
</P>
<P>
   The difference this time is that four-fifths of the team
managing Select leaves together.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Di Teresa, senior analyst at Morningstar Inc. in Chicago,
said the unexpected departures short-circuit American Century's
practice of team fund management.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea (behind a team approach) is if one person leaves it
shouldn't have that big an impact,'' Di Teresa said.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that American Century lost another team when Dong
Zhang and Steve Colton left in June 1997 to join Phoenix Duff &AMP;
Phelps Inc., which runs the Phoenix Funds. They had been
co-managers of the American Century Equity Growth and American
Century Income &AMP; Growth funds. Colton also managed the American
Century Utilities Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Di Teresa said the Select Fund had been performing well since
Ledford joined. It had been ``narrowly'' beating the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 Index through its investments in large-company growth
stocks. Di Teresa noted that such stocks have been highly favored
on Wall Street until recently.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the large-company growth stock funds at Evergreen
haven't been notably successful, Di Teresa said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps Evergreen is looking for some help,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
