<SLUG> BC-NY-MURDER-CONVICTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN CONVICTED OF MURDER MAY GET DEATH PENALTY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By VIVIAN S. TOY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 22-year-old man was convicted Friday of murdering
an off-duty police officer and the owner of a Queens check cashing
business during a robbery in 1996, and could face the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   In the second capital punishment case to be tried in Queens
since the death penalty was restored in New York state in 1995, the
jury will decide whether to sentence the killer, George Davis Bell,
to death.
</P>
<P>
   Queens District Attorney Richard Brown called the verdict ``more
than justified.'' He said that evidence of Bell's guilt presented
during the three-week trial was ``clearly overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's Capital Defender Office, which represented Bell,
said in a statement that Bell's defense team was ``deeply
disappointed by the verdict.'' Bell's lawyers had argued his
innocence, saying that a confession from Bell had been coerced by
detectives.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Bell shot Officer Charles Davis and Ira Epstein
to death on the morning of Dec. 21, 1996, as they opened Epstein's
business, Astoria Boulevard Check Cashing.
</P>
<P>
   They presented testimony that Bell and an accomplice ambushed
the two men, forced them inside the business at gunpoint and
announced a robbery. But before either Davis, who was moonlighting
as a security guard, or Epstein could meet the demand for money,
Bell started shooting and killed both men. Bell and his accomplice
ran from the store empty handed.
</P>
<P>
   Bell was arrested a week after the shooting when another man who
prosecutors said was a lookout during the robbery was arrested on a
minor drug charge. During questioning, the man, John Mark Bigweh,
23, of Brooklyn, led investigators to conclude that he and four
others were involved in the attempted robbery of Epstein's
business. Three of them, including Bigweh, are awaiting a separate
trial, and the other has not been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   The conviction of Bell follows the conviction in December of
James Allen Gordon, the first person in Queens to face the death
penalty since the reinstatement of capital punishment. The jury
spared the life of Gordon, who was convicted of killing three women
and trying to kill two others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-99 0022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
