<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BAKER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN CALHOUN BAKER, 103, OHIO UNIVERSITY PRESIDENT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Mass., Pa., N.J.)   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Calhoun Baker, president emeritus of Ohio University, who
guided it through the burgeoning enrollment when the veterans of
World War II surged in under the GI Bill, died June 9 at a
retirement community in Hightstown, N.J., where he moved three
years ago. A former resident of Essex Fells, N.J., he was 103.
</P>
<P>
   Baker retired in 1961 after 16 years as Ohio University's 14th
president, but he remained a figure on the Athens campus, whose
student center bears his name. He paid his last visit to be feted
there on his 100th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   He took up the presidency in 1945 with a mandate from Gov. Frank
Lausche to make room for the returning veterans. Enrollment grew
during his presidency to more than 8,000 students from 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Necessity made him one of the first college administrators to
develop the regional campus network to avoid overcrowding at
Athens. He oversaw the addition of 32 major buildings and the
start-up of ambitious research and doctoral programs.
</P>
<P>
   One of his initial decisions stopped the demolition of Cutler
Hall, which opened in 1818 and was the oldest academic building in
the Northwest Territory. It was restored and became the seat of
Ohio University's central administration.
</P>
<P>
   University president Robert Glidden said Baker ``was, in a
sense, the founder of modern Ohio University,'' from whose
initiatives grew the system of five regional campuses and the
University Foundation. Established in 1945 to finance research,
scholarships and grants, the foundation has raised more than $300
million since its inception.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Everett, Pa., Baker graduated from Juniata College in
1917 and earned a master's degree in business administration at
Harvard University in 1923. He was the author of several books and
many articles on business administration and, after his retirement
from Ohio University, served as a corporate director of several
companies.
</P>
<P>
   He started his career at the Harvard Business School as a
researcher, instructor, assistant dean and professor of business
administration. From 1939 to 1945 he served as associate dean of
Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife endowed the Baker Peace Studies Program at Ohio
University in 1982. It was designed to promote peace studies as an
academic subject with lectures, conferences, exhibits and courses.
</P>
<P>
   Baker's wife, Elizabeth Evans Baker, died in 1990 after 57 years
of marriage. He is survived by three daughters, Elizabeth C. Baker,
Eleanor B. Steindler and Anne C. Baker, all of Manhattan, and two
grandchildren. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-99 0025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
