<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BENEFITS-CHEATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC CHARGES SEVERAL DOZEN IN A SCHEME ON BENEFITS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL MacFARQUHAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A police detective, four schoolteachers and a New
York City Transit employee were among dozens of government
employees and others charged Friday with cheating the city out of
more than $1.4 million dollars in unjustified housing subsidies or
welfare benefits.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth wave of charges in a continuing inquiry by the
Department of Investigation and the Manhattan district attorney's
office to root out people collecting undeserved benefits by lying
about their income or employment status.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation involves matching the names of more than
900,000 tenants of the New York City Housing Authority against the
city's payroll of 200,000 names and the welfare rolls of at least
1.6 million names, said Kevin Ryan, a spokesman for the Department
of Investigation.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the investigation included people on the
city payroll earning more than $50,000, and 6 of the 59 people
charged were paid at least that much, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said those charged included Emily Hargrove, 40, a police
detective who has been on the force since 1981, has earned more
than $60,000 per year, and has received more than $24,000 in rent
subsidies for a Manhattan apartment. Hargrove has an unlisted
telephone number and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said that some of those charged who were not government
employees had forged the signatures of dead tenants to enable the
rent subsidies to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Those charged Friday were accused of receiving nearly $1.24
million in unmerited rent subsidies by lying about their assets. In
addition, 14 of them used similar deceit to obtain more than
$185,000 in welfare benefits, Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   The charges, from filing false documents to grand larceny, could
lead to prison terms as long as 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The accused are scheduled to surrender during the week beginning
June 21. The spokesman said the 28 public employees involved in the
fraud had been suspended and would probably be fired, and that they
would also be expelled from their publicly subsidized housing if
convicted on the criminal charges. He said a few had already moved
upstate or to New Jersey, but would be pursued for back rent.
</P>
<P>
   Government employees, including police officers, are not barred
from living in public housing in the city. ``They can live in the
city, they can live in the projects, but they just have to let us
know that they work for the Police Department,'' Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   But they must meet the same criteria as anyone else for
subsidized housing, which includes both large projects and
apartments in smaller, privately owned buildings. Ryan said the
approximate income qualifications were less than $20,000 for one
person, less than $46,000 for a family of five, and about $70,000
for 12 people.
</P>
<P>
   The investigative method of matching computerized lists of
tenants, public employees and welfare rolls, first used in 1995,
has resulted in charges against at least 140 people, with 57
convicted and more than $600,000 in illegal payments restored, the
spokesman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-99 0027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2710 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-KOSOVO-     06-12 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-KOSOVO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER:   COMING TO TERMS WITH KOSOVO'S `OLD' HATREDS  
 &HT;    (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN R. WEISMAN  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the annals of U.S. presidents and the Balkans, an arc can be
traced from Bill Clinton back to Woodrow Wilson. At the Versailles
peace conference following World War I, Wilson arrived after
reviewing European history and then helped establish a new southern
Slavic state to fill the vacuum created by the collapse of the
Ottoman and Austrian empires. There is a famous moment in which
Wilson, the idealist, squatted on the floor with his experts over a
gigantic map of places he had never been. His wife walked in and
commented that they looked like boys playing a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alas,'' replied the president, looking up, ``it is the most
serious game ever undertaken.''
</P>
<P>
   A new round in the game has now started with the end of the war
in Yugoslavia and the troubling entry of Russian troops into
Kosovo. Liberated from Serbian administration but not yet a nation,
Kosovo is to be attached to but ``walled off'' from Yugoslavia.
Unhappily, the long-term stability of Kosovo's status may well
depend on Albanians and Serbs being ``walled off'' from each other.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of the crisis in Kosovo, there has been a
debate among intellectuals, historians and policy makers over
whether the violence has resulted from ancient ethnic hatreds or
modern manipulations by ruthless politicians. Clinton recently made
an extraordinary apology for once believing that the Balkans were a
place of ``centuries-old animosity'' impervious to change.
</P>
<P>
   Now, ``after a great deal of time in these last six years
reading the real history of the Balkans,'' he said that he
regretted ``more than I can say'' having once felt that way.
</P>
<P>
   The president's current view is that although ethnic tensions
have long plagued the region, the murderous warfare in Kosovo has
been fomented by Slobodan Milosevic's demagoguery and opportunism.
Thursday night he again appealed indirectly to the Serbs to
overthrow their leaders, who he said ``could have kept Kosovo as a
part of your country without driving a single Kosovar family from
its home.''
</P>
<P>
   The nature of ethnic hatred in the Balkans is relevant to the
kind of nation-building on which NATO and the United States have
embarked. At Versailles, Wilson and the European allies supported
the creation of a Slavic state encompassing various ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   Today's wars involve Serbs, Croats and Muslims, all trying to
redress longstanding grievances. The vision of Clinton that people
of differing ethnic groups can live with each other is appealing to
Americans, but it might be a case of imposing an unworkable image
on an unwilling populace.
</P>
<P>
   While no one doubts Milosevic's ruthlessness, for instance, the
notion that Balkan hatred will subside without his manipulations is
hard to accept. Reports of longtime neighbors raping, murdering and
expelling their neighbors suggest that old hatreds lie so close to
the surface that it may not take much to bring them into the open.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 10 years of Balkan turmoil, people who have felt
that the hatreds will never go away tend to oppose intervention.
Bismarck's famous comment in the 19th century that the Balkans were
``not worth the healthy bones of a single Pomeranian grenadier'' is
echoed by the statement attributed to Secretary of State James
Baker in the early 1990s that ``we don't have a dog in this
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no consensus on the issue of ethnic hatreds in the
dozens of books and articles published in the last few years, and
Clinton is not the only one to have changed his mind. Books by
journalists traveling among the people tend to emphasize the
deep-seated nature of the hatreds, while books focusing on politics
and history tend to emphasize the responsibility of leaders.
</P>
<P>
   As David Remnick pointed out in The New Yorker this week,
Clinton was influenced first by ``Balkan Ghosts,'' by Robert
Kaplan, published in 1993, a powerfully written work of reportage
that pays homage to Rebecca West's ``Black Lamb and Grey Falcon,''
published in 1941 and hailed by Kaplan as ``this century's greatest
travel book.''
</P>
<P>
   But in his diplomatic memoir, ``To End a War,'' Richard
Holbrooke criticizes both Kaplan and Ms. West for implying that
``nothing could be done by outsiders in a region so steeped in
ancient hatreds.'' He even laments the influence of the Kaplan book
on Clinton and others.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the president's favorite Balkan expert is said to be
the British journalist and scholar Noel Malcolm, who in ``Kosovo: A
Short History'' asserts that all the talk about ``ancient ethnic
hatreds'' is ``grossly misleading'' because of the history of
harmony among Muslims, Catholics and Orthodox Christians.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome in Kosovo will be another chapter in the ongoing
conflict between two appealing ideas: self-determination and the
principle that ethnic groups can live together peacefully.
Self-determination has allowed the number of members of the United
Nations to grow from 156 to 185 in the last 10 years. The risk of
applying the principle of self-determination too broadly is that
the number may grow by scores or even hundreds in the years ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
