u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-ARA     06-12 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-ARATON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: IF HIS OLD FRIEND RED   COULD SEE THEM NOW
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More than 50 years around the game, Fuzzy Levane
said, and he has never seen anything like this. He's never seen a
basketball team remake itself in a New York minute, and then keep
winning the way these Knicks have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep thinking, `Is this a mirage, or what?''' Levane said.
</P>
<P>
   No mirage, not this time. In the span of six wacky weeks, the
Knicks have gone from out of the playoffs to the NBA finals. From
eighth to first in the Eastern Conference. From a dysfunctional
team of 12 to an inspirational armada of nine.
</P>
<P>
   Even a pair of discerning, 79-year-old, New York-trained eyes
could not see this coming. No one could, least of all the Indiana
Pacers, who went down for the count, 90-82, Friday night at Madison
Square Garden, even after the Knicks lost their on-court leader,
Larry Johnson, to an injured right knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievable,'' said Andrew ``Fuzzy'' Levane. ``What can
happen next?''
</P>
<P>
   The old scout _ who played at James Madison High School in
Brooklyn and then at St. John's and whose life is practically a
storybook on the subject of the city game _ only wishes that his
soul mate in sports, Red Holzman, had lived long enough to see it.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the highs of a wild playoff ride have come the
saddest of moments when Levane, who has found himself looking over
to the area opposite the visitors' bench, where Red and Selma
Holzman used to sit, where the Hall of Fame coach would shoot him a
look, as if to say, ``Can you believe this?''
</P>
<P>
   Months have passed since Holzman's death and yet there are
particular plays, a Latrell Sprewell-led break, a Marcus Camby
block, when Levane experiences the familiar urge for eye contact,
when he can't believe that Holzman is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the one thing I can't get out of my mind,'' he said.
``Every day, I've been feeling it, thinking, `What a shame.' I find
myself dialing his number and saying, `What the hell am I doing?'''
</P>
<P>
   They were basketball brothers, Levane and Holzman, who was
brought into the Knicks' organization as a scout in 1958, when
Levane was coach. Holzman nearly wound up grieving eight years ago,
Levane having suffered a ruptured aortic aneurysm on the drive home
after being inducted into the New York Basketball Hall of Fame.
Levane hung on, went back to scouring the basketball bush leagues,
looking for another Anthony Mason, another John Starks.
</P>
<P>
   At Holzman's funeral last November, Levane and some of the other
lifers like Dick McGuire wondered if the lockout had made it easier
for a man heartbroken by the recent loss of his wife to surrender
to leukemia. The thinking went that Holzman needed the Knicks for
therapy, but, as it turned out, maybe the Knicks needed their
patriarch more.
</P>
<P>
   With all the duplicity that resulted in Dave Checketts'
foot-stomping deposing of Ernie Grunfeld, Levane surmised that only
Holzman might have been able to prevent it. He was the unifying
front-office thread, the Knicks' moral compass. Grunfeld, Checketts
and Jeff Van Gundy worshiped his record, loved the man. This season
of paradoxical news breaks began, really, at a funeral chapel in
Queens.
</P>
<P>
   It is much too painful to dwell on what might have been, but
Levane has trouble stopping himself. He doesn't feel much like the
warm, Fuzzy character who would come bursting into a room with a
joke, a story, his hands conducting a symphony. He has been to too
many wakes and funerals lately. Selma Holzman's. Red's. His sister
Marie's. His old friend and St. John's teammate, Red Tough.
</P>
<P>
   His doctor tells him he is suffering from traumatic stress,
feeling the anxiety of getting old.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Knicks,'' he said, ``are helping me.''
</P>
<P>
   The short season has turned into a story as long as Camby, the
Knicks' new star on the block, and it has all been medicine for the
mind. On the compelling subject of Camby, Levane went so far as to
draw comparisons with Russell, and he didn't mean Cazzie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Camby blocks the shot and keeps it in play,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the controversy, the obstacles, the injuries, the
Pacers still couldn't win. What Larry Bird suspected after Game 5
was right. His team had every opportunity, but didn't have the
heart. The Knicks simply out-fought them in the fourth quarter,
with half-court defense that would have made Holzman proud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know our half-court defense is excellent, `` Levane said,
``and I don't know if the guys out West have seen a lot of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense being what Holzman preached, Levane said that would be
the best of all tributes, figuring out a way to shut down Tim
Duncan and David Robinson, to win it all.
</P>
<P>
   The funny thing about these Knicks is that the further they go,
the higher the odds seem to get. You just never know, though, and
it doesn't pay to dwell too long on why. ``Just appreciate what you
have,'' Fuzzy Levane said. He will take his own advice for the next
couple of weeks. With so much else gone, he is thanking his stars
that there are still games, championship games now, left to be
played.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
