<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 00:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2717 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-N.J.-TROOPER-CHIEF-NY     06-12 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.J.-TROOPER-CHIEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS SAY BLACK ILLINOIS OFFICER CONSIDERED TO LEAD N.J.
POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Ill.)  (jw) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Gov. Christie Whitman has reportedly offered the
job of New Jersey State Police superintendent to an Illinois law
enforcement commander, state officials said Friday. If he accepts
the position, he will become the first black to hold the top office
in the department, which has been tarnished by complaints of racial
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Andre Parker of the Illinois State Police, who has been
credited with leading the turnaround of the troubled East St. Louis
Police Department, has not yet said whether he will accept the
position of superintendent. But a Whitman administration official
and a state police commander, both speaking on the condition of
anonymity, confirmed that Parker had been offered the position,
which pays $90,563 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman and Attorney General John Farmer Jr. declined to discuss
the matter. But the Rev. Reginald Jackson, a civil rights leader
who has led a surge of protests since two state troopers shot three
unarmed black and Hispanic men during a traffic stop in April 1998,
said he was encouraged by reports that the governor had apparently
resisted pressure to promote a candidate from within the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good news,'' Jackson said. ``I just hope it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than three months, the governor and her staff have been
searching for a new commander. This spring, the Whitman
administration acknowledged for the first time that troopers
routinely engaged in racial profiling, and outlined a series of
reforms that the incoming superintendent would be expected to
enact. The governor forced the previous superintendent, Col. Carl
Williams, to resign after he said in an interview that minorities
were chiefly to blame for New Jersey's drug problem.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Justice Department is investigating allegations that
white troopers targeted black and Hispanic motorists for stops
along New Jersey's highways. The Justice Department is also looking
into allegations that the department discriminated against minority
and female troopers.
</P>
<P>
   Parker, 43, was considered a good candidate because of his
experience in East St. Louis, where he spent two years. In 1993,
Jim Edgar, the Illinois governor then, appointed Parker to the
position of director of public safety, after the state stepped in
to monitor the department, state officials said. Although city
officials and police commanders initially resisted the presence of
an outsider, Parker quickly solved labor problems, updated the
procedure manual and reorganized the department, bringing a speedy
drop in crime.
</P>
<P>
   Parker did not not return repeated phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   If Parker, a 20-year veteran of the Illinois State Police,
becomes the first black to head the 2,700-member New Jersey State
Police force, he is also likely to face resistance from some
officers and commanders in the predominantly white department. In a
succession of lawsuits and numerous public statements this year,
black and Hispanic troopers have described the force as a racially
polarized agency where discrimination is tolerated and where
promotions and choice assignments are disproportionately awarded to
whites. Williams has denied any such bias.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of supervisors also have been lobbying for the
promotion of an insider, and in recent weeks, several state
legislators have publicly urged Whitman to choose someone from
within the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   But civil rights activists have also been adamant in demanding
that the governor nominate an outsider.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
