<SLUG> BC-BINLADEN-PROBE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO IN TEXAS ARE SUBPOENAED TO TESTIFY IN BIN LADEN CASE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two Muslim men from Texas have been subpoenaed to
testify next week before a federal grand jury in Manhattan
investigating Osama bin Laden, who is a suspect in the U.S. embassy
bombings in Africa last year and other terrorist acts.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for each of the men have sharply criticized the
subpoenas, saying that the government is casting its net too
broadly over Muslims and engaging in guilt by association.
</P>
<P>
   Both men are friends of Wadih el-Hage of Arlington, Texas, who
was arrested last year on charges that he had conspired with bin
Laden in terrorist attacks on Americans abroad. el-Hage has been
described in an indictment as a former personal secretary to bin
Laden. He has pleaded not guilty to the charges.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Texas men who received a subpoena is Moataz
Al-Hallak, the imam at the Islamic Society of Arlington, where
el-Hage was an active member. A federal prosecutor said in court
last spring that Al-Hallak ``has served as a contact between
members of the bin Laden organization,'' prompting an angry letter
from his lawyer to prosecutors, asking that they stop slandering
Al-Hallak by unfairly linking him to the suspected terrorist.
Al-Hallak has never been charged in the case.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Stanley Cohen, said Friday that a prosecutor in the
office of Mary Jo White, the U.S. Attorney in Manhattan, told him
that Al-Hallak was being asked to appear as a ``subject'' of the
investigation, which is one step lower than a ``target.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen criticized Ms. White's office Friday, saying that her
definition of subject is too broad. ``Anyone who can read a
newspaper article and recognize the name Osama bin Laden becomes a
subject'' of the investigation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert Hadad, a spokesman for Ms. White, said there would be no
comment about the case or any of the criticisms by the defense
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said he expected his client would be asked about his
relationship with el-Hage, and whether he knows bin Laden, whom he
does not. ``My client does not believe in violence, no matter what
the source,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   He said Al-Hallak has not yet decided what he will do when he
appears before the grand jury, and whether he will answer
questions.
</P>
<P>
   The other witness who has received a subpoena was identified by
his lawyer as Khader Ibrahim. The lawyer described Ibrahim as a
friend of el-Hage who may once have hired him to work in one of his
tire shops in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Lynne Stewart, said she has been told that Ibrahim
was subpoenaed as a subject of the investigation. She said her
client had been interviewed repeatedly in Texas by agents of the
Federal Bureau of Investigation, who visited him again last week
with a videotape of the aftermath of the embassy bombings. After he
watched it at their request, ``they said, `Will you speak with us
now?' He said, `No, I don't want to really speak with you any
further,' '' Ms. Stewart said. She said he was given the grand jury
subpoena the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is another round of Muslim-bashing,'' Ms. Stewart
said. Ibrahim has not been charged in the case, and she said he has
not been involved in any wrongdoing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-99 0042EDT &QL; 
