<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERMOSILLO TO DEBUT WITH GALAXY TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Carlos Hermosillo seemed a little tired during a
recent training session at USC, but he insists he's ready to make
his season debut when the Los Angeles Galaxy plays host to Chicago
tonight at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you need to check my blood, I'll show you later,'' he
joked. ``I feel very good. I took the time I needed to rest and now
I'm very anxious to get started.''
</P>
<P>
   But a word of caution to the popular Mexican striker: a world of
expectations await.
</P>
<P>
   Hermosillo just joined the team Wednesday _ two weeks after the
Mexican winter season _ and already he's addressing questions
regarding the Galaxy's lack of scoring and sagging attendance
figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK,'' he admitted. ``It's not only a challenge for me
but for all of us. As for the fans, they're very demanding. They
want to see goals and I don't blame them.''
</P>
<P>
   Midfielder Mauricio Cienfuegos tried taking some of the pressure
off Hermosillo.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a person like him comes in (late), people start thinking
of him as the savior, especially because of the situation we're in
now,'' Cienfuegos said. ``He's had his rest and he's barely getting
back into the rhythm ... so our troubles shouldn't fall on his
shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   Hermosillo is asked to make immediate contributions to a Galaxy
team hampered by an MLS-low eight goals in 12 games in posting a
less-than-impressive 6-6 record.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Galaxy management hopes Hermosillo can lure back
the Hispanic audience. Los Angeles had a walk-up crowd of 18,000
for his debut last season, when a total of 33,383 turned out.
Averaging only 13,105 this season, the Galaxy is hoping for
something in the range of 20,000 for tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's coming into a good situation,'' Galaxy general manager
Sergio Del Prado said. ``We're obviously having trouble scoring and
he's one of the best scorers Mexico has ever had. He has a high
deal of credibility (with Latin fans) and has always been a good
spokesperson for soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   Hermosillo can ill-afford a start similar to last season's. He
didn't score until his 12th game _ but Los Angeles was winning and
scoring at the time, so few noticed his personal struggles.
</P>
<P>
   The 34-year-old post-up striker admits there have been several
changes in his time away.
</P>
<P>
   Out are former coach Octavio Zambrano and midfielder Martin
Machon. In are former UCLA coach Sigi Schmid and recently acquired
midfielders Simon Elliott, Roy Myers and former UCLA striker Seth
George, who signed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a completely different team than the one I was on last
year,'' Hermosillo said. ``To tell you the truth, it looks better
balanced.''
</P>
<P>
   With Cobi Jones and Robin Fraser out tonight (playing for the
U.S. national team in Sunday's friendly against Argentina),
Hermosillo will start alongside fellow striker Clint Mathis.
</P>
<P>
   Schmid welcomes a 6-foot-1 striker hovering around the
opponent's goal area.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gives us somebody we can play to in the box and somebody
who should be able to get on the end of crosses,'' Schmid said. ``I
think it's important we keep him as high as possible because he's
so dangerous (posting there).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
