<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 00:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2726 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LINCOLN-HOSPITAL-NYT &LR;      06-12 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINCOLN-HOSPITAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. CRITICIZES BRONX HOSPITAL EMERGENCY CARE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Federal health care regulators say they have found
serious problems with the way Lincoln Hospital in the Bronx runs
its emergency room, which is the city's busiest. Their criticisms
include poor assessment of the urgency of cases, waits of several
hours before patients see doctors and shoddy records on what
happens to many patients.
</P>
<P>
   A report by the Health Care Financing administration, prepared
after a surprise visit to the hospital in March, cited one instance
in which a 56-year-old man with a history of high blood pressure
came into the emergency room complaining of chest pressure and a
nurse determined that he needed immediate treatment. Yet federal
investigators found ``no evidence that the patient was seen by a
physician until one hour after triage.''
</P>
<P>
   Another man, who had a history of drug abuse and mental illness,
complained of being suicidal and homicidal, the report said, but
was ``not seen by a physician until two hours after arrival.''
</P>
<P>
   The regulators' findings, first reported Friday in The New York
Post, included several similar examples, and suggested that the
sprawling public hospital had failed to resolve many problems that
had been found during three inspections last year.
</P>
<P>
   The findings also echoed concerns of many former physicians at
Lincoln since another Bronx hospital, St. Barnabas, began a
three-year contract last summer to provide medical services there.
Those former doctors, who were dismissed after St. Barnabas took
over, said that overly aggressive cost-cutting had hurt patient
care at the hospital, including the emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Luis Marcos, president of the city's Health and Hospitals
Corp., vigorously disputed the conclusions of the report Friday,
saying that the hospital's problems were mostly cases of bad
record-keeping, not bad care.
</P>
<P>
   In many instances when federal officials said they found no
evidence that patients had been seen in a timely fashion, he said,
it was simply because records were incomplete. In other instances,
city officials said, the federal report left out important facts.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the report cited an incident in which a 38-year-old
man died after he went to the emergency room in September asking
for insulin. He was found unconscious in a waiting area five hours
later. The report criticized the hospital for not classifying the
man as in urgent need of care.
</P>
<P>
   But city officials said Friday that his death was not a result
of lack of care, but of the patient's use of an illegal drug.
</P>
<P>
   After the man was examined by a nurse, an internal hospital memo
said, he went to a secluded area near a men's restroom and smoked
crack. He was found in cardiac arrest and died several days later,
the memo said. The city's Medical Examiner found that the chief
cause of death was acute cocaine intoxication, the hospital said.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital also said it had improved its patient security and
monitoring since the death.
</P>
<P>
   Marcos said that federal regulators had unfairly singled out
city hospitals for criticism. He said that when a nurse sees
patients and determines that they are not in urgent need of care,
waits of several hours to see doctors are sometimes unavoidable at
Lincoln, where the emergency room can be inundated by up to 400
patient visits a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some issue with waiting, but frankly, most emergency
rooms have waiting times,'' he said. ``I'm very, very comfortable
with the quality of care we deliver at Lincoln.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
