<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOKSON LIVING LIFE-LONG DREAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ Brent Cookson thought about the opportunity to live a
dream when he signed a minor-league, free-agent contract with the
Los Angeles Dodgers in January.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody else thought anything of it.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Dodgers' search for a healthy fourth outfielder, they
couldn't overlook the triple-crown numbers Cookson was putting up
in Triple-A Albuquerque. So in dire need of outfield depth, the
Dodgers promoted Cookson, a former Santa Paula High and Ventura
College star, before Friday's game with the Oakland Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Cookson's contract was purchased from Albuquerque. To make room
for him, the Dodgers designated infielder Chance Sanford, who
joined the Dodgers last Friday, for assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a Dodgers fan since I was 5 years old,'' said
Cookson, who also played at Long Beach State. ``I've been in
professional ball since 1991, but I've always dreamed of playing
for the Dodgers. It's always been my ultimate goal. The opportunity
(to sign) came about and I jumped at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Cookson was in the midst of hitting .333 with 18
homers and 48 RBI, he wouldn't have received the call if the
Dodgers' outfield corps hadn't been depleted.
</P>
<P>
   The team spent the last two games with three healthy outfielders
and with fingers crossed that a fourth wasn't needed.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said he would probably use the
right-handed Cookson as a designated hitter today against Oakland
left-hander Kenny Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Cookson was necessary because center fielder
Devon White (groin strain) won't be ready for outfield duty until
Sunday at the earliest, Johnson said. White was originally in
Friday's lineup, but Johnson scratched him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed a fourth outfielder,'' Johnson said. ``This cold
weather, (White) was going to go, but I said no. I could go with
(Trenidad) Hubbard against the left-hander (today) and I have
another right-hander (Cookson) to go to. If I play (White), I'd
like to have another off day for him (afterward) and see how he
feels.''
</P>
<P>
   If Cookson, 29, starts, it won't be the first time in his
major-league career. He played 22 games for Kansas City in 1995. He
hit .143 with one double and five RBI before bouncing through the
minor leagues of Boston, Baltimore and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``They brought me up for a reason, and that's to take care of
business,'' Cookson said. ``I was down there working my butt off so
I could get this call and get out of Triple-A as soon as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   DH difference: The trip to Oakland was the first interleague
game in which the Dodgers used the designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a veteran manager who managed for two seasons with
Baltimore, said: ``The (designated hitter) in the AL is in the
middle of the lineup,'' Johnson said. ``We don't really know what
to do with the DH. We have pinch-hitters, and you really don't want
to redo your whole lineup for just one guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Hansen was the Dodgers' DH and batted eighth. John Jaha was
Oakland's DH and he batted cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's preference: Being back in an American League park and
playing by AL rules didn't exactly make Johnson giddy.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his feelings in playing by AL rules, he planted
his tongue into his cheek and said, ``Enthralled, baby.
Enthralled.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I takes away a lot of the strategy,'' Johnson added. ``When to
take the pitcher out, when to use a pinch-hitter. There's not as
much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
