<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2731 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-ART     06-12 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS OVERCOME LOSS OF JOHNSON TO EARN BERTH IN FINALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was the final buzzer and the signal to rejoice
over the impossible. The once-fractured and disjointed New York
Knicks _ a team that treated adversity and misfortune like
emotional allies right though Friday night's game _ grabbed onto
each other and danced on the court like kids bouncing on box
springs.
</P>
<P>
   They were on air after winning Game 6 of their Eastern
Conference finals against the Indiana Pacers, 90-82, Friday night
to win the series, 4-2 , and advance to the NBA finals against the
San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   They accomplished what seemed unthinkable for a team that was
mired in turmoil and on the verge of missing the playoffs in late
April. And what seemed improbable for a team that lost its
superstar, Patrick Ewing, to injury last week. And what appeared
bleak when the Game 3 hero, Larry Johnson, left Friday night's game
with a sprained knee midway through the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But as Madison Square Garden witnessed Friday night, nothing is
impossible for the Knicks on a journey that has been abetted by
good karma and inspired by the play of Marcus Camby. On this night,
his partner in producing another kind of miracle _ a victory
without Johnson _ was Allan Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Camby scored 15 points and had eight rebounds, while Houston
added 32 points. As time slipped off the clock, coach Jeff Van
Gundy embraced Houston. He then put a fist in the air toward Camby.
Undaunted by the magnitude of the game, a very loose Camby was
omnipresent as he grabbed rebounds, flew in for tip-ins, blocked
shots and altered the trajectory of jumpers taken by Rik Smits and
Reggie Miller.
</P>
<P>
   He slipped in and around the Pacers, weaving to be everywhere at
once. His defensive presence was only topped by the offense Houston
came up with to counter whatever the Pacers could generate on a
night when Miller could not muster a big shot. Miller shot 3 for 18
with just eight points.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers, the team picked to win it all before the season
began, walked off crestfallen with coach Larry Bird. The Knicks
were the team carrying itself with the confidence of a champion.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear the Knicks were not going to let their chance to
reach the NBA finals for the first time since 1994 go. Houston was
not going to let it happen. He drove the basket and came up with a
3-point play with 3 minutes 53 seconds left to give the Knicks a
76-70 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Each time the Pacers threatened to tighten the pressure, either
Houston or Camby came right back with a huge play. On a missed
layup by Chris Childs, Camby sliced through the air from nowhere
for a put-back that sent the crowd into a frenzy with 2:50 left and
the Knicks ahead, 80-76.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks held their edge from there as chants of ``Jeff Van
Gundy'' rang through the building in the final seconds as another
show of support for a coach who has not had job security since the
early weeks of the season.
</P>
<P>
   There was silence in what had been a raucous Garden when Travis
Best rolled into Johnson's right knee as he came down from a finger
roll with 6:03 left in the first half. Curled up on the baseline,
Johnson was writhing in pain for several minutes while Van Gundy
and the team physician, Norman Scott, hovered over him.
</P>
<P>
   Without putting pressure on his right leg, Johnson grimaced as
he was helped to the locker room by Chris Dudley and Herb Williams.
And a sick feeling sank into the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   What now? The Knicks had already lost Ewing to a torn Achilles'
tendon after Game 2. Their remaining low-post presence _ and their
four-point miracle worker from Game 3 _ was on the way to Beth
Israel North Division for a magnetic resonance imaging test after
spraining the ligaments in his right knee. It was the same knee he
sprained March 30 against the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the uneasiness of Johnson's injury, there was still a
very lively Camby. And as long as he was still creating the kind of
havoc he did in the first half, and as long as Miller was missing
for the Pacers, there was still a chance for the Knicks. Instead of
folding in Johnson's absence, they went on a 13-9 run to end the
first half with a 41-35 lead.
</P>
<P>
   That adrenaline rush vanished at the start of the third quarter
as the Pacers scored 11 straight points to take a five-point lead.
But that roll came to a halt once Camby re-entered the game and
started to fluster the Pacers all over again. Just his presence on
the floor seemed to rattle them.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers had no answer for Camby, who took a missed layup by
Latrell Sprewell and put it back in to tie the score at 51-51 with
4:20 left in the third. Houston was also on fire, taking it upon
himself to score around the struggling Miller and fill the
offensive void left by Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, some way, the Knicks were doing what they have done the
entire series. They were hanging close. In Games 1, 3 and 5, they
kept within striking range and ended up winning as the Pacers fell
apart in the final two minutes. They were doing better than that
against a tentative opponent that could not seize the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   With Houston scoring nine points and Camby coming up with plays
on defense, the Knicks were tied with the Pacers after the third,
59-59.
</P>
<P>
   It took a quarter, but the early jitters that seemed to grip the
Knicks at the beginning of the night disappeared in a hurry. There
was so much riding on this game for the Knicks _ vindication for
Sprewell and Camby and for a team many doubted, a $3.5 million
contract extension for Van Gundy as a reward, and the need to close
out the Pacers without having to travel back to Indiana _ it was
almost understandable for the players to be tight at the outset.
</P>
<P>
   As off as Miller was, so was Sprewell, who shot 3 for 12 in the
first half. But after Sprewell botched plays and even lost a ball
off his foot on a fast break, after Houston and Sprewell hit just
three of their first 21 shots, the Knicks were able to force a
couple of turnovers and get a few fast-break points to gain a head
of steam to pull within three, 17-14, after the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   That momentum rocked the Pacers. The Knicks started the second
by leaning on Johnson in the post and went on a 10-1 run while the
Pacers were turning the ball over and committing fouls. Houston
seemed to feed off Camby's energy and ended the first half with 14
points after starting 1 for 7. Johnson also started to play well
with Camby beside him until his knee gave way beneath Best in a
sober moment in the second quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-99 0102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
