<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2743 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KNICKS-PACERS-RHODEN-     06-12 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KNICKS-PACERS-RHODEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THIS DRAMA HAS ONLY ONE HERO 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Few events can reduce New York to small-town
giddiness, but these new Knicks have broken through the
sophisticated veneer of the city and shrunk it to a quaint village
mad about its local team. Now, with a 90-82 victory Friday night,
the team is Eastern Conference champion, and this cool city known
for its aloofness is going absolutely wild.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks continue to play out an improbable drama that
playwrights wouldn't have dared to craft: disparate players led
through the wilderness by an aging star who, like Moses, collapses
with the Promised Land just in view. The team is carried on the
shoulders of two vilified players, and all this transpires in the
context of a front office feud with players cleverly used as pawns
and shields by an underdog coach hanging on to his job by a thread.
</P>
<P>
   Then a critical game is won on a miracle shot after the whistle.
Friday night, Larry Johnson, who had hit that shot, was injured,
yet that simply heightened the drama of the Knicks' Game 6 victory.
</P>
<P>
   This Knicks' season is an improvised script in progress,
collectively written by journalists, who have taken turns
fashioning characters and developing story lines. With each new
scene, the plot thickens even as it becomes more elastic, more
intricate, each new scene more bizarre than the last. Now the magic
ride continues; the Knicks begin the championship series in San
Antonio on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Now the time has come to name the hero of this drama. Suddenly
this fluid script-by-committee has hit a snag. Latrell Sprewell _
who scored 20 points last night _ is the hero; the dilemma is, how
can the character so positively cast as the villain end up as the
hero?
</P>
<P>
   He can't. So Marcus Camby, the young dynamo off the bench, has
become the leading light. This, in itself, is a wild twist. Camby
was maligned last summer and for most of the season by the very
people who now sing his praises since he has played like a demon in
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell was _ and still is _ a political prisoner whose style,
attitude and baggage make a lot of people nervous. From the time
Sprewell made national news a year and a half ago for attacking his
coach, until January when he held an introductory news conference
in Rye, N.Y., there has been resistance and ambivalence, from the
coach and from many who tell the story of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell attacked his coach; Sprewell boycotted practice after a
popular teammate was traded; Sprewell used a racial epithet against
Oakland police officers who he felt stopped him because he is black
_ this two years before racial profiling by the police became a
national issue.
</P>
<P>
   But anyone who steps away from the passion of the moment and
looks at this season clearly must concede that Sprewell has
provided phenomenal energy and in stretches has been an
extraordinary player.
</P>
<P>
   To a team that often looked over its shoulder and was overtaken
by what was gaining, Sprewell introduced a relentless attack,
stamina and endurance, physically and psychologically. Sprewell,
kept in check by the Pacers' long arms and long bodies for much of
the game, still managed to score six of the Knicks' final 10 points
when the game was on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell has transformed the Knicks into an aggressive,
offense-oriented team that no longer frets about how to stop the
opposition, but makes the opposition fret about how to stop the
Knicks in transition.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell even put pressure on the coaching staff, not simply to
put him into the starting lineup but also to let the team evolve
into what it naturally is. As the coach grew increasingly dependent
on Sprewell's energy, and as his own job status became precarious,
Van Gundy let go.
</P>
<P>
   And he is still learning how to let go. Van Gundy started Camby
in the second half of Game 3 and started Sprewell for Game 4 and
stuck with him in Game 5. With Grunfeld safely out of the way, Van
Gundy's moves are like the last-second confession that comes too
late to save the death row inmate.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 4 on Monday, Sprewell was dismally out of sync in his
first start in months. Camby played great, but the Knicks lost. The
critics were swift and predictably knee jerk: Sprewell plays no
defense; he allowed the savvy Chris Mullin to roast him; he's good
only in transition; put him back on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 5, Sprewell scored 29 points and reduced Mullin to
putty. The spin was that the coach is a genius and Camby is the
hero and Sprewell gained redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the coach is beginning to look like a genius and Camby is
playing heroically.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake: Sprewell is the hero of this drama. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
