   NATIONAL _ GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `w' category)
</P>
<P>
   NRA-WOES (Washington) _ After years of struggling with debt,
rebellions within its ranks and declining membership and revenues,
the NRA finds itself under attack on many fronts, from Congress to
the courts. Despite its internal woes, the NRA has been lavishing
large campaign contributions on its lawmaker allies at the federal
and state levels.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-CONTROL (Washington) _ House Republicans and Democrats began
to file more than 200 amendments Friday to a juvenile crime bill
that has become a vehicle for the kind of modest but bitterly
divisive gun-control measures that the Senate approved in May. By
Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-TESTING (Washington) _ The Education Department's draft of
recommendations on how schools can avoid discrimination suits if
standardized tests such as the SATs, produce racially disparate
results has drawn the ire of conservatives. Critics claim that in
proferring the advice, the Department is telling schools not to use
such tests at all. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POLITICS (Washington) _ President Clinton said Friday
night in a PBS interview that Republicans opposed his policies
because they were frustrated that a Democrat had won the White
House and taken up all of its perks, like parking spaces, and he
suggested that they `lighten up.' By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-ADMISSIONS (Undated) _ The signs have been evident for
several months: top high school seniors rejected by colleges of
their choice, second-tier institutions overwhelmed with excellent
applications, state universities raising admission requirements.
Now, interviews with scores of college and school officials and
preliminary statistics, appear to confirm what stunned high school
seniors and their parents suspect: that the college application
season just ended was the most competitive in the nation's history.
By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   ANGELES-CALLGIRLS (Los Angeles) _ Police say they have busted
one of the most elaborate call girl rings since they cracked the
case of the `Hollywood Madam,' Heidi Fleiss, six years ago. Jody
Diane `Babydol' Gibson, reported to be a former competitor of
Fleiss, was arrested Tuesday after a 10-month investigation. By
James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   PETS-MICROCHIPS (Woodinville, Wash.) _ A look at the use of
microchips in pet collars, designed to identify animals and locate
them when they are lost. 10 years ago, the Marin Humane Society in
Northern California became the first shelter in the country to
implant the chips in all animals put up for adoption. Since then,
the technology has reunited more than 1,000 pets with their owners.
The practice has taken off in recent years, as the three big
manufacturers have tried to overcome proprietary squabbles and move
toward an industry standard, and as many humane societies and
veterinarians have urged pet owners to implant their pets with the
ID devices. By Sam Howe Verhovek. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-LA-SUBWAY (Los Angeles) _ For a brief moment Friday
morning, the cream of the Los Angeles political establishment could
be found deep underground, doing something that residents of this
sprawling, car-crazed city hardly ever do: riding the subway. And
not just any subway, but the five spanking new stops under
Hollywood that, after two decades of striving, setbacks and
billions of dollars, have finally brought the system to just over
11 miles of underground track. By Todd S. Purdum. WITH PHOTO and
MAP.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO-SCOTUS-REACT (Chicago) _ A day after the Supreme Court
struck down a Chicago law that banned loitering by suspected gang
members, people in the affected neighborhoods felt frustrated, yet
were understanding of the court's constitutional concerns.
</P>
<P>
   BINLADEN-PROBE (New York) _ Two Muslim men from Texas have been
subpoenaed to testify next week before a federal grand jury in
Manhattan investigating Osama bin Laden, who is a suspect in the
U.S. embassy bombings in Africa last year and other terrorist acts.
By Benjamin Weiser.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TROOPS (Blace, Macedonia) _ NATO troops entered Kosovo on
Saturday as dawn broke, hours after NATO was confounded by Russia's
surprise entry into Pristina, the capital, which the allied forces
plan to make their headquarters for returning a million local
Albanians to their homes. By John Kifner. WITH PHOTOS (sent as
KOSOVO-FORCE)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA-TROOPS (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ Breaking
assurances given to Washington, Russian troops entered Kosovo and
its capital early Saturday morning amid scenes of wild celebration
by local Serbs. The Russians continued on to the suburb of Kosovo
Polje. Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said the advance, hours
before NATO peacekeepers were to have entered the Serbian province,
was a mistake. By Steven Erlanger. WITH MAP.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-REACT (Washington) _ The White House was stunned and
bewildered to learn that Russian troops had rolled into Pristina,
after receiving assurances from Moscow all day that its troops
would not move in until NATO had given them a green light. By
Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ The entry of Russian troops in Kosovo
raises disturbing questions about the Kremlin's control of its
military. Following NATO's air raids on Yugoslavia, senior Russian
military officials increasingly seem to have had their own foreign
policy. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Whiteman AFB, Mo.) _ President Clinton came to
the home of the B-2 stealth bomber to extol American air power
Friday, but he devoted as much of his speech to praising
American-style race relations, asserting that NATO's victory in
Kosovo had been one of ethnic diversity over `ethnic cleansing.' By
James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBRIGHT (Skopje, Macedonia) _ Madeleine Albright, who
had made the return of the ethnic Albanian refugees the major
mission of the Kosovo war, met face to face with them for the first
time Friday. She hugged some of them, shook hands, and as she
passed along a rope line holding back exuberant crowds, shouted:
`You'll be going home.' By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Kukes, Albania) _ The scene from the Albanian
border where planning continues for what is expected to be the
chaotic re-entry of refugees to their homes and villages. By Ian
Fisher. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBIA (Gniljane, Yugoslavia) _ A scene-stter from the
town where the U.S. peacekeeping forces will be based. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   POLAND-POPE (Warsaw) _ Pope John Paul II pays tribute to Polish
Jews who died in the Holocaust and addresses Parliament. Earlier,
at a reception broadcast on Polish national television, the chief
rabbi of Poland refers to John Paul II as `Mr. Pope' and asks him
to take down the last cross at Auschwitz. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-WARSHIPS (Tokyo) _ South Korean patrol boats bumped three
North Korean vessels Friday, forcing them out of disputed waters on
the fourth day of a tense armed standoff. After retreating, four
North Korean warships sailed back into the disputed zone,
confronting eight South Korean navy ships, South Korea's defense
ministry said. By Nicholas Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-LIBYA (United Nations) _ In their first official meeting in
18 years, the U.S. States told Libya that it would not support the
complete lifting of sanctions until Libya stopped supporting
international terrorism and met other conditions required by U.N.
resolutions. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-SUKARNO (Jakarta) _ The ghost of Sukarno has hung
heavily over Indonesia this week, as the country held its first
democratic elections in more than four decades. The party of
Sukarno's 52-year-old daughter, Megawati Sukarnoputri, seems headed
for a clear victory in the parliamentary vote _ raising the
possibility another Sukarno may be the next leader of Indonesia. By
Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   BEIRUT-BEACHES (Beirut) _ Before the civil war, Beirut was known
as the Paris of the Middle East. In some ways, it still deserves
its slightly libertine reputation. But, particularly in mostly
Muslim West Beirut, that culture has always been overlaid by more
conservative strands, including ideas about what should and not be
seen when it comes to female flesh. Thus, there is segregation on
the sexes on Beirut's famed beaches. By Douglas Jehl. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
