<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN FAILED TO LURE JOHNSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ They hugged each other during batting practice
Friday afternoon, something the Anaheim Angels would have liked to
see more often this season.
</P>
<P>
   But unfortunately for the Angels, Mo Vaughn and Randy Johnson
are not teammates. After the Angels signed Vaughn to a six-year,
$80 million deal Nov. 25, they pursued Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson reportedly chose the Angels only to change his mind and
sign a four-year, $53 million with the Diamondbacks, despite the
efforts of Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn and Johnson developed a friendship when Vaughn played in
Boston and Johnson in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the type of player he is and what he means to a
ballclub, Vaughn said. ``I tried to get him to come here, but
sometimes family is more important.
</P>
<P>
   So just how did Johnson, who lives in Paradise Valley, a suburb
of Phoenix, and Vaughn become friends?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I'm the only left-hander that faces him, Vaughn said.
``It's a little thing we got going. It takes a certain attitude
(for a left-handed hitter) to stand in there against him. You have
to respect him because he's so tough, so nasty. We became friends
because I never backed away.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were in Boston or Seattle, he always looked over and
tipped his cap out of respect. He's the toughest in the business.
When I did face him it settled me down for the rest of the season.
Because after you faced him, you could walk up there with
confidence against anybody.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Help could soon be on the way for the Angels, though it's not
quite what they've been waiting for.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Salmon and Jim Edmonds still have a ways to go until they
are healthy enough to play, but the Angels might get some
desperately needed punch in the lineup from Matt Luke, who began
playing at triple-A Edmonton earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   In five games through Thursday, Luke is 9-for-18 with five
homers and 15 RBIs. He hadn't played since spring training because
of a strained back, an injury he sustained lifting weights during
the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got great power, but we've got to find out how healthy he
is, manager Terry Collins said. ``He's been out two months, we've
got to make sure he's OK.
</P>
<P>
   Luke spent most of last season with the Dodgers, hitting .236
with 12 homers and 34 RBIs in 102 games.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Gary DiSarcina played four innings for single-A Lake
Elsinore on Friday night, going 0 for 3 at the plate and making one
putout and one assist on defense. In two games for the Storm,
DiSarcina is 1 for 4 with a walk. He is expected to DH
tonight. &UR; !dlim!!end! &LR;  &QL; 
--
</P>
<P>
   Marcel Lachemann, formerly the Angels pitching coach and
currently the organization's minor league field coordinator, has
been named pitching coach for the USA Pan Am Games baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   Lachemann was named as a replacement for Dave Wallace, who was
named the pitching coach of the Mets last week.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   The Angels and Diamondbacks play the second game of their
three-game series tonight beginning at 7:05. Chuck Finley (4-6,
4.35 ERA) will start for Anaheim against Arizona's Andy Benes (4-5,
5.40).
</P>
</TEXT>
