<SLUG> BC-BABYDOLL-ARREST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BABY DOLL' LIVED MODESTLY WHILE IN L.A., POLICE SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- As the brains behind a call-girl empire for the
rich and famous from Los Angeles to Europe, Jody ``Baby Doll''
Gibson could have afforded to stay just about anywhere, police say.
</P>
<P>
   She chose a $100-a-night hotel room in the Van Nuys in L.A.'s
San Fernando Valley, and she always made sure to use her AAA card
for the 10 percent discount.
</P>
<P>
   It is this picture of modest living that began to emerge Friday,
a day after police announced her arrest on suspicion of running the
largest prostitution ring since ``Hollywood Madam'' Heidi Fleiss'.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives say she pimped for 34 girls in 16 states and at least
six more in Europe, with a client list that included Hollywood
actors, Fortune 500 executives and even a professional athlete.
They paid from $500 to $3,000 per night or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are no Joe Blow actors. They're people who are known,''
said Los Angeles police Lt. Mike Felix.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, investigators pored over the lists and later attended
an adult entertainment convention at the Los Angeles Convention
Center in hopes of finding pornographic actresses believed to be
have worked for Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they'll be buzzing about Gibson's operation,'' Felix
said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives said she did most of her business by mail, the
Internet and phone. She used mail drops in Toluca Lake and Blythe,
near her home in Palo Verde, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   And when in Los Angeles, she stayed at the Airtel Plaza Hotel in
Van Nuys two to three days a month, said hotel spokesman Jack
McGrath.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in business attire, Gibson blended in with other
business people and families at the hotel next to Van Nuys Airport,
McGrath said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't look flashy or grungy,'' McGrath said.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson began frequenting the hotel at the beginning of 1998 and
last stayed there Tuesday night, always paying her bill with an
American Express card and using her own credit cards for phone
calls, McGrath said.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel staff never reported any problems or unusual traffic
to Gibson's room, McGrath said. ``We never saw her with anybody
else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're surprised that this allegedly was going on. It certainly
was a big surprise because this guest never gave an appearance that
she was in this sort of business,'' McGrath said.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, whose driver's license identifies her as Jody Babydol
Diane Gibson, lives in Palo Verde, a small retirement village on
the California-Arizona border and hard beside the Colorado River.
</P>
<P>
   Several people there who regularly ran into the blonde said
heads would turn on the street to admire her beauty.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta look at her. She's sexy. She'd go into the post
office and she'd say hello. Sometimes, she'd order a
double-espresso and baklava,'' said a restaurant owner who declined
to give his name.
</P>
<P>
   Her neighbors said they wondered about the mysterious woman who
turned heads when she drove by in her teal Mercedes-Benz.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a very beautiful woman. She's the kind of person you
just can't take your eyes off of,'' said Jeanette Hyduke, a real
estate agent for Palo Verde Land. ``Even though she's a woman,
women would turn their heads. She's really quite stunning.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyduke said Gibson has lived over a year in a ``little red
fishing cabin'' with a front porch that overlooks a lagoon. She
also has a ``huge black dog in front of her yard.''
</P>
<P>
   But police say she had a secret: Sometimes using the alias
``Sasha,'' she had run a thriving hooker ring since at least the
late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson was booked at the Van Nuys jail and was released on
$25,000 bail. She is scheduled to be arraigned at the West Los
Angeles Courthouse on June 29, detectives said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
