<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLAST-VICTIMS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOWN, TWO SCHOOLS LEFT REELING AFTER DEATHS OF THREE YOUTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KIMBERY A.C. WILSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLINGHAM, Wash. _ With only one day of classes remaining in
the school year, Friday should have been a day of sunny field trips
and lighthearted yearbook signing at two Bellingham schools.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, teachers and students at Roosevelt Elementary cried
over the deaths of two 10-year-old classmates killed in the
Thursday afternoon pipeline explosion in Whatcom State Park. Across
town at a high school still reeling from three student deaths in
March, Sehome students mourned a newly graduated senior killed in
the same blast.
</P>
<P>
   Outside both schools and across the Bellingham School District,
flags were lowered to half staff in memory of 10-year-olds Wade
King and Stephen Tsiorvas and Class of '99 graduate, Liam Wood. All
three died of burns sustained in the explosion and fire in this
city of 60,000 about 90 miles north of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody feels the loss so keenly I don't know if we'll see
any game faces today,'' said Bill Attebery, director of the crisis
response team that descended on Roosevelt Elementary early Friday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two dozen grief counselors, substitute teachers and
volunteers gathered nearly an hour before students arrived.
</P>
<P>
   While the teachers and students mourned two well-liked,
``high-energy boys,'' wisps of brown smoke still smudged the
cloudless blue sky over the nearby state park. The two friends died
while playing in Whatcom Creek, where the fire raced after the
pipeline exploded. Wood apparently died while fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Principal Stephanie Sadler, who began her morning greeting
crying teachers, later comforted children devastated by the loss of
two classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being hit by a 2x4,'' she said, wiping her face, as
yellow school buses began dropping off students, many of whom fell
into the arms of waiting adults.
</P>
<P>
   Many students and parents, who had learned almost as soon as
they woke up Friday that Wade had died overnight, learned as they
arrived at school that Stephen also had died.
</P>
<P>
   Outside in the parking lot, a father and daughter sat on the
tailgate of the family pickup truck. Dad sipped coffee from a mug,
trying to explain death at a young age to his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they said just one of them had died,'' the girl wailed.
When the school bell chimed, the pair were still sitting there. One
asking, the other searching for elusive answers.
</P>
<P>
   Many parents accompanied their children into the school. Some
arrived late, to find the usual tardy slip replaced by a warm hug.
</P>
<P>
   One young mother reined in her emotions as she walked her
daughter into school. After she learned that the second of the two
boys had died, she broke down in tears.
</P>
<P>
   Both Wade King and Stephen Tsiorvas were ``very athletic, high
energy kids'' who brought home good marks, charmed their teachers
and made friends easily, Sadler, the principal, said.
</P>
<P>
   Wade, who received an orange and black, ``trick'' bike from his
parents when he celebrated his 10th birthday only six days before
his death, was remembered at the only school he'd ever attended as
``a spirited little boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime family friend and neighbor Nancy Cooley, whom Wade
referred to as ``Aunt Nancy,'' spoke sadly of a Dairy Queen sundae
she was keeping in her freezer for Wade. She'd bought it to
celebrate his birthday, but he'd been so busy with baseball
practice that he hadn't had time to eat it yet.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Jack, described Wade as ``having a smile that loved
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents Mary and Frank King, older brother Jason and older
sister Traci are ``doing OK,'' Nancy Cooley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard, but we're trying to make them strong,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler, who had known Wade since kindergarten, said Wade was
``the kind of boy who would get himself into something, but he'd
just make you laugh. He had such a joy.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen, who would have turned 11 this summer, was likewise
remembered by his school principal as a little boy who loved life.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Wade and Stephen do something, they do it with every
heart and soul,'' she explained. ``Both of them, they were kids who
played hard: basketball, soccer, running ... doing what kids are
supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Across town on the sprawling Sehome campus where Liam Wood
completed senior exams last week, students remembered him as a
talented musician.
</P>
<P>
   Wood played violin in the school's advanced orchestra and won
over classmates and teachers with a ready laugh and easy nature. In
a handful of yearbook pictures, a smiling Wood is recognizable by
the deep dimple in his left cheek.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow violinist Lauren Beven, a junior, said Liam was an avid
fisherman and rock-climber.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's good that he was doing what he loved when he
died,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sehome, with a student body of 1,700, is still mourning the loss
of three other students killed earlier in the school year. The
teens, three 17-year-old boys in the school's junior class, were
killed in a highway collision in late March.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a tough situation,'' Principal Larry Brown said.
``This school has dealt with death and dying too much this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
