<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRADUATION-SPEAKER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLAUSE, AND WALKOUTS, FOR COLLEGE REMARKS BY CONVICTED KILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JACK HOPKINS  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLYMPIA, Wash. _ The Evergreen State College's graduating class
politely applauded Maureen Faulkner Friday and then whooped,
cheered and gave a standing ovation to the man convicted of
murdering her policeman-husband.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a dozen seniors walked out of their own graduation
ceremony in protest of the controversial decision to invite Mumia
Abu-Jamal to give a tape-recorded address from his death row cell
in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a dozen more _ one of them a police officer who took off
his green graduation gown to reveal his law enforcement uniform
underneath _ stood and symbolically turned their backs to the
podium and bowed their heads in protest.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the nearly 900 members of the graduating class
overwhelmingly rejected Faulkner's request that they walk out of
the ceremony during the playing of Abu-Jamal's tape during
commencement on the tree-lined campus near Olympia.
</P>
<P>
   Evergreen President Jane Jervis mentioned Faulkner's presence
during opening remarks to students and guests attending the 28th
annual ceremony. That was what sparked the restrained applause for
the Philadelphia woman.
</P>
<P>
   Jervis, who has come under fire from some state legislators and
the law enforcement community for allowing the Abu-Jamal tape,
defended the college's decision to permit the convicted killer to
take part in the ceremony in absentia.
</P>
<P>
   The college often invites controversial people to speak, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not to agree with, to endorse or to glorify the
speaker,'' Jervis said. ``But if we listen only to those we agree
with, we may only speak with ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner, who asked college officials if she could be added to
the list of speakers after learning of Abu-Jamal's taped message,
was not allowed to address the students.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't satisfy Faulkner, whose husband, Daniel, was killed
while on duty on Dec. 9, 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very sad day that I have to be here and I feel very
sorry for the students,'' said Faulkner, who stood on the sidewalk
a short distance away from the graduation ceremony, holding a sign
that said Abu-Jamal had murdered her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Four people testified during Abu-Jamal's trial that they saw the
black man shoot the white officer at close range. The gun that was
used to kill the officer was registered to Abu-Jamal, who was
arrested at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Abu-Jamal has been on death row since 1982. No execution date
has been set. He is appealing to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Abu-Jamal's jailhouse writings about the justice system _ and
efforts to win a new trial _ have given him worldwide attention. A
symbol for death penalty opponents, Abu-Jamal wants a new trial on
grounds that the prosecution withheld evidence, the judge was
biased and his defense counsel was ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Maureen Faulkner accused college officials of being
``irresponsible'' in allowing the playing of Abu-Jamal's tape and
said she should have been given equal time to tell graduating
students about the impact the killing had on her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over 17 years ago, Jamal silenced my husband. ... His life was
snuffed out. What about his voice?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Campus police officers walked up to her as she spoke to
bystanders, police officers and the media. They gave her carnations
and expressed their support.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of placard-carrying demonstrators from both sides were
present for the ceremony and heard Abu-Jamal's plea for the
students to become revolutionaries and fight injustice.
</P>
<P>
   In the 12-minute tape, Abu-Jamal said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Why was it right for people to revolt against the British
because of taxation without representation and somehow wrong for
truly unrepresented Africans in America to revolt against America?
</P>
<P>
   ``For any repressed people, revolution, according to the
Declaration of Independence, is a right.''
</P>
<P>
   He later added: ``Live lives of opposition to the deadening
status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   Students had their choice of wearing yellow ribbons to show
support for Abu-Jamal or blue ribbons to show support for
law-enforcement officers when they arrived for the ceremony under
brilliant sunshine, blue skies and storm clouds of controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those who chose ribbons went for the yellow ones.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Abu-Jamal supporters was new graduate Stephanie
Guilloud, who was a member of the student committee that chose
Abu-Jamal as one of its speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Abu-Jamal was an appropriate speaker, she said, because he
raised public consciousness of the disparate treatment given to
minorities in the criminal justice system and other important
social issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an unprecedented opportunity to hear a censored and
silenced voice,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But not all students agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am against the tape being played,'' said Ripp Campbell of
Shelton, who received her bachelor's degree Friday. ``This is just
not the forum. And on a personal level, my mother was murdered on
the streets of New York. This is a day that I should be happy. But
the day is being tainted by this controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gary Locke was the students' first choice to give the
keynote address at the commencement ceremony. But he bowed out when
he heard Abu-Jamal would be part of the program. The college
replaced him with a popular faculty member, Stephanie Coontz.
</P>
<P>
   Art Costantino, the college's vice president for student
affairs, said before the ceremony that Evergreen has taken heat
from a few of its donors because of the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had some donors writing or e-mailing us, saying they
would no longer be supporting the college,'' he said. The amount
lost has totaled ``probably a couple of thousand dollars. At this
point it hasn't been a major problem for us. But we do not like to
lose even one friend of the college,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
