<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2761 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLAST-ENVIRONMENT-SPI     06-12 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLAST-ENVIRONMENT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENVIRONMENTALISTS BEGIN SIZING UP NATURAL TOLL OF FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HEATH FOSTER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLINGHAM, Wash. _ Two days ago, the sloping banks of Whatcom
Creek were lush with ferns and huckleberry bushes. Willowy alders
and thick old cedars and Douglas firs shaded its cold, rushing
water well-populated with fish in their early stages of life _
resident cutthroat and rainbow trout, kokanee, coho salmon and even
lamprey eels.
</P>
<P>
   But the gasoline-fueled fire that raced furiously down a
mile-and-a-half of this popular city greenway Thursday obliterated
almost everything it touched.
</P>
<P>
   Spill response crews from the state Department of Ecology and
the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency didn't begin assessing the
extent of the biological and environmental damage until late
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But they could confirm that fish hadn't fared well in the
inferno.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hearing from some of our biologists that the water got to
lethal temperatures, in the 80s and perhaps even higher,'' said
Gene Tillett, manager of the hatcheries division for the state
Department of Fish and Wildlife. ``That is way too hot for salmon,
and really too hot for most fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Tillett said if a complete kill of the fish is confirmed, the
creek would likely see some years with depressed runs of trout and
salmon species in the future. And with the disappearance of the
vegetation that has kept the stream's water cold, fish species
could struggle over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   On a walk along a half-mile of the singed creek side Friday,
hundreds of salmon fry, most likely juvenile coho and chinook, were
floating blackened in the water. Every tree in sight was charred
and leafless, and the creek's rock outcroppings looked as if they
had been spray-painted black. The industrial smell of gasoline,
like plastic melting on an open fire, hung in the air and was acid
on the tongue.
</P>
<P>
   And the creek was strangely silent; there were no birds calling
in the morning sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just feels horrible that this beautiful area has been
altered like this,'' said Crina Hoyer, an educator with ReSources,
a Whatcom County environmental group.
</P>
<P>
   Merle Jefferson, the natural resource director for the Lummi
Indian Nation, estimated Friday that it will take the scorched area
three to four years to recover most of its basic vegetation.
</P>
<P>
   The Lummi's 13,000-acre reservation is about seven miles
southwest of the creek. Jefferson spent most of his day worrying
that gasoline from the spill might affect the tribe's vast oyster
and manila clam beds off the shore of the reservation in Bellingham
Bay. But a flight over the bay found that the gasoline didn't
appear to have come close to the beds. The tribe is planning tests
of newly harvested shellfish over the weekend to confirm the beds
have not been contaminated, Jefferson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We walked along the beaches of the reservation this morning,
but so far we haven't gotten any effects from the (explosion),'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But given his tribe's dependence on income from shellfishing,
Jefferson said he was furious the flow of gasoline wasn't checked
more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have got to be more safeguards and engineering put to
into this system, because this was uncalled for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the city's water supply was not contaminated by the
gasoline spill, said Tony Seman, the utilities superintendent for
water distribution at the Bellingham Public Works Departments. He
said the explosion did not affect the pipelines that bring water
from Lake Whatcom to 70,000 customers. It did however, blow out
five pumps near the creek, which left about 6,000 households in
nearby neighborhoods on strict orders to conserve water. Seman said
three of the five pumps should be operational again by Monday. But
over the weekend, he was urging all city residents to conserve
water.
</P>
<P>
   Post-Intelligencer reporter Judd Slivka contributed to this
story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
