<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2764 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      06-12 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO'S BEST NO ISSUE BETWEEN GRIFFEY, BONDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The career arcs of Ken Griffey Jr. and Barry Bonds
crossed again Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   One going up.
</P>
<P>
   One going down.
</P>
<P>
   There was no Kingdome collision to speak of, just a little 7-3
interleague win over the San Francisco Giants. But the intersection
has been made.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's best players in the final decade of the millennium
are still at the top of their games, so distinctions are not
obvious.
</P>
<P>
   But Bonds, 35 next month, is two days off elbow surgery that
cost him 47 games. Griffey, 29, is leading the majors in home runs,
near a career best in batting average and still smothers more
fields than a Redmond software monopolist.
</P>
<P>
   About the only way Griffey and Bonds can be divided is by the
calendar, baseball's most relentless, consistent player.
</P>
<P>
   Asked before the game where he was in his career at 29, Bonds
said, ``Well, in '90 I was MVP, in '92 I was MVP. In '93, there was
another one.''
</P>
<P>
   It's Bonds' favorite exposition on his career, since only seven
other players in history can make such a claim, none of whom are
active.
</P>
<P>
   But the honors occurred at the front end of the decade. In a
culture where yesterday qualifies as ancient history, Bonds'
greatness is seen by the attention-span-challenged as prehistoric.
</P>
<P>
   As Bonds put it, ``Things have died down a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, the '97 American League MVP, is putting up the kind of
season that could leave him trailing Bonds by one in major personal
hardware. The competition might make for a nice little rivalry.
Except that they aren't in the same league, aren't quite the same
age, and they've completely screwed it up by enjoying each other's
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took me out to dinner when I was 17,'' Griffey said of
their first meeting. ``I think it was his rookie year. We just
talked family. We don't talk much baseball. Just like now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll call him a few times in the offseason, sometimes write
him letters. Family's always the main topic, but I do get on him
about his golf game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't right now because he's got a bad elbow.''
</P>
<P>
   As sons of major league stars of the same era, the talk is
unlike any they can have with other friends.
</P>
<P>
   The offspring of baseball history are busy making their own. In
the arcane category of best father-son hitters in major league
annals, Bobby (332) and Barry (415) Bonds are first with 747, which
is 222 ahead of runners-up Griffey Senior (152) and Junior (373).
</P>
<P>
   Health permitting, Griffey may have up to a decade more to run
down the Bondses. To hear Barry tell it, Griffey will have a much
better chance of he stays in the AL, for a reason few but Bonds
might appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walks,'' he said. ``If he were in the National League, he'd
walk so much more, he'd be bored. It's something every good
National League hitter will go through _ McGwire, Sosa, Sheffield,
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you walk 150 times, you miss out on a lot of
oppportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonds last year had 130 walks, and had a career high of 151 in
'96. In fact, Bonds has never had an injury-free year since '91 in
which he has walked less than 107 times.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's high was 96 in 1993, and he hasn't had more than 78
thereafter, including 76.
</P>
<P>
   It happened again Friday, when the only two walks given up in an
otherwise solid game by Mariner starter Jamie Moyer were to Bonds.
Even after the long layoff, Bonds remains the Giants' most
dangerous hitter on a team that entered Friday night 13th in NL
team batting average.
</P>
<P>
   As most seamheaded schoolchildren know, Griffey cannot be
pitched around, not with Edgar Martinez (.317) and Butch Huskey
(.359) backing him with heavy cannon.
</P>
<P>
   There's also one other thing that doesn't happen with Griffey,
in the opinion of the first player to reach a career 400 in stolen
bases and home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't steal bases,'' Bonds said. ``That's the only thing
he doesn't do. But in the American League, he doesn't have to. They
don't manufacture as many runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Might have been different if I hadn't worn myself down by base
stealing.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Griffey stole a career high 20 last year, just eight less
than Bonds. Of course, Bonds would suggest that he was also worn
down by playing left field in Candlestick Park, where the wind does
to fly balls what kittens do to yarn balls.
</P>
<P>
   Said the seven-time Gold Glove winner: ``I've always said if you
can play left field there, you can play anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey would counter that Bonds hasn't lived until he's played
center field behind the Mariner pitching staff, which can be akin
to running a marathon a week. And the running must be done on the
Kingdome surface, which is slightly harder than a Randy Johnson
stare.
</P>
<P>
   But wait. This kind of back and forth sounds like the vague
outlines of a rivalry. It's the sort of thing that can lead to
discussion about who owns this baseball decade, about who is
ascending and who is descending. About whose daddy was better.
</P>
<P>
   We'll certainly have none of that kind of talk around here.
</P>
<P>
   At least, not after this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
