r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-DODGERS-ATHLETICS     06-12 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGERS-ATHLETICS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS ROUTED BY A'S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ In a season of ugly for Los Angeles Dodgers
left-hander Carlos Perez, this was Medusa.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, twice yanked from starts before finishing the fourth
inning, couldn't make it out of the third this time.
</P>
<P>
   He was bombarded for a season-high eight runs in 21/3 innings as
the Dodgers were defeated by the Oakland Athletics 12-6 at the
Oakland Coliseum on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland shortstop Miguel Tejada hit three homers and drove in a
career-high five runs. He hit two-run homers off Perez and Onan
Masaoka and a solo shot off Doug Bochtler in the seventh. It was
the first multihomer game of Tejada's career.
</P>
<P>
   Perez's quick unraveling came a few hours after Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson talked for the umpteenth time about what he'd like
from Perez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see him start pitching with confidence, go after
guys a little bit more,'' Johnson said. ``He's really not the kind
of pitcher who should go five or six pitches on a hitter. Either
they hit it or they don't. That kind of pitcher should be
pitch-efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Ummm, pitch-efficient? Like 79 pitches to record seven outs. Or
one out every 11.3 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   All eight runs were earned off Perez. He gave up six hits and
walked four. It was the fifth time this season he's given up at
least six earned runs and in his last two starts he's allowed 15
earned runs in nine innings. The A's knocked him out during a
six-run third inning, capped by Tejada's second homer.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros homered for the second
straight game, though it didn't seem to matter. His two-run shot
came in the sixth with the Dodgers trailing 9-1. The Dodgers added
three more runs in the seventh inning on Jose Vizcaino's three-run
double to pull within 9-6.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Perez came through with nothing and left little but sheer
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   The next thing to wonder about Perez isn't how he'll perform in
his next scheduled start, which is Wednesday against Pittsburgh,
but if he'll make the start. The Dodgers don't have many options in
the way of other starters, but right-hander Jamie Arnold did throw
61/3 innings of one-hit ball in his only start this season.
</P>
<P>
   Perez was well on his way to his eighth loss in 10 decisions.
His already astronomic ERA is now out of the universe and is light
years away from respectability at 7.18. It's the highest among
starters in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   Perez began down that path in the first inning against the
Dodgers. He walked leadoff man Tony Phillips on five pitches and
Tejada then hit a 1-1 pitch into the second deck in left field to
give the A's a 2-0 lead before Perez recorded an out.
</P>
<P>
   The A's began the third inning with a walk to Matt Stairs and
Olmedo Saenz singled. Grieve struck out, but Mike MacFarlane
doubled inside third base to score two. Ryan Christenson then hit
Perez's next pitch over the left-field fence to give the A's a 7-1
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Only then did the Dodgers' bullpen get busy and after Perez
walked Phillips _ his third plate appearance in three innings _
Johnson lifted him in favor of Onan Masaoka. And the left-hander
allowed a two-run homer to Tejada as Oakland went ahead 9-1.
</P>
<P>
   Karros hit his ninth homer of the season in the sixth before the
Dodgers took a significant chunk out of the lead in the seventh on
Vizcaino's three-run double off reliever Tim Worrell to make it
9-6.
</P>
</TEXT>
