<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A-ROD JUST `85 PERCENT' DESPITE MONSTER MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ They passed around cake in the Seattle clubhouse
before Friday night's game, a thank you for the previous day's
charity function.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Mariners needed another reason to partake in this
high-caloric endeavor, they could have celebrated Alex Rodriguez's
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   It was one month ago Friday night that the All-Star shortstop
came off the disabled list, returning from arthroscopic knee
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   And what a month it was.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Friday night's interleague series opener against San
Francisco, Rodriguez was hitting .360 with 10 home runs and 20
RBIs, with his entire offensive outburst coming in a 30-day span. A
Hall of Fame month.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, Rodriguez insists he's still not himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I'm not 100 percent, but I'm still on the right
track to be 100 percent right after the All-Star break,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If not completely healed, what then?
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty-five percent. You can't ignore the fact that I just had
knee surgery,'' Rodriguez responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did he say 185 percent?'' third baseman Russ Davis said.
``Could have fooled me.''
</P>
<P>
   With the knee under repair, Rodriguez says he's still missing
speed and explosiveness. He feels somewhat limited defensively,
either chasing balls into the hole at short or up the middle. He
doesn't expect to steal 40 bases this season either (he has four).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a lot of room for improvement,'' he said. ``I
still think I can still keep getting better. But I've had a pretty
good stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez acknowledges his exemplary offensive stats so far
could mislead people into assuming he's as good as new.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can't gauge everything by numbers,'' the shortstop
cautioned. ``Sure it's a numbers game, but you can hit a ball
incredibly hard for a month and have nothing to show for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Lou Piniella says Rodriguez only needs to run a little
better to be the player of old.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will come,'' Piniella said. ``He's not pushing it. He's
done a heckuva job with the bat and the glove. I just want him to
take it easy once in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   PART-TIME WORK: The Giants are considering using All-Star left
fielder Barry Bonds, back just two games from elbow surgery, as a
designated hitter for the first time in Sunday's series finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something in our plans, but we'll see how he feels,''
Giants manager Dusty Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with interleague play in use for two years before this
season, Baker said he's never before been tempted to try Bonds at
DH.
</P>
<P>
   ``No need to,'' Baker said. ``He wants to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonds just winked and smiled Friday when asked about the
possibility of batting only.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't ever think about those things,'' Bonds said. ``Dusty's
the manager, he makes those decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it wouldn't look good on the resume or land him a job
in the American League when he gets old, the slugger replied, ``I
play in the National League. I'm just here for three days.''
</P>
<P>
   OUTPATIENT UPDATE: Pitcher Mark Leiter was back in the M's
clubhouse Friday, five weeks after having rotator cuff surgery. His
outlook was decidedly mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be worse,'' Leiter said. ``I could be dying.''
</P>
<P>
   The veteran right-hander, who rejoined his teammates on the
recent road trip, said his spirits weren't great. He was hoping for
a miracle and wanted to hear his recovery might be a matter of
months. He got the worst-case scenario: 12 to 18 months, if that.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter, 36, said the injury has made him reflective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me thankful for as long as I've got to pitch,'' the
pitcher said. ``I was fortunate not to have my career end eight to
10 years ago. I know it's not going to last forever.''
</P>
<P>
   BAT MAN: Former big league pitcher Ken Brett was back on the
mound Friday at the Kingdome, throwing batting practice for
Mariners hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Comeback, maybe?
</P>
<P>
   Good business, the 50-year-old Brett answered.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing his bat business, he asked Mariners president Chuck
Armstrong what it would take to sell him three dozen bats for a
trial run.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I will buy three dozen bats if you pitch batting
practice,''' Brett said. ``I think I impressed Lou (Piniella). I
want Lou to activate me for one game at the end of the season, so I
can get my pension current.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett, who will handle Fox broadcasting duties Saturday for a
national telecast, recently moved his family to Spokane to be near
his business interests, which include the Brett Bros. bat company
and baseball, soccer and hockey franchises.
</P>
<P>
   BLOOMQUIST SIGNED: The Mariners signed eight of their June draft
picks, including 21-year-old infielder Willie Bloomquist from Port
Orchard, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomquist, an All-America selection and Pac-10 Player of the
Year as an Arizona State junior, batted .394 with 10 home runs, 84
RBIs and 32 stolen bases this season.
</P>
<P>
   The M's also signed infielders Justin Leone and Oscar Ramirez,
pitchers Steven Kent, Wayne Hamilton and Timothy Burton and
outfielders Sean Parnell and Kristoffer Gundrum.
</P>
<P>
   CHARITABLE ACTS: The 14th annual Cystic Fibrosis/Mariners Care
Golf Tournament, chaired by M's right fielder Jay Buhner, had its
most successful year. Held for the first time at The Golf Club at
Newcastle in Bellevue, it raised more than $360,000 for cystic
fibrosis research.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
