<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANGELS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS ROUTED BY DIAMONDBACKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ There were those who scoffed when Randy
Johnson said he signed with the Arizona Diamondbacks because he
thought they could win right away.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who also strongly considered the Anaheim Angels,
apparently knew what he was talking about.
</P>
<P>
   With Johnson watching from the bench _ he's not pitching in the
series _ the Diamondbacks routed the Angels, 12-2, before 37,042 at
Edison Field Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got beat, they hammered us, Angels manager Terry
Collins said. ``I can't think of a night we've had like that all
year. You're going to have bad days, and today was a bad day.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona leads the N.L. West by three games over the Giants,
while the Angels fell further into last-place in the A.L. West, 8
1/2 games behind the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has been all he's cracked up to be -- he's 8-2 with a
3.15 ERA and 143 strikeouts, tied with Boston's Pedro Martinez for
the major league lead. But the Diamondbacks showed the Angels that
it takes more than the Big Unit to put up big numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks pitcher Armando Reynoso (4-1) shut the Angels out
on five hits in eight innings. No Angels baserunner reached third
until Troy Glaus' two-out, two-run homer in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can pitch, Collins said. ``He changes speeds, give you
different looks, he never throws the same thing in any particular
count.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Bell, Kelly Stinnett and Steve Finley each homered for
Arizona, which went into the game leading the National League in
hitting (.286) and runs scored. Angels starter Ken Hill (3-5) kept
his team in the game through five innings, but it all came apart in
the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the sixth, Steve Finley's two-run homer made it
5-0 and Hill was gone. But reliever Mike Magnante made sure it was
over, giving up four more runs in what turned out to be a six-run
inning and a 9-0 Arizona lead.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the only thing keeping the fans around was the
fireworks show scheduled for after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who gave up five runs and nine hits in 5 1/3 innings, said
his velocity was down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any pop on the ball, Hill said. ``My velocity
topped out at 88-, 87-mph. I made mistakes and I paid for them. The
hitters over there will make you pay in this league. I didn't feel
good warming up.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The SAN GABRIEL VALLEY TRIBUNE, WEST COVINA,
CALIFORNIA  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
