<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-REDSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS TOSS ASIDE PIAZZA'S COMEBACK SCRIPT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Mets, who seem to thrive on stress lately, nearly
pulled another one out of the confusion Friday night on another day
of chaos at Shea Stadium. But this time they wound up deflated
after a ninth-inning comeback and lost, 3-2, to the Boston Red Sox
in 12 innings.
</P>
<P>
   John Franco allowed a run-scoring single to John Valentin in the
12th as the Mets' four-game winning streak and the Red Sox's
five-game losing streak ended.
</P>
<P>
   With his teen-age days adviser Ted Williams in the house as the
guest of honor, Mike Piazza slammed a two-run home run off Boston's
closer, Tom Gordon, in the bottom of the ninth to tie the score at
2-2.
</P>
<P>
   But three innings later, Benny Agbayani failed to field
Valentin's single to left field cleanly as Jose Offerman scored
from second base, and the Mets' second consecutive ninth-inning
comeback went for naught.
</P>
<P>
   All this came in the aftermath of general manager Steve
Phillips' admission on Thursday that the Mets would consider
releasing Bobby Bonilla and absorbing the rest of the $9.5 million
they owe him. Early in the evening, reporters flocked to Bonilla,
then Phillips, then manager Bobby Valentine, whom Bonilla has been
feuding with since Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to put their troubles behind them, the three met in
Valentine's office shortly before the game, only hours after the
Mets' manager was issued a two-game suspension by the National
League for not leaving the dugout area after being ejected
Wednesday night. Valentine said Bonilla wanted to get back on the
field and contribute, and indeed he did before the night was over.
</P>
<P>
   When the off-the-field business were ended, it was time to honor
Williams, whose former team was in town in the season that marks
the 60th anniversary of his rookie season with Boston.
</P>
<P>
   With Yogi Berra among the baseball dignitaries participating in
the ceremony, Williams was driven out to the pitcher's mound in a
golf cart by Tom Seaver and introduced by Tommy Lasorda.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, who first met Williams when Piazza was a teen-ager
(Lasorda helped set up the meeting), stood at first on the infield
grass as he awaited Williams' ceremonial first pitch. But the
80-year-old Williams waved Piazza back behind the plate and then
fired a perfect strike to the All-Star catcher to the delight of
the 36,700 fans.
</P>
<P>
   Masato Yoshii gave the struggling Mets' rotation its fifth
consecutive quality start. He lasted eight innings, the longest
outing by a Mets starter this season, allowing eight hits and two
runs. But 23-year-old Brian Rose was even better for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   In his fifth start of the season, Rose, a rookie right-hander
who is undefeated in three decisions with two victories over the
Yankees and one over Cleveland, limited the Mets to just three
singles in seven shutout innings.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Manager Jimy Williams decided to lift Rose at the
beginning of the eighth. On came the left-hander Mark Guthrie.
Valentine countered with the right-handed-hitting Agbayani, who
grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   Next up was Bonilla, pinch-hitting for Yoshii. Bonilla quieted
the crowd for an instant by rifling a 3-1 pitch for a single up the
middle, but the booing resumed. Bonilla was immediately lifted for
a pinch-runner and Valentine exchanged a high-five with him in the
dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine had benched Bonilla earlier this week and he then
refused to enter a game as a pinch-hitter. On Wednesday, Valentine
refused to ask Bonilla to pinch-hit against Toronto after a
pre-game shouting match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still figuring it out,'' Valentine said of the
relationship. ``But I'm not worried about it. It's a situation I'll
deal with. I'm not so sure it's as out of hand as it may seem to
be. This is a regrettable situation that I think can go away as
quickly as it came.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla said he could live with a part-time role. And he
insisted he wants to remain a Met. ``Absolutely,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla's single Friday night might have endeared him to a few
more fans, but it did not lead to a run, and the Mets were still
down by 2-0 entering the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   On came Gordon. After converting a major league-record 54
consecutive save opportunities, he had blown his first one in more
than a year last Saturday. John Olerud greeted Gordon with a single
over short, and Piazza belted a 1-0 fastball over the left-field
bleachers. It was his 12th home run, it extended his hitting streak
to 15 games and it tied the game at 2-2, giving Gordon another
blown save.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
