<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-REDSOXMETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BEAT METS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It took seven pitchers _ six after seven shutout
innings from starter Brian Rose _ and John Valentin's two-out RBI
single in the 12th inning to end a five-game losing streak for the
Red Sox, who held on for a 3-2 win over the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   But even on a night Rheal Cormier struck out Robin Ventura with
the bases loaded in the 10th, Jim Corsi notched his first win with
a scoreless 11th, and John Wasdin tight-roped his way through the
12th for his first save of 1999, the news was not good out of the
Sox bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gordon, who blew his second save opportunity in six days
after running up 54 straight in almost 14 months, will be flying
back to Boston Saturday to undergo an MRI on his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who came into the ninth with a 2-0 lead but gave up a
two-run home run to Mets strongman Mike Piazza that cleared the
left-field bleachers and traveled an estimated 429 feet, admitted
afterward that his elbow ``still nags me.'' The fastball he threw
to Piazza was clocked at 87 miles per hour, well below his usual
velocity, and manager Jimy Williams announced after the game that
Gordon would be going home.
</P>
<P>
   Bret Saberhagen, who cut his left foot and took five stitches
after stepping on glass at a team party he hosted at his home
Thursday, may be forced onto the disabled list to make room for
reinforcements for Saturday afternoon's game, unless the Sox elect
to disable Gordon without waiting for the results of his MRI.
Saberhagen already had been ruled out of his scheduled start
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple of outings I've been fighting myself, trying
to get loose,'' Gordon said. ``Some days I feel good, some days I
don't. I'm trying to battle through it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is new. God knows this is new. I'm frustrated with
myself. I don't know. I really don't know. I've got to get to the
point where I can feel better. (The elbow) still nags me. That's
something we're starting to look into.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who lifted Gordon for Cormier immediately after the
home run, told reporters that the Sox closer was going home after
meeting in his office with Sox general manager Dan Duquette, who
was making one of his infrequent road appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid has been trying,'' Williams said. ``He's given
everything he's got. He loves to compete out there. I feel for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday, Gordon gave up a two-run, ninth-inning double to
Javy Lopez of the Braves, a hit that ended his save streak. Friday
night, he went 3-and-0 to John Olerud, the first batter he faced,
before Olerud ultimately lined a full-count fastball over Nomar
Garciaparra's head.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza followed with his 12th home run, which extended his
hitting streak to 15 games and came on the same night that Shea was
visited by Sox Hall of Famer Ted Williams, who once gave Piazza a
private batting lesson when he was a kid, and by Tom Lasorda,
Piazza's honorary godfather from his hometown of Norristown, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe his command hasn't been quite as consistent, but up
until tonight his stuff was good,'' Williams said when asked if
he'd detected Gordon wasn't right even before Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Might the Sox place Gordon on the DL even before the MRI?
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see what the MRI is, what the doctors say. Let them make
that judgment,'' Williams said. ``There are different avenues that
can be taken. Let's wait and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Jason Varitek, asked if Gordon was hurting, said: ``Only
he knows. I honestly can't answer that for him. Obviously, when
he's throwing as hard as he usually does, he's a different pitcher,
and (Piazza) doesn't get a chance to stand there and watch it go
out.''
</P>
<P>
   But the rest of the Sox bullpen, which had endured hard times
during the losing streak, picked up Gordon on an night he blew
back-to-back saves for the first time since he became a reliever 22
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``They needed that plain and simple,'' Varitek said of the rest
of the relief corps. ``I think the only thing the bullpen has been
lacking is confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasdin walked Edgardo Alfonzo and Piazza before Ventura hit a
one-hop smash to first baseman Brian Daubach for the final out.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox winning rally began in the 12th with a pinch single by
Damon Buford, who stole second and took third on Piazza's throwing
error. Buford was cut down at the plate when Jose Offerman grounded
to shortstop Luis Lopez with the infield drawn in, but Offerman
hustled his way to second during the rundown, putting himself in
position to score on Valentin's hit.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin, who had missed the last two games with a strained
groin, was hitless in five at-bats before driving a 2-and-2 pitch
through the left side to score Offerman.
</P>
<P>
   Mets manager Bobby Valentine said afterward he thought of having
Franco intentionally walk Valentin to set up a lefty-lefty matchup
against Daubach, the ex-Mets farmhand who earlier hit his sixth
home run in 15 games to account for the second Sox run.
</P>
<P>
   But when pitching coach Dave Wallace put the question to Franco,
the Mets' closer opted to pitch to Valentin.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Wallace) said, `Which one do you want?' and I said,
`Valentin,' '' Franco said, ``I said, `I'll feed him a steady diet
of changeups.' But the last one went back over the plate and he hit
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
