<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKSPACERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS BEAT PACERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The fans were on their feet for the final three
minutes, swept up in the emotion of the moment, saluting a team
that wouldn't die. The New York Knicks lost another big-time player
Friday night but won another big-time game and are going to the NBA
Finals. The mere suggestion of that a month ago would have been
deemed utterly irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
   With Allan Houston (32 points) leading the way, the Knicks
completed a 4-2 series upset over the Indiana Pacers with a 90-82
victory at raucous Madison Square Garden. Now that the
eighth-seeded Knicks have completed their Eastern stampede by
ousting the first, second, and fourth seeds, they will meet the San
Antonio Spurs for the NBA title starting Wednesday, which gives
their city plenty of time to party and the players time to
celebrate, reflect, rest, and gear up for one more upset.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks and Spurs did not meet in the regular season. New
York is in the Finals for the first time since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't put what this means into words,'' said Houston, who
made eight of nine shots in the second half after a cold start and
went 47 minutes. ``We've accomplished something but not everything.
Still, I was trying to picture what the scene was going to be like
when there were still 25 seconds left in the game. It's something I
can't describe.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory was costly, however. Larry Johnson sprained
ligaments in his right knee midway through the second quarter and
didn't return. His status for the Finals is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   But winning the conference championship was a windfall for
beleaguered coach Jeff Van Gundy, who automatically gets an extra
year added to his contract, worth $3.5 million, as well as a
$500,000 bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about me. It's sweet for the team and the
organization,'' Van Gundy said, looking relieved and even jubilant
for the first time in this series. ``I'm very proud of our guys,
how they kept fighting through this game and, basically, all year.
Sometimes, that's overlooked.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana, meanwhile, fell into the same spell that had doomed
Miami and Atlanta before it. The Pacers lost twice at home and were
outplayed by a team that, in this series finale, was without two of
its biggest guns, having also lost Patrick Ewing after Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously,'' said coach Larry Bird, ``I'm very disappointed in
the way we played this series. It seemed like we always had three
guys who played well when we needed five or six.''
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Miller, who loves to play in New York, shot a pathetic 3
for 18 _ and one of those three was a dunk. He did not score in the
fourth quarter and finished with 8 points. ``Horrendous,'' he said
of his shooting. ``Just horrendous.''
</P>
<P>
   Rik Smits fouled out after scoring 20 points. Chris Mullin
didn't even have a field goal in 24 invisible minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This marked the fourth time in the last six years that the
Pacers have lost in the conference finals _ the second time to the
Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, it was a certifiable upset. The Pacers entered
this series having gone 7-0 in the first two rounds and looking
every bit like the conference favorite. The Knicks, meanwhile, were
alive thanks only to a benevolent roll in Game 5 against Miami in
the first round and to the sheer ineptitude of the Hawks in the
second round.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, however, established themselves as anything but
pushovers by winning Game 1 in Market Square Arena. They also won
Game 5 in the same building. They have faced adversity all season,
from the corporate intrigue to players whining about roles to
injuries. Johnson, who had played big roles in wins in Games 3 and
5, left with 6:03 remaining in the first half after Indiana's
Travis Best clipped him in the knee. The Garden instantaneously
went to hush mode for several minutes as Johnson lay in a fetal
position under the basket. X-rays were negative and he was taken to
a hospital for an MRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emotionally, it takes a toll on the team,'' Van Gundy said of
Johnson's loss. ``But our guys fought.''
</P>
<P>
   Did they ever. And the Pacers wimped out. They had no answer for
Latrell Sprewell, who recovered from a horrible start and finished
with 20 points. Marcus Camby, who Bird said was the best player in
the series, came through again with 15 points, 9 rebounds, and 3
blocks.
</P>
<P>
   In a tight game, with each team spurting and sputtering, it was
a 6-0 burst that sealed things for the Knicks. With New York
leading, 78-76, Camby followed a Chris Childs miss. And then, four
possessions later, he was fouled and made two biggies. Sprewell
then completed the burst, which gave the Knicks their biggest lead
(84-76) with 1:22 left. The Pacers went quietly, as was the case
all series, never getting closer than 5 the rest of the way.
</P>
</TEXT>
