<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SHAUGHNESSY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TED HAS A BALL IN NY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Friday night was ``Ted Williams Night'' at Shea
Stadium. They called it a celebration of the 60th aniversary of his
rookie season, and the greatest hitter who ever lived threw out the
first ball before the Red Sox' 3-2 victory in 12 innings over the
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``My arm is like always, not very good,'' said Teddy Ballgame,
now 80 and utilizing the aid of a walker.
</P>
<P>
   Ted will have to ice his arm for the next month to get ready for
another first-ball toss when the last All-Star Game of the century
is played at Fenway Park one month from Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, going back to Boston will be big,'' the Splendid
Splinter said in his hotel suite Friday afternoon. ``Hell, there's
a bunch of memories there.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams did a battery of interviews early Friday. He chatted
with Fox-TV, answered questions for the Mets' promotional
department, then rested with a glass of ice water and commented on
some more topics.
</P>
<P>
   Ted wore down as the morning stretched into afternoon. A series
of strokes and a broken hip have put him behind in the count. Fans
across the country might remember an unfortunate interview he did
on the ``Today'' show after Joe DiMaggio died. In an unflattering
setting, under bright lights, at an early hour, Williams appeared
sleepy and confused. Such was not the case Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty good, but I get tired easy,'' he said. ``And I
sometimes have a hard time getting through the day. When there's no
game at night, that's a bad day. Not too much going on.''
</P>
<P>
   He was in town as a favor to Mets owner Nelson Doubleday and to
promote the Hall of Fame candidacy of Shoeless Joe Jackson. Teddy
Ballgame is quite passionate about the Jackson topic, and he'd
hoped to meet with baseball commissioner Bud Selig. Bud couldn't
make it, which is a little curious. It's beginning to look as if
Selig is dodging the Joe Jackson shakers the same way John
Harrington shuns those Save Fenway zealots.
</P>
<P>
   Williams and his people have worked up an eight-page manifesto
pushing Jackson for Cooperstown. Space doesn't permit furnishing
too many of the details, but the thrust is that Jackson was never
convicted in a court of law, played hard in the 1919 World Series,
and fully paid his debt to society and baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here, more than anything else, to just say what I can to
create a little excitement about Joe Jackson,'' said Williams.
``And I think he's gonna get in. I go back to 1936 with Joe
Jackson. I asked Eddie Collins in 1936 to tell me about Joe
Jackson. He dropped his head and he paused three or four seconds,
and then he lifted his head toward the sky and said, `Boy, what a
player he was.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's the thing about Joe Jackson: He never was convicted in
court. Twice he was acquitted. He never, ever said a bad thing
about baseball. His record is absolutely on top. It makes you
wonder. You got to at least think about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never met him. We used to go by his house in South Carolina.
We'd be playing near Atlanta at the end of spring training. I never
did go up to say hello. Joe Cronin, my manager, was always trying
to get me to meet old players. I got introduced to Walter Johnson.
And I got introduced to Judge (Kenesaw Mountain) Landis through
Cronin, and I met Ty Cobb through Cronin.''
</P>
<P>
   At 7:25 Friday night, Williams entered Shea in a golf cart
driven by Tom Seaver. Fans stood as Marines saluted the Splendid
Splinter. Ralph Kiner presented Ted with a silver bat. Ted gave a
brief tribute to New York baseball fans and owners, then said the
best team he ever played for was ``the US Marines.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams stood with his arm wrapped around Rusty Staub while the
anthem was sung by a Marine major. Then, supported by Staub and
Seaver, Williams urged former hitting pupil Mike Piazza to back up,
and he lofted a strike to the Met catcher.
</P>
<P>
   Tossing first balls is nothing new for Ted. In the last two
years he's performed the feat in his native city, San Diego, and
his current home state of Florida. He threw out the first ball the
last time the All-Star Game was played at Fenway, in 1961, but said
he had no recollection of the event.
</P>
<P>
   Ted still takes pride in his five-year-old prediction that Dan
Duquette was going to be a ``secret weapon'' for the Red Sox. Now
he says the same thing about Jimy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are two secret weapons they have, and I knew it. Nobody
else knew it, but I knew it. I watch 'em every time I have a
chance. I like a lot of their players. (John) Valentin, I love.
(Nomar) Garciaparra, I love. What a player he is. What a hitter he
is. Jeez, I just hope he doesn't get hurt. He's a good kid. And
that little outfielder, (Damon) Buford, is good. And the other guy
who is a hell of a hitter is (Reggie) Jefferson.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he wants to see the model of the new Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston deserves a new ballpark,'' he said. ``I haven't seen
the new plan, but I'm glad to hear they got the sun setting in the
same direction. That's one thing they're doing right. Just imagine
the money they've lost over 40 years by not being able to get that
extra ten or twelve thousand in the ballpark. With that, they can
compete with anybody. Now it's hard to compete with these guys that
are making nine jillion bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams and his son, John Henry, Saturday will fly to Detroit
to be part of a golf tournament honoring the late Hank Greenberg.
Next month, before coming to Boston, Williams and his entourage
will be in Iowa for a Joe Jackson event at the original Field of
Dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Ted's particularly proud of his son's booming Internet business.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's too smart,'' said the dad. ``He's got 50 people working
for him. I keep asking myself, `How'd he get so damn smart?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ted and your humble correspondent talked about how the Web seems
to be taking over the world. I told Ted that my wife sometimes
shops for groceries over the Net. He wanted to know how much extra
that would cost.
</P>
<P>
   He said he still watches a ton of TV, which keeps him current .
. . and opinionated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get discouraged,'' he said. ``There's nothing smooth or
running nice in the (expletive) world. Jeez. I would take that
Mananovich (sic) or whatever the hell his name is (Yugoslavian
president Slobodan Milosevic) and I would insist that NATO and the
World Court do something. He's a (expletive). I think that's the
way to shorten this thing up.''
</P>
<P>
   Not above name-dropping, I told Ted I'd sat with former
Congressman Joe Kennedy on my flight to New York. I told him that
Joe said hello, but we all know that Ted is a staunch Republican
who campaigned for Richard Nixon in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know Kennedy didn't beat Nixon, either,'' Ted reminded me,
making an obvious reference to Richard Daley's infamous Cook County
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Ted was tiring. He ordered a coke and some chocolate ice cream
from room service. Time for me to go home and let the greatest
hitter who ever lived eat his ice cream and take a nap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
