<SLUG> BC-BKN-RYANCOLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS HAVE BLOSSOMED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You don't have to love 'em, but you sure have to
respect the way they're playing basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Knicks are going to the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   You know the time-honored NBA reference to the ``Second
Season?'' What's going on with the Knicks is more like a second
lifetime. Ever since blowing Game 4 of the first-round series with
Miami right here in Madison Square Garden, the New York Knicks have
been involved in as bizarre and amazing and inexplicable a playoff
story as the NBA has ever seen. They were one possession away from
elimination in Game 5, one debatable sideline out-of-bounds call,
really. And then Allan Houston got The Bounce on that game's final
shot. Since then, just about nothing concerning the New York Knicks
makes any sense.
</P>
<P>
   They played the final four games of this series without Patrick
Ewing. No problem. Friday night they played the final 2 1/2 periods
without Larry Johnson, who sprained ligaments in his right knee. No
problem. Nothing was going to deter them. They just kept playing
their game, and with Friday night's 90-82 victory, they will be in
the Finals, the first No. 8 seed ever to make that statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana Pacers have no excuses. The Knicks beat them. Fair.
Square. In. Out. Right side up. Upside down. New York took whatever
Indiana had to offer in this series and spit it right back. You
might not want to take a few of these guys home to mother, but
right now you'd want them in your trench.
</P>
<P>
   This has to be an unimaginably crushing blow to the Pacers, who
had been deemed the heirs apparent to Chicago's Eastern Conference
supremacy before the season began, and who had begun the playoffs
with seven consecutive victories over Orlando and Philadelphia. But
they were shaky from the very start in this series, losing Game 1
at home, blowing a 17-point lead before pulling out Game 2 on two
dubious Reggie Miller free throws, and then squandering an 8-point
lead in the late stages of Game 3, the affair that ended as
improbably as any playoff game has ever ended when Johnson came up
with a 4-point play. Indiana also coughed up a 14-point
first-period lead in Game 5 in their own building and just to make
this whole thing nicely circular and symmetrical, they couldn't
make the most of an early 9-point lead Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   And who could feel worse in the world of sport this morning than
Miller. The man who has proclaimed just how much he enjoys being
the enemy was poison to his own fans and teammates with a 3-for-18
performance Friday night. Truth be told, it looked even uglier than
that, since one of those three hoops was a sneakaway dunk following
a first-period New York turnover.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but a Reggie Miller type did show up Friday night, only it
wasn't Reggie Miller. It was Houston, who played a lot like the
coach of Indiana used to play in these type of games, pouring in 32
points. He did it with smooth jumpers and aggressive moves to the
hoop. He had 25 of the first 64, if you can believe that. Then
again, with this Knicks team, you can believe just about anything.
</P>
<P>
   Let the record show that the game began to turn in New York's
favor when coach Jeff Van Gundy called on Marcus Camby to reenter
the game in the third period. The Pacers had come out of the blocks
strong in the second half, ripping off the first 11 points to move
from a 6-point deficit to a 46-41 advantage. At that point Van
Gundy knew the game was in danger of slipping away.
</P>
<P>
   Camby did what he has done the entire series. He got on the
boards. He ran the floor. He floated around on defense. He proved
to be the Matchup From Hell. There was never anything a Smits,
Davis, or McKey could do with him. The final numbers Friday night
were 15 points and 9 rebounds, but the effect was incalculable.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens against the favored Spurs when the Finals
begin Wednesday night in the Alamodome, this game was the final
vindication for deposed general manager Ernie Grunfeld, who made
the deal with Toronto to import Camby, and who then had to battle
his own coach in order to get him in the lineup. Van Gundy has to
know just how much he owes Grunfeld.
</P>
<P>
   I'm talking about thanks and gratitude. Words and feelings. But
I could just as easily be talking about cold, hard cash. For with
this victory, Jeff Van Gundy has been enriched by $4 million. Agent
Rob Ades negotiated a clause in Van Gundy's contract that gives him
an automatic one-year contract extension at $3.5 million through
the 2000-01 season should the Knicks make the Finals. There is also
a nice little $500,000 bonus in there for Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   The coach now can think about trading in his Honda Civic. Either
that, or he can give it to Grunfeld. Or he can take him out to
dinner. But he's got to do something. No Camby, no trip to the
Finals. And no bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Logic dictates that this story ends with San Antonio blowing out
the Knicks. Well, bleep logic. As far as the Knicks are concerned,
logic was put on waivers about three weeks ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
