<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIX-RUN FIRST SENDS MARINERS PAST GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Seems like every time the San Francisco Giants call on
their Gardner these days, the grass doesn't get mowed and hedges
are unevenly trimmed.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, things got untidy real quick, with the Mariners
scoring six first-inning runs off Mark Gardner in a 7-3 victory
over their interleague guests before a crowd of 29,527 at the
Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a good matchup from the outset.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner, fighting shoulder soreness that forced him onto the
disabled list in April, hadn't won in 10 starts.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had jumped on opposing pitchers for first at-bat
runs in three consecutive games, including another six-spot Tuesday
in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Ten batters through the Seattle lineup Friday, weeds had
sprouted all over Gardner.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the first, Edgar Martinez slugged a two-run
home run, David Bell singled home two runs and Dan Wilson got a
gift two-run double, providing the Mariner push mower, Jamie Moyer,
with plenty of backing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned,'' said Gardner, a veteran with 78 big league
victories entering the season but winless in five decisions this
year. ``All I can do is go out there and try and pitch well. Today,
I didn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer, with one or two starts remaining at the Kingdome before
his team vacates it for new digs, has no worries these days. Even
his concrete surroundings look good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of like it here,'' said the lefty, now 26-12 as a
Mariner at the Dome. ``But it doesn't matter if I like it here or
not; we're not staying here. I've had success here. Why, I don't
know. This isn't a very forgiving ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer (7-4) posted his sixth victory in a row, and won for the
sixth consecutive start, in his typical efficient fashion. The
lefty pitched into the eighth inning for the fourth consecutive
outing, scattering seven hits and the three runs.
</P>
<P>
   Through the middle innings, Moyer retired 13 batters in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first inning, he didn't have the changeup he usually
has, but as the game went on, he was able to develop it,'' catcher
Wilson said. ``He just pitched the way Jamie usually pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner had no such success, though he came within a pitch of
leaving the first inning unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran San Francisco pitcher made an interleague mistake,
hanging a 3-2, two-out offering on the outside of the plate to
Martinez. The ball sailed 374 feet into the stands, finding the
glove of an appreciative male fan standing in the right-field
concourse. With Alex Rodriguez aboard for taking a pitch off the
hip, Martinez's 11th homer put the Mariners up 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Unsettled, the Giants right-hander walked the next batter, Butch
Huskey, on four pitches. David Segui singled. Russ Davis walked,
loading the bases. Still time for Gardner to reach the dugout with
minimal damage. But Bell wouldn't let him. Bell lined an 0-1 pitch
into left field, scoring two more and leaving two on.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner was in obvious need of help. None was in the offing.
Wilson sent a fly ball to center. Giants center fielder F.P.
Santangelo raced in two steps before realizing he should have
backpedaled. He made a futile stab at the ball as it went over his
head and rolled to the wall. As two runs scored easily to make it
6-0, Santangelo stood with his back to the plate while Gardner
paced the mound in disgust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I hit it good, but I thought he was going to catch
it,'' Wilson said. ``For whatever reason, I saw it land. And I was
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners pushed across another run in the fourth. Wilson got
a legitimate double this time, nearly missing a homer to left.
Brian Hunter bunted for a basehit, moving Wilson to third, and
Rodriguez lofted a sacrifice fly to right.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson also provided a defensive boost in the third when he slid
into his own dugout to catch a Barry Bonds pop foul, the ball
barely missing the edge of the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a great play, wasn't it,'' Moyer said. ``That was a
pick-me-up for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Another was a game-ending, double-play grounder with the bases
loaded, induced by Mariner closer Jose Mesa against his former
team, good for Mesa's 12th save.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, weed killer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
