<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGERS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS ROUTED BY ATHLETICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ In a season of ugly for Los Angeles Dodgers
left-hander Carlos Perez, this was Medusa.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, twice yanked from starts before finishing the fourth
inning, couldn't make it out of the third this time.
</P>
<P>
   He was bombarded for a season-high eight runs in 21/3 innings as
the Dodgers were trounced by the Oakland Athletics 12-6 Friday at
the Oakland Coliseum. The Dodgers again dipped below .500 at 29-30.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland shortstop Miguel Tejada hit three homers and drove in a
career-high five runs. He hit two-run homers off Perez and Onan
Masaoka and hit a solo shot off Doug Bochtler in the seventh. It
was the first multihomer game of Tejada's career.
</P>
<P>
   Perez gave up six hits and walked four. It was the fifth time
this season he's given up at least six earned runs this season and
in his last two starts he's allowed 15 earned runs in nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not much you can say about it when you're not making the
progress you were making (with Perez),'' Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said. ``When he gets behind and comes in there, it's Katy
bar the door. I don't know where we go with him from here.''
</P>
<P>
   One possibility is the bullpen, but that would have happened
already if Johnson had confidence in another starter. But he said
with starter Darren Dreifort, loser of three straight, not pitching
well either, it leaves Johnson with rookies Jamie Arnold or Onan
Masaoka as possible spot starters.
</P>
<P>
   Masaoka's been used only in relief and Arnold made one spot
start. He pitched 62/3 innings of one-hit ball filling in for Perez
against Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You consider everything,'' Johnson said. ``We either need to
get better or I have to make a change. It's that simple. If I
thought that was the solution and I felt we had somebody who was
ready to step in for a start or two, I'd go that route.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez's unraveling came quickly and only a few hours Johnson
talked for the umpteenth time about how Perez needs to pitch with
more confidence and be more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   So Perez (2-8) responded by throwing 79 pitches to record seven
outs. Or one out every 11.3 pitches. Perez's already astronomic ERA
is light years from respectability. At 7.18, it's the highest among
starters in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a tough situation,'' Perez said. ``I've never been like
that in my career. Even in the minor leagues. When I think I'm
going to make a good pitch, they hit the ball good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I'm thinking I want to do better. I'm used to
throwing a lot of nine-inning (games), but I haven't even finished
seven innings this season.''
</P>
<P>
   The A's got right to him on Tejada's two-run homer with none out
in the first inning. In the third inning, the A's scored six times.
Ryan Christenson hit a two-run homer off Perez and Tejada capped
the inning with a two-run shot off Masaoka. &UR; !dlim!!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
