<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, June 13:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Kacanik, Kosovo) _ Ledeall: Some 4,000 NATO troops
and armored vehicles moved methodically into Kosovo early Saturday
morning, hours after a few hundred Russian soldiers infuriated
Washington by driving into Pristina and taking up positions at the
military airport there. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TROOPS (Deneral Jankovic, Kosovo) _ Thousands of NATO
troops poured across the border into Yugoslavia on Saturday and
began to take control of the battered province of Kosovo from
retreating Serb military and police forces. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ Taking a tough line towards Russian
troops who moved into Pristina without NATO's approval, the
alliance's top general warned Saturday that the commander of the
NATO peacekeeping force had authority to order them to leave. By
Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Jolted by Russia's surprise decision to
be the first to send peacekeeping troops into Kosovo, American
diplomats and military representatives Saturday stepped up their
talks with Russian counterparts in Moscow and Macedonia, seeking a
compromise on the key issue of the peacekeepers' command structure.
But the talks were clouded by distrust and confusion, as Russian
and Western observers tried to understand whether President Boris
Yeltsin himself had ordered the deployment. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-YELTSIN-ASSESS (Moscow) _ Analysis. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ Clinton administration officials
expressed puzzlement Saturday over the premature entry of Russian
troops into Kosovo on Friday but said they hoped it would turn out
to be only a ``blip'' in the unfolding deployment of a large allied
peacekeeping force in Yugoslavia. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Kukes, Albania) _ A British transport plane
crashed only 300 yards from a large refugee camp here late on
Friday night, sending refugees running as the fuel and ammunition
on board exploded. No one was killed. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SWISS (Bern, Switzerland) _ The hospitality of
Switzerland, which over the past decades has been home to a sizable
population of Kosovo Albanian guest workers, will be tested on
Sunday when its citizens vote on whether to react to a rising
number of refugees by tightening asylum laws. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INTELLIGENCE-REPORT (Undated) _ Exclusive based on a secret
federal intelligence report on foreign military weapons. By William
J. Broad and Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Will move at 3 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-POLAND (Warsaw) _ Unfazed by the three stitches he received
on his forehead after slipping and hitting his head in the Vatican
Embassy here Saturday morning, Pope John Paul II explained how
Catholics should operate in Poland's newly democratic state. By
Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-CHURCH (Dublin) _ Ireland still looks and feels like
western Europe's most Catholic country, but as the Celtic Tiger
economy roars, the country has become not only richer, but less
formally religious, much like the rest of Western Europe. By James
Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (New Dehli) _ The foreign ministers of India and
Pakistan met Saturday for the first time since fighting broke out
along their border last month, but did not agree on ways to lessen
tensions between the two nuclear powers. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-HABIBIE (Jakarta) _ Indonesian President B.J. Habibie
at once utterly unself-conscious, effervescent, impulsive,
scatterbrained, hyperactive and charming, is one of the most
puzzling ever to rise to the forefront of public life in Indonesia,
and one of the least understood. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-GUNS (Rio De Janeiro) _ Over the outraged protests of a
nascent gun lobby, a new state law prohibiting the sale of firearms
has already gone into effect here. In Brasilia, President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso wants to go even further: His government has
introduced fast-track legislation that would completely ban the
possession of arms throughout this nation of 165 million people. By
Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   SWISS-MOTHERS (Geneva) _ The Swiss will decide whether to
provide new mothers with the kind of salary protections that every
European country affords women after they give birth. By Elizabeth
Olson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   STARR-CLINTONS (Washington) _ Exclusive on the independent
prosecutor's plans for wrapping up his long-running investigation
and the implications for Mrs. Clinton's nascent Senate campaign. By
Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Will move at 3 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   NRA-FIGHTING-BACK (Washington) _ After years of struggling with
debt, rebellions within its ranks and declining membership and
revenues, the NRA now finds itself under attack on many fronts,
from Congress to the courts. But the powerful and much feared
association has mounted an aggressive fund-raising drive and has
been lavishing its lawmaker allies with large campaign
contributions. By James Dao and Don Van Natta.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE-ROWHOUSES (Baltimore) _ Baltimore has declared war on
huge swaths of its formerly treasured row houses, whose distinctive
architecture has sheltered waves of immigrants and the city's
working-class for over a century, but which city officials now
describe as derelict. By Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-IOWA (Cedar Rapids, Iowa) _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
finally takes to the campaign trail, attending the annual Pork Expo
here. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   With:
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-IOWA (TK, Iowa) _ The other Republican contenders gather
elsewhere in Iowa. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Both Iowa political stories are developing late and will
move by 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   CHARTER-SCHOOLS (Phoenix) _ Most states _ including New York,
where the first charter schools are to open in the fall _ are just
beginning to grapple with a future in which families will be able
to choose among dozens of public schools operating under charters
that hold them to state standards, but give them freedom to
experiment and independence in hiring and spending. But Arizona is
already living it. The state now has more than 300 charter schools,
more than 70 in Phoenix alone, serving nearly 5 percent of all
students. By Tamar Lewin.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SUPERMAX-PRISON (Florence, Colo.) _ A look at the federal
government's new high-tech, high-security prison for high-profile
inmates like Ted Kaczynski and Timothy McVeigh. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-ABUSE-REPORT (Undated) _ Few people took notice last July
when an academic psychology journal carried a lengthy, jargon-heavy
report on child sexual abuse, but nearly a year later, the study,
its authors, and the American Psychological Association, which
publishes the journal, are at the center of a political storm. By
Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   MICH-TERM-LIMITS (Detroit) _ Term limits take hold in the
Michigan Legislature, and it is not a pretty sight. By Robyn
Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-RESEGREGATION (Undated) _ Forty-five years after the
Supreme Court ruling Brown vs. Board of Education forced the
desegregation of the nation's schools, a process of school
resegregation is advancing across the country, especially for
blacks in the South and for Hispanic Americans everywhere,
according to a new Harvard University study. By Ethan Bonner.
</P>
<P>
