<HEADER>
A2807 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDO-HABIBIE-ART-NYT &LR;      06-12 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDO-HABIBIE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA'S PUZZLING B.J. HABIBIE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: A map is being sent. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ ``People say I look like a monkey,'' the
president of Indonesia, B.J. Habibie, told an audience of
schoolteachers not long ago. ``But I don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a strange moment of lese-majeste, described with a
bemused shake of the head by Habibie's minister of education,
Juwono Sudarsono. But this man, at once utterly un-self-conscious,
effervescent, impulsive, scatterbrained, hyperactive and charming,
is one of the most puzzling ever to rise to the forefront of public
life in Indonesia, and one of the least understood.
</P>
<P>
   This is the man who in the short space of one year overturned
much of the repressive legacy of his predecessor and mentor,
Suharto, and brought Indonesia galloping toward free elections and
a new era of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Or is he?
</P>
<P>
   Is Habibie responsible for freeing the press, bringing new
respect for human rights and allowing dozens of political parties
to compete on a newly open electoral playing field?
</P>
<P>
   Or was he simply running scared, a weak leader helpless before a
tidal wave of reform that swept all the country's politicians along
with it?
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday's parliamentary election was the capstone on a year
of far-reaching transition that followed Suharto's forced
resignation in May 1998. Already, people here seem to be taking
their new freedoms for granted.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of Monday's vote is still unclear, with vote
counting painfully slow. Whatever the result, Habibie is very
likely to remain one of the leading candidates for president in an
electoral assembly that will meet later this year, although few
people, even in his own party, are touting him as a great reformer.
</P>
<P>
   Most Indonesians seem rather to think that reform belongs to
them, not to Habibie _ that it is a huge national movement born out
of decades of frustration and that no one leader can lay claim to
it.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone can, perhaps, it may be Suharto himself, who fostered
the economic development that allowed the nation to mature, to
learn and then to reject his paternalistic form of leadership. In a
way, the new post-Suharto era is also an extension of the old
Suharto era, which ended in a blaze of violent protest that forced
its maker from office.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel S. Lev, an expert on Indonesia at the University of
Washington, said, ``It's hard to point to anything Habibie has come
up with on his own.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All he did, basically, was to recognize a whole bunch of faits
accomplis,'' he said. ``Free expression was hardly a gift; there
was no way to stop it. He was under terrific pressure to come up
with new laws, to get people out of jail and so on. These are
concessions more than anything else. The guidance came from the
streets.''
</P>
<P>
   The nation's post-colonial founder, Sukarno, was a father figure
who gave Indonesia its identity. His successor, Suharto, developed
the bureaucracy and brought economic growth. It will be the turn of
the next president to begin the process of implanting democratic
institutions and the rule of law, political analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, some analysts concede, Habibie may have been the
right man for the moment _ pragmatic, optimistic and well versed in
democratic values from his many years working as an aerospace
engineer in West Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Even his political weakness may have been an advantage, Juwono
said. ``In this period of openness, the last thing you want is a
strong president. In a way, you could say his weakness is his
strength.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is also true that Habibie's weakness is his weakness. By
his nature, Habibie is a hard man to take seriously.
</P>
<P>
   A shocking contrast to his studiously enigmatic predecessor and
mentor, Habibie seems to be bubbling over with ideas that his aides
say are sometimes brilliant, sometimes nutty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Habibie's problem as president is that people neither respect
him nor fear him,'' a Western diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   This is a particular handicap in a nation that is accustomed to
being governed by a powerful personality.
</P>
<P>
   Juwono, who was also a Cabinet minister under Suharto, seemed
still to be under his spell, speaking of ``the density of his
silence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He would stare you in the face and create a sense of awe,''
Juwono recalled in a recent interview. ``It was his presence and
his stare. He looked right through you. Every five years, 1,000
people met in a congress and there was not one who was brave enough
to stand up and say, `Enough.'''
</P>
<P>
   Habibie has another problem. Correctly or not, most people see
him as a vestige of a despised old order who must be pushed aside
before the country can truly move on.
</P>
<P>
   His personal association with Suharto is strong. Suharto
virtually adopted him as a boy and later brought him into public
service as his minister for Technology and Development. Three
months before he resigned, Suharto named his friend to be vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   There is an unanswered puzzle here. Though he was one of
Suharto's oldest and closest friends and most obedient servants, it
was Habibie who began almost from his first day in office uprooting
the structure Suharto had built over three decades in power.
</P>
<P>
   Although he remained studiously respectful of Suharto in his
public comments, there may have been a personal rupture at the end.
Aides say Habibie was badly hurt by a public display of disdain
when Suharto presented his vice presidency as a sort of sick joke
on the country.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto warned critics explicitly, in so many words, ``Watch
out. If you drive me from power this is what you'll get.''
</P>
<P>
   The international financial markets responded in kind. It was on
the day Habibie was named vice president that the currency, the
rupiah, fell to its lowest point, 17,000 to the dollar, less than
one-sixth of its earlier value.
</P>
<P>
   Habibie's claims to being a reformer have two weak points, both
of them connected to Suharto's legacy. First, his government has
dodged and prevaricated in the face of public calls for an
investigation of Suharto's stolen wealth. Second, he has allowed
the military to evade calls for thorough investigations of past
misconduct, putting only a few low-ranking officers on trial.
</P>
<P>
   From one perspective, Habibie has virtually defined his
presidency by overturning the Suharto legacy. But from another, he
has shied away from directly challenging the abuses of the
government of which he was a key member.
</P>
<P>
   As time passes and today's political battles fade, people here
may begin to remember Habibie with affection as an eager and
well-meaning man who met the needs of his day.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, he gave Indonesians the freedom to laugh again,
particularly at their president, and he laughed along with them.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about criticisms that Habibie's possible successor as
president, Megawati Sukarnoputri, may not be smart enough, a
television commentator, Wimar Witoelar, offered a witticism that is
now repeated everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already have a rocket scientist as president,'' he said,
``and look where we are now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
