<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISS-MOTHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS VOTE SUNDAY ON SALARY PROTECTIONS FOR NEW MOTHERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ The Swiss will decide on Sunday whether to provide new
mothers with the kind of salary protections that every other
Western European country affords women after they give birth.
</P>
<P>
   While such benefits are tenuous in the United States, they are
common in Europe. Only Switzerland fails to guarantee a woman's
salary following childbirth _ even though it requires by law that
women take eight weeks off after having a baby.
</P>
<P>
   The Netherlands grants new mothers between 16 and 68 weeks off
at 100 percent guaranteed salary. Britain allows 18 weeks at 90
percent of wages, Austria allows up to two years at reduced wages,
with a guarantee of the same job back, and the Scandinavian
countries all have generous benefits. Even tiny Liechtenstein
guarantees new mothers 12 weeks off at 80 percent pay.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents argue that money for the new benefits would come from
state coffers, which are strained by above-average unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would require employers to grant a 14-week leave at
80 percent salary and allow mothers in lower income families _
regardless of whether they work _ a certain sum for ``maternity
leave.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is part of a packet of options, including whether
to toughen Swiss asylum laws and to continue to subsidize heroin
treatment, being put before voters in Switzerland's direct
democracy system.
</P>
<P>
   The maternity benefits were approved in principle in 1945, but
the Swiss have voted down three attempts _ in 1971, 1984 and 1987 _
to put the policy into practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there were a Nobel Prize for patience, it would be given to
Swiss women,'' Switzerland's president, Ruth Dreifuss, said in
launching a campaign for the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no real maternity benefit for a young woman today,
even though it was promised to her grandmother,'' she said.
``Fifty-four years of waiting, that's enough.''
</P>
<P>
   She and the justice minister, Ruth Metzler _ neither of whom
have children _ have campaigned energetically for the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Among its opponents is a conservative, Veronique Fontana, a
mother and lawyer in Lausanne.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a family choice,'' she said in an interview. ``I worry
when people tell me this will make the difference whether they have
a child or not.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that most Swiss women are insured against income loss
after pregnancy and that welfare benefits are already generous.
</P>
<P>
   Some Swiss women already benefit from ample maternity plans. For
instance, the canton of Vaud, just east of Geneva, allows women 16
weeks of leave at full salary. According to government statistics,
employers in Switzerland provide maternity benefits totaling some
$225 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   But workplace conditions vary widely in Switzerland, where
federal statistics say that women are often paid up to 30 percent
less than men.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits' backers say the annual cost, estimated at $333
million, could be met from surplus government funds and a small
sales tax increase. Employers are fighting against the benefits,
arguing that they would add to labor costs.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, on Mother's Day, Ms. Dreifuss told a rally that
women should be able to become mothers without worrying about
money. Her call came two days after a poll indicated that most
voters favored increasing maternity support. Later polls have been
less definitive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
