A2809 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-ART-NY     06-12 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA AND PAKISTAN DISCUSS BORDER CLASHES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI _ The foreign ministers of India and Pakistan met
Saturday for the first time since fighting broke out along their
border last month, but did not agree on ways to lessen tensions
between the two nuclear powers.
</P>
<P>
   India has asserted that insurgents who crossed into Indian
territory in the disputed Kashmir region are Islamic militants
supported by Pakistan and accompanied by Pakistani troops. Pakistan
denies the accusation and describes the insurgents as indigenous
fighters determined to free Kashmir and its mostly Muslim
population from Indian rule.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict is the first confrontation between India and
Pakistan, who have fought three wars since gaining independence
from Britain in 1947, since both countries successfully tested
nuclear weapons last year.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's meeting was welcomed as a sign that the fighting in
Kashmir is not likely to escalate into full-scale war.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, Foreign Minister Jaswant Singh of India insisted
that Pakistan immediately arrange for the withdrawal of all
insurgents from Indian territory. He rejected what he said were
Pakistani suggestions that the border running through Kashmir is
unclear and needs to be renegotiated.
</P>
<P>
   According to his aides, Singh told his Pakistani counterpart,
Sartaj Aziz, that the border ``is well defined and well delineated
on authentic maps signed by military authorities of both
countries.''
</P>
<P>
   In an indication of growing regional concern over the Kashmir
crisis, Aziz arrived in New Delhi after a one-day trip to China,
which he called ``a time-tested and steadfast friend of Pakistan.''
</P>
<P>
   The two foreign ministers met for about 70 minutes, and
afterward Aziz met for half an hour with Prime Minister Atal Bihari
Vajpayee. Before the meetings began, Aziz said he regretted India's
decision to try dislodging the insurgents by force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope India would prefer dialogue rather than a military
option or a military solution to this escalation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy fighting is reportedly continuing in the rugged mountains
of Kashmir. Indian officers said their forces had recaptured a
strategic outcropping at Batalik in a seven-hour battle Friday that
cost the lives of 23 insurgents and 15 Indian soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Reports in the Indian press said there was ``frenzied military
activity'' on several fronts as Indian troops sought to block new
efforts at infiltration from the Pakistani side of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Angry demonstrators shouted epithets at Aziz as he arrived for
the talks Saturday. They reflected rising emotions here in the wake
of new accusations the government has made against Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Singh said at a news conference on Friday that
the bodies of six Indian soldiers returned by Pakistan this week
showed signs of torture. He called the episode ``a reversion to
barbarous medievalism'' and said: ``I feel outraged, I feel
personally violated that the dignity of the Indian soldier has been
subjected to this.''
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan issued a statement rejecting the ``absurd allegation''
of torture and called it ``a crude attempt to malign Pakistan and
its armed forces.'' A Pakistani military spokesman said the six
Indians were killed last month ``while they were trying to make an
ingress into Pakistani territory.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indian authorities also released what they said were
transcripts of intercepted conversations between two of Pakistan's
top military commanders. The transcripts depict the officers
speaking as if they had full knowledge of the insurgents' operation
and were actively involved in planning it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire reason for the success of this operation was the
total secrecy,'' Gen. Mohammed Aziz, the chief of Pakistan's
general staff, was quoted as having told the army commander, Gen.
Parvez Musharraf, on May 29. ``So the priority is to accord
confidentiality to insure success.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Singh said Indian intelligence agencies had
approved release of the transcripts to ``pre-empt any designs that
Pakistan may be nurturing about obscuring the central issue of
their involvement, complicity and continued support of the an armed
intrusion and aggression in which Pakistani troops are
participating.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kashmir dispute is increasingly stirring regional concern.
Aziz said that during his talks in Beijing, Chinese leaders had
assured him of their ``deep and abiding interest in and support for
the sovereignty, territorial integrity, independence and security
of Pakistan.''
</P>
<P>
   In an apparent reference to China, a leading opposition figure
here, Mohan Prakash, asserted that the Kashmir intrusion was part
of a ``larger conspiracy'' and said, ``Some other countries are
engaged in a strategy of dividing the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Another opposition leader, Sonia Gandhi, visited hospitals in
Kashmir on Saturday. She told wounded soldiers that she was sure
their comrades would soon ``dislodge all Pakistani intruders from
Indian soil.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
