<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-GUNS-NYT &LR;      06-12 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SOARING HOMICIDE RATE MOVES BRAZIL TO PROPOSE BAN ON GUNS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain, Colo.)   By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ Over the outraged protests of a nascent
gun lobby, a new state law prohibiting the sale of firearms has
gone into effect here. In Brasilia, President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso wants to go even further: His government has introduced
fast-track legislation that would completely ban the possession of
arms throughout this nation of 165 million people.
</P>
<P>
   In proportion to its population, Brazil has the world's highest
rate of homicides committed with guns, according to a U.N. study
published last year. But recent shootings around the country and
the school massacre in Littleton, Colo., have galvanized the
Brazilian government into pushing for what would be one of the most
restrictive gun control systems anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to offer an example to the entire world,'' Justice
Minister Renan Calheiros said in a telephone interview this week.
``We know that this will not entirely resolve the problem of
violence in Brazilian society. But it is a concrete and courageous
first step toward combating the problem, a radical measure that
shows we are serious about confronting the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the United States, this nation has a history of cowboys and
explorers pushing to open a rugged frontier. While government
records indicate that there are only two million legally registered
guns in Brazil, estimates of the number of unregistered weapons
range as high as 20 million, and in rural areas there is a strong
hunting tradition, more out of necessity than for sport.
</P>
<P>
   But large cities like Sao Paulo and Rio de Janeiro suffer from
levels of violence even higher than those of American cities. In
1997, for instance, an average of 13 people were slain in Sao Paulo
every day, nearly 90 percent of them with guns, compared with fewer
than three a day in New York City, a bit more than half the size of
Sao Paulo.
</P>
<P>
   In an episode in April that particularly disturbed Brazilians
because it seemed to echo the Littleton massacre, a student in a
Sao Paulo suburb was killed by a stray bullet as she was leaving
classes. The gunman, who was not captured, had come to the school
to settle accounts with a group of girls who had quarreled with his
sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many other 14-year-old girls are going to have to die
before the government does something?'' a brother of the victim,
Jandira Martins, asked at her funeral, parts of which were
televised.
</P>
<P>
   Tulio Kahn, research director of the U.N.s' Latin American
Institute for Crime Prevention, said two things were driving the
effort to prohibit totally the possession and sale of arms in
Brazil. ``One is the shootings in the schools in the United
States,'' he said, ``and the other is that Fernando Henrique
Cardoso visited England in 1997 and returned impressed by the
rigorous system of gun control he saw there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rio de Janeiro State law, which went into effect on June 7,
prohibits the sale of guns and ammunition to anyone but police
officers and security companies. In a widely publicized ``blitz''
of stores that had been selling guns, the police even arrested a
lawyer who was trying to buy a new supply of bullets for a hand gun
he had at home.
</P>
<P>
   The federal legislation, which is expected to be voted on within
a month, is even more drastic. It would not only prohibit the sales
of arms throughout the country, but would also require gun owners
to turn over all firearms in their possession, including antiques.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which even opponents say they expect will pass, calls
for owners to be compensated, provided they surrender their weapons
within a one-year grace period. After that, carrying a firearm
would be a crime without bail and punishable by a jail sentence of
up to two years; airlines and bus companies that accept armed
passengers would be subject to fines of as much as $115,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intent is to deal with crime at its roots,'' Calheiros
said. ``We too have a problem of violence increasing in our
schools, but we also want to prevent the pointless violence that is
the cause of so many murders in Brazil: the traffic dispute, the
argument in a bar or soccer stadium, the gun a child finds in a
drawer.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the measure, however, maintain that it is a
demagogic exercise doomed to failure. Roberto Jefferson, a
congressman who says he will vote against the restrictions,
compared the effort to ``trying to promote morality and proper
behavior by prohibiting women from wearing bikinis on the beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonardo Arruda, a spokesman for the newly formed National
Association of Gun Owners and Retailers, said, ``We don't have a
Second Amendment like you do in the U.S., but this proposal is
totally unconstitutional ... and we are going to challenge it in
the courts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
