A2822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPERMAX-PRISON-ART-N     06-12 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERMAX-PRISON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SUPERMAX' ISOLATES THE `WORSE OF THE WORST' FROM FEDERAL PRISONS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Colo.)   (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLORENCE, Colo. _ Holding 378 of the nation's most dangerous
prisoners here, the ``Alcatraz of the Rockies'' is as quiet as a
monastery.
</P>
<P>
   Walking down an empty, fluorescent-lit hallway, a visitor does
not hear shouts called across cellblocks, prisoners banging on
bars, or even the murmur of a radio.
</P>
<P>
   In this bland beige building that looks like a corporate campus
at the foot of the Wet Mountains, the federal Bureau of Prisons
seeks to modify violent prisoners by entombing them in isolation
cells for up to 23 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Known officially as the Administrative Maximum Facility but
locally as Super Max, the prison has won national attention for its
``bomber wing,'' a unit that keeps under multiple locks and keys
Timothy J. McVeigh, the Oklahoma City bomber, Theodore J.
Kaczynski, the Unabomber, and Ramzi Ahmed Yousef, the mastermind of
the World Trade Center bombing.
</P>
<P>
   But the real work is with the ``worst of the worst'' from the
100,000 inmates of the federal prison system. Of the men sent here,
in what officials call a control unit prison, 35 percent have
committed murder in prison, 41 percent have tried to escape, and 85
percent have committed assaults in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is behavior that gets you in here, and behavior that will
get you out,'' Blake R. Davis, executive assistant to the warden,
said, explaining the ``step down'' program designed to return
cooperative prisoners back to normal prisons in three years.
</P>
<P>
   After four and half years of operation, the $60 million prison
has proved successful, Davis said. Almost 75 prisoners have
graduated from the prison. By concentrating highly violent
prisoners here, prison violence has dropped across the federal
prison system.
</P>
<P>
   Under the program, well-behaved prisoners can, in their third
year, earn the right to be out of their cells for 14 hours a day,
to eat meals in a prison cafeteria, and to work making chair seats
in a prison factory.
</P>
<P>
   About 57 maximum security units in 42 states now hold about 1
percent of the nation's 1.8 million prisoners, according to the
National Campaign to Stop Control Unit Prisons, a group opposed to
the use of solitary confinement. Started about 15 years ago, these
prisons largely restrict prisoners to their cells 23 hours a day,
and allow a prisoner to move outside the cell only with leg irons,
handcuffs and an escort of two or three guards.
</P>
<P>
   Here, movement is regulated by 1,400 electronically-controlled
gates and watched over by 168 television monitors. With almost one
prison employee for each prisoner, it costs about $50,000 a year to
incarcerate a prisoner here, far higher than the average cost in
other prisons.
</P>
<P>
   To Angela Davis, a group member who protested outside this
maximum security prison shortly after it opened, control unit
prisons are throwbacks to penitentiaries of the early 19th century
where a prisoner was locked in a stone cell with a Bible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic because the penitentiary system began in the early
1800s with solitary confinement as a rehabilitative strategy, an
alternative to corporal punishment,'' said Ms. Davis, a history
professor at University of California at Santa Cruz. ``The
etymology of the word penitentiary is `penitence.' Prison was seen
as a way to be in touch with God. It was a silent regimen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Davis said the psychological effects of isolation are the
same, whether for a prisoner in 19th century cell, or for a
prisoner here, locked in a suicide-proofed cell, watching anger
management classes on a black and white television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles Dickens visited penitentiaries and saw that it created
the worst kind of mental illness to hold people in isolation for
many, many years,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis, the prison spokesman, said that the average prisoner
here talks to about 10 people a day, including his case manager and
his counselor. Asked about the mental impact of isolation, he said,
``We have no evidence to show that people are deteriorating.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence K. Feitell, lawyer for one inmate, Luis Felipe, the
leader of the Latin Kings gang in New York, retorted, ``Receiving
food through a slot, handed out by a prison guard, I don't consider
that contact.''
</P>
<P>
   The isolation has taken a toll on Felipe, the lawyer said. ``He
has retreated into himself, that is where the destruction of his
personality is taking place,'' Feitell said from New York. ``He has
deteriorated to the extent where he prefers to stay in his cell. He
takes no recreation.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with two prisoners here yielded different views on
the isolation system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prolonged isolation is the worst punishment you can put on a
human being,'' said Raymond Luc Levasseur, who has served 10 years
of a 45-year sentence for his involvement in a left-wing bombing
campaign around New York in the 1970s. ``The common denominator
among prisoners is rage, pent-up anger, frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people stay in their cells, and they won't come out for
recreation,'' he said. ``They get anti-social. They get jumpy, get
enraged when they deal with people.''
</P>
<P>
   While Levasseur, 52, expects to graduate to a less-restrictive
prison this year, Charles Voyde Harrelson, 61, the father of the
actor Woody Harrelson, is serving two consecutive life sentences
for murdering a federal judge 20 years ago. ``I don't care to leave
here to go to another penitentiary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't particularly dislike my own company and I do like the
peace and quiet,'' said Harrelson, whose son is seeking to win a
new trial for him. Noting that the last prison he was in had ``no
shower in the room and a lot of noise,'' he added, ``Peace and
quiet here is paramount for people like me who like to write.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for people who can't read and write it must be pure
hell,'' continued Harrelson, who had swung his bulky, jumpsuited
frame on a table to better hear a visitor's voice, distorted by a
microphone. ``They designed this place for sensory deprivation.
It's an Orwellian experience.''
</P>
<P>
   From their cell windows, prisoners can only see a patch of sky.
But in recreation pens, some prisoners can get a reminder that they
are in Colorado. Bernard V. Kleiman, lawyer for Yousef, the Trade
Center bomber, said: ``They can look up and see the sky. If they go
to one end and look at an angle, they can see the mountains.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
