u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICH-TERM-LIMITS-NYT &LR;      06-12 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-TERM-LIMITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERM LIMITS IN MICHIGAN SHIFTS POWER AND REVERSES ROLES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Mary Ann Middaugh had been an aide in the Michigan
Statehouse for a quarter-century when her husband, state Rep. James
Middaugh, was forced out of office after 16 years by the state's
term limits law. Middaugh left last year, but she stayed: After
all, she won the race to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   The other 63 who lost their Michigan House seats last year when
the 1992 term limits law took effect have landed all over the
political map. Several are in local political posts _ sheriffs or
judges or county commissioners _ and many have gone back to being
the teachers or lawyers they were before they were first elected.
Some moved to different buildings in Lansing, the state capital,
where they were appointed by the governor to state jobs, became
lobbyists or took jobs as aides to those still in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``All kinds of funny things have happened with term limits,''
said Ken R. Sikkema, who in 12 years rose to be House Republican
leader and then was tossed out by term limits. He successfully ran
for an open state Senate seat, and now he is a freshman senator who
can serve until 2006, when term limits will force him out of that
office, too.
</P>
<P>
   Term limit fever swept across the country in the 1990s, with
advocates calling for an end to the near-permanent political
careers of those who had lost touch with their constituents. The
Michigan law, passed as a ballot initiative in 1992, limits
legislators to three two-year terms in the House and two four-year
terms in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Experts on both sides of the issue agree it is too soon to tell
what the effects of the limits will be on a national scale. But
here in Michigan, where the House found itself with a freshman
membership of 58 percent last year, and the Senate will see a
turnover of at least 84 percent in a few years, the consequences
are beginning to take shape.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most significant is a kind of role reversal, with
institutional memory and power flowing from elected legislators to
other people who have been around longer: staff members, state
bureaucrats, the governor, lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   Many freshmen ``don't know and they don't know that they don't
know'' how to get things done, said state Sen. John J.H. Schwarz, a
Republican from Battle Creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Term limits are going to make lions out of lobbyists, and the
good lobbyists don't like that,'' said Schwarz, who after 16 years
will be turned out by term limits in 2002, when he plans to go back
to his district and resume practicing medicine. ``They don't think
they should be the trainers of last resort'' for new legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Lt. Gov. Dick Posthumus, said they thought term
limits had had a positive effect. Posthumus was a Republican state
senator from the Grand Rapids area for 16 years until Gov. John
Engler named him lieutenant governor last year. His appointment
made room for Sikkema to move to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see legislators coming in wanting to move their agenda
quicker,'' Posthumus said. ``The pace is a little quicker and the
quality of the new legislators coming in has actually improved.''
</P>
<P>
   W. Frank Fountain, senior vice president for government affairs
at the DaimlerChrysler Corp., the big automaker, said he had been
impressed by the caliber of the freshmen. ``We were all afraid of
what term limits were going to do to the Legislature,'' Fountain
said. ``I don't think the Legislature has missed a beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Others think the term limits have had mixed results _ good in
the short term and bad in the long term.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those swept out of the Statehouse by term limits needed
to move on, said Mario L. Morrow, a Detroit political consultant.
``A lot of them had lost touch with the reality of their
constituents, and their ideas were old ideas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the long-term effects could be problematic, Morrow said.
``What do legislators need when they first come to Lansing?
Knowledge, understanding and money, and the lobbyists have all
three,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether good or bad, what happened in the Michigan House in the
1998 elections is likely to be repeated soon in the Senate, where
at least 32 of the 38 senators will be freshmen after the 2002
election, the first time incumbent senators will feel the sting of
term limits. This year, 64 of the 110 House members are freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   Term limits used to be rare, but have become common in recent
years. In 1990, just three states had term-limit laws. Now, 21
states have similar laws.
</P>
<P>
   Mark P. Petracca, chairman of the political science department
at the University of California at Irvine, said it was too early to
tell the full impact of term limits, which he favors. But Petracca
said that in California, where in 1990 voters passed term limits
that took effect in 1996, more candidates are running, there are
fewer uncontested primaries and general elections, and the margins
between winners and losers has shrunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Term limits have led to more competitive elections for the
state Legislature,'' Petracca said. ``That there may be other
negative consequences is without a doubt, but competitive elections
are pretty important for making accountability possible and
responsiveness possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Common Cause, the public-affairs lobbying organization that has
long opposed term limits, agrees that competitive elections are
good, but argues that term limits are not the way to get them. ``We
just don't see that term limits is going to create something
better,'' said Edwin H. Davis, director for state issues at Common
Cause. ``The better solution is to make sure that the elections are
more competitive'' by changing the campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   One effect of the limits in Michigan, Sikkema said, is that
legislators spend more time raising money to compete in the
contested elections.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, freshmen legislators face a steep learning curve.
``We can see right now the difference between the experience of the
House and the Senate,'' said Sarah L. Hubbard, a lobbyist for the
Detroit Regional Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Because so many members of the Republican-led House lack the
experience and know-how to push their own agenda through, they
often look to Gov. John Engler, a Republican, for guidance, Ms.
Hubbard said. Because there are so many new members, it is hard to
predict how they will vote on issues, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is more work for lobbyists, Ms. Hubbard disputes
the notion that they have more influence. ``So far we're
frustrated,'' Ms. Hubbard said, because there are so many new
legislators to get to know.
</P>
<P>
   Some expect that voters will be asked to extend the term limits
to 12 years in both the House and Senate, to give new legislators a
longer time to learn their jobs before leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Many incumbents who now face term limits support that extension.
</P>
<P>
   Burton Leland, who spent 18 years representing Detroit in the
House before term limits ended his time there, laments the loss of
institutional knowledge and power.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will never be experts who will know a lot about a
particular subject,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Leland defeated an incumbent state senator, and now
he is one of the longest-serving legislators in Lansing. ``I'm one
of the last of the Mohicans,'' Leland said.
</P>
<P>
   Not for long. In 2006, he will be forced from his Senate seat by
term limits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-99 1302EDT &QL; 
