<HEADLINE>
BRITISH TRANSPORT PLANE CRASH JUST MISSES REFUGEES
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ A British transport plane crashed only 300
yards from a large refugee camp here late on Friday night, sending
refugees running as the fuel and ammunition on board exploded over
and again.
</P>
<P>
   ``They finally signed this agreement and we were supposed to go
back to Kosovo,'' said Izer Berisha, 50, whose tent looks out onto
the plane's burnt tail, poking out of the sloping grain field where
it landed. ``And when we saw the plane and the flames and the
explosions _ oh, my God. I thought this was the end.''
</P>
<P>
   But no one, either among the 12-member crew or on the ground,
was killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky,'' said Kristina Torgeson, a spokeswoman for
Doctors Without Borders, the aid group that runs the camp of 5,900
people. ``It was so close.''
</P>
<P>
   The crash came amid stepped-up military activity here, as NATO
forces prepared to go into Kosovo from the same southwestern route
that some 450,000 ethnic Albanians used to escape from their homes
to here. Some time Saturday _ on the day that the first NATO
soldiers entered Kosovo from Macedonia to the east _ a convoy of
300 or so trucks carrying 1,500 German soldiers is expected to roll
across the pot-holed roads toward the border.
</P>
<P>
   As early as Sunday, the troops are expected to cross the border,
across the region where some of the worst fighting of the war took
place, to the southern Kosovo city of Prizren. An advance party was
supposed to arrive Saturday, but Lt. Col. Helge Eriksen, a
spokesman for NATO troops in Albania, said they were delayed.
</P>
<P>
   The plane crash underscored again the problems _ and dangers _
of having so many refugees packed in so close to the various
fighting factions of the conflict: The city of Kukes is only 10
miles from the border, where NATO planes had been bombing Kosovo
for several weeks, and within easy range of Serbian artillery.
</P>
<P>
   Eriksen said he did not know the cause of the crash and was
intentionally vague about what exactly the British military plane,
a C-130 transport plane, was doing at the time.
</P>
<P>
   He would say only that it was on a ``military'' mission and that
most of the 12 people on board were British soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the soldiers hurt his leg in the crash; others suffered
from light burns and respiratory problems, Eriksen said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the plane crashed at 11:10 p.m. Friday, shortly after
takeoff from an airstrip less than a mile away from the camp. The
plane clipped a stone wall six feet high before dropping into the
field, and Saturday one of the landing wheels as well as another
piece of metal lay between the wall and the rest of the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the plane screeched down into the field,
exploding several times after it hit. Camp officials evacuated some
500 refugees that lived in the tents nearest the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very, very scared,'' said Elfije Sahitaj, 34, whose
seven children were sleeping in the first row of tents facing the
plane crash. ``It was really hard to wake them up. We ran with no
shoes on or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in very great danger,'' she said. ``It was luck that
he stopped there.''
</P>
<P>
   Several witnesses said the plane had circled over the camp at
least twice and appeared to be in trouble because it was flying
unusually low. Berisha said the engine was making loud noises. He
said the pilot appeared to turn the plane away from the camp before
it crashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pilot didn't want to crash here,'' said Atni Burduri, 30,
who was sitting on a bench facing the field where plane crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said soldiers from the United Arab Emirates, as well
as the Kosovo Liberation Army, the rebel group fighting Serbian
forces inside Kosovo, rushed to the burning plane and pulled out
the passengers.
</P>
</TEXT>
