</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALTIMORE-ROWHOUSES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERCROWDED BALTIMORE AIMS A WRECKING BALL AT DERELICT ROW
HOUSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Conn., Mich., Fla., Minn., N.J.)  (ART ADV: A map is being sent. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Teresa Oliver remembers when her block of North
Castle Street was tidy and picturesque, its handsome brick houses
lined up in an unbroken row, their marble steps gleaming from a
combination of soft soap and hard scrubbing. In the evenings, their
work done, families sat out on the sidewalks in webbed folding
chairs with their beers, laughing while their children played
around them.
</P>
<P>
   But that was almost 20 years ago. Now, the chairs and families
are gone. Now the city plans to tear down the 20 row houses on Mrs.
Oliver's east-side block.
</P>
<P>
   ``This used to be, well, just a real solid neighborhood,'' she
said, standing on her stone stoop in time-honored Baltimore
fashion. So were the blocks along Edmondson Avenue, on the west
side of town, where dozens of three-story row houses have been
knocked into rubble. Windows of abandoned houses that still stand
are stoppered with plywood or nothing at all; lace curtains fly in
tatters, ripped by the wind. Marble steps lie broken in half.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore has declared war on huge swaths of its formerly
treasured row houses, whose distinctive architecture has sheltered
waves of immigrants and the city's working-class for over a
century, but which city officials describe as derelict. More than
4,000 row houses have been bulldozed in the last three years,
virtually all in poor neighborhoods, part of the city
administration's mission to remove unsafe urban eyesores. Thousands
more have been abandoned and will be demolished. The city has no
plan to replace them and is not yet sure what it will do with the
empty land.
</P>
<P>
   Census tracts show about 66,000 houses in the center city. If
demolition continues as planned, the city will have torn down 20
percent of them by the year 2004, in what preservationists assert
is a disorganized rush to destruction and city officials describe
as an urgent necessity. The designated houses are usually vacant
and always rundown, they say, sometimes serving as crack houses and
headquarters for drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked the communities what is your worst problem _ and
we've tried to respond with the wrecking ball,'' said Daniel P.
Henson III, the city housing commissioner. ``I want to get rid of
11,000 of the worst between now and 2003.''
</P>
<P>
   But preservationists like Richard Moe, president of the National
Trust for Historic Preservation, shudder at the prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The destruction of these historic row houses will result in a
loss of a major part of Baltimore's identity, its greatest asset,''
Moe said.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Scully, professor emeritus of architecture at Yale,
praised the form of Baltimore's row houses, ``their doors and
windows showing the scale of human use.''
</P>
<P>
   The style of Baltimore's row houses _ stretching north and
south, east and west in seemingly unbroken patterns _ has been
toasted by Frances Trollope and H.L. Mencken, commemorated in film
by Alfred Hitchcock and John Waters and relished by the millions of
travelers who gazed down at their flat roofs from the
Boston-Washington express train.
</P>
<P>
   Built for newly arriving Poles, Italians and Irish in the mid-
and late-19th century, these narrow houses remained largely
undisturbed while glossy tourist hotels and a model baseball
stadium were erected down by the harbor, where an increasing number
of visitors flock to see the Orioles baseball team and enjoy the
paddle-it-yourself harbor skiffs.
</P>
<P>
   But Baltimore, like many older cities, _ Philadelphia, Detroit
and St. Louis, among them _ has been losing population at an
alarming rate. The population drain has resulted in 11,705
abandoned houses, said Mayor Kurt L. Schmoke.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 city residents a month are moving out, notably
African-American workers moving to the suburbs in Baltimore County,
following the white exodus in the 1960s and 70s to the land of
horse farms and better schools. From 1980 to 1990, 76,000 people
migrated to the county and of those, 57,000 were black.
</P>
<P>
   In a trend urbanists refer to as ``undercrowding,'' Baltimore
City's population plummeted to about 657,000 in 1997 from 950,000
in 1960, according to city planning documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, we'll have a net loss of about 6,000 people,'' said
Henson, who grew up in a West Baltimore row house but moved his
family to a house with a lawn and a pool near the county line.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore's problems, while common to other American cities, are
more pronounced, said Douglas Rae, a professor of urban management
at Yale who coined the term ``undercrowding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Baltimore's very heavy reliance on row houses sets it apart,''
Professor Rae said. ``Also the scale of the population loss is
larger. And finally, the intensive suburban development in the
county is more extreme than most other cities facing
undercrowding.''
</P>
<P>
   The poor, inner-city neighborhoods began to deteriorate visibly
in the late 1970s. Rows of houses started to show their age and a
few were boarded up. But since then the changes have accelerated.
Hensen said that by the early 80s, sizable chunks of West Baltimore
and East Baltimore and parts of North-Central Baltimore near Johns
Hopkins Hospital had lost much of their sense of neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had the lowest test scores, the highest incidence of
crime, and the most trash to be removed from their alleys,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent visit to West Baltimore, the parlor floor of one
empty sky-blue house was littered with used syringes.
</P>
<P>
   The Schmoke administration, elected in 1987, made the
renaissance of Sandtown-Winchester, a 72-block neighborhood of row
houses in West Baltimore, its priority, with a $70 million
investment in schools and job programs.
</P>
<P>
   Henson conceded that ``we're just getting to the point where
we're starting to think about bricks and mortar.''
</P>
<P>
   But officials are not thinking about restoring the old row
houses; they are mostly thinking of tearing them down. Today, whole
blocks lie in rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Officials contend that not enough people are moving to
Baltimore, and those who are _ ``urbanites or empty nesters,''
Henson said _ do not want an antique row house unless it is near
the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   In the past five years, the price of restored row houses in
waterfront manufacturing areas has tripled or quadrupled. Canton,
once a seedy warehouse area east of the glamorous harborside
renewal, now has row-house prices of $150,000 _ compared with the
virtually valueless houses in West Baltimore and parts of East
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the older neighborhoods that are suffering.'' said
Vincent P. Quayle, founder and director of the St. Ambrose Housing
Association, a community group that encourages home ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a market for these older houses?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not presently,'' Quayle said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when the city demolished Lafayette Court, a public housing
high rise, it built air-conditioned row houses clustered along
cul-de-sacs, just like the suburban dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``People didn't want three-story houses,'' Schmoke said. ``They
wanted two-story houses with modern conveniences _ and yards.''
</P>
<P>
   Another deterrent to rehabilitation of the old houses has been
the expense: $85,000 to $100,000 for each full-scale renovation. An
average mid-block row house costs $30,000 to demolish, which
includes shoring up the survivors on either side with cinder block
and mortar.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This spring, the Schmoke administration got what it was seeking
from the state Legislature: a speeded-up demolition process under
which the city can get approval from a judge to demolish a block
when 70 percent of its housing is vacant, rather than wait for the
block to empty.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Samuels, a housing lawyer with the American Civil
Liberties Union, called the city's demolitions ``completely
planless _ the last slap in the face for the mostly elderly
homeowners left.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a steam roller,'' Ms. Samuels said of the bill's
passage, which allots only seven days' eviction notice.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Samuels said she feared the bill will speed up the the
deterioration and abandonment.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, if you lived in a block with significant vacancies,
would you put on a new roof?'' she asked. ``Not if you knew your
house could be seized in seven days, you wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmoke, who has announced that he will not run for a fourth
term, said of the new law, which will take effect in October: `On
my good days, I look at it as an opportunity for renewal. On my bad
days, I'm just depressed a little about the loss of population.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mrs. Oliver, 62, , ``I feel as if I had been done a great
injustice.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The city bought her house for $13,000 in a forced sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had got burned out in `92,'' she said, ``and I took all the
insurance money and put it back into the walls, the paint, the
insides.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, she refused to leave the house, which she and her late
husband bought in 1981, from her husband's aunt and uncle, who had
lived there since 1954. For three years, she fought the eviction,
and watched her neighbors move. Finally, she took the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on a fixed income and these houses on all sides are
vacant,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few weeks, she said, ``with the storms, the water
came running down in my basement and my hot water tank rusted
out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The big rats are tearing around,'' she added.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucille Gorham, who heads a block association in West Baltimore,
worries about the people being displaced. But like many community
leaders, she supports the demolitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The houses are being demolished in order to create a different
kind of environment and I think it's good,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of demolition always point to the an innovative solution
offered in the 70s by Robert C. Embry Jr., then Baltimore's housing
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Embry earned national plaudits for a program in which the city
took over whole neighborhoods of mostly vacant houses and sold them
to prospective homeowners for $1, offering 3 percent fix-up loan.
</P>
<P>
   After a stint as secretary of housing and urban development
under President Jimmy Carter, Embry has returned to Baltimore as
head of the Abell Foundation, set up to foster better schools and
housing conditions.
</P>
<P>
   In his office recently, overlooking the model Orioles' stadium,
Embry said the $1 house program could still work _ not where
deterioration is far-gone, but in solid neighborhoods like
Patterson Park, where houses are just beginning to deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to entice new center-city dwellers this spring, the Abell
Foundation and the Patterson Park Association, a neighborhood
group, started a program that guarantees the value of a row house
for five years, no matter how much prices may drop.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no takers.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ellen Hayward, a preservationist and the co-author with
Charles Belfoure of ``The Baltimore Rowhouse,'' scheduled for
publication in July by Princeton Architectural Press, says the city
is ``misguided'' in its demolition approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do we know the population will continue to decline?'' Ms.
Howard said. ``How do we know these houses won't come back into
fashion?''
</P>
<P>
   Preservationists also worry about elegant neighborhoods like
Union Square, where Mencken lived and where ``For Sale'' signs have
sprouted in the windows of the superb brownstones. A gentrified row
of pastel-painted brick houses, each with a similar hand-made flag
hanging from its cornice, is starting to fray: the pale paint is
flaking off, a window pane is missing, and a ``No Trespassing''
notice is stuck in a window.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is reaching out for solutions for hard-hit
neighborhoods. Early this year, the city and the Historic East
Baltimore Community Action Coalition picked an area near Johns
Hopkins Hospital and held a design competition.
</P>
<P>
   One of the two winning entries, from Glatting Jackson, an
architectural firm in Orlando, Fla., proposed lining the old alley
streets with new garage buildings, with apartments overhead. The
other entry, by A. Nelessen of Princeton, N.J., called for 50
percent of the narrow houses to be renovated, with some joined
together to make loft-like spaces. Houses also incorporated
garages, that symbol of suburbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to compete with the suburbs, you have to offer
amenities like garages,'' said Rob Inerfeld, program coordinator
for the Neighborhood Design Center. ``When most of Baltimore was
built, people didn't drive.''
</P>
<P>
   To William Rees Morrish, director of the Design Center for
American Landscape at the University of Minnesota, and a juror for
Baltimore's design competition, the row-house problem is an
ecological one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Animals, when their shells grow obsolete, they shed the shell
and move on,'' he said. ``Many row houses have reached the point
where they're falling down and the city has to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Henson, the aggressive campaigner for demolition, is
sad. How does he feel when he drives through his old neighborhood
in West Baltimore and sees the rubble and ruin?
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me feel so bad,'' Henson said, ``I want to cry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
