<HEADER>
A2851 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SWISS-NYT &LR;      06-12 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SWISS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING NEW INFLUX, SWISS TO VOTE ON LIMITING ASYLUM-SEEKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ELIZABETH OLSON  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERN, Switzerland _ The hospitality of Switzerland, which over
the past decades has been home to a sizable population of Albanian
Kosovar guest workers, will be tested Sunday when its citizens vote
on whether to react to a rising number of refugees by tightening
asylum laws.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss opinion has varied widely about Kosovo Albanian refugees
who _ fleeing increasingly brutal Serbian aggression _ have been
drawn here over the last 16 months, not only by geographic
proximity but also by relatives who have been working in the Alpine
country for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, many Swiss outspokenly opposed the new arrivals,
fearing serious crime would come with them, since Kosovo has been
linked to the international drug trade. For example, European
police say that a well-established heroin-smuggling route runs
through Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But this spring, there was an outpouring of money and sympathy
in reaction to the Serbian expulsion of Kosovo Albanians from their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   In April, when Swiss President Ruth Dreifuss visited a refugee
camp in Macedonia, she brought back 20 Albanian Kosovars, mostly
women and children, all of whom had relatives in Switzerland.
Newspapers greeted her impromptu action as upholding the nation's
humanitarian ideals, while opposition politicians accused her of a
``kindergarten'' gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Those reactions reflect the dichotomy between Switzerland's
humanitarian traditions and its time-honored aversion to outsiders.
This tension surfaced in the early 1990s, when many Bosnians fled
to Switzerland, and again with the influx of Albanian Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of the year, more than 20,000 refugees have
sought asylum in Switzerland, with that number expected to surpass
60,000 by the end of 1999. According to United Nations figures,
Germany and Switzerland have sheltered the largest number of
Albanian Kosovars. Per 100,000 inhabitants, the Swiss have accepted
four times as many as Germany, which has the greatest overall
number of Kosovo refugees but is a much larger country.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over the vote on asylum laws has taken place in the
shadow of revelations in recent years that Switzerland turned away
as many as 40,000 refugees during World War II. Swiss Jews last
year publicly urged the government not to deport any Kosovo
Albanians who were refused asylum.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of the earlier Bosnian arrivals, most Albanian
Kosovars arriving here have relatives among the 180,000 Albanians
who already live in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Many, like Xhavit Hetemi, who left southern Kosovo in 1979, were
invited here to work. Hetemi has worked steadily in construction in
Switzerland's capital. These guest workers have lived in the
country long enough to be permanent legal residents, meaning that
they believe that their relatives have the right to remain here at
least until Kosovo is safe again for them to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the years that I have been here, I never heard anything bad
about Albanians,'' Hetemi, 58, said. ``We were considered good and
honest workers, until now.'' He was alluding to reports in some
German-language Swiss newspapers depicting Albanian Kosovars as
drug dealers and criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been trying to whip up anti-foreigner sentiment,''
said Suzanne Auer, of the Swiss Organization for Aid to Refugees in
Bern. Her group recently issued a study indicating that criminality
among asylum seekers was mostly in the categories of minor thefts
and burglaries, not drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception that Kosovo Albanians are criminals, when nine
out of 10 are behaving correctly, is very bad for the community,''
said Roger Schneeberger, spokesman for the federal refugee office.
``But,'' he added, ``there are people applying for asylum who, in
reality, are here to sell drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the greater long-term worry is that Switzerland has been
used as a staging ground for the armed Albanians of the Kosovo
Liberation Army. Last fall, police broke up a weapons smuggling
ring, seizing a half-ton of ammunition and guns said to be bound
for Kosovo. This followed the discovery of bank accounts controlled
by the separatist rebel group, which were frozen by the Swiss.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to cope with the refugee inflow, the Swiss government has
set, and canceled, three deadlines to return Albanian Kosovars
home. Local press reports have highlighted the slow pace at which
Swiss officials in Macedonia have processed applications from
Kosovo refugees there seeking to come to Switzerland. Swiss
authorities eventually announced they would accept Kosovo Albanians
at least until the situation in the Serbian province stabilizes _ a
move last taken during the 1992-95 Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   These actions contrast with generous public donations to help
refugees and the government's commitment of more than $34 million
in aid, including building camps for up to 15,000 refugees in
Albania and 25,000 in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The revised asylum law up for voter approval would enshrine the
government's right to declare certain groups eligible for entry
into the country, thus eliminating individual refugee reviews and
saving money. But critics fear that this wholesale admissions
process will undercut the refugees' right to make their case for
individual persecution, which is necessary to be granted permanent
asylum in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Voters must also decide whether to give a retroactive rubber
stamp to emergency measures taken last year as the Kosovo refugee
inflow was gathering steam. Those measures allow rapid ejection of
people without identity papers, in order to foil entry by those who
are actually economic immigrants, said Urs Arn, of the federal
refugee office.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are abuses,'' agreed Ms. Auer, of the refugee aid group.
``But can you imagine being Albanian and going to the Serbian
police for identity papers? It's just not possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
