<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2857 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-NYT &LR;      06-12 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. GENERAL SAYS NATO CAN ORDER RUSSIANS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Taking a tough line toward Russian troops
who moved into Pristina without NATO's approval Friday night, the
alliance's top general warned Saturday that the commander of the
NATO peacekeeping force had authority to order them to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley Clark, the American commander of NATO forces in
Europe, said here that the allies would welcome Russian
participation in the force, but only under a command arrangement
with the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we're going to be able to work this out in the
fashion soldiers normally do,'' he said, playing down any threat of
armed confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson, commander of the NATO
force entering Kosovo, known as KFOR, would be in charge under the
terms of the agreement reached with Serbian generals this week on
how their forces would withdraw from Kosovo and let 50,000 allied
peacekeepers come in.
</P>
<P>
   Under that military agreement, Clark emphasized, the NATO
commander ``has the authority to direct all operations on the
ground to control all facilities and can tell forces, all forces,
any forces, to redeploy and move.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By virtue of the fact that the Russian vehicles have been
marked with KFOR lettering,'' he added, ``one would assume that
they recognize this authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, like other officials here, said there was no cause for
worry about clashes between the Russians and other peacekeepers,
who did not delay their entry into Kosovo early Saturday morning
because of the unexpected Russian arrival in Pristina in the middle
of the night.
</P>
<P>
   But the allies did not conceal their bafflement and displeasure
at the Russian unit's move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would describe it as more or less a quartering party,''
Clark said in characterizing the Russian forces _ one with the
ability to stake out but not defend a position. ``It was an element
that was pulled out of another command unit that was sent racing
along to apparently move to an airfield to do some mission, we
can't imagine what, in an uncoordinated fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be an isolated element that's out there by
itself,'' he added, ``and I'm sure it will have to be brought into
the design of the overall mode of NATO and Russian work in KFOR.''
</P>
<P>
   About 200 of the soldiers, he said, had unilaterally dropped
their duties with the NATO peacekeeping force in Bosnia and headed
off for Kosovo instead, without giving advance notice to the U.S.
general under whose command they were serving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly this was not in keeping, and the lack of notification
was not in keeping with agreements that were established three and
a half years ago when this force was put in place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The allies are hoping that the Russians will eventually agree to
a special arrangement like the one they have in Bosnia, where the
1,200 Russian troops are deployed in a U.S.-commanded sector but do
not technically report to NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is still our firm intention that there should be a single,
unified command structure under Sir Michael Jackson,'' said NATO
spokesman Jamie Shea.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has so far refused to agree to put troops directly under
his command, but talks in Moscow on possible arrangements continued
Saturday with Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, and Clark
said Russian officers remained in contact with their NATO
peacekeeper counterparts as well.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, NATO made light of the dramatic standoff with the
Russians, accepting the Russian Foreign Ministry's proffered
explanation that the troop move had been a ``mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the Russians to be part of the force,'' Shea said,
``and we clearly see that Russia wants to be part of the force. Of
course, we have to work out the precise coordination arrangements,
that's very important.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said Friday night, before the surprising news from
Pristina, ``From a military standpoint, I think Russia has military
capacities that could provide some significant assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Some allied diplomats and military officers expressed anger at
the Russian move. ``There's not going to be any fait accompli,''
one senior diplomat said, ``and the Russians are not going to be
stationed or given a sector in Pristina just because they are
there. This is a political game, not a military challenge, but it's
disturbing enough. Nobody's in a state of alarm, but there's a lot
of queasiness.''
</P>
<P>
   At allied headquarters, officials were concerned about what they
saw as either the flagrant deceit of the Russian Foreign Ministry
or, equally worrisome to them, the lack of civilian control over
Moscow's military.
</P>
<P>
   Allied peacekeepers started moving into Kosovo in force at 5:10
a.m. as planned despite the news of the Russian arrival in
Pristina, Shea said, after having delayed the start of the
operation 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said Friday night that the allies had agreed to the delay
at the request of Serbian officers, who had asked for more time to
get heavy equipment together in western Kosovo and clear obstacles
from the roads.
</P>
<P>
   Now, one allied diplomat said, there were questions about
whether the Serbs had asked for the delay to give the Russians time
to get to Pristina before the allies did.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Clark said Saturday afternoon, the Serbs had
withdrawn about 10 percent of their tanks, 30 percent of their
artillery and mortars, and 12 percent of their 40,000 soldiers,
police officers and paramilitary troops so far under the agreement,
which gives them 11 days from last Thursday to pull out.
</P>
<P>
   Now the allies are forced to confront the changed nature of
their relationship with Russia, which until the bombing of Serbia
began March 24 had seemed to be improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just shows once again that the Russians are not
interested in building a security relationship with NATO,'' one
officer said. ``What they are trying to do is put obstacles in
NATO's way at every turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Hungary, a new NATO ally that had granted permission Friday for
Russian transport planes to fly over its territory to Belgrade,
withdrew that permission Saturday after discovering that the planes
would apparently contain troops in uniform rather than food and
medicine for refugees, a diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that there's a lot of explaining that has to be done
at many levels,'' Clark said Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-99 1413EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2861 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-YELTSIN-ASSESS     06-12 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-YELTSIN-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: THE MUDDLE IN MOSCOW _ WHO'S GIVING THE ORDERS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ There are but two conclusions that can be drawn from
Russia's abrupt and befuddled deployment of troops in Kosovo,
neither of them reassuring. One is that President Boris Yeltsin no
longer has full control of his government. The other is that he
does.
</P>
<P>
   If critical government organs like the Defense Ministry are
free-lancing Russian foreign policy, as seemed all too possible
Friday night, then a struggle to peel away Yeltsin's powers almost
surely is under way, with ominous implications for democracy here
and Russia's rocky relations with the West.
</P>
<P>
   But if Yeltsin either hatched or blessed the troop deployment
plans, as appeared more likely Saturday, the implications are
hardly more comforting. It would mean that Russia's 68-year-old
president tossed aside obligations under an international peace
agreement barely a week old without even consulting his foreign
minister, much less the other parties to the accord.
</P>
<P>
   And that suggests that Russia in Yeltsin's final year as
president is an increasingly unreliable and unstable nation, driven
more by domestic politics and anti-West nationalism than by any
internal compass.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, who could settle the matter, has remained silent. A
Kremlin official on Saturday evening refused to say who issued the
order, suggesting that some better explanation would be forthcoming
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Russian politicians themselves confess confusion over what the
Kremlin is doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's commotion in Western capitals is quite justified,''
said a member of the foreign affairs committee of the lower house
of parliament, Vladimir Averchev, ``because it's not clear who
makes decisions in Moscow.''
</P>
<P>
   From the outside, the incident appears to be the most troubling
episode in what has become Yeltsin's stock pattern of conduct: a
penchant for secrecy, surprise and sometimes Byzantine intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   Deliberately or otherwise, the president has become so secretive
about major policy decisions, and so cryptic in explaining them,
that many politicians here suspect that he is really parroting the
commands of one or more shadowy Rasputins.
</P>
<P>
   But that seems out of character for Yeltsin, who is nothing if
not strong-willed and jealous of his powers. Nobody outside his
inner circle really knows, however, because Yeltsin seldom explains
his surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere has that been more apparent than in domestic affairs,
where he stunned the nation in May by firing the popular Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov and then ignited an internal struggle
over his successor by dividing power in the next government between
rival camps.
</P>
<P>
   One camp is led by former Prime Minister Anatoly Chubais, who
has contended that he enjoys Yeltsin's support. The other includes
the financier Boris Berezovsky, who was under indictment and
investigation for financial misdeeds before Yeltsin fired Primakov,
and has since enjoyed a remarkable rehabilitation. Berezovsky, too,
claims Yeltsin's blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, typically, has sent mixed signals. He told legislators
twice in May that he would appoint Berezovsky's favorite, Railroad
Minister Nikolai Aksyonenko, as his prime minister _ and then,
hours later, appointed Chubais' favorite, Interior Minister Sergei
Stepashin, to the post.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin's Cabinet has been racked since then by power
struggles as Aksyonenko contended he had a mandate to control the
nation's economic policy, Stepashin's choice for that job resigned
in protest and his successor reclaimed some of that command.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's domestic agenda has slowed to a crawl as the rivals
debate economic plans, like a 2 percent levy on corporations that
was immediately dubbed a slush fund for next year's presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It is accepted as fact here that a battle is under way within
the government to control economic policy _ and thus the nation's
wealth _ in order to finance the presidential race of next year's
favored candidate.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Yeltsin has been studiously quiet on the subject
of rivalries, except to say that they do not exist and that
Stepashin's government is a harmonious one.
</P>
<P>
   The latest flap bears all the earmarks of the domestic
situation, except that its international ramifications are far more
troubling.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's conduct of the policy in Kosovo became increasingly
vague as the weeks of bombing dragged on, to the point where it was
not clear in the past week whether his top advisers were even
paying him much heed.
</P>
<P>
   After the president's personal envoy, Victor Chernomyrdin,
sealed the deal for the withdrawal of Serbian forces from Kosovo
last week, Yeltsin congratulated him for a job well done.
</P>
<P>
   But in discussions with parliament, the president's deputy
foreign minister disassociated his agency from the accord, saying
it was a cave-in to NATO demands. Senior military officials
privately called the agreement traitorous, and one of the Defense
Ministry's representatives at the talks, Col. Gen. Leonid Ivashov,
said publicly that it was up to the public to decide whether
Yeltsin and Chernomyrdin had betrayed their country.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin met these attacks with official silence, a response that
has only placed the origins of this weekend's troop movement _ and
his control over events _ in even more doubt.
</P>
<P>
   It is obvious is that some key Kremlin officials were left in
the dark when the decision was made to send an advance force of
some 200 Russian paratroopers to Kosovo's capital, Pristina, on
Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov initially said that the deployment
was a mistake and that the troops would be withdrawn, suggesting
that the Defense Ministry had acted on its own. But as dawn broke
and the troops stayed put, military officials issued their own
statement saying the troop movement was cleared at the highest
level.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday, Chernomyrdin, said that he was not told in
advance about the deployment, either.
</P>
<P>
   There are growing hints, through press leaks and other sources,
that Yeltsin was in fact behind the entire move. But no one on the
outside appears to know for sure because the Kremlin refuses to
acknowledge it. Nor is it clear whether there are plans to deploy
still more troops, as has been rumored. Asked Saturday who was
responsible for the decision, Chernomyrdin replied: ``You will
learn from the president. He will say everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
