<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2866 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RDP-2TAKES-NYT     06-12 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO UNITS ENTER KOSOVO BUT RUSSIANS HOLD POSITION
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KACANIK, Yugoslavia _ Some 4,000 NATO troops and armored
vehicles moved methodically into Kosovo early Saturday morning,
hours after a few hundred Russian soldiers infuriated and startled
Washington by driving into Pristina, the Kosovo capital, and taking
up positions at the military airport there.
</P>
<P>
   The embarrassing squabbling between Moscow and the West took
some luster off NATO's triumphal entry into the blasted province
after a 78-day bombing campaign, which succeeded in forcing the
Yugoslav government to cede effective control over Kosovo and allow
the eventual return of nearly a million refugees to what remains of
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   As Yugoslav and Serbian army and police units continued to pull
out of the province, soldiers of the British 1st Battalion of the
Parachute Regiment, in combat fatigues and burgundy berets, landed
in Kosovo from Macedonia by helicopter about 5:15 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   They touched down about 15 miles into Kosovo to secure the main
road to Pristina as heavier-lift helicopters brought in jeeps and
armored personnel carriers to Kacanik. Later, infantry units,
including members of the Gurkha rifle regiment, began to move
slowly up the hot, dusty road toward Pristina, the Kosovo capital.
</P>
<P>
   At roughly the same time, some 1,200 French troops moved into
Kosovo to the east, but were apparently making slow progress over
heavily mined, rugged terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Paul Gibson, commander of the British parachute
battalion, said his troops disarmed about 30 civilians and had
cordial discussions with Yugoslav army officers.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson said he told a local commander of the Kosovo Liberation
Army, Xhabir Zhadku, to order his men ``to unload their weapons and
to shoulder them.'' Gibson said the commander told him he had 500
men, ``which was exaggerated'' by a factor of 10.
</P>
<P>
   He said Zhadku engaged him in a political discussion, saying,
``We've come this far, and we intend to get independence.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO troops, as the main part of this peacekeeping mission
authorized by the U.N. Security Council, are committed to
demilitarize the rebels and preserve Kosovo's status as a sovereign
part of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Other British officers said they were allowing all uniformed
personnel to keep their weapons and were disarming civilians. But
they took sidearms from Yugoslav border control officers and gave
them a military escort to move north to Pristina. Customs officers
were allowed to remain at the crossing from Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Adrian Freer, the overall regimental commander, said, ``The
operation is going reasonably well and I'm happy.'' Seventeen years
ago, he said, he took part in the decisive battle of the Falklands
war between Britain and Argentina, the capture of Mount Longden.
</P>
<P>
   But the Russian troops camped in Pristina at Slatina Airport,
intended to be the headquarters for the entire KFOR, or Kosovo
Force, presented another military and diplomatic quandary for NATO.
NATO commanders considered an airborne operation early Saturday
morning to seize the airport from the Russians, British officers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Late on Friday, the Russian foreign minister, Igor Ivanov, said
that the entry by Russian forces into Kosovo was a mistake and that
they would withdraw. But a senior Russian officer said Saturday
morning that his troops, which moved into Kosovo from peacekeeping
duties in Bosnia, intended to stay in place as part of the
international security force.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to give his full name, but he was addressed as
``general,'' and he said that the Russians would be in Kosovo ``a
long time,'' and that more Russian troops would come.
</P>
<P>
   The race for Pristina had bizarre aspects, but the Russian
entrance into the capital created great enthusiasm among ordinary
Serbs, who greeted the Russians like a liberating army at about
1:30 Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs, many of whom are afraid of revenge from returning
Albanians, and are considering leaving here, yelled slogans of
gratitude to the Russians, and for President Boris Yeltsin. They
cheered, chanted and threw flowers at the Russian troops, and fired
hundreds of rounds of ammunition into the air for hours in
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning, the streets of central Pristina were littered
with empty shell casings.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear how much Belgrade, or the Kremlin,
had orchestrated the Russian move. The Russian military is angry
over Moscow's role in pushing the Yugoslav president, Slobodan
Milosevic, to give in to most of NATO's key demands, and has
insisted on having its own command structure if it is to
participate in the Kosovo force.
</P>
<P>
   One Yugoslav official said Saturday that the race between East
and West to Pristina was a pale comparison to the race to conquer
Hitler's Berlin as the Nazi regime collapsed. It reminded him, he
said, of Marx's dictum that history repeats itself, ``the first
time as tragedy, and the second as farce.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that the Russian voice would soon become muted
in Kosovo's affairs as the rest of the NATO-led force moved into
the province and hundreds of thousands of Albanians began to return
to their homes, aided by thousands of foreign refugee workers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But for poor Serbs from the western part of the province, close
to the Albanian border, events have been anything but farcical.
Thousands have already left for Serbia proper.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, near the airport, a column of poor Serbs from
Djakovica, a few miles from the Albanian border, waited for the
Serbian police to let them continue out of the province.
</P>
<P>
   Vukosav Slavkovic, 86, had just left the home of his
grandparents to travel with his family in a tiny red Yugo car to
relatives near Kragujevac. A battered suitcase sat on the roof,
with a large blanket. ``I left everything, a house and furniture,''
Slavkovic said. ``This is what we took, one blanket.''
</P>
<P>
   He was distraught and angry. ``When the Serbs had a state 600
years ago, Indians were hunting in California,'' he said. ``Why are
we guilty?''
</P>
<P>
   Every Serb from Djakovica would leave, said Dijana Ranlenovic,
21, who was fleeing with her family. ``In our whole building of
more than 40 apartments, just two Serb families are still there,''
she said, ``and they are refugees from Croatia.''
</P>
<P>
   The police tried to persuade the Djakovica Serbs to remain in
Kosovo, taking some of the families to houses where local Serbs
were prepared to let them stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are brothers, and if you leave tomorrow, we will also have
to leave,'' pleaded a local Serb, Milka Simonovic. ``If we have to
go later, let's go together.''
</P>
<P>
   As they talked, another long column of Yugoslav army vehicles
and soldiers moved up the road toward Pristina and then Serbia,
clearing out before the slow advance of NATO troops who were moving
up the same road, 50 miles behind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
