<HEADER>
A2872 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      06-12 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, June 13, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Broken bands of showers will reach the coast from southern New
England to North Carolina on Sunday as weak low pressure drifts
near the Virginia Coast. Clouds will spread as far west as the
central Appalachians as onshore winds draw ocean moisture inland.
Meanwhile, ample sunshine and very warm conditions will persist
from northern New England through the eastern Ohio Valley where
afternoon temperatures near 90 will be common.
</P>
<P>
   Sultry air will cover a large area from the Southeastern States
to the Great Lakes. Scattered afternoon showers and thunderstorms
will erupt in the humid air mass during the heat of the afternoon
especially in the southern Mississippi Valley and near the Gulf of
Mexico Coast. Weak high-level winds will result in some slow-moving
thunderstorms which will produce local flooding rain. Farther
north, some potent storms will also develop from central Missouri
to the central Great Lakes States as a cold front arrives from the
northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Cooler and less humid air will follow a front over the northern
parts of the Plains and Mississippi Valley. Farther south, some
strong thunderstorms with areas of torrential rain will develop
from the eastern slopes of the central and southern Rockies to
western Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the interior West will be very warm with plentiful
sunshine, although some afternoon clouds will develop over many
mountain peaks in central and northern sections.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical Storm Arlene with central winds around 50 mph will
drift over the central Atlantic around 500 miles southeast of
Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Summer In Buffalo
</P>
<P>
   In Buffalo, N.Y., sunshine is abundant in the summer, but heat
is uncommon. On Friday, the mercury at the Buffalo surged to 90
degrees marking the first time since August 19, 1995, that the
90-degree threshold had been reached. Nearby Lake Erie, which is
the breeding ground for Buffalo's famous winter snows, is also
responsible for the pleasant summer climate. Prevailing breezes
from the cool waters typically keep temperatures in the upper 70s
during summer days and discourage the growth of cumulus clouds. On
Friday, winds from the southeast brought the unusual heat to
Buffalo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-99 1431EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
