<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2873 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-2TAKES(TR     06-12 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TRIES TO SORT OUT RUSSIAN MOVE IN KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Clinton administration officials expressed
puzzlement Saturday over the premature entry of Russian troops into
Kosovo on Friday but said they hoped it would turn out to be only a
``blip'' in the unfolding deployment of a large allied peacekeeping
force in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton scheduled a telephone call to Russian
President Boris Yeltsin but it was not expected to occur until
Sunday, the White House said. High-level talks between military and
foreign-affairs officials continued Saturday in an attempt to sort
out the muddle.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the administration publicly projected no sense of
urgency, adopting the same tone as NATO's leadership, the
continuing presence of Russian troops at the airport near Pristina,
Kosovo's capital, and their welcome by Serbian residents of the
area contrasted starkly with the White House's depiction of the
development as a mistake, a trivial matter or a mere enigma.
</P>
<P>
   The defense attache at the Russian Embassy in Belgium sent a
letter Saturday to the NATO Commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, informing
him that a vanguard element of Russian troops has been deployed at
the Pristina airport, officials said in Washington. The letter
suggested that the decision by the Russian troops to enter Kosovo
was not a mistake, as Russian officials _ and their Western
counterparts _ had said earlier.
</P>
<P>
   A senior White House official said that while the Russian troops
remained at the airport in Pristina, British troops had seized
control of the airfield and the surrounding region.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we know is that they're still there,'' the official said
of the Russian forces. ``Perhaps they trying to make some kind of
point, but we don't know what it is. They made public assurances on
television last night that they were leaving, but it appears
they're staying.''
</P>
<P>
   While officials said they were perplexed by the developments,
there was an expectation at the White House on Saturday that the
problem would be sorted out within the next day or two.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the confusion over Russian motives in Kosovo, the United
States held military-to-military talks with Russians throughout the
day to hammer out precise details of the Russian role in the
peacekeeping mission. Brig. Gen. George W. Casey of the Pentagon's
Policy and Planning staff and several Russian generals flew
together Saturday from Moscow to Macedonia aboard an American
military plane to continue those discussions, according to Kenneth
H. Bacon, the Pentagon spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd very much like to work with the Russians in a mutually
cooperative and effective way,'' Bacon said. ``We worked this out
very well with the Russians in Bosnia and we expect to work it out
in Kosovo. They played a fundamental role in getting the peace
agreement in Kosovo. Now we'd like them to play a fundamental role
in implementing the agreement.``
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Casey is exploring Russian ideas about the unified
command required under the U.N. Security Council agreement and
where Russian troops will be stationed in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those talks, and the talks in Moscow, are moving in the right
direction,'' said Joe Lockhart, the White House press secretary.
``What shouldn't get lost in all of this is that KFOR deployed
today. That's the important news.''
</P>
<P>
   One senior official said that the Russians appeared to be
sending simultaneous and ambiguous signals to NATO, to the restive
Russian parliament and to the Serbian people. He said that, for the
moment, officials in Washington were not terribly concerned about
the Russian move. But he said that uncertainty about Moscow's
motives had cast at least a temporary pall over the entry of
American and European troops into the shattered Yugoslav province
of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think our military people are all that worked up about
this,'' a senior administration aide said Saturday. ``They don't
like the idea they were lied to by the Russians. But on the other
hand, there's a lot going on in the Russian government, so who the
hell knows what they're up to.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that the Russian force's
operational security was good enough on Friday to prevent the U.S.
intelligence community from intercepting any communications
ordering the troops into Kosovo. Officials say they are not sure
whether any orders were issued from senior commanders at the last
minute to the troops because they have no intercepts to study. It
is possible they were working off orders issued earlier to avoid
interception by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say they do not believe all of the
Russian troops that are planned for deployment to Kosovo will come
from the contingent in Bosnia, but officials interviewed Saturday
morning could not say how many Russian troops are expected.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The confusion over the timing and location of the deployment of
Russian troops in Kosovo arose from the unexpectedly abrupt end of
the air campaign and the vague terms under which the conflict
ended. NATO and the Russians had not yet agreed on Moscow's role in
the peacekeeping operation or on the complex issues of command and
control of forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow might have been trying to settle some of those questions
pre-emptively by dispatching its troops to Pristina, an
administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   Still undetermined is where Russian troops will be stationed in
Kosovo, which for now has been divided into five military sectors
to be supervised by the Americans, British, French, Germans and
Italians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know ultimately where the Russians will be,'' a
senior official here said. ``All the sectors will have
participation by a number of countries.''
</P>
<P>
   But this official emphasized that wherever the Russian forces
are stationed, they will be under NATO command, even if the
alliance has to devise some sort of fig leaf to disguise the fact
that Russian troops are reporting to a NATO officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a unified command structure, I can assure you,''
the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Another senior administration aide said that the sense in
Washington on Saturday was that the perplexing Russian move was at
worst a temporary hurdle at the outset of a long military and
humanitarian operation. Moscow never approved of the NATO bombing
of Serbia, a historical ally of Russia, and might feel the need to
assert its independence from the alliance for domestic political
consumption and to signal its sympathy to the Serb populace, this
official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not clear whether this is a stunt or something serious,''
the official said. ``But we're trying not to get distracted by
something that in the long run won't be important. We hope it's
just a blip.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott is trying to devise a
way for the Russians to take part in the peacekeeping operation in
a way that does not violate the unity of command, this aide said.
He said that Yeltsin and Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov were trying
to persuade the political leadership of the Russian parliament that
Russian troops will not be answering to NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a serious problem in the Duma,'' he said, referring
to Russia's lower house of parliament. ``They're trying to show
that they're playing a real role but not taking orders from NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   The official said that the first reaction in Washington to the
arrival of Russian troops in Pristina was surprise and anger.
</P>
<P>
   But those feelings soon gave way to puzzlement over Russian
motives and a determination to move forward with military and
diplomatic talks to resolve the matter and speed the entry of
Western forces into Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
