<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2875 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-APPOINT-REVIEW     06-12 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-APPOINT-REVIEW-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JET-AGE POLITICS, A BUGGY-WHIP TACTIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla., W.Va., Calif., S.C.)  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The future leadership of the U.S. Embassy in
Luxembourg, a landlocked European duchy with about as many people
as Oklahoma City, might seem an unlikely issue to pit the White
House against the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But the appointment of a gay San Francisco businessman as the
new U.S. ambassador there has provoked a clash between two of the
most venerable _ and arguably most anachronistic _ traditions of
the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the right of the White House to make government
appointments during congressional recesses without Senate
confirmation vs. the right of individual senators to block any
nomination that comes before them. Recess appointments vs.
nomination holds.
</P>
<P>
   It is probably safe to say that the Founding Fathers never
envisioned this type of showdown. The concepts of both recess
appointments and nomination holds reflect the interests of a
different era of American history. When the Founding Fathers sat
down to hammer out the Constitution, they believed that Congress
would often be out of session, with lawmakers returning to their
states by horse and buggy, and out of contact for weeks or months
at a time.
</P>
<P>
   So they came up with the idea of recess appointments, enabling
the president to make important appointments _ Cabinet members,
ambassadors, judges _ when Congress was not in session and senators
were not available to give their ``advice and consent.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Senate meets most of the year, and members travel by
jet and can be back in Washington for an important vote within
hours. But still, the recess appointment privilege lives on, and
presidents continue to use _ and possibly abuse _ their power to
push through appointments that would otherwise never be approved by
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The current struggle began when President Clinton used the
Senate's Memorial Day recess as an opportunity to appoint James
Hormel as the nation's first openly gay ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   He sent Hormel to Luxembourg without seeking Senate approval
under a 32-word clause in the Constitution that permits the
president ``to fill up all vacancies that may happen during the
recess of the Senate.'' Hormel can serve until the end of the next
session of Congress, which is likely to be the fall of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Hormel, heir to his family's meat-processing
fortune and a prominent backer of gay-rights groups, caused a furor
among conservative Senate Republicans who had opposed the
nomination because of his sexual orientation when it was first
offered two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And many Republicans complained that the appointment amounted to
pandering to gay-rights organizations that are expected to provide
important backing to Vice President Gore in the next year's
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   So last week, one outraged Republican, Sen. James Inhofe of
Oklahoma, invoked the traditional privilege of any senator to block
_ or hold _ Senate approval for nominations by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   While nomination holds in the Senate are not enshrined in the
Constitution, they have nearly as long a history as recess
appointments, and reflect the view of early members of the Senate
that the body should operate by consensus.
</P>
<P>
   Inhofe, known for both stubbornness and fierce conservatism,
accused Hormel of promoting a ``gay agenda'' and vowed to block all
White House nominations until he receives a commitment from Clinton
to strictly limit the use of recess appointments.
</P>
<P>
   The move could delay Senate confirmation for both Lawrence
Summers to be treasury secretary and Richard Holbrooke to be the
next chief diplomat at the United Nations. If Inhofe insists and is
willing to block every presidential nomination that comes to the
Senate floor, he can only be stopped, under Senate rules, by a vote
of 60 members.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Controversy over recess appointments dates from the earliest
days of the Republic. President George Washington used a Senate
recess in the summer of 1795 to appoint John Rutledge of South
Carolina as chief justice, knowing that the majority Federalists in
the Senate were hostile to Rutledge.
</P>
<P>
   Rutledge had presided over only two cases as chief justice when
the Senate returned from its recess that fall and, presented by
Washington with a formal nomination, voted to reject it, forcing
Rutledge from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   President Dwight D. Eisenhower placed three justices on the
Supreme Court during recesses: Earl Warren, William Brennan and
Potter Stewart, all of whom were later confirmed by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   President Reagan made liberal use of the power and granted 239
recess appointments, prompting a fight with the Senate similar to
the one involving Inhofe.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., who was then majority
leader, placed holds on nearly 6,000 presidential nominations in
protest over what he described as Reagan's effort to circumvent
Congress with recess appointments. Reagan eventually agreed to
limit the appointments.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Dove, the Senate's parliamentarian, said the use of
nomination holds reflects the Senate's view of itself as a place of
cautious deliberation, where all voices will be heard and where a
senator from a small, underpopulated state has as much power as a
senator from the largest state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the system works amazing well,'' Dove said. ``Senators
are normally very restrained in the use of their powers because
they need to form alliances if they want to get things done. From
an idea of pure democracy, that's why the Senate is here _ to force
consensus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-99 1442EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6972 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-APPOINT-REVIEW     06-12 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-APPOINT-REVIEW-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JET-AGE POLITICS, A BUGGY-WHIP TACTIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla., W.Va., Calif., S.C.)  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
