<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2879 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DEATHS-0613-CO     06-12 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DEATHS-0613-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DYING AS REFUGEES: Sadly, some will never return home to Kosovo
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-TROOPS; KOSOVO-AID.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ Peace did not come soon enough for Halil Emini.
</P>
<P>
   He did not get killed by Yugoslav forces or NATO bombs. He just
drowned Friday while swimming with his children near their refugee
camp.
</P>
<P>
   Now, instead of planning a return to his homeland, Emini lies
under a mound of dirt on a plateau with 140 other deceased ethnic
Albanians who fled Kosovo during the Serbs' ethnic cleansing
campaign. In a new section the local city cemetery, their graves
show the signs of a people dispossessed.
</P>
<P>
   Wooden stakes mark the identities of the dead. Their names,
birth dates and home villages are marked with a ballpoint pen and
usually, to protect them from the elements, covered by half of an
old plastic soft-drink bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Far from the hubbub of the crowded refugee camps, there is
cemetery silence here. The wind rustles through the trees, only
occasionally interrupted by crackling gunfire from a nearby Kosovo
Liberation Army training ground.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a few graves carry the wreaths and ribbons of slain
fighters in the rebel KLA. But most here died in mundane ways -- a
child hanged accidentally on a rope in a refugee camp, a
middle-aged man had a heart attack, many died of old age. A baby
died of Sudden Infant Death Syndrome, or SIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Aid officials say mortality rates are normal among the refugees,
maybe even lower for people in camps than those traveling roads and
doing work. Figures were not available, but as many as 500 have
died among Albania's 440,000 Kosovar refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees' long wait for NATO troops to move into Kosovo came
to an end Saturday, as the vanguard of British forces began
streaming into Pristina, determined to ensure peace in the
provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
   The was no jubilation among the families of Emini and others for
whom the entry of NATO forces came too late, however.
</P>
<P>
   While death is a fact of life, for refugees it comes on a
foreign land, where they die in new-found poverty and far from
realizing their dreams of returning home.
</P>
<P>
   Just an hour after Emini's death, his widow huddled silently
with other women in one of the 200 tents at the seedy Bashkia
refugee camp. A bearded man, a relative, squatted on the hard red
dirt near the tent flaps and cried. A group of men stood nearby,
angry and sad and lamenting their plight.
</P>
<P>
   They described Emini as a 38-year-old dye supervisor in a
textile plant in the Kosovo provincial district of Opoja. He was
tall and thin.
</P>
<P>
   They said he was quieter and poorer than the other refugees. He
had traveled for about a week on a neighbor's tractor to flee
marauding Serb troops and paramilitary thugs and arrived here April
4.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, when word came of the peace agreement between the NATO
alliance and Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosovic, Emini did not
celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said this is the moment to be very careful, that we cannot
trust anything until we touch the realities,'' said friend Nazim
Tahiri.
</P>
<P>
   There is little to do in the Bashkia camp, run by the Kukes
municipality. The tents lack the double-sheeting that can provide
insulation from the sweltering sun. So people leave for a half-hour
walk to the White Drin River, which flows from Kosovo. The
turquoise water is less peaceful than it looks.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, a child found an old hand grenade in the river
and got his hand blown off. Friday, swimming with his 12-year-old
daughter, and eight- and six-year-old sons, Emini apparently
strayed past a steep drop off of the river bed. He called for help,
but no one could reach him in time.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, his brother-in-law was helping plan his pauper's
funeral, clearly frustrated as much as saddened.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was thinking we should go back as soon as it is safe,''
Ramadan Jafir, 40, said. ``That is our place. That is our land.''
</P>
<P>
   By Saturday morning, about 200 men from the camp were trudging
away from the Muslim funeral for Emini in the Kukes cemetery. They
wrote his name on a stake and jammed it in a large mound of dirt
over Emini's plain wooden casket, then slipped a two-liter soda
bottle over it and poured water on the grave, as is customary here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their place is in Kosovo so it is better they should be buried
there than here,'' said Idriz Gjana(CQ), a Kukes Albanian who earns
about $60 a month digging graves. ``But, since they were pushed out
and died here, this land is theirs as much as ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Gjana said many Kosovar Albanians say they will someday return
to take their family members' bodies back to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But aid officials say that the destruction in Kosovo, a southern
province of Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant republic, may require
half the refugees here to wait months before returning.
</P>
<P>
   Just like the camps, which are becoming more developed and
entrenched, the graveyard is taking on signs of permanence. Gjana
said they must always have a few empty graves ready. A few actual
headstones are appearing.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only one has an epitaph, those words used to sum up a
life.
</P>
<P>
   Between the two cloth flowers on the smooth white cement stone
of 70-year-old Abedin Liman Telaku, it names his village as Banje
and says simply, ``Forced out by Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
