<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUNNED BY RUSSIAN DEPLOYMENT, U.S. STEPS UP TALKS
</HEADLINE>
  (With KOSOVO-YELTSIN-ASSESS)  
(rk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Jolted by Russia's surprise decision to be the first to
send peacekeeping troops into Kosovo, American diplomats and
military representatives held talks with Russian counterparts
Saturday that were clouded by distrust and confusion over whether
President Boris Yeltsin himself had ordered the deployment.
</P>
<P>
   The talks, held in Moscow and Macedonia, centered on how to make
the best of the de facto presence of some 200 Russian soldiers in
Kosovo. The suspicions of Russia's intentions were heightened by
the growing consensus in Moscow that the deployment was no mistake,
as Russia's top diplomats had originally suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how you slice it, I don't think sending Russian
troops into Kosovo has been a particularly helpful step,'' said a
Clinton administration official in Moscow. ``Overall, this kind of
confusion in Russian government ranks, and Russian troops leaving
Bosnia without notification, doesn't help Russia's credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, ordered back to Moscow
late Friday after the Russian troop movements became known, met
through the night, and again Saturday, with Russian Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov. Talbott was scheduled to meet with Vladimir
Putin, chairman of Russia's security council, later Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Although Yeltsin has yet to make any public comment on the troop
deployment, some observers here suggested that the decision to put
Russians in the Kosovo capital, Pristina, well ahead of their NATO
counterparts was made inside the Kremlin itself.
</P>
<P>
   But whether the order came from the Russian Defense Ministry or
the Kremlin, it was obvious Saturday that the move had been planned
well in advance. As one source told the Interfax news agency, this
was ``not an amateur'' operation.
</P>
<P>
   There were other signs Saturday that at least part of the
Russian political establishment is trying to torpedo any future
Russian cooperation with NATO in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   One official unnamed source, also quoted by Interfax, accused
the Americans of trying ``to usurp the right to its own exclusive
presence in the region, leaving a secondary role for Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Such statements ran counter to the more official comments on
Saturday's negotiations with Talbott, which suggested that some
headway had been made. More talks at the Foreign Ministry are
planned for either Saturday or Sunday, Talbott told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin is expected to talk by telephone with President Clinton
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The main issue in the talks is to match Russia's insistence on
its own command for its proposed 2,500 troops in Kosovo, with
NATO's stance that the international force be led by a ``unified
command'' structure, with NATO at its core.
</P>
<P>
   That issue _ left unresolved in the peace agreement accepted by
Belgrade last week _ has been the stumbling block for the smooth
introduction of an international force into Kosovo. NATO began
moving its own troops into the province Saturday afternoon, 12
hours after the small Russian contingent arrived in Pristina, to a
delirious welcome by local Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Gen. George Casey, a one-star American general
attached to the Joint Chiefs of Staff who has accompanied Talbott
on Kosovo negotiations, left Moscow Saturday morning with two
Russian military commanders to join negotiations, now underway in
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   At the Kremlin Saturday, where Yeltsin was reported to have met
with top government officials, including Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev, official spokesmen cast little light on the question of
whether Yeltsin himself gave the orders for the Russian troops to
proceed into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But new pieces of evidence _ plus the Kremlin's failure to
disown the troop deployment _ suggest that the president made the
decision himself, apparently without notifying the Foreign
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other clues was the announcement Saturday that Yeltsin
had decorated Viktor Zavarvin, Russia's military representative to
NATO who accompanied the Russian troops to Pristina, and promoted
him from lieutenant general to colonel general.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation here and in the West had first focused on the
possibility of a breakaway decision by the Russian military to make
a unilateral move into Kosovo. That theory was supported by the
unusual statement by Ivanov, delivered to the CNN television
network midway through a marathon negotiating session with Talbott,
in which he said the troop deployment had been an unfortunate
mistake, and that an order to pull back had been issued.
</P>
<P>
   As the day progressed, no such withdrawal order was announced.
Instead, by late afternoon, Interfax quoted military and diplomatic
sources as saying that ``an additional contingent of several
hundred servicemen'' is being prepared to be airlifted to Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   According to Interfax, the additional troops would fly through
air space provided by Ukraine and Bulgaria, after Hungary _ one of
NATO's three new member states _ denied Russia air rights.
</P>
<P>
   The same sources, insisting that the order to deploy had come
from the ``highest levels,'' told Interfax that Russia had had to
deploy Friday night or else it would have ended up being squeezed
out of the international security force.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Interfax reports, again quoting unnamed
sources, Moscow had become increasingly convinced that negotiations
were a facade, behind which NATO would proceed with its own
deployment. ``Moscow was made to move ahead,'' the agency quoted
one official as saying, noting that the troop deployment had been
planned long in advance.
</P>
<P>
   In a televised interview, Viktor Chernomyrdin, Russia's special
Kosovo negotiator, said Yeltsin will clarify his position Sunday.
``You will learn from the president, he will say everything'' said
Chernomyrdin, who noted that he himself had not been informed of
the troop movements.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear when, how, or if Russia had coordinated the
troop deployment with Yugoslavia. Top Yugoslav military officers
traditionally have maintained strong ties with their counterparts
in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin's top foreign policy adviser, Sergei Prikhodko, also
dodged the issue in a statement issued late Saturday, in which he
said ``the deployment of the advance unit of a Russian peacekeeping
contingent is part of the first phase of the international security
presence in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Necessary presidential directives in regard to such presence
are available,'' said Prikhodko. ``Responsibility for their
scrupulous implementation rests with the military.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Kremlin official, who asked to be unnamed, said the main
issue now was to press ahead with a negotiated settlement on the
thorny issue of a mutually acceptable command structure. ``All the
problems that have developed in recent hours are technical
problems, minor problems,'' he said.``Now we are looking forward,
rather than backward.''
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion that Yeltsin _ and not the Russian military _
played the role of hawk in the late stage of the Kosovo peace
negotiations runs counter to a view, held by some in Western
governments, that the Russian president has steered Russian policy
on Yugoslavia away from any confrontation with the NATO allies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
