<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AID AGENCIES SHIFT FOCUS TO THE NEEDS INSIDE BORDER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ The refugees stopped arriving only three days
ago, but now, like trying to turn around a battleship, the aid
agencies handling the 120,000 Kosovo Albanians in this border town
are having to reverse focus to the refugees' safe return _ plus
preparing to feed and help shelter an estimated 500,000 Albanians
still inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has not been the biggest refugee movement, and it's not
been the worst emergency, but it's shaping up to be by far the most
complex,'' said Rupert Colville, a spokesman for the United Nations
High Commissioner for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Although aid organizations say there is no evidence so far of
starvation, refugees crossing the border in recent days say they
left family members behind who had run out of food.
</P>
<P>
   One refugee who had been imprisoned by the Serbs and then
released this week near the Albanian border, and who said he was
too frightened to give his name, said he was worried about his wife
and six children left behind in the village of Zhabar I Ulet in
northern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``For three days they didn't have anything to eat,'' he said.
``They didn't have enough flour to make bread.''
</P>
<P>
   Relief agencies say they have heard reports of Kosovo Albanian
``displaced persons,'' as they call them, hiding in the mountains
but moving from hamlet to hamlet looking for something to eat.
``They've been scavenging in empty houses,'' said Anna DiLellio, a
spokeswoman for the World Food Program.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, a U.N. mission in Kosovo determined that on top
of widespread destruction _ burned houses, destroyed roads and
bridges _ one third of the arable land in Kosovo had not been
cultivated this year. In addition, Serbian forces had taken over
the main World Food Program warehouse in Kosovo, where they were
said to be charging the equivalent of $2.50 for a pound of sugar _
an astronomical price in impoverished Kosovo. They also have
reportedly shot cows, goats and sheep. ``I think _ forget milk,''
Ms. DiLellio said.
</P>
<P>
   Although only a few relief workers are to go into Kosovo from
Albania on Sunday behind NATO troops, U.N. aid agencies are
preparing to establish offices in seven cities in Kosovo within the
next weeks. The World Food Program expects they will find that many
people in Kosovo have no electricity and water and are unable to
cook and so has readied 1.5 million ready-to-eat daily meals
intended to last three months.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The ration comes in a yellow plastic bag, with ``Food Gift from
the People of the United States'' printed prominently on the front,
in three different varieties, or ``menus'' that contain a one-day
supply of food.
</P>
<P>
   Menu No. 3 contains a compressed rice loaf, shrink-wrapped in
thick plastic, that tastes like a dry, cinnamon-flavored rice
pudding. It also includes a shrink-wrapped rice with vegetables in
sauce, a fruit pastry bar, vegetable crackers, shortbread cookies,
blackberry jam, peanut butter and a book of matches (for smokers)
with an American flag and ``U.S.A.'' on the cover.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Saturday aid agencies continued to prepare returning refugees
about the danger of land mines, many of which are thought to have
been placed in the border area. Tehnaz J. Dastoor, Unicef's
specialist in land mines, and Eric M. Filippino, a demining expert
from Geneva, held a class Saturday afternoon at the Unicef office
here to educate a group of 16 Kosovo Albanian youths, elected
``representatives'' from five of the refugee camps here.
</P>
<P>
   They also showed the representatives posters warning about land
mines that are to go up in the refugee camps and asked for their
opinions about them _ in essence, test-marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the first thing you thought when you saw it?''
Filippino asked the group about a poster showing a land mine with a
large hand covering its spike that simultaneously prevents a small
child's foot from stepping on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must be careful when you walk,'' said Sanije Seferaj, 23,
an economics student from Pristina, the Kosovo capital, who now
lives in the Kukes I refugee camp.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Aid workers here are nervously hopeful that the refugees will
heed the lessons and return slowly but are worried about the
possibility of a chaotic rush to the border after NATO troops go
in. Although NATO will be clearing the main paved road toward
Pristina of mines, the troops will not get to the fields and
smaller roads for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the roads in Kosovo are dirt roads,'' said Ms.
Dastoor. ``It's going to be a huge process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
