at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO
</P>
<P>
   KOSOV0-TROOPS _ ABLE SENTRY BASE, Macedonia _ The first American
troops that are part of the international peacekeeping force in
Kosovo will enter the war-torn province Sunday morning, three days
ahead of the previous schedule. They follow the 12 Apache attack
helicopters _ which had been sitting and waiting for weeks to see a
different type of action in Kosovo _ that ushered in the first
British and French troops that moved in on Saturday. Is there more
concern for the U.S. troops' safety than for others? Developing.
(Albright, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-AID _ PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Ever so slowly,
mile-by-treacherous mile, the convoy of deteremined humanitarian
aid workers who have waited so long to bring much-needed aid to
this war-ravaged province made their way here behind the NATO
convoy of military vehicles. Was it what they expected? Developing.
(Kunstel, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DEATHS _ KUKES, Albania _ Peace did not come soon enough
for Halil Emini. He did not get killed by Serb forces or NATO
bombs. He just drowned Friday while swimming with his children near
their refugee camp. Now, instead of planning a return to his
homeland, Emini lies under a mound of dirt on a plateau with 140
other deceased ethnic Albanians who fled Kosovo. In a new section
of the local city cemetery, their graves show the signs of a people
dispossessed. Wooden stakes mark the identities of the dead. Their
names, birth dates and home villages are marked in ballpoint ink
and usually, to protect them from the elements, covered by half of
an old plastic soft-drink bottle. (Kaplow, Cox News Service) WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
