   WITH
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-SCHOOL _ BAGHDAD, Iraq _ With their sneakers, cartoon
backpacks and pony tails, these girls could fit in at any school.
But, when visitors enter classes at the Hidayeh (Enlightenment)
Elementary School in Baghdad, the students rise together with
smiles and shout, ``Welcome and long live the leader, Saddam
Hussein!'' There's something else different about schools in Iraq.
This one, with about 1,200 girls, has one telephone and no copying
machine, lights are often out and many students sit on the floors
for lack even a broken-down desk. Each year, the girls start their
studies by erasing the penciled-in work in last-year's workbooks so
they can be reused. Serious Samar Khatab, a 13-year-old in fifth
grade, sums up the problem saying, ``It is because of the
sanctions. The enemy countries want to take everything from us
because we were rich.'' (Kaplow, Cox News Service). 15. WITH
PHOTOS. MOVED Tuesday in (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON-ACCORD _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The Dayton Peace Accord is four
years old and while it ended a nightmarish civil war, the codicils
in it that have not been completely ignored have been broken.
Bosnia-Herzegovina is an increasingly fractured country where
ethnic Serbs, Muslims and Croats largely refuse to live together
anymore; which was the goal of the Serbs in the 1992-1995 fighting
in the first place. Looking at what the peace that bears Dayton's
name has done. (Bebbington, Cox News Service). 50.
</P>
<P>
   MONTSERRAT-VOLCANO _ MONTSERRAT _ This small island made
headlines when Soufriere Hills, its long-dormant volcano, awoke
from its slumber in 1995, eventually killing 19 people and forcing
the evacuation of much of the island. Although scientists
maintained that the northern third of the island was safe,
Montserrat's tourism industry was decimated. Still, 3,000 residents
-- of the original 10,000 -- refused to leave their homeland in the
hopes that their volcano would quiet down. The volcano continues to
steam, but scientists say it has entered a period of repose. So how
do you rebuild an island when so many roads, houses and schools
have been completely wiped out? (Emling, Cox News Service). 30.
WITH PHOTOS and info for locator map. MOVED Tuesday in (i)
International and (t) Travel categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MONTSERRAT-EXPATS _ MONTSERRAT _ On this island, Robert and
Beverly Kleeb are known as the ``cliffhangers.'' The couple retired
here in 1994, building an $800,000 dream house on a cliff in Isles
Bay, a posh area often referred to as Montserrat's own Beverly
Hills. A year later, the island's long-dormant volcano erupted. But
the Kleebs, who say they have all their money tied up in their
retirement home, have refused to leave. They alone have stayed on
in the shadow of the volcano in open defiance of a government order
to leave the so-called danger zone. ``I'm 70 years old and I've
done everything I've wanted to do in this world,'' said Beverly
Kleeb, a retired psychiatrist from Michigan. ``If I have to be
french-fried, then that's OK with me.'' (Emling, Cox News Service).
20. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED Tuesday in the (i) International and (t)
Travel categories.
</P>
<P>
   MONTSERRAT-BOX _ With locator map information; data on
Montserrat. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-COKE _ MIAMI _ Is Fidel Castro going to start selling
counterfeit Coca-Cola? The Cuban president is threatening to make
knock-offs of Coke and other U.S. brands to protest a recent New
York court ruling that gives Bacardi, and not Cuba's joint venture
with Pernod Ricard, a French company, rights to the Havana Club
trademark in the United States. Pernod has appealed. But if that
fails, tourists may have a hard time detecting the ``Real Thing''
in Cuba. Havana Club rum is the communist island's prize liquor.
(Emling, Cox News Service). MOVED Thursday in (i) International and
(f) Financial categories.
</P>
