<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2902 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-12 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: LIGHTEN UP, BABY! 
</HEADLINE>
  (With STARR-CLINTONS) 
 (bl)  
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If Hillary Rodham Clinton runs for the Senate, she
will be roughed up by a vengeful, two-fisted, single-minded
prosecutor, a guy who actually enjoys slapping manacles on people.
</P>
<P>
   And as though that weren't scary enough, she'll also have to
contend with Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Even a Yankees cap might not save her.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr and Hillary Clinton, it seems, have some
unfinished business. Of course, with Starr, business is always
unfinished.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the first lady is about to achieve lift-off as a Senate
candidate, and an independent woman, who should pop out to drag her
back down into the scandal swamp but the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, gentle readers, you won't believe this, but Javert is still
on the case, darkly scheming to destroy a Clinton on our dime. The
only thing that has changed is the Clinton _ now it's the Mrs.
</P>
<P>
   If he had any sense of shame, or any survival skills, the
prosecutor might have decided to stop investigating when the
Justice Department began investigating him. He might have decided
to shut down the Starr Chamber before the independent counsel law
expires at the end of June. He might have decided to give up once
he realized there was not enough evidence to indict the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   But he is still on revenge autopilot, carrying on the charade
that he is not partisan.
</P>
<P>
   Now he plots to release his final report on the Clintons at a
time when it could scald Hillary's nascent Senate campaign. A Starr
associate told Neil Lewis of The New York Times that the report's
descriptions of Mrs. Clinton's actions could be ``blistering.''
</P>
<P>
   It's likely to stir up the Gatsbyesque flotsam and jetsam
floating in the wake of her Senate dream. He will want to dredge up
all the damaging Hillary garbage: the woeful Whitewater, the crass
Castle Grande trailer park, the disappearing and reappearing Rose
Law Firm billing records, and other White House scandals in which
her name figured prominently _ the firing of the travel-office
staffers and the violation of FBI confidential personnel files,
many on Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The great struggle of the buttoned-down prosecutor and the
unbuttoned president seems risible in retrospect _ like some
Washington version of ``Austin Powers,'' with Starr cast as the
peevish, power-mad Dr. Evil scheming to destroy our puerile but
lovable hero, the shagadelic playboy with the pelt on his chest,
Bill Clinton.  &UR; Oh, behave, baby! &LR;
</P>
<P>
   But Starr does not seem to realize he is a figure of ridicule.
Even one of his own advisers suggested to the Times that if Starr
can't bring charges, perhaps he should just ``shut up.'' Far from
shutting up or shutting down, he is trying to reclaim the limelight
by going on a Sunday show on conservative-friendly, Murdoch-owned
Fox TV. Even though television cameras blessedly no longer record
his morning coffee imbibing and trash disposing, he is still
insistent on sitting in moral judgment of the Clintons. He cannot
indict. He cannot impeach. But he can still impugn.
</P>
<P>
   He is also pursuing two trials prosecuting Webster Hubbell. In
one, which is scheduled to begin in August, Hubbell is charged with
hiding information about the role he and one of his Rose Law Firm
partners, Mrs. Clinton, played in an Arkansas land deal that
contributed to the fall of an S&AMP;L.
</P>
<P>
   In that indictment of Hubbell, Hillary is identified only as
``The Billing Partner.'' But Starr could call her as a witness in
the trial, and that would be embarrassing, coming right as she is
starting her new life as a carpetbagger.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a capital that has seen plenty of riveting feuds, this
one is remarkable. The liberal first lady and the conservative
prosecutor have always seemed destined _ or doomed _ to slug it
out, ever since she went on television after the Monica story broke
and branded Starr as part of what she called a conspiracy of hate
against the Clintons, ``a politically motivated prosecutor who is
allied with the right-wing opponents of my husband.''
</P>
<P>
   As Alessandra Stanley wrote in the Times in January 1998, the
two are opposite-sex doppelgangers. They are both accomplished,
brainy lawyers, devoted parents, religious, relentless and, when
they wish to be, charming.
</P>
<P>
   A Starr associate told the Times that while the special
prosecutor would like to leave, ``he doesn't think he can.''
</P>
<P>
   Think again, Mr. Starr.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
