<HEADER>
A2910 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLAND-POPE-ART-2TAKE     06-12 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLAND-POPE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE, HURT IN FALL, TELLS POLES TO RESIST SECULARISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW _ With three stitches in his forehead after he slipped
and hit his head in the Vatican Embassy, Pope John Paul II
explained Saturday how Catholics should behave in newly democratic
Poland.
</P>
<P>
   The pope, who according to his spokesman, Joaquin Navarro-Valls,
suffered ``no neurological repercussions'' or other serious effects
on his health from the fall, omitted the harshest condemnations of
``free love'' and the ``culture of death,'' his term for abortion,
that were in his prepared homily and that are leitmotifs of his
homilies to American and European Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, wearing a small bandage and speaking in a strong voice,
the Roman Catholic leader urged Poles to resist secularism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not be afraid to live in a way contrary to fashionable
opinions and ways of life in conflict with God's law,'' he told
more than 400,000 followers who gathered for a Mass in Sandomeirz,
a small town in southeastern Poland.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the 79-year-old pope's moral preachings have had a
gentler, more understanding tone than in 1991, when he scolded
Poles, perhaps prematurely, for allowing themselves to be seduced
by the worst excesses of freedom.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the softening is that since 1997 a center-right
government coalition has replaced one dominated by former
Communists, and it has passed laws, including restrictions on
abortion, that are closer to church teaching.
</P>
<P>
   But the pope, who told his bishops on Friday that this 13-day
trip to his native land is his ``crowning'' pilgrimage, does not
want the Polish church to retire from public life now that the
struggle against Communism is won. He wants to coax bishops,
priests and, most important, Catholic laymen to work harder to
inject Christian moral values into a democratic Poland before
Western-style secularism has a chance to seep in.
</P>
<P>
   The church has lost some of the power it held when it was seen
as the country's main bastion against the Communist authorities.
But by European standards, the Catholic Church in Poland remains
unusually influential. The pope is seeking to secure the church's
moral authority without inhibiting Poland's newly minted democracy.
</P>
<P>
   But to do so, he has to resolve conflicts wedged deep in the
Polish church, which since Communism collapsed has found itself
more subject to public scrutiny and criticism. Within the Polish
hierarchy, formed by World War II and the battle against Communism,
there are clashing ideological views and lingering prejudices.
</P>
<P>
   As the pope was reminded on Friday, when Poland's chief rabbi
implored him to remove a large cross at Auschwitz, a deeply
contested issue in Poland, his calls for interfaith understanding
are not always heeded in full.
</P>
<P>
   When John Paul held a Mass earlier this week in Torun, close
observers of church politics in Poland wondered how he would handle
Radio Marya, the powerful and virulenty right-wing Catholic station
based there. Radio Marya has five million listeners and is so
outspoken that the priest who founded it was chastised by the
conservative Catholic primate of Poland, Jozef Cardinal Glemp,
three years ago. The pope did not say anything about the station on
his last visit, in 1997, disappointing many liberal Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   At the Mass, Radio Marya had front-row seats under a large
yellow-and-white Radio Marya banner. The pope wished its listeners
and employees joy, and thanked them for ``the catechization
conducted through radio waves.'' Its founder, the Rev. Tadeusz
Rydzyk, however, was noticeably absent.
</P>
<P>
   In Torun, the pope hinted that the most gratingly partisan
voices of the church should simmer down, without relinquishing
their larger pastoral mission. But he sometimes has to overcome the
instincts of his own bishops.
</P>
<P>
   Many conservative Catholic leaders were initially opposed to
their country seeking membership in the European Union, fearing
that the kind of anticlericism found in France and Germany could
infect Poland. The pope, however, wants Poland's deeply rooted
Catholicism to infect the rest of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe needs a Poland that believes deeply and is culturally
creative in a Christian way, conscious of the role that providence
has entrusted to it,'' he told the bishops on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   George Weigel, a papal biographer from the United States, said,
``In Poland's church, it is not really an issue of conservatives
vs. liberals, it's the Wojtyla church versus the national church.''
</P>
<P>
   The political pronouncements of Catholic clergymen have
noticeably declined even since the pope's 1997 visit, which was
seen by Catholics and non-Catholics as ushering a new mood of
reconciliation in Poland. Perhaps accordingly, the spiritual side
of the church is relatively healthy, but it is hard to measure its
real weight. Bishops complain that church attendance is down,
especially among the young. Yet priestly vocations are back up to
nearly 1,800 new seminarians, the same number as in 1987, when the
church was seen as a national defender of freedom and had immense
prestige. They had dropped to 1,350 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Poland's new Constitution does not refer to the Catholic Church
as the state religion, but in all but name it is. Ninety percent of
the population is Catholic, and while religious instruction in
schools is voluntary, few students have the nerve to decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be considered strange if I didn't go,'' said Bartosz
Rzepczynski, 19, of his high-school religion classes. ``But that
doesn't mean I listen. It's boring.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope, however, still fascinates the young. Rzepczynski had
traveled by train to Torun from his small town of Dzialdowa to
attend the pope's Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The pope has held a number of ecumenical services in Poland,
including a service alongside bishops of the Polish Orthodox Church
in Drohiczyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pope wants every Catholic to be ecumenical, to be open to
dialogue, especially with the Eastern Church,'' said the Rev.
Maciej Zieba, a Dominican priest in Warsaw who is an informal
adviser to the pope, ``That means better relations with Russia and
the Orthodox Church, and that can be difficult for the older
generation. There are deep wounds on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Semitism remains a problem for the Catholic Church here,
where the pope's message of reconciliation is sometimes filtered by
Polish nationalism and the country's own tragic memories of the
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jews are not part of the Polish martyrology,'' Zieba said.
``Every family has a father or uncle who died in the camps. They
are not as aware of the Jewish tragedy. Especially in the church we
should keep that memory alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most outspoken anti-Semites in the church have been
curbed, most notably Henryk Jankowski, who was once a spiritual
adviser to Lech Walesa, the founder of the Solidarity trade union
movement, and is now barred from preaching. But there are bishops
who are openly uninterested in interfaith dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Liberal Poles who follow internal church politics were heartened
by the recent promotion of Archbishop Henryk Muszynski, who is an
advocate of ecumenicism, to metropolitan of Gniezno, a prestigious
post.
</P>
<P>
   ``These days, good relations with Jews won't hurt your career in
the church, and can help it,'' said Konstantin Gebert, a journalist
and Jewish activist. ``But even today, expressing mildly
anti-Semitic thoughts won't hurt your career, either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
