<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2915 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-ART-750     06-12 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-ART-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO FORCES POUR INTO KOSOVO, TAKING CONTROL FROM RETREATING SERBS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DJENERAL JANKOVIC, Yugoslavia _ As NATO troops surged into
Kosovo from Macedonia Saturday morning, American Apache
helicopters, which President Clinton had dispatched to Albania two
months ago but then kept out of combat, coursed overhead, providing
air cover to the vanguard force.
</P>
<P>
   British paratroopers from the 5th Airborne Brigade, who seized
the mountains on either side of the valley that wends its way north
of this border town, led the way as NATO troops, mostly British and
French, moved into Kosovo from the south and east.
</P>
<P>
   The border crossing here had been abandoned by Serbian
authorities, although the Yugoslav flag still fluttered in the
breeze. In a valley down the hill from the border, there was a vast
field of cars that Kosovo Albanians had been forced to abandon when
they fled.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, a hulking cement factory showed severe damage from NATO
bombs. Four donkeys stood in the shade outside. An ethnic Albanian
village near the border, Seciste, remained deserted, some of its
houses scarred by fire.
</P>
<P>
   NATO moved into Kosovo only after 78 days of intense bombing and
missile strikes, which succeeded in wearing down the Serbian
forces, but at the cost of destroying many of Kosovo's bridges,
roads and other facilities.
</P>
<P>
   It will take at least eight more days before the last Serbian
forces withdraw and the NATO force, which will ultimately include
some 50,000 peacekeepers, takes control.
</P>
<P>
   By midday, NATO officials had reported few problems, although a
column of French troops, entering from the south, stalled only a
few miles inside Kosovo, when it encountered an unmarked minefield.
</P>
<P>
   There were reports that retreating units of Yugoslavia's
Serbian-dominated army and police had torched houses in Djakovica
and Janik, but by and large, the Serbs were said to be cooperating
with the occupation of the province. In the case of the French
troops, a Yugoslav officer helped identify the location of the
mines so they could be cleared.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Richard Dannert, commander of Britain's contingent
here, said that the first troops encountered a few groups of
Serbian civilians, as well as members of the separatist Kosovo
Liberation Army, but no resistance. ``In both cases, their attitude
was compliant,'' he said from his base in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, Gen. Wesley Clark, NATO's top commander in Europe,
said Saturday afternoon that NATO troops had secured the road to
Pristina from Macedonia's capital, Skopje.
</P>
<P>
   On the Macedonia side of the border Saturday morning, thousands
of refugees spilled out of the sprawling, dusty camps that have
been their homes for weeks and cheered as tanks, armored vehicles,
troop carriers and other NATO vehicles rumbled toward the Kosovo
border.
</P>
<P>
   One refugee called it the liberation of Kosovo. A group then
began to sing a Kosovar anthem: ``I gave my word; I will give my
life for Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   At Stankovic 2 Camp, Alije Latifaj, who fled Kosovo with six
members of her family on May 27, was ecstatic. ``Yes! Yes!'' she
said when asked if she expected to return home soon. ``This is the
hope that keeps us alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, at the border crossing here, refugees were not rushing to
go home. Most said they would wait at least a few days before
trying to return to the villages they had to flee when Serbian
forces swept through.
</P>
<P>
   One man, however, did not wait. Shaban Bella, 65, crossed the
border back into Kosovo on foot, ignoring the entreaties of U.N.
refugee officials. ``I am going to see if my house is burned,'' he
said, vowing to walk to his village, Kacanik, a few miles up the
road.
</P>
<P>
   Blerta Mustafa, a Kosovo Albanian translator who accompanied a
reporter into Kosovo Saturday morning, used a cellular phone to
call her father in Macedonia to tell him that she had returned to
Kosovo, two months after fleeing her home in Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's troops entered the province from two directions: British,
Italian, German and a platoon of Americans from the Army's 82nd
Airborne Division from the south, and the French along two mountain
roads to the east. A force led by German troops will enter from
Albania, crossing the border on the road between Kukes and Prizren,
an area of intense fighting between Serbian forces and the Kosovo
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   The operation faces many uncertainties, including the ultimate
role of the Russian troops within the Kosovo peacekeeping force.
There are also the rebels, land mines and the thousands of
displaced Albanians who never left the province.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Land mines hampered the progress of the French troops. A
contingent of 250 French marines in armored personnel carriers
towing mortars departed at dawn from the border as planned but
immediately found mines crisscrossing the dirt road inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   For the next five hours a scouting party searched for
alternative routes while the soldiers in sunglasses joked, smoked
cigarettes and read magazines to pass the time.
</P>
<P>
   After a six-hour delay, the column moved down another road but
found mines there too and began the painstaking process of clearing
them.
</P>
<P>
   A second column of roughly 450 French soldiers tried to enter
Kosovo on a slightly better dirt road. But they too were thwarted
by land mines and had only made their way a few miles inside Kosovo
as of Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the American troops amassed in Macedonia, led by
troops from the 82nd Airborne and the 26th Marine Expeditionary
Unit, were expected to enter Kosovo over the next few days, when
they will take over one of five sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Second Lt. Toma Kim of the 82nd Airborne led the first American
ground troops into Kosovo. His squad, a convoy of 10 vehicles,
including armored Humvees mounted with 50-caliber machine guns ,
merged into the main column heading north.
</P>
<P>
   After spending two months in Albania with the Apache
helicopters, he said, the Americans were eager finally to go, but
anxious about what they would find.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to go up there and see how bad it really is,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
