<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2939 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAFFLEHOUSE-SUITS-COX     06-12 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAFFLEHOUSE-SUITS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waffle House: Customers dish out bias suits across 3 states
 &HT;    (Package includes WAFFLEHOUSE, WAFFLEHOUSE-SUITS,
WAFFLEHOUSE-TRIVIA and photos.)
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They call themselves the vampires, the overnight
workers who unload trucks and restock shelves at the Wal-Mart
Supercenter in Hiram. It was Dec. 11, the Christmas rush, and with
four trailers to empty before dawn, they were looking forward to
their meal break. At 2 a.m., nine of them piled into their cars and
drove down U.S. 278 to one of the few restaurants open at that hour
in Paulding County, a Waffle House.
</P>
<P>
   They sat at several uncleaned tables and waited. Half an hour
later, still waiting, they confronted a waitress about why they
weren't being served.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y'all can go eat somewhere else,'' they say she told them.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers Rachel couldn't understand it. The restaurant wasn't
busy. His friends weren't acting rowdy. They'd eaten at the place
once before without problems. The waitresses were serving other
people, including two white women. Rachel's party was mixed: six
black, three white.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only reason I could figure,'' he says. ``That was
the hurtin' thing about it.''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, all nine of the night-shift workers filed a
federal lawsuit charging Waffle House with racial discrimination.
It's one of five pending civil rights suits brought by customers
against the company or its franchisees in Georgia, Alabama and
South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have the makings of a Denny's situation here,'' says
Daniel Huff, the Atlanta lawyer who is representing the Wal-Mart
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Denny's _ the word can send shivers up the corporate spine. In
1994, the Spartanburg, S.C.-based chain of coffee shops showed how
costly civil rights controversies can get when it paid $46 million
to settle two class-action suits involving thousands of black
customers. The case began with six Secret Service agents who said
they had been denied service at a Denny's in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Waffle House and its franchisees have contested the allegations
in each of the suits. Some 30,000 people work in 1,200 Waffle
Houses across the Sun Belt, half of them company-owned. All
staffers are governed by a thick employee handbook, ``The Waffle
House Way,'' which forbids discriminatory behavior and directs
anyone who sees it to ``stop it, fix it and report it'' by calling
a toll-free line at corporate headquarters in Norcross.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our policy is zero tolerance,'' says Chris Jacobsen, vice
president for communications. He would not comment on specific
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the most troublesome area for Waffle House has been
gender relations. In 1997, a federal judge in Texas stung the
company with an $8.1 million verdict in a sexual harassment
complaint brought by a personnel recruiter who had worked with
Waffle House for 3 1/2 years.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Therese Scribner claimed that her immediate
bosses had made fun of her large bust and had once placed a camera
between her legs and snapped a picture. In an unusually angry
opinion, Judge Jerry Buchmeyer called her superiors ``liars'' and
concluded that Waffle House CEO Joe Rogers Jr. knew of the
harassment but did nothing to stop it, fix it or investigate it.
The two supervisors accused of the worst harassment still work for
the company, one of them at headquarters. Waffle House is appealing
the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least six other sexual harassment suits pending
against Waffle House and its franchisees.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only two racial discrimination cases have cost the
restaurant chain. Last year, two black couples who said they had
been refused service in a Clinton, Ala., Waffle House settled out
of court with the company that ran the unit, Treetop Enterprises
(now SouthEast Waffles) of Nashville. And in January, a federal
jury awarded eight Atlanta teenagers $440,000 for emotional
distress in an incident at a Waffle House in Commerce, Ga. The
teens, part of the North Atlanta High School band, said a cook
called them racist names when they stopped by after performing at a
football game in 1996. Although the jury sided with the eight, it
did not find evidence of discrimination. Hillcrest Foods of
Suwanee, which runs the unit, is appealing.
</P>
<P>
   The other discrimination cases are so similar they could have
been poured from the same pot of coffee. All happened late at night
and all involved white waitresses and black customers.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Alabama, six customers say a waitress refused to serve them
at a unit in the Birmingham suburb of Hoover. They sued in March.
(The franchisee, SouthEast Waffles, investigated and fired the
waitress within 24 hours, says Hugh C. Howser Jr., an attorney
representing the company.)
</P>
<P>
   _ In South Carolina, nine family members took a break from
visiting a sick relative and went to the Waffle House in Santee.
They say a waitress accused them of stealing silverware and loudly
berated them with racial slurs. They sued her, the manager and
Waffle House.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Georgia, an emergency room clerk and his wife say they were
denied service when they tried to eat at a Waffle House in Forsyth.
When they grew upset, a white Forsyth police officer who was there
off-duty advised them not to make a scene but to contact a lawyer
if they wanted to press their case. The officer, Alvin Bearden,
later gave a deposition supporting their complaint. ``None of the
Caucasian patrons had any problems getting service that I
noticed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The night-shift workers in Hiram say they were not eager to join
the roster of Waffle House litigants. After they left Wal-Mart
around 7 that morning, still hungry from having missed their meal,
they went back to the restaurant as a group and asked the manager
in charge why the waitress had treated them so rudely.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he'd just apologized and offered us a free breakfast or
something, it probably would have stopped right there,'' Rachel
says. ``But he folded his arms and said he hadn't been there, so he
hadn't seen anything. There was nothing he could do.''
</P>
<P>
   The group talked it over and then contacted a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   For Shari Chase, a 37-year-old white co-worker, it was a matter
of accountability. ``If I treated a customer like that at
Wal-Mart,'' she says, ``I'd be fired.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachel's motivation in suing was more personal. The 60-year-old
Paulding County native was a grown man before segregation was
outlawed in 1964. He drove a rig back then and remembers what it
was like to be turned away from a truck stop because of the color
of his skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought all that was over,'' he says. ``I've got a
10-year-old daughter now, and I don't want her to see anything like
this again, ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
