<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waffle House: Weird and wonderful trivia
 &HT;    (Package includes WAFFLEHOUSE, WAFFLEHOUSE-SUITS,
WAFFLEHOUSE-TRIVIA and photos.)
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WAFFLEPRAISE: Waffle House joined the likes of Spago and Chez
Panisse on Saveur magazine's ``Saveur 100,'' the gourmet
publication's list of things it loves. How did a chain of
greasy-spoon diners rate such recognition from such a
discriminating magazine? One of the editors, Ann McCarthy, grew up
with WH in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   WAFFLEBELLS: People have been known to marry at WH. In
Lawrenceville, Ga., a cook and a waitress said their vows in front
of the jukebox. In Attalla, Ala., witnesses tossed uncooked grits
and hash browns at the happy couple.
</P>
<P>
   WAFFLEGRUB: The most popular menu item isn't waffles; it's
coffee, followed by hash browns, then waffles. And, no, don't ask
for pancakes _ unless you know the cook real well.
</P>
<P>
   WAFFLESONGS: ``Waffle Doo Wop,'' ``Good Food Fast,'' ``There Are
Raisins in My Toast'' _ the kitschy house music you find in every
WH jukebox is available on CD. For information, call 1-877-923-3532
or go to www.wafflehousesongs.com.
</P>
<P>
   WAFFLEMATH: WH claims it has found 844,739 ways to prepare a
hamburger. In a song about it, a customer describes what happened
when he asked a waitress to name them: ``She said, `You can have it
rare, medium or well inside; single, double or triple fried; mayo,
mustard, lettuce, onions and ketchup, too; pickles, cheese, chili,
bacon ...' and suddenly her voice started shakin', she was runnin'
out of air and turning blue.'' The 844,739 figure, incidentally,
was calculated by a mathematics class at Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   WAFFLEFIGHT: Four co-workers at the Grand Bay, Ala., WH sued a
waitress to force her to share winnings from a lottery ticket that
had been given to them by a customer. A jury told her to split the
$10 million.
</P>
<P>
   WAFFLEPOLS: During the last presidential campaign, Bob Dole
joked that Bill Clinton had turned the White House into the Waffle
House.
</P>
<P>
   WAFFLEBOSS: Joe Rogers Jr., WH's CEO and majority owner, is a
mover and shaker in Republican politics who has signed on with
George W. Bush's finance committee.
</P>
<P>
   WAFFLEWOOD: In the movie ``Tin Cup,'' the golf pro played by
Kevin Costner celebrates his unlikely victory at WH.
</P>
<P>
   WAFFLEJOCKS: Athletes eat up WH. Among its frequent customers
are Deion Sanders, Evander Holyfield and Pete Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   WAFFLEWEAR: Musicians like WH, too. Customers at the WH near
Nashville's Opryland swear that Marty Stuart once stopped by for
coffee _ in his pajamas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
