<HEADER>
A2942 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAPTISTS-PRESIDENT-CO     06-12 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-PRESIDENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern Baptists focus on issues at convention
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Southern Baptists from around the country will gather
in the Georgia Dome this week for what promises to be a meeting
full of praising, preaching and politicking over issues ranging
from TV violence to human embryo research.
</P>
<P>
   About 14,000 ``messengers'' are expected to register, with
thousands of family members and employees of Baptist agencies and
institutions also attending.
</P>
<P>
   Early risers will convene at 8 a.m. Tuesday for music led by the
Revival Choir and Sunday Celebration Orchestra of First Baptist
Church in Snellville. The faithful will leave after 9:10 p.m.
Wednesday and the benediction by Alabama evangelist Junior Hill.
</P>
<P>
   In between, there will be a welcome by Chick-Fil-A founder
Truett Cathey, testimony by football player Reggie White and a
prayer by the Rev. Jerry Falwell, best known as founder of Liberty
University and the now-defunct Moral Majority.
</P>
<P>
   This year's annual presidential election is expected to be
uncontested, with the Rev. Paige Patterson, president of
Southeastern Baptist Theological Seminary in Wake Forest, N.C.,
sliding into a second term.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson, an architect of the conservative resurgence in the
denomination over the last quarter century, said he plans to focus
on the need to reach the nation's major urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   His push comes when the Southern Baptist Convention has recorded
its first loss in membership since 1926.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson said in a recent telephone interview that he is
especially concerned about ``getting out of our traditional South
area.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to move the image of the denomination beyond Dixie,
two messengers to last year's convention proposed changing the name
to something less regional. But the denomination's executive
committee found in February that there is ``no compelling
rationale'' for a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The geographical designation in my estimation is not the most
helpful,'' Patterson said. ``The problem is there really isn't a
good name out there that anybody's come up with that is any better.
And although Southern Baptist is no longer a geographical
designation, it is the truth that 'Southern Baptist' says something
theologically. If somebody says I'm Southern Baptist, everybody
knows to either pucker or duck.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's meeting of Southern Baptists may be asked to take
stands on several issues in the news, according to Richard Land,
president of the SBC's Ethics and Religious Liberty Commission.
Land says his agency, which address social issues on behalf of
Southern Baptists, wants the commission to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Come out against research on human embryos. Last month, a
panel appointed by President Clinton recommended that the federal
government begin funding some research on human embryos, citing
evidene that some embryo cells can potentially grow into
replacement tissues to treat a variety of diseases. ``When you
start arguing that it's all right to kill human embryos in order to
do treatments and research that benefit other people, you're
lowering yourselves to biotechnical cannibalism in which you're
eating your own young in order to sustain your health or extend
your life,'' Land said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Condemn ethnic cleansing, wherever it occurs. ``If the 20th
century has taught us anything, it has taught us where that
leads,'' Land said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Urge a reduction of violence in entertainment. ``These people
who are pimping this kind of behavior to our children need to be
called to account, and we need to be called to account for not
having stopped this kind of emotional abuse of our children,'' Land
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
