<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2945 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORME-COX     06-12 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORME-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mel Torme: The crooner loved his craft
 &HT;    By Richard L. Eldredge
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was a songwriter, arranger, actor, drummer and author. What
jazz listeners worldwide will miss most about Mel Torme, however,
is that voice.
</P>
<P>
   It was soothing, silky and fluid. It was the audio equivalent of
warm butterscotch inching lazily down scoops of ice cream in a
parfait glass. And whether it was coming from a phone, echoing from
a stage or seated across from you, it was the first thing that
rattled and awakened your senses in the singer's presence.
Incredibly, its strength and range actually improved as Torme aged.
``I've never smoked or drank or messed with any kind of drugs
ever,'' he explained in 1989. ``I guess that's why everything still
works.''
</P>
<P>
   On June 5, at age 73, the complications from a 1996 stroke
finally silenced ``the Velvet Fog.'' But Mel Torme leaves behind a
singing legacy matched, arguably, only by Frank Sinatra, Ella
Fitzgerald and Billie Holiday.
</P>
<P>
   If not for the love of his craft, the jazz and pop vocalist
could have been but a tiny footnote in a guide to American
songwriters. At age 21, in 40 minutes on a sweltering day in
California's San Fernando Valley, Torme and lyricist Bob Wells
banged out ``The Christmas Song (Chestnuts Roasting on an Open
Fire).'' The result was a lifelong pile of money for both. There
are close to 3,000 recorded versions of the seasonal standard
written in the July heat in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never, ever thought I would be sitting here discussing the
50th anniversary of that tune,'' Torme said in 1995. ``Everyone
thought it was a one-night song. We just hoped that the Nat Cole
version would do OK. Every time I get a royalty check, I'm stunned.
Sure, I could have retired, there's no question about that. I just
enjoy performing too much.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing Torme enjoyed more was his role as an
international jazz ambassador. Even during interviews, he spoke
using a jazz musician's vocabulary. Conversations were sprinkled
liberally with ``babes'' and ``cats.'' Concerts were ``gigs'' or
``dates.'' Musical mistakes were ``clams.'' His arrangements were
his ``charts.'' Torme's reputation as a scat singer, matched only
by his idol Fitzgerald and Jon Hendricks, was a source of great
pride.
</P>
<P>
   The crooner enjoyed blurring racial divides. The first sentence
of his 1988 memoir, ``It Wasn't All Velvet,'' reads: ``Ethel Waters
was once widely quoted as having said, `Mel Torme is the only white
man who sings with the soul of a black man.'''
</P>
<P>
   The accomplished artist was equally savvy at business. He
actively marketed himself to the children and grandchildren of the
bobby-soxers who first swooned to the crooner in the 1940s. He did
13 guest shots on the NBC sitcom ``Night Court'' and popped up on
an episode of ``Seinfeld.'' He recorded with new wave rock combo
Was (Not Was). In 1995 he faked a sky-diving jump while singing ``I
Get a Kick Out of You'' in a Mountain Dew commercial. ``I actually
jumped just 30 feet,'' quipped Torme. ``At my age, it felt like
200!''
</P>
<P>
   In between concerts and acting, Torme turned to writing. In
addition to an autobiography, he penned ``Wynner,'' a novel; ``The
Other Side of the Rainbow,'' a 1970 memoir of his time spent as the
musical arranger on Judy Garland's ill-fated television show;
1991's ``Traps,'' a biography of pal and jazz drummer Buddy Rich;
and 1994's ``My Singing Teachers: Reflections on Singing Popular
Music.''
</P>
<P>
   Before a stroke stripped him of his greatest instrument, Torme
reflected on his place in the music world. ``People are always
asking me, `Who's going to take your place?''' he said. ```Who's
coming up who can sing scat and sing jazz with your approach?'
Sadly, I've looked and I can't point a finger at anyone in the
business right now.'' As far as male performers go, only Harry
Connick Jr. comes to mind as a figure currently on the jazz scene
who shares Torme's ability to write, arrange, play a variety of
instruments and act and who has Torme's respect for jazz
traditions.
</P>
<P>
   On his final live recording, ``A&AMP;E Presents an Evening With Mel
Torme,'' released in 1996, Torme paused midway through his set to
pay tribute to a recently departed singing idol. ``Ella
Fitzgerald,'' he said. ``There was only one of those. We've lost a
heavyweight.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could well be said of ``the Velvet Fog.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
