<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2947 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC-PREVIEW-COX     06-12 1881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-PREVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fallout continues as IOC convenes
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The seismic upheaval that shook the foundation of the
Olympic movement is just over six months old. The aftershocks could
be felt for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   In Sydney, International Olympic Committee members will feel the
tremors on the streets, where cost-cutting organizers threaten to
transport the highnesses in buses rather than Mercedes-Benzes
during the 2000 Summer Games. They also might have to tone down
playing facilities and athlete housing.
</P>
<P>
   In Salt Lake City, where a bribery scandal involving 2002 Winter
Games officials and IOC members erupted last November, organizing
committee president Mitt Romney just cut $98 million out of his
budget. The shaking will be felt under the skis and skates of U.S.
athletes, who face limited training access to venues before the
Games.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Congress is considering legislation that could
drive sponsors away from the Games and deter cities from seeking
the Olympics. And there's no telling what shock waves would emanate
from Atlanta when congressional investigators, looking for evidence
of fraud and bribery in Olympic records at the Atlanta History
Center, go public with any findings.
</P>
<P>
   In Lausanne, Switzerland, home of the IOC, 10 members have been
booted, and reforms are being considered on how the committee does
its business.
</P>
<P>
   How far will those reforms go? Will the aftershocks cease and
normalcy return? Or will the Olympic landscape someday be reshaped
and unrecognizable? Some clues will emerge this week when the IOC
begins to put the darkest days of its 105-year-history behind it as
the general assembly meets in Seoul, South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the IOC's private club still claim that the Salt Lake
scandal and its spread to other bid cities was a creation of
overzealous media and ambitious U.S. politicians. They cannot
comprehend how $1 million worth of vacation trips, cash,
scholarships, skis and semi-automatic shotguns provided by
ambitious hosts of the 2002 Games could have wrought all this
global handwringing.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, in an effort to silence the critics and reassure its
corporate sponsors, the IOC has promised to change its ways. In
addition to running off its worst offenders, the committee
appointed an ethics panel to forge a code of conduct and created an
80-member reform panel that includes such luminaries as former
Secretary of State Henry Kissinger and Peter Ueberroth, who
operated the successful Los Angeles Games of 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The reform group gathered two weeks ago to consider ways to
restructure the IOC and revamp the Olympic bidding and selection
system. While they came up with little consensus on the specfics,
Kissinger, one of 36 outside members on the panel, said he thinks
that the IOC is moving in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a legitimate forum, and I think serious efforts
have been made,'' Kissinger said, giving some credibility to the
IOC's commitment to change.
</P>
<P>
   The reform panel will present preliminary findings at this
week's meetings. It says the IOC should include athletes who are
elected by active Olympic competitors. And it proposes a new
bidding system for the 2008 Summer Games, for which 10 cities are
lining up to compete.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC has a poor history of enacting reforms, especially in
efficiency and frugality. Next year's Summer Games will offer 300
medal events, 29 more than in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bigger is not better,'' Ueberroth told the reform group. ``If
the Games get any bigger, no city or country will be able to do it
well.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC also shows little inclination to curb its mushrooming
membership, which generally amounts to a lifetime privilege.
Corruption attrition hasn't done the trick. Even after six IOC
members were expelled in March and four resigned after being
accused of receiving cash and lavish gifts from Salt Lake City's
bid team, the body still has 105 members. Elections for newcomers
are expected this week.
</P>
<P>
   One more member might get the ax. Phil Coles of Australia
already has been censured for his Salt Lake City escapades and now
is under fire from colleagues for the personal dossiers he compiled
on their tastes and habits and allegedly turned over to bid groups.
</P>
<P>
   A former Olympic rower, Coles barely has been hanging on since
the Atlanta organizers reported to the U.S. House Commerce
Committee that he brought two companions _ one over the limit _ on
an expenses-paid trip here in July 1989. The tab cost $13,053.21,
which the Atlantans said they were happy to pick up.
</P>
<P>
   One member who appears to have weathered the storm is the man at
the top, Juan Antonio Samaranch. The IOC president says he is not
going anywhere, despite pressure from worldwide media and small
segments of his fractured IOC club.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Un-yong, a close ally of Samaranch, said the general
assembly will solidify the president's position this week. ``Mr.
Samaranch has absolute support,'' Kim said. ``In his opening
remarks in Seoul, he will make clear that he will stay on until
2001 and finish his mandate.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim himself has survived an investigation of his own
gift-gobbling, which included a $616 Tiffany jewelry box from
Atlanta bidders.
</P>
<P>
   However, Dick Pound, an IOC vice president, recently echoed out
loud the whispers within the Olympic family _ that Samaranch might
leave after ushering in reforms at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   (Long optional trim begins here)
</P>
<P>
   Kim shares the sentiment of many IOC members, who maintain that
the Salt Lake scandal is being kept alive as a campaign platform
for ambitious U.S. politicians.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz), a presidential contender and a
harsh IOC critic, conducted Senate hearings in which the committee
was accused of fostering a ``culture of corruption'' and not acting
swiftly enough to enact reforms. As chairman of the Senate Commerce
Committee, he has threatened to take away tax deductions given
companies for sponsoring the Olympics, which would hit the IOC
where it really hurts _ in the pocketbook. A proposed bill also
would give the U.S. Olympic Committee control over this country's
television-rights fees for the Games, the IOC's single biggest
source of income.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the House Commerce Committee is investigating
Atlanta's bid for the 1996 Games, while pressuring the White House
to place the IOC under international anti-bribery laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can do what they desire,'' Samaranch said. ``But I
repeat: The IOC is run by the IOC members. . . . We highly respect
the Senate of the United States, but I am sure they also will
respect the IOC.''
</P>
<P>
   Uprooting corruption entirely from the IOC won't be easy, if
only because the roots go deep. Samaranch has been accused of
ignoring accusations for years that some members have had their
hands out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Salt Lake City is, in my opinion, probably one of the most
innocent bid cities in recent times,'' Ueberroth told the panel.
``You know that, and I know that. The culture that caused the
problems started in 1956 and can be easily disposed of by this body
and current leadership of the IOC.''
</P>
<P>
   But Samaranch says he thinks that the scandal has been disposed
of and that reform is on the way. ``This meeting is only the
beginning,'' he said. ``Our aim is to have final decisions by the
end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that is soon enough _ and whether the reforms go far
enough _ is an issue for Sydney and Salt Lake City organizers, who
are facing $400 million shortfalls in their combined budgets. Some
potential sponsors are taking a wait-and-see attitude before
paying. Just last week, the most vocal critic from the corporate
ranks cautioned any sponsors about signing on now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way for corporations to keep the IOC's feet to the
fire on reform is to withhold any new IOC sponsorships until we see
what the reforms are,'' the president of John Hancock Financial
Services, David D'Alessandro, wrote in a newspaper article.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney organizers, who remain about $100 million short of
sponsorship goals, this month trimmed $48 million from their $1.6
billion budget. They blame the IOC's greasy palms for hurting
sponsorship and consumer confidence in the Games and consequently
have cut $3.7 million from their spending on the IOC, sports
federations and National Olympic committees. The Olympic VIPs will
share cars, enjoy reduced catering and get fewer free tickets than
planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly keen to get the IOC to behave as much as
possible like ordinary citizens of Sydney,'' said Sydney Organizing
Committee president Michael Knight. There's also a freeze on
hiring, and organizers reportedly foresee less paid staff and more
volunteers during the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Australian Olympic Committee President John Coates said any
cutbacks could mean changes in the athletes' Olympic Village and in
the stadiums and arenas.
</P>
<P>
   The reduction in Salt Lake's $1.45 billion budget tentatively
includes $5 million lost for the operation of ski jumps, the
bobsled and luge track and the speedskating oval. The venues would
remain closed until just before the Games. U.S. athletes had hoped
to begin training free at the venues beginning next winter.
</P>
<P>
   Romney needs to find money somewhere. Some $300 million short in
sponsor fees, he has asked the IOC to pick up some of its members'
costs in Salt Lake, including hotel charges.
</P>
<P>
   And he is expected to ask the IOC this week to renegotiate its
contract to cut Salt Lake's costs in the same way Sydney's costs
for 2000 are being trimmed _ by deferring royalty payments on
merchandise, sponsorships and tickets.
</P>
<P>
   An IOC spokesman said Salt Lake should not expect much relief.
``We're not the sugar daddy who has all this money hidden under a
tree in Lausanne,'' Franklin Servan-Schreiber said.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC marketing staff isn't helping Salt Lake's cause, either.
It recently announced an increase in worldwide sponsorship fees,
from $40 million to $55 million, for the 2001-2004 quadrennium.
Nine of the 11 current international sponsors are based in the
United States, where the heat from the scandal is hottest.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers in the next two host cities vow that any cutbacks
will have no impact on the spectators or the athletes once the
Games begin.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Ebersol, chairman of NBC Sports, says viewers will forget
the scandal when the flame is lit in Sydney. ``The Olympics, in
terms of viewers and advertisers, are the athletes and competition.
At no reasonable level does anyone think that has been impacted.''
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   The other order of business this week is the selection of a host
city for the 2006 Winter Games. As the IOC copes with the excessive
trips, lavish entertaining and expensive gifts received by its
members, most of the candidates are complaining about an emergency
ban that prevented the members from touring their cities. Under a
trial format this week, a 16-member panel of members and outsiders
will vote to eliminate four hopefuls virtually sight unseen. Then
the entire IOC will pick the winner.
</P>
<P>
   If no loser threatens litigation, the temporary fix might be
made permanent. It would generate yet another after-shock to the
scandal that has shaken the Olympic movement.
</P>
</TEXT>
