<HEADER>
A2999 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAPTISTS-ADVANCE13-CO     06-12 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-ADVANCE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baptists go door-to-door before convention
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Close encounters of the Baptist kind occurred all over
metro Atlanta on Saturday as the Southern Baptist Convention hosted
a giant family festival in Centennial Olympic Park and block
parties in some 20 neighborhoods. Meanwhile, hundreds of Baptists
canvassed door-to-door in about 40 communities from the city to the
farthest suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The effort, known as Crossover Atlanta _ for the sweep across
Atlanta and for Jesus's cross over the city _ will continue on a
smaller scale through Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Junior Carter, a homeless tap-dancer sat on a bench in
Centennial Olympic Park surrounded by four teen-age girls from
Peachtree Corners Baptist Church in Gwinnett County.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me to marry him,'' said Laura Hayes, 15. ``He was
real nice, though.''
</P>
<P>
   The girls had already spent four hours talking to people in the
park.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just ask if they're Christian, and stuff,'' said Sarah
Shaw, 13, also of Peachtree Corners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been awesome,'' said Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-afternoon, teams had reported more than 1,000 religious
conversions with many more groups yet to call in, according to Jack
Smith of the Alpharetta-based North American Mission Board, the
agency responsible for evangelism in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Not every team made a convert, but most had memorable
conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of one group's activities as they canvassed
Candler Park, an urban, gentrified neighborhood, on behalf of three
small Baptist churches in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Archie, 40, is watching her recording of last night's
basketball game when she hears a knock at the door. She opens it to
two young women and a middle-aged man going door-to-door on behalf
of the Southern Baptists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't attend church because they say I'm going to hell
because I'm homosexual,'' says Archie, 40, a graphic artist who
lives with her partner.
</P>
<P>
   The conversations goes on, moving through a discussion of heaven
and a solicitation of prayer requests. Then it comes back to
Baptists and gays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bible-believing, practicing Baptists love you,'' says Ken
Taylor, who teaches urban missions at New Orleans Baptist
Theological Seminary. ``There are things about your likestyle we
don't like, but if we follow the Bible, we know God loves you just
as much as anybody else. That means we love you, too.. . ``
</P>
<P>
   ``The church is fellowship,'' says Agnes Karivki, a masters
degree student at the University of Utah who is originally from
Kenya. ``It's Jesus Christ that binds us together.''
</P>
<P>
   Archie: ``I don't need a church to connect with Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   Kariviki: ``Do you pray?''
</P>
<P>
   Archie: ``I talk to God all the time. . . .To me church is
politics. It's power. We don't need to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor: ``Can I leave this? `` He sticks out a blue photocopied
paper with information about the churches.
</P>
<P>
   Archie: ``I don't want to go. I won't go, I swear. But if it
will make you feel better, I'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor: ``It will make me feel better if you take this.''
</P>
<P>
   Archie, taking the paper: ``All right, darlin'. God bless you.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the street Kerry Clemmons, 33, has been working on the
computer while her 15-month-old son naps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi. I'm Melanie Lawler,'' says the third member of the team, a
graduate student in Christian Education at New Orleans seminary.
</P>
<P>
   Clemmons, standing on the porch of her two-story gray house,
tells them she was not raised in a church and does not go now. If
she did, she would want a church ``that did a lot of things that
mattered to us as a family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you believe people can know for certain that they will
go to heaven?'' asks Lawler, working from a prepared questionaire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't necessarily have a good answer for that,'' says
Clemmons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I tell you what the Bible says?'' asks Lawler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' Clemmons replies.
</P>
<P>
   Clemmons listens intently as Lawler reads about the ``stops'' on
the ``road to hope'' whose destination is eternal life. ``Would you
like to accept Jesus Christ as your personal savior?'' asks Lawler
when she is through.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' says Clemmons. ``I'm not ready for that.''
</P>
<P>
   At a smaller house with brown siding, Joel Kidd, 26, a
Nationsbank manager is asleep. He comes to the door barefooted in
shorts and a t-shirt. He is a regular churchgoer, he tells them, an
Episcopalian by birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were really nice,'' he said when they had gone. ``I've
got to respect them for their faith. I'm not looking to change, but
I think they're doing a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   As he talks, a tatooed man walks his dog down the street
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me, but who are those people?'' the dog-walker asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're from out of town. They're Southern Baptists,'' said
Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southern Baptists,'' the man replied, shaking his head, as he
walked on down the street.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
