<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3000 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS-GEORGIA-COX     06-12 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-GEORGIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia congressmen wrestle with upcoming gun vote
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the weeks since the Senate passed new gun
legislation, Rep. Johnny Isakson (R-Ga.) has heard an earful from
his conservative constituents in the Atlanta suburb of Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson has personally answered more than 500 letters. After a
metro television report misrepresented his position on new gun
measures, saying he favored blanket gun control, Isakson sat at his
desk to field scores of irate calls.
</P>
<P>
   In each letter and call, Isakson said he has patiently explained
that he favors legislation requiring safety locks to be sold with
guns and requiring that all gun purchasers submit to criminal
background checks at gun shows, where 20 percent to 40 percent of
such sales are now exempted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have yet to have anyone tell me that these positions are
inconsistent with a common-sense approach to guns,'' said Isakson.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Isakson and Georgia's 10 other House members will
cast important votes on new gun control. For Isakson and a majority
of the Georgia delegation, some of whom campaigned against
Congress' adoption of the assault weapons ban in 1994, the votes
will be their first on the controversial topic since joining
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Prompted by the deadly shooting in Littleton, Colo. and the near
catastrophe at Heritage High School in Rockdale County, Ga., the
House on Wednesday will take up a massive juvenile crime bill that
now includes new restrictions on the sale of guns to juveniles,
mandatory trigger locks on gun sales and background checks at gun
shows.
</P>
<P>
   An ABC News/Washington Post poll recently found that 89 percent
of Americans favor criminal background checks at gun shows and 75
percent support mandatory trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals have sharply divided Republicans in Congress, and
Georgia's Republican members are among the most vocal critics of
the new legislation. Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.), the state's senior
Democrat, strongly favors the new proposals, while Rep. Sanford
Bishop (D-Ga.), a member of the National Rifle Association whose
rural southwestern district includes thousands of gun owners,
remains uncommitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from an area where people hunt ... and enjoy
shooting,'' Bishop said. ``Guns are a part of the lay of the land.
... My constituents don't want to be punished for the misdeeds of a
few juveniles.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's other Democrat, Rep. Cynthia McKinney, declined to
discuss her views.
</P>
<P>
   Most Georgia Republicans don't think that gun control, however
modest, works, and many are angry that Congress is being forced to
consider the new measures at all.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jack Kingston (R-Ga.) derisively refers to the legislation,
dubbed the Child Safety Act, as the ``political protection act.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What outrages me as a father of four kids, including two
teenagers, is that it's being done on the blood of innocent
children in Colorado and it will do nothing to prevent another
Colorado from happening,'' said Kingston.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Norwood (R-Ga.), who shot and killed a childhood
friend in an accident when he was 16, said he had yet to see any
gun control legislation reduce crime or prevent accidents. Norwood
said trigger locks might even cause more accidents, even though
several studies have shown that they can reduce accidental firings
if properly used.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had people tell me that a lot of these locks are
dangerous,'' Norwood said. Norwood spokesman John Stone later said
the House member does support trigger locks on new guns, but he is
concerned that they could make the guns less useful in
self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nathan Deal (R-Ga.), who voted against the assault weapons
ban in 1994 when he was a Democrat, said he is opposed to mandatory
trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   Most Georgia lawmakers said they favor closing the gun show
loophole. While licensed gun dealers are required to give criminal
background checks, whether at a gun shop or a gun show, unlicensed
dealers are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't know why we allowed that exception at gun
shows,'' said Rep. John Linder (R-Ga.), whose district includes
Conyers. ``That's just crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Linder and other Georgia Republicans, including Isakson,
said they favor only ``instant'' checks at gun shows. Under both
the House and Senate legislation, law enforcement officers would be
allowed up to three days to complete background checks if the
instant check turned up a question. The extra time would give law
enforcement the opportunity to check court records that might not
be immediately available over weekends, when most gun shows take
place.
</P>
<P>
   Some opponents, such as Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), say the time
frame amounts to a waiting period. Most GOP House members are also
suspicious of some of the special record-keeping requirements
imposed on sellers at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA has claimed to its members that the requirements amount
to a national gun registry. Supporters of the measure say it is
essential for law enforcement officers to solve crimes and track
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see the need for a national registry,'' said Rep. Mac
Collins (R-Ga.). ``I'm going to have to take a real close look at
all these gun control provisions because I just don't believe in
taking away people's rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Saxby Chambliss (R-Ga.) said he supports criminal
background checks for all purchases at gun shows and will support
an amendment to be offered by Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde
(R-Ill.) to raise the legal age of handgun purchase to 21, which is
currently the limit in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue in my mind is not gun control,'' Chambliss said.
``These are gun safety measures.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr, meanwhile, said he will oppose all the gun restrictions
and, if the House floor rule allows for it, offer amendments to
remove the gun control provisions from the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right to bear arms is an express right people are
guaranteed in the Constitution,'' said Barr, an NRA board member.
</P>
<P>
   While Democrats for the most part are solidly behind the new
measures, House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt (D-Mo.) is giving
members such as Bishop the freedom to vote they way they choose.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert (R-Ill.), who personally supports
most of the provisions, says he will do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has their points of view on this and I think they
will be able to work their will in the House,'' Hastert said.
``Even within our conference there are two or three different
points of view, and legitimately so.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
