<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3002 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIOLENCE13-COX     06-12 2125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLENCE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some anti-violence programs show promise
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Eddie and Travis Feltman, father and son, huddled
together to read the well wishes scrawled on a card from a group of
counselors, parents and children gathered in the student center of
the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Haltingly, they repeated the words out loud; messages of hope
and encouragement for the 12-year-old freckled kid already in
trouble with the law for aggravated assault. Moments later, Feltman
gently patted his son on the shoulder; a small touch of pride
marking their completion of a 10-week program called Family
Solutions, designed to change the troubled paths of young,
first-time lawbreakers.
</P>
<P>
   No one has a higher stake in this program's success than the
mothers, fathers and sons who sat at tables last week in a blue
reception room, munching on chicken wings, pizza and pecan pie.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the hugs: anxiety. Along with hope: worry.
</P>
<P>
   Will this program stick? Will these boys _ some in low-slung
pants, others in baseball caps _ remember that their fate is tied
in part to how well they learned their lessons here?
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, the questions remain the same. As communities _ from
Littleton, Colo., to Conyers, Ga. _ reel from violence among
children, a host of anti-violence programs like Family Solutions
are flooding the schools, churches and counseling centers.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers are hesitant to declare victory. Too many
programs are well-intentioned, but don't have either the data or
the history to show they can live up to their promises, scientists
say. The conclusion: Hundreds of programs, working with shoestring
budgets and unclear missions, probably don't work.
</P>
<P>
   Which leaves researchers with a critical goal: learn what works,
and learn it fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that America will not give up its guns _ not in my
lifetime, not in your lifetime,'' said Dr. Stephen Thomas, director
of the Institute for Minority Health Research at Emory University.
``So we must find, and find quickly, effective solutions to save
our kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Do not envy the violent, and do not choose any of their ways _
Proverbs 3:31
</P>
<P>
   Children killing children has become one of the most disturbing
trends of the century. In the past 20 years, homicides has become
the second leading cause of death for young Americans between the
ages of 15 and 24. And for children 10 to 14, homicide is now the
third leading cause of death, according to the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Black teenage males are seven times more likely to be murdered
than white teenage males, and are eight times more likely to commit
murder, according to mortality statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had kids killing each other for years,'' Thomas said.
``But since urban black kids don't shoot each other in school,
apparently no one noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   And although there's been a slight decrease in national youth
homicide rates since 1993, the number of teens who die violently
``remains unacceptably high,'' according to the CDC. Between 1992
and 1994, more than 8,000 children were homicide victims, agency
figures show.
</P>
<P>
   In response, hundreds of programs have been launched nationwide
to help kids stop the violence.
</P>
<P>
   The Girl Scouts offers an anti-violence program. So does the
YMCA and the Boys and Girls Clubs of America. Cities have
experimented with school programs, theater groups, boot camps,
mentoring and Internet police sites that allow children to send
tips to law enforcement about violent activity.
</P>
<P>
   Congress set aside $300 million in April for federal grants to
fund youth violence prevention programs in 50 communities.
President Clinton is getting into the act as well. This month, he
ordered a review of whether the entertainment industry markets
aggression to children. He also plans to create an
anti-youth-violence program modeled after the federal government's
anti-smoking campaign.
</P>
<P>
   I
</P>
<P>
   Nothing enduring can be built on violence _ Mohandas K. Gandhi
</P>
<P>
   I
</P>
<P>
   But which of these programs actually work?
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have been studying that question since the early
1990s. The CDC selected a dozen projects to fund and study in 1993.
Of those, five ``showed promise'' and are continuing to receive CDC
funding, according to Alex Crosby of the CDC's Division of Violence
Prevention at the National Center for Injury Prevention and
Control.
</P>
<P>
   Those programs _ in Arizona, Michigan, Virginia, South Carolina
and Oregon _ targeted at-risk and very young children.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the results are in, but preliminary findings suggest
successful programs have some common traits.
</P>
<P>
   Programs that had multiple goals appear to do better than ones
focused on one area. It's not enough to merely teach kids how to
avoid a fight. Instead, a program should teach a variety of life
skills.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Self Enhancement Inc., of Portland, Ore., not only
provided middle school students counseling sessions on conflict
resolution, but also mentoring, peer counseling, recreational
opportunities and academic tutoring.
</P>
<P>
   And Second Step, a Seattle program now in 10,000 schools,
teaches younger children not only how to avoid conflict, but to
feel empathy for others and control impulses.
</P>
<P>
   Second Step successfully reduced aggressive behavior and
increased ``pro-social'' behavior in second- and third-graders who
had gone through the program, according to a 1997 study published
in the Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got teachers telling me that we've got kids on the
playground helping other kids to calm down,'' said Joan Immerman,
school counselor at Midway Elementary School in Forsyth County,
Ga., one of two local schools using the program. ``We're already
starting to see the fruits of our labor.''
</P>
<P>
   Programs that showed collaboration between multiple agencies and
community leaders also seemed to be effective. For example, input
from public health departments, social workers, and churches
improved a program's chance of working.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence is not limited to one arena; it spills into every
aspect of life,'' Crosby said. ``It goes back to the idea of taking
a village to raise a child _ in this case, it takes a village to
interact with kids and stop the violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the Center of the Study and Prevention of
Violence in Bolder, Colo., developed four nuts-and-bolts criteria
for a successful violence prevention program:
</P>
<P>
   _ It must be theoretically sound.
</P>
<P>
   _ It must be able to prove it has a deterrent effect _ in other
words, it keeps kids out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   _ It must show that it is able to sustain that effect for at
least a year.
</P>
<P>
   _ It must have worked some place other than where it was
created.
</P>
<P>
   I
</P>
<P>
   Violence is an admission that one's ideas and goals cannot
prevail on their own merits _ Sen. Edward Kennedy
</P>
<P>
   I
</P>
<P>
   Family Solutions is an example of a program that meets those
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, administrators from the Office of Juvenile Justice
and Delinquency Prevention in Washington traveled to Athens, Ga.,
to listen to parents discuss Family Solutions. The agency, part of
the U.S. Justice Department, is interested in duplicating the
program elsewhere in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an opportunity for a second chance,'' said Brenda Bush,
whose 17-year-old son, Tony Johnson, has been part of Family
Solutions since April. ``This let them know what they had done
wrong, but it lets them get back up and go forward with their
lives. It puts them back on the right path.''
</P>
<P>
   Family Solutions is designed for first-time offenders who have
committed what's considered low-level crime, such as assault,
criminal trespassing or delinquency. Killers and rapists are not
eligible. It requires that parents and children attend support
groups for three months. The groups, one for the teens and one for
the adults, are designed to give participants a chance to vent. But
they also seek to help parents and children to role-play,
strengthen communications, and learn social and conflict-resolution
skills.
</P>
<P>
   I
</P>
<P>
   Violence is as American as the Fourth of July and cherry pie _
H. Rap Brown
</P>
<P>
   I
</P>
<P>
   But nationally, the vast majority of programs are probably not
meeting standards _ or simply don't have the data or a clear enough
mission to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we saw was a fairly glaring need to evaluate
these violence prevention programs,'' said Crosby of the CDC. ``We
see a lot of activity (to stem youth violence), but we don't see
much scientific data that shows whether any of it works or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that most violence prevention programs
are run on a shoestring. ``And it costs far more to evaluate them
than to run them,'' said Pete Colbenson of Georgia's Children and
Youth Coordinating Council, which has given Family Solutions a
$20,000 juvenile justice grant to start the program in Macon. ``So
if you've got to pick, what are you going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is the organizers often don't know how to
evaluate their progress. ``Family Solutions is special, in part
because it had the resources of UGA behind it,'' Colbenson said.
``Most of these are grass-roots projects that simply don't have the
academic sophistication to prove what they're doing works.''
</P>
<P>
   Many programs sprang up in the wake of recent school shootings
and are simply too new to gauge. Others are too vague in their
mission to be successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is complicated; there is no quick-and-easy fix,'' said
Jeffrey Fagan, director of the Center for Violence Research and
Prevention at Columbia University. ``A prevention program is not
like a Viagra pill.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason: There are many types of violence. Violence against
strangers. Domestic violence. Violence against girlfriends. School
violence. Urban street violence.
</P>
<P>
   An outreach program has to know what it's trying to address.
</P>
<P>
   Kids Alive and Loved targets urban youths dealing with
unresolved grief and post-traumatic stress caused by witnessing
violence. The program was started by Cobb County, Ga., resident
Bernadette Leite, whose son, Khalil, a 17-year-old high school
graduate, was shot in the back and killed in 1993. The program
provides intensive counseling, but maintains a kind of street
savvy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had young men lose six friends in a year,'' said
Emory's Thomas. ``And yet they had not talked about that. Can you
imagine?''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of pent-up emotion, paired with an unsafe,
crime-ridden neighborhood, leads to a ``tough man mentality,'' and
a rage that can result in instant violence, Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're in a neighborhood where one person just got out of
prison and the other one's just finished his school-based conflict
resolution class,'' Thomas said. ``Now, you tell me _ really _ who
do you think is going to win?''
</P>
<P>
   I
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Blessed are the peacemakers, for they will be called children of
God _ Matthew 5:9
</P>
<P>
   I
</P>
<P>
   Frans DeWaal of Emory's Yerkes Regional Primate Research Center
stood before a friendly, erudite crowd filled with tweed jackets,
bow ties and custom-made crosses. His topic: How monkeys control
violence.
</P>
<P>
   DeWaal, author of ``Peacemaking Among Primates,'' ($16.95,
Harvard University Press) was the third speaker at a recent
international conference entitled ``Violence Reduction in Theory
and Practice,'' a gathering of theologians, linguists and
scientists at Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   With slides of monkeys behind him, he explained how some
primates were very good at teaching their young to be, well, kind
to one another. If there was a fight, family groups often worked
hard _ through grooming, kissing and sex _ to patch things up.
</P>
<P>
   A question was politely raised: So what?
</P>
<P>
   DeWaal pondered for a while, then reminded the audience that
humans, big brain aside, are still animals. And what might work for
monkeys could work for us. Maybe we too could learn how to stop
violence before it destroys our communities.
</P>
<P>
   His message wasn't much different that those of the boys in
Family Solutions, who talked slowly of new hope and second chances.
</P>
<P>
   Experts predict that newfound enthusiasm will help find the
theories and programs that work _ and bring our children out of the
killing fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really felt bad about what I did,'' said Tasha Lynn Fielder
of Winder, a 13-year-old who hit her mother. She graduated in April
from Family Solutions in Barrow County.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now, things are so much better,'' Tasha said. ``I've
learned I don't have to fight every time I get mad. I can control
my temper better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of myself. It feels great.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
