<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: WHEN BOARD MEMBERS ARE LIABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On May 27, a state appeals court issued a decision
that put co-op and condominium board members on notice that they
can be held personally liable for their actions as corporate
directors. The court ruled that when board members are sued as
individuals for actions they perform as directors, they cannot be
reimbursed by their co-op or condominium if they are found liable
for damages that are punitive in nature.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate lawyers say that the decision also calls into
question the ability of co-ops and condominiums to reimburse board
members for penalties imposed under various local, state and
federal laws and regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, they say, the decision raises the issue of whether, to
protect themselves against claims not covered by insurance, board
members facing punitive damage claims should consider hiring their
own lawyers to look over the shoulders of counsel provided by
insurance carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a significant case by an important court,'' said
Richard Siegler, a Manhattan co-op lawyer, explaining that the
decision, issued by the Appellate Division, First Department, is
binding on lower courts in Manhattan, the Bronx and Westchester
County. ``It is a clear warning that willful misconduct by a board
member that leads to punitive damages can end up being very costly
for the board member personally.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision arose out of a 1996 federal lawsuit in which
Gregory and Shannon Broome sued Beekman Hill House Apartment Corp.
and its board for denying the couple's application to sublet an
apartment in the building at 425 East 51st St. According to court
papers, the Broomes filed the case under the federal Fair Housing
Act and other anti-discrimination laws, charging that the denial
was based on Broome's race (he is black).
</P>
<P>
   After a jury trial, the Broomes were awarded a total of $640,000
in damages. Of that amount, Nicholas Biondi, the president of the
board, was ordered to pay $230,000 in compensatory damages and
$125,000 in punitive damages. The balance was to come from the
co-op corporation and four other directors.
</P>
<P>
   After settlement conferences with Biondi, the compensatory
damages for which he had been liable ended up being paid by the
co-op corporation, and Biondi remained personally liable for the
punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   Biondi then filed a lawsuit against Beekman Hill House in state
Supreme Court seeking indemnification _ a form of reimbursement _
for the punitive damages he was required to pay.
</P>
<P>
   And while the trial court rejected the co-op's motion to dismiss
Biondi's complaint, the Appellate Division overturned that decision
and ruled that under the state's Business Corporation Law,
indemnification cannot be made to a director ``if a judgment
adverse to the director establishes that his acts were committed in
bad faith.''
</P>
<P>
   The court concluded that the acts for which Biondi was found
liable in the federal case _ violating the Broomes' civil rights _
``could only have been committed in bad faith'' and dismissed his
claim for indemnification.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the court is saying is that if you decide to serve on a
board, you better stop and take a deep breath before making any
important decisions, because you're taking on a serious
obligation,'' said Errol Brett, a Manhattan co-op lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Brett explained that the bylaws of many co-ops and condominiums
contain provisions indemnifying board members for liabilities,
judgments and even fines they incur in the good-faith execution of
their duties. Such provisions, he said, are a practical necessity
if co-ops and condominiums are to be able to encourage shareholders
and unit owners to serve on their boards.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Brett said, indemnification has become increasingly
important because of the personal exposure board members face under
regulations like the Window Guard Law, the Elevator Inspection Law,
city, state and federal human rights laws, sexual harassment laws,
and federal lead-paint disclosure regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these laws contain provisions for punitive damages,''
Brett said. ``And all of them expose the directors to fines and
penalties.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he said, directors who are required to pay fines for
actions they take _ or fail to take _ as directors may have to pay
out of their own pockets even if their co-op or condominium wants
to indemnify them. Brett explained that since fines are punitive in
nature, the Appellate Division's decision prohibiting
indemnification for punitive damages could easily be extended to
them.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Schiff, one of Biondi's lawyers in his case against
Beekman Hill House, said that the decision also puts directors on
notice that when faced with punitive damage claims, the lawyer
provided by the insurance carrier may not be working entirely in
their best interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any director who finds himself a defendant in a lawsuit that
contains a claim for punitive damages should hire his own lawyer to
ensure that his individual interests are protected,'' Schiff said.
He added that a decision had not yet been made on whether to appeal
the ruling.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He explained that a lawyer hired by an insurance carrier to
defend a claim against a co-op or condominium is working primarily
for the co-op or condominium. And since the carrier can be held
responsible only for compensatory damages _ coverage for punitive
damages, he said, is prohibited by law _ it is possible that a
claim for punitive damages would receive less of the lawyer's time
and attention than the claim for compensatory damages.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Livingston, another Manhattan co-op lawyer, said that
while board members should take steps to protect themselves when
faced with punitive damage claims, it is unlikely that such claims
will result in liability unless the board member is found to have
engaged in willful misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a potential for exposure to punitive damages, you
might very well want your own lawyer looking over the shoulder of
the lawyer hired by the insurance company,'' he said. ``But the
number of instances where board members are actually hit with
punitive damage awards is relatively small. And I certainly
wouldn't want this decision to keep competent candidates from
serving on boards.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-99 1739EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3004 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-IOWA-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      06-12 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-IOWA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH IOWA TRIP SIGNALS REAL START OF 2000 RACE FOR THE PRESIDENCY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.H., Tenn.) (Eds: Added starter NYT Page 1, replacing Starr-Clintons) 
 (rk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMANA, Iowa, _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas ended his shadow
presidential campaign Saturday and flew to this state to directly
declare his interest in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   His announcement effectively inaugurated what is shaping up to
be the earliest and quickest presidential nominating processes in
recent history.
</P>
<P>
   Bush dropped any pretense of ambivalence about his ambitions as
he left Austin for his first explicitly political trip _ nearly
four days that have brought him first to Iowa, which will hold
party caucuses next February, and then will take him to New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm coming here today to tell you this, I'm running for
president of the United States,'' Bush said, stating what has, for
most Republicans, become the obvious, standing on a stage piled
with bales of hay, a shiny red tractor behind him. ``There is no
turning back. And I intend to be the next president of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Setting the theme for his campaign, Bush said that he would be
at once an activist and a conservative president _ a
``compassionate'' Republican who would advocate using the nation's
prosperity to help its downtrodden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is compassion beneath us?'' Bush said, speaking in this town
of cornfields outside of Cedar Rapids. ``Is mercy below us? Should
our party be led by someone who boasts of a hard heart?
</P>
<P>
   ``I am proud to be a compassionate conservative,'' the son of a
former president declared, invoking what his aides said would be
the rhetorical core of his race for the White House. ``I welcome
the label. And on this ground, I'll take my stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Three other Republicans who are also seeking their party's
nomination for 2000 _ Lamar Alexander, the former governor of
Tennessee, Elizabeth Dole, former Red Cross president, and Rep.
John R. Kasich of Ohio _ were campaigning in Iowa as well, speaking
at the World Pork Expo at the Iowa State Fairgrounds in Des Moines.
</P>
<P>
   Their days were largely lost to the tumult of Bush's visit. His
utter dominance of the political stage, notwithstanding the fact
that he is one of a half-dozen Republicans who would like to be the
next president, was testimony to the success with which Bush has
managed to use early political endorsements and fund-raising to
present himself as the prohibitive favorite for his party's
nomination _ even though no Republican will vote on this field for
nearly seven months.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Saturday's visit appeared to mark the real start of
the 2000 presidential nomination process.
</P>
<P>
   While it is hardly unprecedented for candidates to begin running
17 months before an election, the race this year is unusual for the
early strength _ in endorsements, in fund-raising, and in the sheer
size of their political apparatus _ that is brought to the fight by
the two presumptive front-runners among the Republicans and the
Democrats, Bush and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore flies next week to Carthage, Tenn., his family home, to
announce _ just in case anyone had any doubts _ that he, too, is
running to succeed President Clinton in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Even though both are opposed and there is plenty of time for the
tide to suddenly turn against either of them, both are eager to
portray themselves as assured of victory.
</P>
<P>
   With his broadly thematic speech appearance Saturday in the
state where the first presidential caucus will be held next
February, the two-term governor dropped any pretense about the
nature of his presidential ambitions. ``I believe you can expect
someone named George W. to win this nomination!'' he declared to a
clutch of noisy supporters who greeted him at an airport hanger
rally in Cedar Rapids.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's appearance in Iowa Saturday was the first of nearly four
days of explicitly political appearances, and it had all the
trappings of a full-scale political invasion.
</P>
<P>
   He was accompanied by a planeload of staff, security and press
(including one reporter on hand to write a story about the
reporters) and appeared at events that were planned to the last
footstep and camera angle, producing the kind of frenzied campaign
day that Iowans customarily do not have an opportunity to witness
until the final days before the February caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was upbeat and jaunty throughout what clearly was among the
more challenging days of his political career, starting from the
moment he boarded his campaign plane at 7:28 a.m., picked up the
intercom and made light of the precipice he now stood on after
weeks in which his staff had invited interest in this inaugural
political trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please stow your expectations securely in your overhead bins
as they may shift during the trip and can fall and hurt someone _
especially me,'' said Bush, who was wearing cowboy boots and a
shiny brass ``Governor George W. Bush'' belt buckle.
</P>
<P>
   As chuckles rolled through the cabin, Bush added: ``Thanks for
coming. We know you have a choice of candidates when you fly, we
appreciate you choosing Great Expectations'' _ a reference to the
name that Bush's staff had attached to both the campaign and the
tour in its effort to defuse the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Iowa, Bush gave what his aides described as the keynote
speech of his day, setting out the themes of his campaign while
drawing some unstated, if sharp contrasts, with the Democratic
leadership of the past seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels to me like an old era of American politics is ending
_ like Americans are waiting for new hopes, new energy, new
idealism,'' he said. ``We will prove that someone who is
conservative and compassionate can win without sacrificing
principle. We will show that politics, after a time of tarnished
ideals, can be higher and better. We will give our country a fresh
start after a season of cynicism.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bush spoke in the kind of rural setting that was, down to the
country music and Pledge of Allegiance, reminiscent of the
backdrops that his father used. But his rhetoric was clearly
different in tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am running because our country must be prosperous, but
prosperity must have a purpose,'' he said. ``The purpose of
prosperity is to make sure that the American dreams touches every
heart. The purpose of prosperity is to make sure no one is left out
and no one is left behind. I'm running because I want our party to
match a conservative mind with a compassionate heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that as president, he would advocate for what he
described as ``the responsibility era,'' again drawing an unstated
if clear contrast with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first goal is to usher in the responsibility era _ an era
that stands in stark contrast to the last few decades, what our
culture has said: If it feels good, do it, and if you've got a
problem, blame someone else. Each American must understand that we
are responsible for the decision each of us makes in life.''
</P>
<P>
   His second goal, he said, was ``to rally the armies of
compassion that exist in every community,'' _ a reference to
churches and charities to help the poor. He said he would lift
regulations that hamper involvement of such organizations in such
programs as after-school programs. ``Supporting these men and women
_ the soldiers in the army of compassion _ is the next, bold step
of welfare reform,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His third goal, he said, is that ``every child should be
educated, and no child should be left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's first trip was arguably as intriguing for what he had to
say, as for how he actually took to campaigning. The governor, in
contrast to the campaign style of his father, lingered at every
crowd, shaking hands and taking advantage of a schedule that
specifically gave him time to ``mingle'' with supporters at each
stop.
</P>
<P>
   At the tarmac, two students from the University of Northern
Iowa, Dan Strenchuk and Mike Russell, told Bush that they were
running for student government and imposed on him for a picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will sink your campaign,'' he said as he slung a hand
over their shoulders and gazed into a camera. Then, as he was
leaving, he turned to the two youths, and said: ``Thank you all for
coming. You make sure to show up for the caucuses _ no matter how
cold it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
