<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3006 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SC-NAVYBASE-REAL-2TAK     06-12 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-NAVYBASE-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: OLD NAVY BASE WITH NEW CONTROVERSIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LYN RIDDLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Sprawling on a spit of land beside the
Cooper River, the 1,600 acres of the now-closed Charleston Navy
Base have come to represent both an enormously valuable development
opportunity and a continuing focus of charges, countercharges and
commercial and political maneuvering.
</P>
<P>
   With three miles of riverfront, the former base represents
hundreds of millions of dollars of real estate. It includes 21
first-rate piers and some 600 buildings, from large warehouses to a
handsome colonial-style house that once housed admirals.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 68 companies with a total of 4,200 workers have moved
into two-thirds of the buildings. But very public controversies
have surrounded the competing plans of a handful of companies and
agencies for some of the prime facilities within the base.
</P>
<P>
   Even selecting who would oversee the redevelopment of the former
base was not easy. In most communities where a base is closed, the
redevelopment agency is run by a city or county. But here the
Charleston Naval Complex Redevelopment Authority, which oversees
the site, is run by the state.
</P>
<P>
   The base is in this city, but just a few miles upriver from
Charleston, which by size and tradition has been the most
influential in the region. Three counties are close to the base,
and all entities wanted a say in what would become of the land. So
the counties, cities and state all have representatives on the
redevelopment board.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is uniquely Charleston,'' said Jack Sprott, the director of
the redevelopment agency. ``There's a lot of jealousy between
Charleston and North Charleston and the political folks said this
was the best way to handle it, and it's worked pretty well. The
only drawback is the city has zoning powers. We've had our lumps
and bumps, but we're in lock step now.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the sharpest controversy involved how the north end of
the base would be used. The city of North Charleston wanted
residential development. But the Charleston Naval Complex
Redevelopment Authority wanted a cargo operation. The city
eventually won. According to James Bryan, chairman of the
authority, his agency expects to begin work on a waterfront park,
commercial buildings and residences for North Charleston within a
year.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement in 1993 that the base would close was met with
instant panic. ``It was gloom and doom all over Charleston,'' said
Sprott. But in the six years since, Sprott said, community leaders
have managed to regain the 25,000 jobs lost when the base closed
with the arrival of new businesses throughout the region, while the
redevelopment agency continues to foster commercial operations at
the former naval complex.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent visit to the site, William Cassidy, deputy assistant
secretary of the Navy, called the redevelopment authority ``a model
for the country'' in base reuse, according to Sprott.
</P>
<P>
   The companies that set up shop at the former base perform a wide
range of services, from repairing ships to preparing small boats
for overseas shipment.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy shipyard here was established in 1902. During World War
II it grew to become the Navy's third-largest home port, behind
Norfolk, Va., and San Diego. When closing was announced in 1993, 80
ships and submarines were based at North Charleston. The Navy
turned the base over to the redevelopment agency in April 1996, but
the final land conveyance has not yet taken place.
</P>
<P>
   Sprott said his agency put off those negotiations, preferring to
find tenants first. The first was Charleston Marine Manufacturing,
a consortium of area businesses that leased the largest dry dock to
repair ships.
</P>
<P>
   Ten government operations occupy space at the base as well,
including the Border Patrol, the Postal Service and the state's
National Guard. Soon the South Carolina State Ports Authority plans
to operate a cargo facility here, a plan that has resulted in a
fair share of controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the state's Ports Authority, which operates four
terminals in the Charleston area, wanted to set up a break-bulk
facility on the northern tip of the base.
</P>
<P>
   But the city of North Charleston had other plans for the site.
Mayor Keith Summey said he wanted the area for residences,
businesses and a waterfront park. The base includes the only
waterfront in the city. Plus, he said, the site abuts a residential
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had been a break-bulk facility for 100 years'' said Sprott,
``and we thought that was the best use. But the last thing we
wanted was a controversy with the city.''
</P>
<P>
   He worked out a deal to lease land at the center of the base to
the Ports Authority, leaving the north end for North Charleston.
The north end is now the subject of a lawsuit by Braswell Shipyard,
which contends that the redevelopment authority did not execute an
agreed-upon sublease there. Sprott declined to comment on the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   In still another dispute, Carolina Marine Handling, one of the
base's current tenants, has charged that the agency had improperly
signed leases and has not been diligent in protecting assets left
behind by the Navy. When the military closes a facility, more than
just buildings are left behind. Pencils are even left in holders,
said James Kenney, a former chief of staff at the base.
</P>
<P>
   H.R. Stender, president of Carolina Marine Handling, said he had
applied to lease the north end of the base with virtually the same
plan that was originally espoused by the Ports Authority, but this
was turned down. Now, he said, the authority will soon move onto
the pier in the central part of the base that he had been using for
his break-bulk operation, whose lease was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``One billion dollars is being chipped and diced and given out
to friends of the former governor, David Beasley,'' said Stender,
whose family has operated stevedoring companies in the Charleston
area for three generations.
</P>
<P>
   He also maintains that the redevelopment agency and the Ports
Authority have conspired to drive him out of business, using his
own business plan, which he sent to the agency when he applied for
the land at the north end of the base.
</P>
<P>
   The regional state legislative delegation has looked into his
claims but found them groundless. But four of its 20 members have
asked for a review by the state's Legislative Audit Council, which
is scheduled to begin its study later this year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The state Law Enforcement Division has turned over its report on
Stender's allegations to the state attorney general but the results
have not been released.
</P>
<P>
   Sprott calls Stender's claims ``garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done more for him than anybody,'' Sprott said. ``We had
a fair competition and we did not pick him. Now he's irate.''
</P>
<P>
   Stender operated a break-bulk facility, loading frozen chicken
on ships destined for Russia, until a few months ago on one of the
base's prime piers, called Zulu.
</P>
<P>
   But his operation dwindled as word spread that the company he
leased from _ Charleston Shipbuilders _ was out of business and
that this company's lease would be canceled. Charleston
Shipbuilders intended to overhaul Navy ships to supply electricity
to rural areas in South America, but the one ship it completed was
not able to supply power adequately.
</P>
<P>
   Sprott said the Zulu Pier would be used by the Ports Authority,
but Stender was offered the use of another pier.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Miller, a spokesman for the Ports Authority, said that its
terminals were public ``and anybody and everybody can come and
operate there.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that his agency had been interested in operating another
break-bulk terminal for years. He also rejected Stender's charges
of political favoritism.
</P>
<P>
   Sprott said the next step in redevelopment would be to negotiate
the cleanup of the property and get the land deeded to his agency.
The agency wants not just to occupy existing buildings but to build
new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Now considering leasing space on the base is a company that
wants to convert the former Navy hospital and a number of smaller
buildings into a film studio, at a cost of $30 million. The company
would rent out space for the production of commercials, television
shows and feature films.
</P>
<P>
   The company, called Carolopolis, is making ``a serious effort to
develop a motion picture studio in the state,'' said Isabel Hill,
director of the South Carolina Film Office.
</P>
</TEXT>
