<HEADER>
A3009 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CUP-USA-NYT &LR;      06-12 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUP-USA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS TURN LOSS INTO A SUCCESS STORY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No one ever wants to lose, especially the U.S. women's soccer
team, but some defeats can be instructive and revelatory. A 1-0
defeat to Norway in the semifinals of the 1995 Women's World Cup
was a short-term calamity but a long-term benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had won that World Cup, I believe we wouldn't have won
the Olympics,'' forward Tiffeny Milbrett said. ``A lot of things
were not right about that team. You have to be ready to give it the
best you have. In '95, we weren't ready. Sometimes it takes crisis
to initiate change.''
</P>
<P>
   Since that defeat, much has changed for the American women, from
their defensive formation to their style of attack to their
dedication to reclaim the title as the world's best soccer team.
The United States won the gold medal at the 1996 Olympic Games _
defeating Norway, 2-1, in overtime of the semifinals _ and it is
favored to regain the world championship the team secured at the
initial Women's World Cup in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   There is much pressure on the American team: to win, to sell
tickets, to lay the framework for a women's professional league
that could start in 2001, to expand the game as a pioneer to a
wider audience. And there is no assurance that the United States
will prevail in the 16-team field. Twice this year, China has
defeated the Americans, snapping their 50-game unbeaten streak at
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's pressure, but what's the alternative?'' coach Tony
DiCicco said. ``The alternative is that we stress over it, or that
we aren't good enough to do well. It's not going to be easy, but we
obviously know we're capable of doing well. We've just got to make
sure we've done things as well as we've ever done them.''
</P>
<P>
   After serving as an assistant coach to Anson Dorrance during the
1991 Women's World Cup, DiCicco took over as head coach in 1994.
Reluctant to fix something that did not appear to be broken, he did
not make many changes for the 1995 World Cup. But, after the United
States lost to Norway and went home disappointedly with a bronze
medal, he re-created the team.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of continuing with three defenders, and being vulnerable
to counterattacks, he employed four. Instead of attacking the way a
hockey team would, knocking the puck into the corners and digging
it out, he employed a more sophisticated possession game. The
attack is purposeful and attractive.
</P>
<P>
   With 109 international goals, Mia Hamm has scored more than any
other woman or man to play the game. Cindy Parlow, at 5 feet 11
inches, is a lighthouse of a target. And Milbrett, with a squat
build and explosive acceleration, appears ready to become a
breakout star. She and Hamm have combined for 100 goals and 83
assists in their last 84 games.
</P>
<P>
   In the midfield, Kristine Lilly, often overlooked and
underappreciated, has played in 180 international matches, more
than any other player in the game. Julie Foudy is an offensive
threat and a vocal leader.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Akers, after scoring 10 goals in the inaugural World
Cup, has moved to defensive midfield, where she can still control a
game with her tackling, heading and passing skills, although she
struggles daily with the effects of chronic fatigue syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the best woman that's ever played the game, period,''
DiCicco said.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, Carla Overbeck is captain of the American team for
a third World Cup. Joy Fawcett is often considered one of the
world's best defenders and is also a frequent threat in attacking
from the back.
</P>
<P>
   Brandi Chastain, formerly a striker, is perhaps the team's
savviest player. Kate Sobrero brings toughness and reliability.
Always a capable shot-blocker, goalkeeper Briana Scurry has matured
into a traffic cop who excels at organizing the defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans are fast, athletic and experienced _ six are
competing in their third World Cup _ but they succeed in large part
because they have bought into the simple but vital concept that
they are a team, not a collection of individuals.
</P>
<P>
   It shows in the way they play, the way they joke with each
other, even in the way they make commercials. In the television
spots, when one goes on a date, they all go on the date. When one
gets dental work, they all get dental work.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm gets far more attention than anyone else, but she
constantly defers to her teammates _ a point guard dishing off
verbal assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has the luxury of finding and developing a group of
young women who have many of the same values,'' DiCicco said. ``A
lot of that has to do with being fit and having self-discipline. If
you don't buy into the culture, you're left by the wayside.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
