<HEADER>
A3013 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CUP-LILLY-NYT &LR;      06-12 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUP-LILLY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: KRISTINE LILLY IS A PLAYER WITH CAPS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Ill., N.C.)  (rk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   She has played more international soccer games, 180, than
anybody else in history, male or female. But Kristine Lilly is
hardly alone.
</P>
<P>
   Seven teammates have also reached the 100-game level, helping to
form the most cohesive national team ever to represent the United
States, any gender, any sport. And it is important to all of them
that they be something more than a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a second family,'' Lilly said the other day.
``Female sports are different. You do a lot better when you care
about each other. We are nurturing people, caring people. I'm glad
to have my friends out there. It goes a little bit deeper than just
sports. We all want to see each other happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Their next international game _ known as a cap in soccer _ will
be Saturday in Giants Stadium against Denmark in the 1999 Women's
World Cup. Many of the players were also together in the two
previous cups, in 1991 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   `You mean, the old bags?'' Julie Foudy asked.
</P>
<P>
   They are not that old, so their record needs explaining. The men
play in leagues, accumulating their caps with national teams in
occasional World Cups and other tournaments. The men's world record
for caps is 147, held by Majed Abdullah of Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   The American women, without a league, play an extensive
international schedule. In 1996, Lilly, 27, a left-footed,
left-side midfielder with an aggressive penchant for moving
forward, passed the women's record of 152, set by Heidi Stoere of
Norway, and she has kept going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some NBA teams are together a long time, but this is unique,''
Lilly said, talking about players who know where each other will
be, just as the old Boston Celtics and Montreal Canadiens always
knew.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is something else. The women also need to feel a
togetherness they say is uniquely female. A communications graduate
from the University of North Carolina, Lilly recently spoke with
great animation and respect about her seven 100-cap teammates:
</P>
<P>
   _ Michelle Akers, age 33, 141 caps, who has missed games to
injuries and chronic fatigue syndrome: ``It's unbelievable to see
what she's gone through. She's one of the smartest players I've
ever known. Her shooting is like clockwork, the way she can get out
of pressure. Now you don't expect her to take on the world anymore,
but when the game is on the line, I wouldn't mind the ball at her
feet. I just think, `Get the ball to Michelle.'''
</P>
<P>
   _ Joy Fawcett, age 31, 142 caps: ``She's got such a great right
foot. She's the quiet one in the background, who deserves more
attention. Sometimes reporters are talking to everybody but Joy,
and I just look at her and say, `You are awesome!'''
</P>
<P>
   _ Julie Foudy, age 28, 155 caps: ``Jules is one of my roommates
and usually I play against her in practice. I think I'm getting the
ball from her, and she just toe-pokes it away. One time she kicked
the ball at me, and I kicked it out of bounds. Same thing all over
again. I said, `Jules, we can do this all day.' Afterward we
laughed. She is so competitive, but she knows it's just soccer, not
life and death.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Mia Hamm, age 27, 173 caps: ``She's always been an incredible
player. She's the one you want with the ball on the final third of
the field. I'd love to have her mentality. There are great scorers,
and there are finishers. Finishers can do it different ways, like
Pele and Ronaldo. Like Michael Jordan. Like Mia. It's like she's
skating on ice with the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Tiffeny Milbrett, age 26, 118 caps: ``Millie, she's a little
fireball. I've gotten to know her better; she'll give you a little
hug after a goal. She's so genuine. On the field, Millie and Mia
are so different. Millie wants the ball on the 18-yard line. She's
got a great volley.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Carla Overbeck, age 31, 144 caps: ``Another of my roommates.
She's the vocal leader. You can play your worst game and she'll
say, `Come on, Lil, forget about it.' She's so positive, so
competitive. She'll fire you up, saying, `Come on, guys.' It's why
she's the captain.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Tisha Venturini, age 26, 122 caps: ``Tish has the most
incredible headers I've ever seen. She can just get up there and
time it, the most amazing grace. Once in a great while I head one,
and I just look at her and say, `Tish, see?' She just starts
laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Brandi Chastain, who left the team for a few years,
has 95 caps, and Briana Scurry, the goalkeeper who sometimes sits
out lesser games, has 90 caps. Carin Gabarra finished with 117 caps
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Lilly said she was stunned at the fuss when she broke Stoere's
record in Kobe, Japan, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more, I realize what it means,'' Lilly said. ``It's
hard to believe, eight of us at 100. I have gone to work and given
all I had. I've missed games because of weddings and personal
things, but not because of injuries. I was hurt at the '91 World
Cup, but I played.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in New York, Lilly began playing at 6 _ ``my incentive was
the oranges at halftime'' _ after her family settled in Wilton,
Conn. She followed her older brother, Scott, and five of her
cousins, all boys, into soccer. She made her debut with the
national team in China at 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's the running around outdoors,'' she said. ``Maybe
it's the team aspect. Maybe it's because I was good at it. I love
the mental part of soccer. There are a lot of losses in soccer, and
you have to have the mentality to put it together, and you have to
be fit to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Since graduating from North Carolina, Lilly has become a typical
soccer nomad, training in California and Florida, and seeing her
boyfriend in Chicago whenever possible. Wilton is still home _ as
proven by the road sign there: Home of Kristine Lilly.
</P>
<P>
   Lilly said she would keep playing until the Summer Games in
Sydney, Australia, in 2000, ``and then see how my body feels.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The travel is the hardest part,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She would not mind seeing the huge international schedule be
limited by a national women's league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to compete against Jules,'' Lilly said. ``If she were
my opponent, there'd be a fire between us.''
</P>
<P>
   But they would remain friends. Women's soccer is different.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
