</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUP-NORWAY-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORWAY'S RIVALRY WITH UNITED STATES IS INTENSE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HYANNIS, Mass. _ When Norway won the 1995 Women's World Cup, one
of every four Norwegians watched the championship match on
television, team officials said.
</P>
<P>
   When the players returned from the tournament in Sweden, their
plane was escorted into Oslo by two F-16 fighter jets. The 1999
world soccer championship begins next weekend, and Norway is taking
no chances that it will be caught off guard in defending its title
by either the heat or the time difference in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   At home, temperatures have been in the low 60s, which is great,
except when preparing for the oven of an American summer. So,
Norwegian players have been drinking up to one and a half gallons
of water a day to practice hydration. Some have approximated the
sweaty, saunalike conditions ahead by training in waterproof rain
suits.
</P>
<P>
   Before arriving at their training base on Cape Cod on Wednesday,
the Norwegian players had grown accustomed to the six-hour time
difference by staying up until 3 or 4 in the morning at home and
sleeping until noon. ``My mother was calling me at 1 in the
morning, my coach was calling me at 1 in the morning,'' said Linda
Medalen, the Norwegian captain. ``Time was upside down.''
</P>
<P>
   Having overcome a rash of injuries, Norway is among the four
favorites in the 16-team tournament, along with the United States,
China and Germany. The Americans open play next Saturday against
Denmark at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Norway plays its first match next Sunday against Russia in
Foxboro, Mass. All of its matches will be broadcast live in Norway,
and large audiences are expected to watch again, even in the middle
of the night. In case anyone falls asleep, the matches will be
replayed in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 Women's World Cup is the largest sporting event ever
held for women. Organizers expect to sell half a million tickets.
All 32 matches will be televised by ABC, ESPN and ESPN2. More than
65,000 tickets have been sold for the American opener. And if the
United States, as expected, faces Norway or China in the final on
July 10, organizers hope to fill the 92,542 seats at the Rose Bowl
in Pasadena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-Norway rivalry in women's soccer is what the
Yankees-Red Sox are to baseball, the Packers-Bears are to football
and Ali-Frazier was to boxing. There is an edgy respect between the
teams, which have met in epic matches at every important moment in
the emergence of the women's game.
</P>
<P>
   At the inaugural Women's World Cup, in 1991, the United States
defeated Norway, 2-1, in the championship match. They met again in
the semifinals of the 1995 World Cup, and Norway won, 1-0. A year
later the Americans prevailed, 2-1, in overtime, in the semifinals
of the 1996 Summer Olympics. Last year, in a tournament in
Portugal, Norway handed the American women their worst defeat ever,
4-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Archenemies'' is how Tiffeny Milbrett, the American forward,
describes the rivalry. That loss in the 1995 World Cup was a bitter
defeat for the Americans, some of whom felt affronted by the
Norwegians' post-game celebration. Joined hand to ankle, the
Norwegians crawled around on the field in a maneuver known as ``the
train'' after derailing the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very shocking,'' Milbrett said of seeing her teammates
inconsolable in defeat. ``I don't think I had ever seen anyone on
the team cry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun to beat the Americans because they get so upset, make
so much noise, when they lose,'' said Medalen, who will be 34 on
Thursday. ``This is a problem. Never be weak.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Once one of the game's top forwards, Medalen has moved to
central defense, anchoring with speed and experience a back line
that has been plagued by injury and retirement since the 1995 world
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of her teammates, who receive a $10,000 yearly stipend
from the Norwegian soccer federation, she plays in an amateur
women's league and works a second job. A former sergeant in the
Norwegian army and officer in the Oslo police department, Medalen
now is a part-time private investigator.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has the necessary skills for listening and quickly
analyzing what to do,'' said Harald Olsen, one of her investigative
partners. ``It's very similar to football. You get a clue and you
have to make quick decisions. There is a very short response
time.''
</P>
<P>
   In one case, a man disappeared on a ferry boat ride from Norway
to Denmark. While the police suspected the man might have jumped
overboard, or pulled a scam and walked away from his previous life,
Medalen established that he had quarreled with others on the ferry
and might have been pushed or thrown over the side of the boat,
Olsen said.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, a father who kidnapped his daughter and took
her to Italy was traced by placing an eavesdropping device into a
videocassette of ``The Lion King,'' Olsen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the police went in, they were gone,'' Olsen said. ``We
are still looking. We are going to find them. Again.''
</P>
<P>
   On the soccer field, Medalen and her teammates use a much more
direct approach, excelling at a physical, grinding style of long
ball. Norway has recently preferred a possession-type game, but the
Norwegians do not defer in the slightest to the Americans, as some
teams do, and this assertiveness can put the United States in the
unusual position of backpedaling on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Norway was the first team to play aggressive against the
U.S.,'' said Leonardo Cuellar, the coach of the Mexican team.
``They play very directly. Very few teams can make the American
players run back to get the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Gro Espereth, Norway's sturdiest defender, will miss the World
Cup with a knee injury. Otherwise, the team is relatively healthy
for the first time in a year. Goalkeeper Bente Nordby has mended
her balky knee. Hege Riise remains an impeccably reliable
midfielder. And Ann Kristin Aarones, the tall striker who is one of
the world's top headers, has recovered from a viral infection. It
was Aarones who redirected a corner kick for the lone goal against
the Americans in the 1995 Women's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Norway is a squeaky machine right now, coach Per-Mathias Hogmo
said, but it should become well oiled in first-round matches
against Russia, Canada and Japan. The farther into the tournament
Norway goes, the more threatening it should become.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the World Cup, so anything can happen,'' Hogmo said.
``We are good enough to beat anyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
