<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3015 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-CHILDS-NYT     06-12 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-CHILDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REDEEMED CHILDS SALUTES FALLEN STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ So many thoughts were running through Chris Childs'
head, so many emotions running through his body that he must have
felt like he was going to burst.
</P>
<P>
   The team's leader, Patrick Ewing, being knocked from his arduous
and seemingly endless championship bid by a torn Achilles' tendon
four games ago. Larry Johnson writhing on the floor midway through
Friday's second quarter after spraining ligaments in his right
knee. The good work of the deposed Ernie Grunfeld, who was fired as
the Knicks' general manager with eight games left in this
then-forlorn season. Even Stephon Marbury, the brash Nets point
guard who said that Childs and Charlie Ward would never get the
Knicks near a championship.
</P>
<P>
   All of that was on Childs' mind while the Knicks were en route
to shocking everyone but themselves by defeating the Indiana
Pacers, 90-82, Friday night to win the Eastern Conference title by
four games to two. So when the mission was accomplished and Childs
exhaled, he released all the energy and passion that had been
swirling around inside of him by bounding around the court and
hurling the game ball into the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to throw it to the top of the rafters,'' Childs said
after the Knicks advanced to the National Basketball Association
finals for the first time since 1994. ``I tried to throw it as far
as I could but I was exhausted. I was real emotional. This is what
you play all your life for. I was thinking of the guys on this team
that went down, Patrick and Larry. Larry and I came here at the
same time, so I saw all the work that he put in to get us to this
point. And to see Patrick play the years that he did and not really
be a part of this, you get choked up behind it. So I went out there
and played with all of those guys in my heart to let them know that
what they put forth on this team I appreciate and I'm going to go
out there and do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Largely because Childs put forth such a splendid effort in Game
6 and throughout the entire series, the Knicks will meet the San
Antonio Spurs in the finals that begin Wednesday night at the
Alamodome. Childs, who has been viewed as something of a bust since
the Knicks signed him as a free agent three years ago, was a
lifesaver in this series since Ward, the starting point guard,
struggled mightily against the Pacers' bigger, stronger Mark
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Childs' significance was never more evident than Friday night.
The box score read that Childs contributed 9 points, 4 assists, 4
rebounds and 2 steals to the Knicks' victory, but close observation
of the game revealed that Childs had done much more. In the 37
minutes that Childs was on the floor, the Knicks outscored Indiana
by 86-60. In the 11 minutes that he wasn't, the Pacers drilled the
Knicks by 22-4.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, after Indiana sprinted to an 11-4 lead,
Van Gundy subbed Childs into the game and all became well for the
Knicks. The offense began running smoothly, Jackson was kept under
control, and the Knicks scored 20 of the next 27 points.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at the start of the second half, with the Knicks reeling
because of the injury to Johnson, the Pacers ran off 11 unanswered
points in &QC; 1 minute 55 seconds to turn a 6-point deficit into a
5-point advantage. Again, Van Gundy turned to Childs, and again the
backup point guard delivered. Less than five minutes later, the
score was tied. Two minutes after that, the Knicks regained the
lead when Childs buried a 15-foot jumper and honored Johnson by
making the ``L'' signal with his arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just emotion,'' said Childs, who went on to score 7
points in the fourth quarter and hold Reggie Miller to three field
goal attempts and no points. ``A lot of people didn't like it when
Larry started doing that. I think he just carries a lot in his
heart and I just wanted to let him know that he was still a part of
this team and that the things that he's accomplished, the things
that he's given us as a player, the unselfishness that he possesses
each and every night, was with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Childs, still emotional, reminisced about the Knicks'
wild and improbable journey to the conference title. Asked what he
would have said two months ago if a friend had told him the Knicks
would be playing for the league championship, he responded: ``You
need to gointo rehab. You're definitely on some kind of drug.''
</P>
<P>
   That the newest Knicks, Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby, have
keyed the Knicks' run is not lost on Childs. Neither is the now
seemingly foolish and premature release of the man responsible for
bringing them to New York, Grunfeld. ``I wish he was here,'' Childs
said, referring to Grunfeld. ``I wish he was in the building to
feel what was going on because what he's done has given us the
opportunity to play for the championship. Maybe I should put E.G.
on my ankle tape to let him know that he's a part of this team
also.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally, this Knicks point guard who was so excited that he
was admittedly rambling in answering questions, addressed Marbury.
Back in April, when the Knicks were floundering, Marbury criticized
Childs and Ward after they outplayed him in a Knicks' victory,
saying the Knicks would never win a title with them quarterbacking
the team. At the time, Childs said the comment did not bother him,
but when he was asked how satisfying it was to get the Knicks to
the finals, he replied with a smile, ``Ask Marbury.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``People have opinions. But I've been around Charlie
for three years and two heads are better than one any time and we
believe in each other, the team believes in us and that's all that
matters. People don't have to believe in us because we're strong
enough in our character that we're going to go out there and play,
not to prove anybody else wrong but to just prove to ourselves that
we are worthy.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
