<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3016 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-SALMON-NYT &LR;      06-12 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-SALMON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: THE SALMON OBSESSION THAT WENT UNSATISFIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NELSON BRYANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAGALLOWAY PLANTATION, Maine _ A recent trip to Maine's remote
and tumultuous Rapid River reminded me that I can become
inordinately obsessive about catching fish, in this instance,
landlocked salmon.
</P>
<P>
   When my companion Ruth Kirchmeier and I launched our canoe,
laden with gear and grub for a week, at the public ramp on the
Androscoggin River in Errol, N.H., I was already planning how I
would cook the salmon I was going to catch that evening. We were
heading for the upper end of the pool, just below the rapids, where
the Rapid River tumbles into the western side of Lake Umbagog, a
long, essentially shallow body of water that straddles the
Maine-New Hampshire border and is now within a national wildlife
refuge. Much of the refuge is unspoiled wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   It is five miles from the ramp to the cabin at the mouth of the
Rapid River, a little more than half of the distance involving
running up the Androscoggin to where it leaves the lake. From
there, we cross to the Maine shore. Ruth, I knew, was thinking less
of salmon than of the trip across Umbagog. In the decade we have
been visiting the area, there have been some wet and challenging
crossings. Often, the wind suddenly pours out of the mountains,
making the lake a churning welter of whitecaps in a quarter of an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   This time there was nothing more than a gentle breeze. The
camp's owner, Dick Celli of Lenox, Mass., greeted us and an hour
later I was assembling my fly rods _ one with a sink tip line, the
other with a floating line.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth and I were at the Rapid River's outlet pool for two hours
that evening and I caught nothing. The water temperature was 61
degrees, a bit warm for salmon.
</P>
<P>
   The following evening Celli ran his pontoon boat up to the pool
and caught two salmon, one 13{ inches long, the other just over the
minimum legal length limit of 14 inches. (The daily limit for
salmon on the Rapid River is one. It's fly fishing only and all
trout must be released. The river has good numbers of wild brook
trout, and two-pounders _ particularly a few miles upstream at Pond
in the River _ are not uncommon.) That same evening Ruth and I
remained at the pool until 8 p.m. and I caught three 12-inch salmon
and several large white suckers.
</P>
<P>
   Celli was up at dawn the next day and took a nice male salmon
nearly 20 inches long on his sixth cast. I slept late that day, my
last such indulgence. Celli left for home, planning to return in a
couple of days with his wife, Liz. He has two camps he owns on the
peninsula which juts out into the lake on the south side of the
junction of the river and Umbagog.
</P>
<P>
   I soon began to fret that we might not have even one evening
meal of salmon. An unusually warm spell _ it was in the mid-80's by
noon most days _ had begun on the weekend and showed no signs of
departing, and the river became a degree warmer each day. In
addition, upstream dam releases had raised its level about 10
inches, making it impossible _ the current was too strong and the
water too rough _ for us to anchor our canoe as far upstream in the
rapids as I would have liked.
</P>
<P>
   The hot weather stayed with us save for one afternoon when a
short-lived cold front came in from the northwest just before
sundown, and for a few hours Umbagog looked familiar, waves
crashing against the point and the gale stripping leaves from the
poplars, maples and birches that are between the camp and the
water. When the wind died, several loons began wailing and it was a
good night for sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   Another day had gone by with no salmon when Fred Andrews of
Florida Mountain, Mass., arrived and offered us a 12-inch brook
trout that he had caught trolling 17 feet down in the lake. We
accepted it with unseemly alacrity. We later visited Fred's camp at
nearby Sunday Cove, and he gave me some gasoline for my
2-horsepower outboard so that I could step up the frequency of my
unrelenting visits to the outlet pool. Fred later caught nothing
there. As far as I know, Celli's salmon were the only ones taken
the week I was there.
</P>
<P>
   My quest possessed me. Day after day, we motored to the pool,
anchored the canoe in the thrashing, foaming water while I cast
hundreds of times with various fly patterns and Ruth sketched the
same scene over and over, alternately concentrating on waves and
towering conifers. By the end of each such session, I began to be
slightly giddy from all the jouncing.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth never complained although she once commented mildly that it
seemed as if I was going to work rather than having fun. In other
years we took hikes upriver, but the heat, the general lack of wind
and the plethora of black flies and mosquitoes made walking in the
woods unappealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to catch a salmon,'' I said as we sat in our
lurching canoe. ``When you are 76, you lose agility, but gain in
sagacity and persistence.''
</P>
<P>
   One evening after all of the various streamer, wet fly and nymph
patterns had produced nothing, I _ even though no salmon were
rising _ put a dry fly, a No. 12 White Wulff, on my floating line,
made a long cast to a smooth glide in the dark, sliding water to my
left and was rewarded with a savage strike. The fish vaulted into
the air in the near darkness and I jubilantly proclaimed that I had
finally ended the jinx.
</P>
<P>
   The fish jumped again, and this time I noted that it was
unusually dark and chunky for a salmon. It jumped again and I began
to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a smallmouth bass,'' I announced to Ruth, and relaxed,
all salmon madness shed away. The bass was so large, about five
pounds and 20 inches long, that it barely fit into my trout net. I
baked it for supper that night, garnished with onions and sun-dried
tomatoes from last year's garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it better than salmon,'' said Ruth, and she wasn't
kidding. I liked it well enough to devote the next day, our last,
to a hike upriver to Smooth Ledge.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
