<HEADER>
A3018 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-INTERLEAGUE-NYT &LR;      06-12 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-INTERLEAGUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERLEAGUE THRILLS COMING FROM UNEXPECTED SOURCES THIS YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A primary attraction of interleague baseball games is supposed
to be the opportunity it affords fans to see stars from the other
league they normally wouldn't see: Ken Griffey Jr. in Denver, Larry
Walker in Arlington, Texas, Barry Bonds in Seattle, Greg Maddux in
Boston, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, though, unheralded players provide an unexpected
bonus, either for their teams' fans or someone else's: Guillermo
Mota and Dan Smith of Montreal, Nelson Cruz of Detroit, David
Newhan of San Diego, for example. Players have mixed feelings about
interleague play, but these rookies just love the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awesome, especially since we were playing Oakland,'' said
Newhan, who began his career in the Athletics' organization. ``I
know about half their lineup. It was real fun to get to play
against those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Newhan, a 25-year-old second baseman, was promoted June 4 from
Las Vegas of the Pacific Coast League, where he was hitting .307
with 10 home runs and 9 stolen bases, when shortstop Chris Gomez
was placed on the disabled list with a strained knee.
</P>
<P>
   In the Padres' first interleague game, against Seattle, he went
in as a pinch-runner in the eighth inning, stole second and scored
the winning run. In his first start, against Oakland last Tuesday,
he stroked three hits in a 5-3 victory. When he rapped a double in
the second inning for his first hit, he said, ``They gave me a
standing O; it was neat.''
</P>
<P>
   On that same night, Smith and Cruz discovered that, like Newhan,
they liked interleague play. Smith, a 23-year-old right-hander,
made his major league debut for the Expos and gave up three hits to
the first four Boston batters, then retired the next 20 he faced
before leaving for a pinch-hitter in the seventh en route to a 5-1
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz, who pitched in relief 19 times for the Chicago White Sox
in 1997, made his first major league start and was the winning
pitcher in the Tigers' 11-4 victory over Pittsburgh. The
26-year-old right-hander allowed one run and two hits in seven
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Mota, Smith's teammate, discovered a different reason for liking
interleague play. The 25-year-old Dominican, once an infielder in
the Mets' minor league system, pitched the final one and two-thirds
innings against the Red Sox on Wednesday night and retired all five
batters he faced. But that wasn't the most memorable experience he
took from his first interleague game. Making his 12th major league
relief appearance but batting for the first time, Mota socked a
three-run home run. As a minor league infielder, Mota hit 16 home
runs in five seasons. He became a pitcher in 1997 after the Expos
drafted him from the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   With Mota, Smith and their teammates beating up on Boston, then
the American League East leader, it did not enjoy the first two
series of interleague play. Five losses in six games with the
Atlanta Braves and the Expos wiped out Boston's game-and-a-half
lead and dropped it half a game behind the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   In sweeping the Red Sox, the Expos did the unthinkable. They
beat Pedro Martinez, something only one American League team, the
Chicago White Sox 10 starts earlier, had done this season. In the
first game of the series, the Red Sox lost to Carl Pavano, whom
they traded to Montreal for Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   F.P. Santangelo, who spent the previous 10 years in the Montreal
organization, the last four with the Expos, is another player who
likes interleague play. Now playing for the San Francisco Giants,
Santangelo had not hit a home run all season. Then he hit one
against Oakland and the next day his second one against Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   White Sox closer Bob Howry likes interleague play. He had eight
saves in the team's first 28 games, then went without one for the
next 24. However, in the space of three interleague games, he
earned his 9th and 10th saves, one against Pittsburgh, one against
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Erickson of Baltimore likes interleague games. Erickson,
who is the only major league pitcher to start a game in Cuba in the
last 40 years, had gained one victory in his first 12 starts but
then beat the Florida Marlins, who themselves think interleague
play is the greatest.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens in their weekend series with the Yankees,
the Marlins have had another successful segment of interleague
games. Even with the decimated team they had last year, the Marlins
had an 8-8 interleague record (compared with 46-100 intraleague)
and came into this season's games with a two-year 20-11 record,
best in either league. Then they won their first five games this
season, sweeping three from Tampa Bay and beating Baltimore twice
before Erickson beat them. Not everybody loves inter-league play.
Think Wil Cordero does? The Cleveland player broke a wrist making a
sliding catch of a Jeromy Burnitz fly ball. Chan Ho Park? He was
suspended for seven games for attacking Tim Belcher of Anaheim with
a move right out of a kung fu movie.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Two Sets of Rules
</P>
<P>
   Interleague play continues to generate debate among its
supporters and its critics, but one element gets no argument from
most people, that is, most people who don't make the rules. It
makes no sense to play by two sets of rules _ designated hitter in
American League parks, no designated hitter in National League
parks.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees went to Philadelphia last week and might as well
have left Chili Davis at home. They used him as a pinch-hitter in
two losing efforts. The Orioles left Harold Baines on the bench in
Florida, calling on him to pinch-hit once. Edgar Martinez missed
three of six Seattle road games last week, played first base twice
and pinch-hit once. Tampa Bay sent Jose Canseco to left field twice
and to the plate as a pinch-hitter once.
</P>
<P>
   Two other teams used the games as an excuse to return their
designated hitters to their rightful positions. Mo Vaughn, who
missed 17 games with an ankle injury, had been serving as the DH
since his return from the disabled list, but the Anaheim Angels put
him back at first base for six games in Los Angeles and San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Palmeiro, recovering from knee surgery, had been the
Texas Rangers' DH all season. He sat out the first interleague game
in Arizona because Randy Johnson was pitching and the left-handed
Palmeiro thinks the best position to be in to face him is on the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   But for the next five games in Arizona and Los Angeles, Palmeiro
was at first base. His hitting did not suffer. He batted .391 and
drove in nine runs. Nevertheless, when the Rangers returned home
Friday night, Palmeiro was the DH. once again.
</P>
<P>
   When National League teams play in American League parks, they
generally use the DH spot to give some of their regular players
half a day off. Playing in Cleveland last Thursday night, the
Milwaukee Brewers used Jeromy Burnitz as their DH after he had
started in right field in every one of their first 58 games.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
