</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTEBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raging in the Dugout
</P>
<P>
   In a dugout scene in Florida last Wednesday night, Albert Belle
played the part of Reggie Jackson, Ray Miller played Billy Martin
and Jeff Reboulet took the supporting role of Elston Howard. It
was, 22 years later, a re-enactment of the dugout confrontation at
Fenway Park between Jackson and Martin.
</P>
<P>
   In that encounter, Jackson raged at Martin after the Yankees'
manager (Chapter I of V) yanked him out of right field after,
Martin believed, he had loafed going after a hit. Howard, a coach,
stepped between the men as they screamed at each other.
</P>
<P>
   Reboulet was the man who stepped into the middle in the
Baltimore dugout as Belle stormed at Miller. Belle, for at least
the third time this season, had not run out a grounder in the
Orioles' ninth. Although Miller said he had planned to replace
Belle in right field with Rich Amaral before the play, Belle went
out to right and had to run back in. When he reached the dugout, he
confronted the manager.
</P>
<P>
   Miller had made a similar move eight previous times this season,
six times in one-sided games, twice with the Orioles ahead by one
or two runs. This time they led by two. But if the manager wasn't
punishing Belle by removing him from that game, he was certainly
acting punitively Friday night when he left Belle out of the lineup
for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Belle has been a shell of his former self. When he was omitted
from the lineup, he was hitting .244, had driven in 35 runs and had
hit 10 home runs, one in 21 games since May 16.
</P>
<P>
   The Winner, and Still Unbeaten
</P>
<P>
   Eight pitchers, five relievers and three starters, have run
their records this season to 5-0. Only one, however, has gone
beyond. He is Jeff Zimmerman, an unheralded reliever for the
Rangers, who only two years ago was pitching in the independent
Northern League.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman gained victory No. 6 at Los Angeles last Tuesday
night, pitching the 11th and 12th innings of a 13-inning 7-6
decision, then picked up No. 7 Friday night with a one-inning
appearance against Colorado. Those decisions gave him four of the
Rangers' last eight victories. John Wasdin of Boston has a chance
to join Zimmerman beyond 5-0. He went from a 3-0 record to 5-0 with
victories in consecutive games against Detroit May 31 and June 1.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens of the Yankees, John Smoltz of Atlanta and Brian
Bohanon of Colorado each reached 5-0, but each starter also lost
his next decision. Suffering the same fate were relievers Jason
Grimsley of the Yankees, Dennis Cook of the Mets and T.J. Mathews
of Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Part Marlins, Part Yankees
</P>
<P>
   John Henry, the commodities trader who rescued the Florida
Marlins from H.Wayne Huizenga earlier this year, still holds a 1
percent piece of the Yankees. The 60-to-90-day period he was given
to sell that tiny share has passed, but officials are not concerned
about his dual ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave us a representation that he would not participate in
any Yankees activities and not vote on any Yankees matter,'' said
Robert Dupuy, Major League Baseball's executive vice president for
administration.
</P>
<P>
   As if any limited partner of the Yankees has ever had a say in
club decisions. John McMullen said it best 20 years ago: ``There's
nothing more limited than a limited partner in the Yankees.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
