<SLUG> BC-OBIT-LOUIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARIE ST. LOUIS, 71, JAZZ FESTIVAL CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marie St. Louis, a jazz festival talent executive who
booked such artists as Duke Ellington, Louis Armstrong and Ella
Fitzgerald during a 37-year career, died of cancer Thursday at Beth
Israel Hospital in Manhattan. She was 71.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. St. Louis was senior vice president of Festival Productions
Inc., which promotes the JVC Jazz Festival, the New Orleans Jazz
and Heritage Festival, the Newport Jazz Festival and other major
events. Officials of the JVC Festival, which begins in New York
next week, announced that they would dedicate the event to her. She
was one of the first women to achieve prominence in the jazz music
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. St. Louis was married briefly to Roy St. Louis in the
1950s. Survivors include her brother, Jack Barrow; her son, Marc
St. Louis, a music producer, and a grandson, Cameron.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-99 1750EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3022 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRAWFORD-ARTS-COX     06-12 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRAWFORD-ARTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A decorative arts dynasty
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Art &AMP; Enterprise: The Virginia Carroll Crawford Collection of
American Decorative Art, 1825-1917''
</P>
<P>
   10 a.m.-5 p.m. Tuesdays-Thursdays, Saturdays; until
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Fridays; noon-5 p.m. Sundays. Through Sept. 26. $6; $4,
seniors and students; $2, children 6-18; free for members and
children under 6. High Museum of Art. 1280 Peachtree St. N.E.,
Atlanta. 404-733-4437.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The High Museum of Art is not often on the receiving
end of museum envy. It can, however, boast two exceptions in patron
Virginia Carroll Crawford and the 19th-century decorative arts
collection her largesse and enthusiasm have built.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one of the great collections of 19th-century material,''
says Kevin Stayton, decorative arts curator at the Brooklyn Museum
of Art. ``That collection couldn't be put together now at any
cost.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who has a serious exhibition on the subject has to
borrow from the High,'' says Atlanta dealer Deanne Levison.
</P>
<P>
   But not right now.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred seventy-five of the 230 objects amassed over 20
years are staying put through Sept. 26 in ``Art &AMP; Enterprise: The
Virginia Carroll Crawford Collection of American Decorative Art,
1825-1917,'' an exhibition that opened Saturday at the High.
</P>
<P>
   Diversity is the hallmark of the era, which tapped historical
styles as relentlessly as postmodern architecture. The collection
follows rapidly changing fashions. You can find Gothic Revival
andirons and classically styled silver tea sets, Egyptian-themed
mantel decorations and Arts and Crafts furniture. Pieces are as
subtle as Japanese-inspired pottery and as over the top as the wild
west chair and ottoman with backs and legs made out of steer horns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The collection is about social history as well as art
history,'' says High curator Donald Peirce, who has devoted at
least half his time to the collection since arriving in 1981. He
organized this exhibition and wrote its catalog entries.
</P>
<P>
   From the shimmering elegance of a Louis Comfort Tiffany vessel
to the stately geometry of Louis Sullivan's elevator grille, the
Virginia Carroll Crawford Collection is a window on American taste
_ affluent taste, that is. During the 19th and early 20th
centuries, the United States grew in wealth and power and, like a
three-dimensional set of Architectural Digest magazines, this show
lets us peek into a world where money was frequently no object.
Five pieces, including a delicate side chair and luxurious ottoman
by the famed Herter Brothers, came from the palatial Fifth Avenue
home of William Vanderbilt.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, perhaps, the exhibition is a celebration of a great
patron, and what such a person can mean to a museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virginia Carroll Crawford is a unique donor,'' Peirce says,
voicing an accolade seconded by curators around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``More often, collectors collect what they are interested in,''
says David Hanks, an independent curator who has been the
collection's New York consultant since its inception. ``She was
willing to collect what the museum wanted. I don't know another
parallel to that.''
</P>
<P>
   When Crawford, 72, decided in the late 1970s that she wanted to
focus her giving, she agreed to the proposal, made by curator
Katherine Farnham, to build a collection of 19th-century American
decorative arts, an area not in vogue at the time. One big reason?
Since pre-1825 American decorative arts were the rage, later
19th-century objects would be more available and less expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though it was not her interest, Mrs. Crawford showed an
openness and willingness to learn,'' Peirce says. ``Along the way,
she developed an appreciation and an eye.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The High made a bold move, and it was extraordinarily
successful,'' says Alice Cooney Frelinghuysen, curator in American
decorative arts at New York's Metropolitan Museum of Art. ``To have
a supporter who had the confidence in the institution, and the
curatorial staff to form something new, and the means to make a
difference, is a museum's dream.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Hanks served as bird dog, watching auctions and
dealers, and informing Peirce about possible purchases. If an
important piece surfaced and passed muster with Peirce, he would
present it to Crawford. These objects needed only Crawford's OK.
Thus, a purchase could be made in a matter of days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we could act quickly, we were offered the best
pieces,'' Hanks says. ``Otherwise we would have missed half the
collection.''
</P>
<P>
   Building the collection became a great adventure for Crawford.
``Once I started, I wanted it to be the best of its kind,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   For the first several years, due to lack of space at the old
High building, objects were stored in a New York warehouse, which
Crawford would occasionally visit. The collection debuted in
Atlanta along with the new museum building in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thrill was seeing the trucks carrying the
collection arrive at the new museum, and the special display
(architect) Richard Meier had created for them,'' Crawford recalls.
</P>
<P>
   The collection stimulated interest at other museums.
Subsequently, prices escalated. But the High had a head start and a
persevering patron: Peirce recalls no talk of a budget during his
18 years of working with Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have maintained our desire to have the finest,''
Crawford says. ``There are still things we want to add.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
