<SLUG> BC-DAVIDKELLEY-COLLEAGUES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What co-workers have to say about David E. Kelley
 &HT;    (With DAVIDKELLEY-Q&AMP;A.)
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer and Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What his colleagues have said told the news media about David E.
Kelley:
</P>
<P>
   Camryn Manheim (Ellenor on ``The Practice''): ``We know that
he's there with his yellow pad and churns stuff out from 9 to 5 and
goes home every night to be with Michelle Pfeiffer. I think he's an
idiot-savant. And I mean that in a really good way.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Nicole Carson (Renee on ``Ally''): ``He's warped.''
</P>
<P>
   Jane Krakowski (Elaine on ``Ally''): ``I think it's really cool
that David knows that women don't completely like each other at all
times. They like each other, but certain elements are not
attractive to the other person. Nobody is a clean package. He sort
of explores that concept with all the women.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter MacNicol (John Cage on ``Ally''): ``I don't know when I've
ever experienced this kind of symbiosis with a writer.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry Hamlin (``L.A. Law''): ``I left `L.A. Law' for one reason,
and that was because David Kelley was leaving. I said, `If you find
someone as good as Kelley, I'll stay.' They couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Elodie Keene (director who's worked on Kelley shows from ``L.A.
Law'' to ``Ally''): ``I've been on shows when David left, and what
happens to the writing and the characters is a sad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Bochco (Kelley's mentor, who hired him for ``L.A. Law''):
``I am in awe of David Kelley, simply in awe.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelli Williams (Lindsay on ``The Practice''): ``He's like a rock
star who doesn't sing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
