<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3024 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAVIDKELLEY-Q&AMP;A-COX     06-12 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIDKELLEY-Q&AMP;A-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Changes afoot for `Ally,' writer Kelley says
 &HT;    (With DAVIDKELLEY-COLLEAGUES.)
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the universe according to David E. Kelley,
attorneys quickly get over the shock of finding a severed head in a
bowling ball bag and start plotting legal strategy. A brilliant
surgeon on the edge of a nervous breakdown warbles ``And the Band
Played On'' in a desperate vibrato. People gather in a unisex
bathroom and break into shuffle-step choreography to a Barry White
oldie.
</P>
<P>
   And just as the real universe is expanding, so is Kelley's
uniquely skewed fantasy universe. This fall, the creator of Fox's
``Ally McBeal,'' ABC's ``The Practice'' and CBS' ``Chicago Hope''
will be on three networks with five series (including a new ABC
series ``Snoops'') _ or four-and-a-half, depending on how you count
the strange idea of repackaging ``Ally'' as a half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley leaves most people in the TV industry shaking their heads
in wonder. This past season, he wrote all 22 episodes of ``Ally''
and most episodes of ``The Practice,'' virtually unheard of in an
industry that uses entire teams to write one half-hour of comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley, 42, was a Boston lawyer when he started writing scripts
for ``L.A. Law'' in the late '80s. He moved to Los Angeles and
started honing his vision, which frequently involves serious social
issues being discussed in a bizarre context.
</P>
<P>
   In New York recently to accept two Peabody Awards for ``Ally''
and ``The Practice'' _ added to Golden Globes for both shows and a
best drama Emmy for ``Practice'' _ the soft-spoken Kelley answered
questions about his shows and, a little more reluctantly, himself.
</P>
<P>
   Q:The new half-hour ``Ally'' is puzzling a lot of people. How
much is going to be recycled and how much will be new stuff we
haven't seen?
</P>
<P>
   A:It'll play more fresh than people think. The majority will be
material people have seen, with one, maybe two new scenes in any
given episode. They'll have new music and be recut. These are
funnier and a little more quickly paced.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Who came up with this idea and why?
</P>
<P>
   A:I'm sort of embarrassed to say. I'm always accused of being a
horrible businessman, but my business nose led with this one. The
syndication market for one-hours is not as strong as for
half-hours, and there was this feeling this show might not be as
timeless as other shows. I thought I could crunch this show to a
half-hour. Once I started to do it as an experiment, I was
surprised to find some of these half-hours played better than the
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Q:You're also going back to ``Chicago Hope'' in the fall. What
is the deal?
</P>
<P>
   A:The deal is just trying to have it survive. It was on life
support in terms of being renewed. I just felt there was some
potential in it that was untapped. I won't be writing the episodes,
but I will play more of an active role, which I really haven't been
doing. I expect I'll be polishing up the (Dr. Jeffrey) Geiger
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Q:How are you going to get all this done?
</P>
<P>
   A:I'm building more of a (writing) staff on ``The Practice,''
and maybe next year will be a little easier. By and large I'll
still be hands-on with ``Ally'' and ``The Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Q:And (the new ABC detective drama) ``Snoops''?
</P>
<P>
   A:``Snoops'' I'm launching, and I'll be a consultant. That show
has writers who are better suited to that genre than I am anyway.
I'm probably doing them a favor by getting out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Q:The shows other than ``Ally'' are probably easier for other
writers to take over. Is it hard for other writers to get into that
(Ally) voice?
</P>
<P>
   A:Yeah. I haven't found 'em yet. But I'm not actively looking.
The prospect of continuing to write all the episodes for three,
four, five more years isn't that daunting.
</P>
<P>
   Q:The whimsy of ``Ally'' _ if that's a word that doesn't give
offense _ may be hard to sustain over a long period. Maybe the show
starts to taper off, or the audience says we've been though this
before. Is that a concern?
</P>
<P>
   A:I think that will always be something we have to be conscious
of. Ally always has to grow and change to refresh itself. Sometimes
it's by adding new characters, sometimes by taking existing
characters down new paths. There's not a pressure to come back next
year and do it like we did last year. That's what's fun for me as a
writer. Lord knows on most television shows, if it ain't broke,
don't fix it. That doesn't apply here. It's not a question of being
broke, it's a matter of growing to stay viable.
</P>
<P>
   Q:On ``Ally,'' is there a fine line between establishing
something unusual, be it dancing babies, frogs, Barry White and
making sure you get out before you overdo it?
</P>
<P>
   A:Absolutely. And you never know where that line is. There was
one case where I felt I couldn't be objective and that's where the
jury started singing ``Trouble'' with (John) Cage. And I always
loved ``The Music Man,'' but I was seriously wondering, ``Am I the
only one that thinks this is funny?'' I took it home and put the
cassette in for my wife (actress Michelle Pfeiffer) because she'll
tell me. And I said, ``Did we cross the line this time?'' And she
said, ``No, it's funny.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't want to play it too safe. And you don't want to fall
over and go splat. There have been some cases where we have.
</P>
<P>
   Q:In the (unisex) bathroom?
</P>
<P>
   A:The bathroom never bothers me. People have told me that you've
gone too far in the bathroom, but I continue to be amused by it.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Sexual harassment and gender war issues play a huge role in
``Ally,'' and somewhat of a role in ``The Practice.'' Why are you
so interested in these issues?
</P>
<P>
   A:I'm interested in themes of women in the workplace and men in
the workplace contending with women. That workplace is evolving,
and so is the law _ the law has just been all over the place. It's
great fodder.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Do you ever get sick of everyone in the industry telling you
how wonderful you are and kowtowing to you?
</P>
<P>
   A:Especially with ``Ally,'' there's a lot of people who don't
like the show, who find it annoying. If you want to accept the
accolades, then you have to accept the criticism. It feels over
here like the company is in the middle of its 15 minutes (of fame),
and we're just trying to enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   Q:The notion of Ally as a post-feminist icon and lightning rod
seems to have died down some. What was that scrutiny like?
</P>
<P>
   A:It was very surprising to see the show being taken so
seriously. We were ill-equipped to respond to it. When we started
out, we got a lot of criticism aimed at our ``intent'' to depict
Ally as the personification of womankind. That was never our
intent.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Of all the characters on your shows, whom do you feel
personally closest to?
</P>
<P>
   A:I don't know. The two characters would probably be Cage and
Ally. There's more of me in them than in the others. But I don't
liken myself to either Ally or Cage.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What parts of you are like them?
</P>
<P>
   A:I suppose the inner worlds that both of them retreat to is
something I identify with, as a writer who spends most of my day in
an imaginary world.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Do you have a theme song?
</P>
<P>
   A:I don't. I think I have a lot of theme songs. The effect that
a theme song can have on Ally, or Barry White on Cage, I've
experienced that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
