<SLUG> BC-OBIT-KALBACHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUGENE KALBACHER, 47, JAZZ JOURNAL EDITOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Eugene Kalbacher, the publisher and editor of Hot
House, a small monthly magazine covering the jazz world, died on
May 25 at his home in Rockaway Township, N.J. He was 47.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, said his wife, Lynn.
</P>
<P>
   Kalbacher was a young jazz journalist who saw great potential in
jazz developments of the early 1980s, and when the New York-area
radio station WRVR changed its format from all-jazz to all-country
at the beginning of the decade, it was a signal to him to start a
replacement all-jazz media outlet. In 1981 he and another jazz
journalist, Jeff Levenson, founded Hot House, a free monthly
publication that ran feature stories on musicians playing in New
York and carried complete listings of jazz in clubs and concert
halls in the metropolitan area. The magazine, available at jazz
clubs and record stores, has been published regularly ever since;
now it will be run by Mrs. Kalbacher. While running the magazine,
Kalbacher also wrote for the magazines Downbeat, Pulse and College
Music Journal and wrote liner notes for the record labels Enja and
Evidence.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by his mother, Gladys
Kalbacher, and two brothers, Bruce and Paul, both of Ghent, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-99 1807EDT &QL; 
