<HEADER>
A3034 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-KIDS-ID-NYT &LR;      06-12 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KIDS-ID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WHERE'S YOUR ID, KID? 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial Sunday, June 13:
</P>
<P>
   So, it's Saturday night at the movies. The ticket seller is
taking forever, especially when the buyer has acne or green hair.
Somebody starts to mutter, and a few customers threaten to boycott
the theater's profitable golden popcorn. How long, then, will
theater managers maintain their pledge made to President Clinton
that they will demand photo ID's for young people trying to go to
R-rated movies? The answer is probably until the public starts
worrying about something other than violent entertainment and
Congress stops threatening to curb media violence with unworkable
and unconstitutional laws.
</P>
<P>
   Over three decades ago, the movie industry launched the rating
system it still uses, shoving sex, violence and rough language
under an all-purpose R label. Anyone under the age of 17 is barred
from an R-rated movie unless accompanied by an adult. Enforcement,
however, has always been uneven. In most rural areas, theater
owners tend their doors like surrogate parents. In urban areas,
theaters too often focus not on the buyer's years, but on the
number of dollars thrust through the ticket window.
</P>
<P>
   Despite photo ID's and parental admonitions, determined teens
will find a way to see ``The Matrix.'' The most persistent can
enlist a willing adult to chaperone. The most patient can wait for
the video. The wiliest might go to the nearest multi-theater
complex, buy a ticket to see ``Aladdin'' and then try to slip
next-door for Bruce Willis.
</P>
<P>
   Still, trying to enforce the code is a helpful step toward
sparing youngsters the blood-and-guts cinema that is often made for
global markets where explosions and gun battles need little
translation. Another important step came last weekend when Jack
Valenti, the Washington lobbyist for the major Hollywood studios,
advised film makers to cut ``gratuitous'' violence from their
pictures and to ask themselves, ``Is this the best I can do?'' That
is a very good question, not only for those who make movies, but
also for producers of video games, television and music.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-99 1813EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
