<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3036 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SICKLECELL-SUCCESS-CO     06-12 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SICKLECELL-SUCCESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sickle-cell patient appears to be clear of disease
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An experimental procedure to cure sickle cell anemia
appears to have eliminated all traces of the disease from a
suburban Atlanta boy.
</P>
<P>
   Although the doctor who performed the procedure is not yet
claiming a cure, his experiment is being closely watched because it
could dramatically increase the number of potential blood donors
for the 70,000 victims of the blood disease. Sickle cell is an
inherited disease which strikes mostly black people and can be
fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Andrew Yeager, director of hematology, oncology and bone
marrow transplantation at Emory University School of Medicine,
performed the procedure on Keone Penn last December.
</P>
<P>
   The experiment, done at Atlanta's Egleston Children's Hospital,
was groundbreaking on three fronts: It marked the first time that a
sickle cell patient was treated with stem cell blood; the donor was
not related to the patient; and the donor blood was not a complete
match with Keone's _ only five of six key blood properties matched.
</P>
<P>
   But it has worked _ so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I have hope for my kid, college and getting married, and
all the things people hope for for their kids,'' said Keone's
mother, Leslie Penn.
</P>
<P>
   Keone celebrated his new-found health _ and his 13 birthday _
Saturday at his home in Gwinnett County's Centerville community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made it,'' Keone said, grinning under a new head of hair
grown out since chemotherapy. ``I'm talking, my heart's beating and
my brain is working.''
</P>
<P>
   Up until now, the only successful bone marrow transplants for
sickle cell sufferers have involved the patients' siblings or an
extremely rare marrow match found through a national registry.
</P>
<P>
   Yeager performed what was believed to be the world's first stem
cell transplant for a sickle cell patient, using a newborn's
umbilical cord blood, which is rich in the substance that grows new
bone marrow. It's a dangerous procedure that posed the potentially
fatal risk of an overwhelming infection attacking Keone's
suppressed immune system.
</P>
<P>
   But it looks like the risk paid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks great, and spiritwise he's really up there,'' Yeager
said. ``And his cord blood (transplant) remains stable and fully
functioning.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Yeager said he can't use the c-word _ cure _ quite yet.
``I want to, but medically I can't say it. We need a longer
observation time, six more months....There's always that slight
chance he may reject his new blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Sickle cell disease causes great pain as odd-shaped blood cells
get stuck in veins. It often triggers strokes, infections and
premature death.
</P>
<P>
   The disease was considered incurable until recently, when
doctors began experimenting with bone marrow transplants similar to
those given to cancer patients. Yeager performed the most risky
bone marrow procedure _ a stem cell transplant. The cells were
collected from the placenta and umbilical cord of an anonymous
woman and found through the New York Blood Center. Keone had been
unable to find a close enough bone marrow match from his
half-sister or from the national donor registry.
</P>
<P>
   The disease was devastating for Keone. He suffered a stroke at
age 5, excruciating pain, numerous infections and needed monthly
blood transfusions.
</P>
<P>
   Keone received the stem cell blood Dec. 11 after undergoing 10
days of chemotherapy to kill his own bone marrow that contained the
sickled cells. The cord blood gave him a whole new system of red
cells, white cells and platelets.
</P>
<P>
   Gathering for his birthday, friends and family rejoiced in the
news that his body now shows no sign of the blood disorder. ``This
is a wonderful celebration,'' his mother said. ``We have so many
things to be thankful for. We're so blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
