<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3037 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAYTON-ACCORD-COX     06-12 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAYTON-ACCORD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kosovo's future? Bosnia-Herzegovina enters fifth year of
enforced peace
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ Four years after the end of a
brutal war, Bosnia-Herzegovina and its capital city of Sarajevo
have come far toward healing the wounds.
</P>
<P>
   But as the international community begins looking at problems
elsewhere in the region and the world, much of the Dayton Peace
Accord that ended the war in Bosnia remains a work in progress,
with all sides from the war still objecting to some of the
provisions in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a peace agreement, but at the same time it was a
declaration of separation,'' Sarajevo Mayor Rasin Gacanovic told a
goodwill delegation from Dayton, Ohio, last week.
</P>
<P>
   Sarajevo is still dealing with emotional and physical scars that
printed words on the Dayton Peace Accord are having difficulty
healing.
</P>
<P>
   A flood of international aid has come to Bosnia since the war's
end, and armed United Nations peacekeepers move about the cities
and countrysides, creating odd juxtapositions for Bosnians in daily
life.
</P>
<P>
   As well-dressed Sarajevans bustle through their downtown
commercial district, they must make room for a dizzying array of
international aid organizations and regular appearances by the
peacekeeping troops.
</P>
<P>
   The international workers are immediately obvious, driving in
the largest, newest cars or rugged sport utility vehicles. Local
residents' tend toward small, European cars that can more easily
dart through the city's narrow streets.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the only weapons visible in Sarajevo are the
automatic rifles of camouflage-wearing peacekeepers. Their constant
presence has begun to aggravate some city residents.
</P>
<P>
   For people who lived through three years of war, just the sight
of camouflage and guns brings on a momentary panic.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Graconivic spoke of no aggravation, just disappointment
Bosnia-Herzegovina needed to turn to outside help at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately our country did not have the necessary forces
and it was necessary for a third-party to take part in the peace
plan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sarajevans know when their three-person presidency is meeting at
its offices in town. It's when Italian troops drive jeeps, mounted
with machine guns, onto the streets in front of the federal
government building.
</P>
<P>
   One Muslim, one Croat and one Serb sit in each seat of the
presidency, and continued tension and ill will from the war between
the ethnic groups brings in the peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Haris Silajdzic, one of two prime ministers, said the situation
has become almost unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is just impossible to live this way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The effects of the war are still heavily on the minds of
Sarajevans.
</P>
<P>
   Gacanovic used the visit by the Dayton delegation to repeat his
call for people who committed atrocities to be brought to justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no unification without having all the war criminals
charged and tried,'' Gacanovic said. ``We know that justice will be
satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout a pleasant evening on a hillside patio last week,
beneath the spreading branches of rose bushes and grape vines, a
retired Sarajevan couple talked matter-of-factly about the war.
Many Sarajevans do. The war was such a consuming part of their
lives, there is no way not to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   The father could not gesture and talk about his beautifully kept
vegetable garden without recounting the number of mortar shells
that landed in it. Scars are showed. Some residents carry pieces of
shrapnel still in their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The hills of the city make the region beautiful, but it is from
there that shells and bullets rained down for three years.
Residents said the beautiful hills that help give Sarajevo its
identity had suddenly become the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Residents recall vividly the fluttering sound incoming shells
made when they were likely to pass overhead. The ones coming
straight in near you made a piercing, high-pitched whine.
</P>
<P>
   Several U.S. officials said the Bosnians are being urged to
implement the major elements of the Dayton Peace Accord because the
commitment international forces have made to the country is
unlikely to last forever.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. military officials claim the ethnic Serb part of the
country, the Republika Srpska, is in political and military
disarray. But it still maintains its own armed forces and has a
huge superiority in artillery over the rest of the country. The
Yugoslavian army and Bosnian Serbs used that artillery to earn what
military success they achieved during the war.
</P>
<P>
   There are millions of mines still scattered along what was the
final border between the armed forces when the war ended in 1995,
but eliminating them is going so slowly as to be of little use.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 3,500 years this sector will be clear of mines,'' U.S. Army
Col. Mike Milano said.
</P>
<P>
   The city's old downtown section is once again brimming with
cafes and fashion boutiques crammed into storefronts that still
have bullet holes and evidence of shelling. Couples stroll through
the area, young couples holding hands and young adults wheeling
baby carriages.
</P>
<P>
   But the city would be having a difficult time of things even if
the first mortar shell had never fallen. The country is still
trying to shake off communism, which was in place for 45 years
before petering out a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Capitalism has already created some of the conditions that are
reported to be out of control in the former Soviet Union. There are
signs of great wealth and even a middle class, but children beg on
the streets, asking for a Deutschmark for wiping a car's windshield
or ``standing guard'' over a car in the airport parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   For all the new wealth has refurbished and built anew, the
majority of the buildings in the city still are pock-marked with
huge scars left by mortar blasts.
</P>
<P>
   The economy is down, and there is little sign of direct
investment by U.S. companies. One senior state department official
said companies like McDonald's have tried to come in but pulled out
after being blocked by bureaucracy and cronyism in the Sarajevan
government.
</P>
<P>
   Officially the unemployment rate stands at 70 percent, and
locals say joblessness is a problem, but that many people work for
cash and never report their wages to the government.
</P>
<P>
   Residents repeatedly apologize for their rutted, rumble-strip
roads.
</P>
<P>
   But there are signs of work. Buildings throughout the region
have been rebuilt, out to the smallest distant village. In
Sarajevo, scaffolding and cranes dot the skyline.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the war's message _ and a sign that underlying tension
still exists _ hits Bosnians every day as they pass through their
damaged city.
</P>
<P>
   On the wall of the National Library, which Serb shelling burned
and destroyed early in the war, is posted a sign meant to remind
what ``Serb criminals'' did to the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not forget,'' the sign reads. ``Remember and warn.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bebbington writes for the Dayton Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
