<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3038 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FOOD-FRENZY-830(2T     06-12 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FOOD-FRENZY-830(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORKERS ARE HAVING A FEEDING FRENZY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Ky.)  (lb) 
 By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The astonishing explosion of New York City's
specialty food markets began as a gustatory version of Genesis: In
the beginning there was Balducci's, Dean &AMP; DeLuca and Zabar's. And
they were good. And culinary darkness no longer blighted the face
of Manhattan. And the merchants said: Let there be more.
</P>
<P>
   And so there was Vinegar Factory and Gourmet Garage and Eli's
Manhattan and Healthy Pleasures and Grace's Marketplace and Agata &AMP;
Valentina and Garden of Eden Farmers Markets and Amish Manhattan
Farmers Markets and a grand mitosis of Greenmarkets.
</P>
<P>
   And they were good. But how much of a good thing can you have
before it becomes, well, bad? Is the city now the world's capital
of gourmet glut?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is just so much stuff for sale, it can be really
confusing,'' said Chris Sadoff, a violinist who has lived on West
73rd Street for two decades and has watched her neighborhood become
a microcosm of the city's galloping gastronomy. ``Who are these
people living on caviar all the time? I'm not sure why all these
stores are opening.''
</P>
<P>
   She was peering into the new addition at Fairway on Broadway and
74th Street, now the epicenter of a fiercely competitive
seven-block food fight on the West Side of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In coming weeks the market, which has expanded three times since
1975, will complete its incursion into the two-story space that was
once the no man's land between no-frills Fairway and its primordial
rival, Citarella, where fish, meats, poultry and produce are
arrayed like jewelry on two floors at the corner of West 75th
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Only 60 paces to the south of Fairway, Food Emporium _ perhaps
aspiring to capitalize on the hungry hordes from Donald Trump's
Riverside South development _ established its 22nd upscale
beachhead in December. The store even has a
green-and-white-uniformed doorman with a gold-braided cap who calls
cabs for customers. He directs shoppers to the sleek escalator that
takes them down to the anti-Fairway: a cheerful 21,000-square-foot
basement space.
</P>
<P>
   And to the north, plugging the Broadway gap between Citarella
and the legendary Zabar's on West 80th Street, the unlegendary
Westside Supermarket gives customers yet another shopping option at
the corner of West 77th Street.
</P>
<P>
   In the bull-market, fin-de-siecle rush to excess, the city's
gourmet generals have been seizing strategic territory.
</P>
<P>
   A year after the perpetually expanding Fairway leapfrogged north
to establish a bastion at 132nd Street and 12th Avenue, Citarella
opened a satellite across town from its main store, at 75th Street
and Third Avenue; Citarella has leased another space in Grand
Central Station.
</P>
<P>
   And Gourmet Garage _ the warehouse-style purveyor that provides
specialty foods to 180 restaurants, including Le Cirque 2000 and
the Four Seasons _ has cloned itself in four Manhattan locations
since 1992. ``We are expanding aggressively, and our plan is to do
two or three new stores a year,'' said John Gottfried, a partner,
who said he has made offers on two new properties.
</P>
<P>
   Eli Zabar's Vinegar Factory on East 91st Street, which was
originally opened by Gourmet Garage and taken over by its landlord,
Zabar, has siblings at Eli's Manhattan on Third Avenue at 80th
Street, and E.A.T. on Madison Avenue at 80th.
</P>
<P>
   Balducci's has planned to establish suburban satellites.
Balducci family feuds led to a diaspora and the establishment of
the high-end Agata &AMP; Valentina at 79th Street and First Avenue
(which recently doubled its space) as well as the upscale Grace's
Marketplace at 71st Street and Third Avenue, which also has
expanded and added a butcher.
</P>
<P>
   Whole Foods Market has leased 40,000 square feet of space on
Seventh Avenue and 24th Street for a blockbuster organic food
market. Healthy Pleasures on University Place in the Village, which
claims to be the city's largest natural-foods store, has opened a
satellite in SoHo on Broome Street.
</P>
<P>
   Amish Manhattan Farmers Market in Hell's Kitchen opened a
sibling on East 45th Street near Third Avenue, and just this month
unveiled another at Cedar Street. And the two Garden of Eden
Farmers Markets, in Gramercy Park and Chelsea, are planning an
outpost on West 14th Street.
</P>
<P>
   The food retailing frenzy leaves some shoppers all epicured out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have five places now where I can buy cheese instead of
two,'' said Nora Ephron, the director and writer, who lives in the
Zabar's orbit and who shot scenes there for her most recent film,
``You've Got Mail.'' ``At first I thought, well, someone will go
out of business, but apparently there is no telling how much food
you can sell.''
</P>
<P>
   While many consumers are benefiting from runaway variety, new
challenges are being posed by the New York's superabundance of
brie. ``It is very easy to go into one of these places and walk out
with a small bag that costs you $100,'' said Tim Zagat, whose
latest New York City Marketplace Survey, an overview of 1,360 food
purveyors, has just been published.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hardy specialty-food shoppers have refined their coping
strategies. Especially scorned by the store owners are the
bargain-hunting cherry pickers, who ``go for sale items,'' said one
store manager. ``We don't make any money on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the uptown strategy. David Brody, an entomologist
at the American Museum of Natural History, walks north along ``the
strip,'' as he calls it, heading from the Food Emporium to Zabar's.
``I check the price, I see what's fresh, what looks good. It's
entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrarily, Mildred Grant favors the downtown search, starting
at 75th Street. ``I just start at Citarella and work my way
south,'' she said, winding up at Food Emporium, which is owned by
Great Atlantic &AMP; Pacific Tea Co., ``for sales and staples.'' She
smiled. ``I was born to shop.''
</P>
<P>
   There are even those so victimized by gourmet glut that they
totally opt out of high-end shopping. ``It's too crazy here,'' said
Nina Rhodes, a West Side resident for 20 years, as she glanced past
the sidewalk flower stand to the frenzy within Fairway. ``I just go
to the A&AMP;P on West End Avenue and 70th, where it's not so hectic.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, shoppers are not only sought after but studied.
``You need a population of about 14,000 upper-income people to
support one of these stores,'' said Gottfried of Gourmet Garage.
With their high-margin offerings and prepared foods, specialty
markets can soar: Their competitors estimate that Zabar's and
Fairway, only six blocks apart, each take in $50 million in revenue
each year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the current market proliferation is surprising, given the
hard realities of the business.
</P>
<P>
   Yearly retail rents of $100 to $150 a square foot in Manhattan
make opening new stores prohibitively expensive in the fickle,
labor-intensive grocery business. Worse, experts say that for every
10 feet of selling space, a store needs about 3 feet of
nonproductive storage and preparation space.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, merchants cannot throw in a few tubs of Kumomoto
oysters just anywhere and reap a windfall. Gottfried estimated that
the market for Manhattan specialty food stores is ``about 80
percent saturated, but there are still neighborhoods that haven't
been penetrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond this, the city's retail specialty-food economy, which
analysts estimate at close to $300 million, ``is incredibly
competitive,'' said Saul Zabar, president of Zabar's, the
gastronomic landmark that has been around since 1936. ``We are
always running scared here, and we have to be on our toes more than
ever. That said, all I know is that we are selling substantially
more fish and prepared foods than we did last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the turf battles can get sort of ugly (Fairway and
Citarella actually engaged in an awning war this year), even fierce
competitors see an advantage in proximity. ``We overlap with
Fairway's customers,'' said Mindy Birnbaum, a spokeswoman for
Citarella, when asked about the Fairway expansion. ``So if more
people come to the block, then we're bound to benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Citarella's archrival was no less optimistic. ``I think there is
an infinite market for the good operators,'' said Howard Glickberg,
an owner of Fairway. ``The Red Apples, the Sloan's, they draw 90
percent of their customers from a four-block area. But we draw from
all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the specialty merchants are such a draw that bus
companies are mounting day trips for food worshippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first stop is Zabar's,'' said Greg Abbott, a spokesman for
Dattco in New Britain, Conn., which conducts a ``Noshing Tour'' of
Manhattan 20 times a year. After about 50 foodies per busload have
descended on Zabar's, they head back into their red-and-white MCI
tour bus and proceed to Balducci's. That is followed by a visit to
Guss' Lower East Side Pickles, a tour of Chinatown markets and
finally a stroll through Little Italy.
</P>
<P>
   But academics are traveling even greater distances. ``My
students ooh and aah in these markets,'' said Nancy Graham, an
assistant professor in the hospitality department of Morehead State
University in Morehead, Ky. She and her daughter stood near the
$2.99-a-pound New Zealand pears at Fairway and explained that they
had brought 13 of their hotel students to New York to research the
exotic markets of the natives, starting at Balducci's and working
their way up to Zabar's.
</P>
<P>
   Given such interest, some insist that New York markets are
poised to conquer the nation. ``Whatever food you may want in Sioux
City, Iowa, you can have it delivered in less than 24 hours,
through mail order and the Internet,'' Zagat said. ``Soon every
major store in New York will be online and available to the entire
country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
