<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECKETTS MIGHT BE ROOTING FOR VAN GUNDY AS A GENERAL MANAGER,
TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeff Van Gundy has dedicated his professional life to coaching,
preferring to remain on the sideline and away from the corporate
offices of the team. But as his stature grows in New York, one
wonders if the Knicks would dangle the dual role of general manager
and coach in front of him after the team's stunning post-season
run.
</P>
<P>
   Since Ernie Grunfeld was reassigned by Madison Square Garden
president Dave Checketts in April, Checketts has taken over
day-to-day duties of the team. After Friday night's clinching Game
6 victory over Indiana, Checketts admitted to being caught up in
the emotion of the moment enough to join in the post-game chanting.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Checketts insisted he would wait until the season to
deal with Van Gundy's job status, as both parties agreed to do
earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the image of the Garden president mouthing the words, ``Jeff
Van Gun-Dee!'' along with nearly 20,000 others, cannot help but
speak volumes.
</P>
<P>
   As the Knicks head for San Antonio for the league championship
series this week, perhaps the ill will between the two is
subsiding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think tonight, you know, if you want me to make a definitive
statement, it's not about that,'' Checketts said after the Knicks'
90-82 victory. ``It is about the fact that we're working very well
together, we're communicating. We both agree: we're going to sit
down after the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Checketts entrusted Ed Tapscott, the assistant general manager,
to take care of scouting for the draft and other personnel details.
Tapscott should be in the running for the general manager's job _
especially if Van Gundy, whom he has worked with for most of the
last decade, is retained as coach.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of Checketts remaining in that role should not
be ruled out, either.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if Van Gundy can take the team to its first championship in
26 years, he may be in line for not only a long-term extension but
also more say and power in organizational matters.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it may be the only way he would want to be retained by
the Knicks. Negotiating the maze of politics in the Garden was
something he detested this past season, his feud with Grunfeld over
personnel the obvious indicator.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, in lieu of all the underhanded behavior at the
Garden this season _ some of which Van Gundy has privately admitted
taking part in _ would the Knicks be willing to give Van Gundy that
kind of authority?
</P>
<P>
   Would Checketts' superiors at Cablevision, some of whom have
openly questioned in staff meetings how the coach runs his team,
give Van Gundy a long-term deal worth in the neighborhood of $20
million?
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, the coach who figured to be out of a job less than
a month ago is now sitting pretty on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   A berth in the finals guaranteed the final year of Van Gundy's
contract, and thus insured him of collecting $6 million over the
next two seasons regardless of whether the club plans to relieve
him of his duties.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the $2 million he will receive as coach, the club is
forced to pick up an option year worth $3.5 million based on a
contract clause that stipulated the money must be paid if Van Gundy
guided the Knicks to the championship round.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy can also earn another $300,000 guaranteed if the
Knicks win the title.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the emotional satisfaction transcended the financial
reward on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he felt like he just had won the lottery, Van Gundy
said: ``No. I won't even dignify that.''
</P>
<P>
   Divorce in Orlando
</P>
<P>
   When Doc Rivers was interviewing for the Orlando Magic head
coach's job before accepting it last Monday, he made one point
clear to management: Before the team moved Anfernee Hardaway, the
disgruntled point guard, he wanted to sit down with him and gauge
his feelings about remaining in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   If Hardaway felt his relationship with the franchise could be
mended, Rivers would back the former All-Star's return. But
Hardaway beat him to the punch on Friday, exercising an escape
clause in his contract to become a free agent July 1.
</P>
<P>
   That means the Magic must perform a sign-and-trade deal with
another team to obtain any compensation for Hardaway. If he does
not cooperate and decides to sign with Toronto, the Clippers or
Chicago _ the teams with the kind of salary-cap room to pay him
handsomely _ the Magic will have lost their second franchise player
in four years for nothing in return.
</P>
<P>
   Losing Shaquille O'Neal was a crime. Losing Hardaway may be the
best thing. Regardless of whether the Magic gets anything in
return, it would rid itself not only of his burdensome salary but
also the petulance and inconsistency of his past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   According to one Eastern Conference team official, Rivers
informally surveyed former teammates and coaches of Hardaway and
found a consensus: Hardaway was difficult to coach and play with,
and coddling wouldn't change that.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond a possible sign-and-trade-deal for Boston's Ron Mercer
and Kenny Anderson, the Magic is thinking about trying to coax Gary
Payton away from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``No disrespect to Penny, but it would take more than him to pry
Gary from Seattle,'' one Western Conference team official said.
``They're going to have to come back with much more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton is watching what the Sonics do in the off season to
improve the team before demanding a trade. Hersey Hawkins may be
one of several players, along with draft picks, that Seattle
packages in an attempt to lure a legitimate big man. The Lakers,
Minnesota and Houston are all interested in Payton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary's situation is he's sitting back and seeing what the
Sonics do,'' Aaron Goodwin, Payton's agent, said. ``He wants to
retire in Seattle, but only time will tell if that's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Vin Baker's stock has fallen after a miserable, injury-riddled
season with the Sonics. As one of the few prized free agents this
summer, he may be on his way out as well.
</P>
<P>
   Around the League  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From the Don't Worry About Paying Your Dues file: Doc Rivers,
37, was recently asked why he became such a hot commodity the last
few months. ``They hear me on TV, that's why,'' he said of his
Turner Sports analyst's job. ``That was Chuck Daly's advice. When I
retired and was thinking about taking an assistant job, Chuck said:
`Well, if you want to be a head coach, I think more people will
hear you on TV than they'll see you sitting next to the head coach.
He was right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
