A3041 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-NY-LEGI     06-12 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-NY-LEGIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: ALBANY FORGETS HOW TO PRETEND TO LEGISLATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York state Legislature has always posed a challenge to
people who believe in the inevitable progression of human history.
But critics who have called it impervious to change are wrong.
Lately the system has gotten worse.
</P>
<P>
   The state has long led the nation in overdue budgets while
bringing up the rear in ethics regulation. But now, the legislative
paralysis is accompanied by a veritable frenzy of campaign
fund-raising. If a committee holds a meeting in which a bill is
actually discussed, it is a day to remember. But if the chairman
takes a break from legislative business to walk across the street
and host a fund-raising party for the lobbyists who work his
committee, it is par for the course.
</P>
<P>
   These parties have grown so pervasive that it scares people.
``When I came here in 1984, there were occasional fund-raisers, but
now some nights you have 18,'' says Blair Horner of the New York
Public Interest Research Group. In the past, lobbyists at least
honored the fiction that there was no direct connection between
their willingness to pay hundreds, or even thousands, of dollars to
eat cocktail weenies with lawmakers and the legislative process
itself. But now, members report that they are being pressed for
favors right over the hors d'oeuvres.
</P>
<P>
   ``The niceties are falling apart,'' said Senate Minority Leader
Martin Connor. ``I don't think anybody's selling their vote, but
you also aren't supposed to give the appearance of selling your
vote.'' There is a growing fear that somebody  &UR; will &LR;  eventually get
caught up in an influence-peddling scandal, particularly since
legislators have gone for months without being paid, under a new
law that stops their salaries once the budget is overdue.
</P>
<P>
   Albany has always been a highly partisan culture in which
individual lawmakers are expected to follow the party leader. That
works fine if voters can identify the party that is making the
decisions and throw it out when things go badly. But over the last
few decades, the legislative leaders, armed with the latest
computers, have perfected a gerrymandering that makes most seats
safe for whoever happens to be occupying them. That gave the
Republicans a death grip on the state Senate and the Democrats a
death grip on the Assembly, throwing the place into perpetual
stalemate. Figuring out who was really responsible for anything
became a puzzle even for Capitol regulars. The leaders became
stronger in their ability to control the party troops and to raise
money from lobbyists, even as they lost power to actually pass
serious legislation. Now, the Legislature revolves around raising
money to win elections in which the outcome is already assured. The
public has long since lost interest in a process it cannot
comprehend, and the lawmakers are performing for an audience of a
few thousand people _ themselves, the lobbyists, the staff and a
handful of reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The rituals of a real, functioning democracy are slowly falling
away. Lobbyists and special-interest groups still occasionally drag
their constituents up to the Capitol to buttonhole legislators,
because they have always done it. But more and more of them simply
stick to working the fund-raisers. ``They don't even bother to have
people write letters,'' says one committee chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Some legislators still slave away on major initiatives, like
Assemblyman Alexander Grannis of Manhattan, who points with pride
to bills he has worked on this year, including auto-insurance
reform and an ``integrity in government act'' that would ban
political fund-raisers in Albany while the Legislature is in
session. But he admits that the state Senate has no interest in the
insurance bill, and that his own leaders will never allow lobbying
reform to make it to the floor for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Grannis, a 25-year veteran, came to Albany with the
post-Watergate generation, which was actually interested in
politics. The newer members, even the most dedicated, know that the
way to rise in the system is to raise more money than your
neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki, although himself a former legislator, has no
respect for the legislative culture. He ignored a deal between the
Assembly and Senate on last year's budget, vetoing a raft of items,
most of which were Democratic priorities. He refuses to rule out
doing the same thing this year, and the Democrats have no real
comeback except delay. Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver can hardly
appeal to the public, which has long since tuned out on the whole
incomprehensible mess.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, there are a few state laws governing health care
that expire soon, which the governor wants to see renewed.
Eventually, when time has run out, Silver may be able to use that
leverage to get a deal, and the Legislature will be able to go
officially out of session with the traditional flurry of
special-interest bills that always get passed under the cover of
the rush to adjournment.
</P>
<P>
   Albany is like a foundering boat, held together only by the
barnacles. There are probably enough barnacles in place to get the
state through another year, but what is really needed is a new
hull.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
