u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMUSEMENT-PARK-DEATH-     06-12 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMUSEMENT-PARK-DEATH-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE KILLED AND EIGHT INJURED ON AMUSEMENT-PARK RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 17-year-old girl was killed and eight other people
were injured late Friday night when an amusement park ride in Coney
Island malfunctioned, hurling the girl from her seat and pinning
her between one of the ride's cars and the tracks below, the police
said.
</P>
<P>
   The girl who was killed, Nadine Caban, had been on a fast-moving
circular ride called the Himalaya about 11:20 p.m. when a coupling
between cars broke, causing violent gyrations that threw her from
the ride, said Jerry Varson, a Police Department spokesman. She
died an hour later at Lutheran Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Caban, who had a 10-month-old son, was planning to attend
hairdressing school this summer, her sister Elsie said. She added
that Ms. Caban loved Coney Island and the rides, and had chosen the
Himalaya on Friday specifically because she thought it was safe.
</P>
<P>
   Eight other passengers, many of them part of a group attending a
birthday party at the amusement park, suffered minor injuries in
the accident and were treated at Coney Island Hospital before being
released, Varson said.
</P>
<P>
   The ride, which is owned by Norman Kaufman, had passed a city
inspection on March 27 and was given a certificate to operate
through the end of the summer, according to Paul Wein, a spokesman
for the Buildings Department.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ride was closed briefly when inspectors found
electrical violations in 1984, Wein said that Friday's accident was
the first malfunction ever reported on the ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still investigating but we do know that the car did
come loose from the track,'' he said. ``We have inspectors out
there now and that part of the park is closed to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   The Himalaya, tucked between slow-moving children's rides and
more ominous-sounding rides such as the Cyclone and the Jumbo Jet,
takes riders on a fast circular route, undulating and sometimes
reversing along a track banked by snowy mountain backdrops, as
speakers blare rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   It is a popular and exciting ride, according to those who had
been on the Himalaya at the time of the accident, some of whom had
already taken the trip once or twice on Friday night. But it was
also known as a safe ride, less scary than some others. No one ever
expected to be hurt, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just this fun ride that keeps going around and around,
pulling you one way and that way, to the beat of the music,''
explained Ismerelda Cruz, who had been in the car immediately in
front of Ms. Caban's. ``Something just happened.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Cruz, 19, said she and eight others had gone to the
amusement park to celebrate the birthday of a friend, and part of
the fun had been riding the Himalaya. Shortly before 11:30 p.m.,
they decided to ride it again.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Ms. Cruz said, she and her friend Josephine Garcia
stepped into the car that later hurled Ms. Caban to her death. But
they moved to the one directly in front because they saw a Puerto
Rican flag tucked into the side of the car.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Caban took their place. She had gone to the park with her
two sisters and the fiance of one of the sisters. She was alone in
the car. Her sisters, Elsie, 19, and Magalie, 23, got in about two
cars back. The ride's announcer was playing loud salsa music and
yelling for Puerto Rican riders to let themselves be heard. The
ride whirled faster and faster, and then started to reverse course,
witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly it looked like the ceiling caved in and I ran onto
the platform and yelled, `Stop the ride, stop the ride,''' said
Elsie Caban's fiance, Edwin Oyola, 21, who was standing with others
waiting to get on the Himalaya. ``But it took too long and the ride
just kept going. When they finally stopped it, everyone jumped off,
but we noticed that Nadine was missing. Then we saw her hanging
from the ride about 8 feet from the ground. Everyone was
panicking.''
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters and paramedics were able to dislodge Ms. Caban, who
was trapped between the track and one of the cars, witnesses said.
They said she was conscious, but covered with blood. ``She kept
saying, `What's happened to me, what's happened to me?''' said her
sister Elsie. ``They got her and were taking her to the hospital
and she didn't want me to leave her side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night Nadine told me she didn't feel well and didn't want
to go on any dangerous rides,'' Elsie Caban said Saturday. ``She
said: `Let's just go the Himalaya. Its a safe ride.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been on it so many times before,'' Elsie Caban said
before trailing off in tears outside the family's home in Brooklyn.
``She was so kind-hearted and outgoing; nothing stopped her from
doing what she wanted to do. She lived to have fun and that's what
we had gone to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
