<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DUVAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 FOR DUVAL, PRACTICE IS A No. 1 PRIORITY  
 (bl)  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Duval, the world's No. 1 ranked golfer, spends far more
time practicing his chipping and putting than practicing his
driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``My short game saved me my first year,'' Duval said. ``I left
the West Coast my rookie year third on the money list. I learned
then what it could do, how much it could help you, how much it
would pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Duval's favorite putting drills is to place four balls
around the hole, anywhere from 3 to 5 feet from the cup. Then he
will force himself to make anywhere from 12 to 20 in succession. If
he misses a putt, he starts over.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tell yourself, `I've got to go around this hole four
times,' and if you miss, you've got to start over,'' Duval said.
``You hate missing that fourth one on the fourth leg because you
don't want to stand out there all day. But it teaches you to keep
concentrating.''
</P>
<P>
   For lag putts of 40 feet or more, Duval practices by standing on
the green and putting toward the fringe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to get the ball to stop on the fringe of the green
without rolling off,'' Duval said. ``If you can do that, you've got
the right speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he has enjoyed some hot streaks with his putter, Duval
thinks the key to making putts is getting himself in birdie
position with his approach shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think getting on a roll with your putter is more accurately
described as getting on a roll with your iron play,'' Duval said.
``Nobody is going to make seven 30-footers in a row. But you can
make a 4-footer, then a 15-footer, then an 8-footer, then a
6-footer. If you keep getting it that close, you can get on a
roll.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval grew up playing a lot of golf with his father, Bob Duval,
who is on the Senior PGA Tour. Playing with older players, Duval
learned early that there was a difference between playing for fun
and playing with something at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not encouraging kids to gamble, but if you play golf, it's
good to play for a Coke, a dime or whatever,'' he said. ``Just play
for something. Believe me, it makes a difference. You don't want to
lose, and it adds a little pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Many players use the lettering on the golf ball to help align
their putts, but Duval does not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to see white when I look down,'' Duval said. ``For one
thing, if you try to line up the lettering, it takes longer and
makes you a slower putter. Second, I don't think you can line it up
exactly right all the time. If you line it up wrong, do you start
over? Do you keep doing it until you get it right? Or do you just
finally hit it?
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get ready to putt, first I read it, the break and the
speed. Then I make sure I get the putter flat, what I call flush,
make sure it's square to the ground. I don't want the toe up or the
heel up. Once I get my line picked out, I try to pick it out quick.
I think about the speed and try to putt it on that line.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens when Duval goes into a putting slump?
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually I get the ball too far forward in my stance,'' Duval
said. ``It just works its way in there. You've got to move the ball
back, be uncomfortable for a couple of days until it's comfortable
again.''
</P>
<P>
   When Duval was a child, he used to stand on the green and putt,
imagining that he was standing over a putt to win the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I missed, I'd give myself a do-over,'' Duval said,
laughing. ``They don't do that out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Duval believes in positive thinking, which showed when
he was asked to recall the most important putt he had ever missed.
Duval paused for a long time before answering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember,'' he said. ``By no means am I saying I've
made every big putt. But I try to forget the bad stuff. That's
important.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-99 1838EDT &QL; 
