<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3045 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-USOPEN-PUTT-NYT &LR;      06-12 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-PUTT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 BIG ON SHORT GAME: PUTTING AT PINEHURST COULD BE DECISIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The speaker was David Duval. The subject was putting.
</P>
<P>
   As Duval held his trusted putter in his hand during a recent
conversation, he was asked about this week's U.S. Open, which is
being played for the first time at Pinehurst's revered No. 2 course
beginning Thursday. Duval has never played a tournament at
Pinehurst, a course characterized by unusual greens that drop off
on all sides, like bowls turned upside down. But when it comes to
making putts, Duval believes that some basics never change, that it
is important to take the same attitude to Pinehurst in North
Carolina, to Augusta National in Georgia or to anywhere else in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this level, I'd say confidence would be 96 to 97 percent of
putting,'' said Duval, who is the world's No. 1-ranked player but
will be trying to play in the Open less than a week after burning
his right thumb and forefinger in a home accident.
</P>
<P>
   Duval said confidence is born of practice. ``It comes from hard
work,'' he said. ``It comes from facing different situations and
making putts. It comes from knowing you've worked on the right
things, so when you get under the gun, you can execute what you've
practiced.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be a good putter and make a lot of putts, but can you
do it when you need to do it on Sunday to win a tournament? There's
a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Chipping and putting will be the keys to winning at Pinehurst.
Approach shots that are not accurately placed will roll off the
green into minivalleys. Everyone will be required to chip and putt
a lot. And there are so many hidden breaks in Pinehurst's greens,
reading some putts will be like reading a book written with
invisible ink.
</P>
<P>
   This U.S. Open will be different from most, because instead of
hacking out of deep rough around the greens, players will have a
chance to be creative with their short games. You will see putts
over mounds from off the green. You will see a variety of chip
shots. And because so many pins will be in difficult locations, you
will see many nerve-racking putts, both short and long. Some will
be for birdies, many to save par, others simply to avoid
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone's putting stroke will be under pressure, but that has
become a way of life. Any golfer would love to crush the ball the
way Tiger Woods does, or hit irons with the precision of Jose Maria
Olazabal. But ask players what they have to do to win, and they
usually answer, ``I hope I'll make a few putts.'' With talent so
deep among the world's top players, putting often makes the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many players are so equal,'' said Davis Love III, one of
the favorites this week. ``Over the course of a year, lowering your
putting one-hundredth of a stroke makes a huge difference. If you
say, `I'm going to improve one putt a week over the course of a
week,' you're talking about a huge difference. And one putt a round
can take you from 150th on the money list into the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitting one more green a round helps, but you've still got to
make the putt. That's where you have the biggest room for
improvement, and that's also where you see guys disappear quickly,
when their putting stroke goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Go to any tournament, and you will see players gathered at the
practice green, hitting putt after putt. Some will be doing drills,
like hitting putts between two tees. Others will try different
styles, such as the conventional style used by Duval, or the
left-hand-low, or cross-handed, style favored by Vijay Singh, Fred
Couples and Jim Furyk. And on some occasions, you will see someone
using a long putter, as Rocco Mediate does. Mediate dismisses the
notion that using a long putter is easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was easier, everybody would use it,'' Mediate said. ``It
takes the strain off my back and allows me to practice more. But
the truth is, it's just me. I feel the most comfortable with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But gaining a comfort level on Pinehurst's greens will be
difficult for everyone. The last professional event played there
was the 1992 Tour Championship, and many players have never been
there.
</P>
<P>
   One of those looking forward to this tournament is Dave Pelz,
author of the recently released ``Dave Pelz's Short Game Bible''
(Broadway Books), who has worked with more than 40 players at his
short game school, including U.S. Open defending champion Lee
Janzen and other major winners like Paul Azinger, Mark Brooks,
Steve Elkington, Tom Kite, Payne Stewart, Ian Woosnam and Singh.
Pelz knows how critical the short game and putting will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a short game paradise,'' Pelz said of Pinehurst. ``The
good putters will still make putts, because the greens are in great
shape. However, local knowledge is key. I'm encouraging every
player I've spoken with to get there early, because you just won't
believe what the ball will do on some of these greens until you see
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as I like Colin Montgomerie's game, I'm a little
worried that coming over from Europe, he won't have enough time to
adapt to these greens.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to name his favorite putters in the game today, Pelz gave
a short list of Duval, Janzen, Stewart, Brad Faxon and Loren
Roberts. And Pelz believes there is an excellent chance that either
Janzen or Duval will be holding the U.S. Open trophy next Sunday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duval is putting about as well as anybody at any time,'' said
Pelz, who has done numerous studies on the short game. ``And while
everyone knows that Janzen is an assassin when he has a chance to
win, people overlook the fact that he's a pretty good putter all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoever putts best this week could hold the key to winning a
major championship. And Duval, looking for his first major
championship, knows exactly the kind of putt he wants. ``A
one-footer, uphill, to win any tournament,'' he said, smiling.
``That's my favorite putt.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
