<SLUG> BC-DAYTON-ACCORD-SERBS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Serb refugees in Bosnia-Herzegovina have lessons for newcomers
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANJA LUKA, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ In a small house on the
northern edge of this capital city of the ethnic-Serb portion of
Bosnia-Herzegovina, a family worked last week building an addition
onto a home they do not like and would leave tomorrow if they
could.
</P>
<P>
   Bogoljub Popovic, 61, two friends and some workers piled rough
bricks and homemade mortar up onto the walls of a tumble-down
one-room building at the rear of their rural home.
</P>
<P>
   Popovic, his wife, two sons and other members of his family have
been in Banja Luka for almost four years. But even though the war
that pushed them from their home in the Croatian village of Sibenik
ended in 1995, they still feel aggrieved over the loss of their old
home and say they want to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will feel like a refugee until I go to my own house,'' the
grey-haired Popovic said. ``I feel like a refugee until I can go
onto my own property.''
</P>
<P>
   Bosnia-Herzegovina, war-torn for much of the early 1990s, has
now become a home to refugees such as the Popovics. Besides the
estimated 105,000 Muslims who have recently come there from the
Yugoslav province of Kosovo, the country houses an estimated 1.7
million people who have not returned to their pre-war homes.
</P>
<P>
   It is a problem that has perplexed U.S. officials who are part
of a United Nations effort to retain peace in Bosnia and get the
residents to return home, or truly settle into their new homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long will it take before they lose the will to go home,''
said U.S. Army Gen. Kevin P. Byrnes at a military base in Tuzla.
``There is a certain point that that (desire) will fall off.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the Republika Srpska, the northern and eastern part of
Bosnia-Herzegovina where ethnic-Serbs have fled, that desire
remains strong.
</P>
<P>
   The Popovics live in a small home at the end of a dirt lane.
Popovic said they got the home by swapping for it with its former
Croatian owners. The Croats took the Popovics' apartment building
in Croatia, and the Popovics went to Banja Luka.
</P>
<P>
   The transition was difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody cared,'' said Zoran Popovic, Bogolub's son and a news
editor for the Bosnian television network.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb refugees still do not feel welcome in Bosnia, but
neither do they feel it is safe to go back to the villages of their
grandparents along the Adriatic coast.
</P>
<P>
   Banja Luka has become the refuge for Serbs kicked out or
escaping other countries in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   License plates of many newer cars showed their drivers live in
Belgrade, Novi Sad or other cities that were bombed by NATO forces.
Local residents say the city has seen an influx of temporary
residents, Serbs who fled the bombing in Yugoslavia to wait out the
war.
</P>
<P>
   But in front of them are veteran Serb refugees _ ethnic Serbs
like the Popovics, forced out of Croatia four, five and six years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Bosnia you have the international community and political
pressure (for resettling refugees),'' Zoran said. ``In Croatia, you
don't have anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Zoran said he, at least, would not return to Croatia even if it
were safe. He has married in Banja Luka and has a good job.
</P>
<P>
   But his parents feel less settled, and their views are shared by
many others.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. military officials here claim all three sides _ Serbs,
Croats and Muslims _ are using the sympathetic plight of refugees
to continue the land grabs that they conducted during the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategic war continues through the operational
resettlement of women and children,'' U.S. Army Col. Mike Milano
said.
</P>
<P>
   Banja Lukans have backed Yugoslavia throughout the NATO
campaign, but some residents last week said they were angry at the
United States not so much for bombing Serbia as for leaving
Slobodan Milosevic in office.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Americans are told to expect a cool reception, at
best, in Serbian areas of Bosnia, and U.S. employees were told to
stay out of the region during the NATO offensive.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of cool stares, the Popovics greeted an American
reporter warmly and spoke passionately about the injustice they
feel at not being able to return to their villages.
</P>
<P>
   The war has created what a military official described as a
``daisy chain.'' Croats, Serbs and Muslims who were in the minority
of their regions fled to where their groups were more populous.
Many took residences in the homes that other refugees had just
left.
</P>
<P>
   Now, few people are willing to take the first step to go back
home, and so no vacant housing is available for people to move
into.
</P>
<P>
   It is a stalemate with no signs of ending soon.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the hopes of some in the international community
that the refugees will get on with their lives, some feel they can
never do that until they go back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be stupid to say anything other than that I want to
go back to where my grandfather and great grandfather were born,''
Bogoljub Popovic said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bebbington writes for the Dayton Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
