<P>
   COXNET FOCUS 0612 KOSOVO AIR _ There has never been an air
campaign quite like it. Over 78 days, NATO warplanes flew 35,000
sorties, dropped 23,000 bombs, destroyed 1,500 targets and
shattered the backbone of a central European military force, all
without losing a single U.S. or allied pilot in combat. But the
campaign has raised questions and sparked debate whether air power
alone can win a war without the use of ground troops. (Deans, Cox
Washington Bureau). Art includes 3-column color photo of a jet
fighter leaving the flight deck of a carrier; a 2-column photo of
soldiers aiming guns out of a helicopter; a 12-pica photo of a B-2
bomber; a 6-pica photo of a helictoper delivering goods to troops.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO FUTURE -- Although the political future of Kosovo is left
vague in the settlement that ended the war, American and NATO
officials say they envision an international protectorate that will
in theory be part of Yugoslavia but that may well, after a few
years, become independent. (Perlez, N.Y. Times News Service) Art
includes 2-column color photo of worried Albanian refugee.
</P>
