<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3057 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEAVENLY-LAWYER-ART-N     06-12 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAVENLY-LAWYER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORPORATE LAWYER TRADES IN SUIT FOR MISSIONARY'S ROBE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Peru)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARYKNOLL, N.Y. _ Joseph M. Everson III was sitting on a very
hard rock inside a crumbling hut in the mountains of Peru, slicked
with mud after an exhausting climb to give Catholic communion to a
peasant family, when his mind stumbled into a thicket of doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought to myself, `What am I doing here?''' he said Friday.
``I used to be an attorney. I was at Skadden, Arps,'' as in
Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher &AMP; Flom, the Manhattan law firm where
Everson, 37, had negotiated financial contracts with banks and
brokerage houses. ``Here I am, sitting on a rock, covered with mud,
sitting in an adobe house. What am I  &UR; doing &LR;  here?''
</P>
<P>
   That was January 1997. Saturday, there was no such disquiet in
Everson as he lay, as ritual dictates, face down on the floor of
the Maryknoll Seminary's church, swathed in a white robe, before
Cardinal John O'Connor, the archbishop of New York. Saturday, Joe
Everson _ once a richly compensated corporate lawyer who rode a
gondola from Roosevelt Island into lower Manhattan each morning _
became Father Joseph Everson, a Catholic priest bound for the
forests of the Peruvian Andes with a salary of $300 a month.
</P>
<P>
   For him, the drastic change from corporate lawyer to missionary
priest could not have felt more natural.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of my closer friends said this seems to fit me much
better than when I was an attorney,'' he said Friday over the
twitter of birds in the grassy courtyard of the Maryknoll Seminary,
near Ossining in Westchester County. ``I feel a deeper meaning, and
I feel closer to God.''
</P>
<P>
   Born into a Catholic family that raised 10 children in the heart
of San Francisco, Everson said he had always felt drawn toward the
priesthood. It started in Catholic grammar school, reading
missionaries' accounts in Maryknoll magazine.
</P>
<P>
   He put off a decision until after college at Berkeley, where he
studied history. Then he went to law school in Texas, clerked for a
federal judge in Florida and, in October 1989, joined Skadden, Arps
as a lawyer specializing in asset-backed finance, drawing up
documents and negotiating contracts with investment bankers'
lawyers. He lived in a 12th floor apartment on Roosevelt Island,
waking up to a view of Manhattan's skyline.
</P>
<P>
   Everson, a short, stout man fond of khaki pants and simple
polo-style shirts, resigned in 1992 to begin training as a
Maryknoll seminarian, leaving many of his corporate colleagues
baffled. Why give up the money, the expense account, the morning
gondola rides to trudge up mountainsides in the rain to give
communion to a family of peasants?
</P>
<P>
   ``As an attorney at Skadden, I'd achieved success as society had
defined it,'' said Everson. ``But then I turned around and did the
opposite.'' Intent on helping the poor , he signed for two years of
academic and divinity training at the Maryknoll Seminary here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just about the most wonderful thing that could happen,''
said Everson's mother, Virginia Everson, 77, who flew in from San
Francisco to witness the ordination along with her nine other
children. ``I have six sons, and he was the last one, and hope was
getting thin there.''
</P>
<P>
   Maryknoll, a society of the Roman Catholic Church, was founded
in 1911 by two priests dedicated to ministering to the destitute in
many of the world's poorest countries. Today, more than 1,400
Maryknoll missionaries work in dozens of foreign countries in South
America, Africa and Asia. The hilltop seminary here, completed in
1954, was built of stone and mortar in the winged tile roof style
of a Chinese pagoda and is part of a sprawling bucolic compound
that has its own postal code.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his training for the priesthood, Everson spent three
years in Yunguyo, Peru, a farming village square in the shadow of a
dormant volcano 12,500 feet above sea level in the Andes and 20
minutes from the border with Bolivia. There, under the supervision
of another Maryknoll missionary, he learned the craft of priests,
helping poor farmers from 42 neighboring villages build homes,
administering communion and aiding in baptisms.
</P>
<P>
   Each morning, as the sun rose up through the chilled mountain
clouds, he would wake at 6 a.m. and spend an hour in prayer. For
exercise, Everson would hike to the border of Bolivia and back
again.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what the most difficult part of being a priest is, Everson
bowed his head for a moment and thought. The loneliness, he said,
can be intense. Being away from the one's own language and culture.
Foregoing marriage. ``It's important to think why you made
decisions,'' he said. He made his decision, consummated today, he
said, ``because I felt my life could have deeper meaning for
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Everson was the sole seminarian to be ordained a
Maryknoll priest. During the two-hour ordination ceremony, O'Connor
spoke of how priests do not choose God but are chosen by Him, a
lesson seemingly apt enough for Everson and his experiences abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Father Everson will return to Peruvian Andes in August to begin
a term as a priest to many of the same peasant farmers he left in
1995 to finish his spiritual education. As before, his life will be
an ascetic one. But in this age, when even priests routinely carry
pagers and cellular phones, Everson will adorn his life in the
Andes with one modern convenience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll bring a laptop with me,'' he said, cracking a smile.
``For my ministry.''
</P>
<P>
   And for one other reason, too. ``e-mail.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
