   (NYT5) PHOENIX, Ariz. -- June 12, 1999 -- CHARTER-SCHOOLS-2,
6-12 -- The Learning Institute, a small Phoenix school, switched
districts to become a Higley district chartered school this year.
The school, which now has freedom to experiment and independence in
hiring and spending, features computer-assisted learning for
at-risk students. Each student is assessed upon entering the
school, and from then on, spends about half of each day at the
computer, choosing from a menu of individualized lessons. (Jeff
Topping/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) HIGLEY, Ariz. -- June 12, 1999 -- CHARTER-SCHOOLS-1, 6-12
-- Larry C. Likes, superintendent of the Higley Elementary
District, has found a source of income in issuing charters for
innovative schools throughout Arizona, which will bring in $350,000
this year. Still, he understands the repercussions for public
schools -- losing students. ``There are a lot of kids for whom
public school just doesn't work, and I'm tickled to see all the
neat things the charters we've put out there are doing,'' says
Likes. (Jeff Topping/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) FLORENCE, Colo. -- June 12, 1999 -- SUPERMAX-PRISON-2,
6-12 -- The Administrative Maximum Facility, known locally as Super
Max, in Florence. In this bland beige building that looks like a
corporate campus at the foot of the Wet Mountains, the federal
Bureau of Prisons seeks to modify violent prisoners by entombing
them in isolation cells for up to 23 hours a day. ``After four and
half years of operation, the $60 million prison has proved
successful,'' says Blake R. Davis, executive assistant to the
warden. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) FLORENCE, Colo. -- June 12, 1999 -- SUPERMAX-PRISON-1,
6-12 -- Raymond Luc Levasseur, 52, an inmate at the Administrative
Maximum Facility, known locally as Super Max, in Florence.
Levasseur expects to move to a less-restrictive prison this year as
a part of the prison's ``step down'' program that is designed to
return cooperating prisoners back to normal prisons in three years.
``Prolonged isolation is the worst punishment you can put on a
human being,'' he says. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) KUKES, Albania -- June 12, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ALBANIA, 6-12
-- Kosovar refugees gather on Saturday near the wreckage of a C-130
British transport that crashed next to a camp near Kukes, late
Friday. All 12 people aboard survived and no one on the ground was
injured, a NATO spokesman said. The crash comes amid stepped-up
military activity, as NATO forces prepare to go into Kosovo from
the same southwestern route that some 450,000 ethnic Albanians used
to escape from their homes to Kukes. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
