<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 06/12/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- June 12, 1999 -- BKN-KNICKS-CHILDS, 6-12 --
The New York Knicks' Chris Childs making an ``L'' sign to honor the
injured Larry Johnson in the second half of Game 6 of the Eastern
Conference finals at Madison Square Garden. Largely because Childs
put forth such a splendid effort in Game 6 and throughout the
entire series against the Indiana Pacers, the Knicks will now meet
the San Antonio Spurs in the finals that begin Wednesday night at
the Alamodome. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- June 12, 1999 -- BKN-KNICKS, 6-12 -- The
Indiana Pacers' Reggie Miller, who so often has denied celebrations
by the Knicks, was in the middle of one Friday night as the clock
ran out on the Pacers' season. In the span of six wacky weeks, the
Knicks have gone from out of the playoffs to the NBA finals. From
eighth to first in the Eastern Conference. They will now meet the
San Antonio Spurs in the finals that begin Wednesday night at the
Alamodome. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) MARYKNOLL, N.Y. -- June 12, 1999 -- HEAVENLY-LAWYER-2,
6-12 -- Father Joseph M. Everson 3d, 37, a lawyer who traded in his
suit for a priest's robe, laying down in the Maryknoll Seminary's
church on Saturday as part of an ordination ritual, while his
mother, Virginia Everson, at right, watched. ``It's just about the
most wonderful thing that could happen,'' says Ms. Everson, 77, who
flew in from San Francisco to witness the ordination along with her
nine other children. (Dith Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MARYKNOLL, N.Y. -- June 12, 1999 -- HEAVENLY-LAWYER-1,
6-12 -- Father Joseph M. Everson 3d, 37, a lawyer who traded in his
suit for a priest's robe, being ordained by John Cardinal O'Connor,
the Archbishop of New York, at the Maryknoll Seminary's church.
Born into a Catholic family that raised 10 children in the heart of
San Francisco, Everson says he had always felt drawn toward
priesthood. ``Some of my closest friends say this seems to fit me
much better than when I was an attorney,'' says Everson. (Dith
Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BLACE, Macedonia -- June 12, 1999 -- KOSOVO-TROOPS-2,
6-12 -- A British soldier prepares to enter Kosovo along the
Macedonian border Saturday morning. NATO troops are ready to move
in and secure the way for hundreds of thousands of returning ethnic
Albanian refugees. It will take at least eight more days before the
last Serbian forces withdraw and the NATO force, which will
ultimately include some 50,000 peacekeepers, takes control.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BLACE, Macedonia -- June 12, 1999 -- KOSOVO-TROOPS-1,
6-12 -- As NATO troops surged into Kosovo from the Macedonian
border Saturday morning, a convoy of British troops lined up at the
Macedonian border. The troops are ready to move in and secure the
way for hundreds of thousands of returning ethnic Albanian
refugees. It will take at least eight more days before the last
Serbian forces withdraw and the NATO force, which will ultimately
include some 50,000 peacekeepers, takes control. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PHOENIX, Ariz. -- June 12, 1999 -- CHARTER-SCHOOLS-2,
6-12 -- The Learning Institute, a small Phoenix school, switched
districts to become a Higley district chartered school this year.
The school, which now has freedom to experiment and independence in
hiring and spending, features computer-assisted learning for
at-risk students. Each student is assessed upon entering the
school, and from then on, spends about half of each day at the
computer, choosing from a menu of individualized lessons. (Jeff
Topping/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) HIGLEY, Ariz. -- June 12, 1999 -- CHARTER-SCHOOLS-1, 6-12
-- Larry C. Likes, superintendent of the Higley Elementary
District, has found a source of income in issuing charters for
innovative schools throughout Arizona, which will bring in $350,000
this year. Still, he understands the repercussions for public
schools -- losing students. ``There are a lot of kids for whom
public school just doesn't work, and I'm tickled to see all the
neat things the charters we've put out there are doing,'' says
Likes. (Jeff Topping/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) FLORENCE, Colo. -- June 12, 1999 -- SUPERMAX-PRISON-2,
6-12 -- The Administrative Maximum Facility, known locally as Super
Max, in Florence. In this bland beige building that looks like a
corporate campus at the foot of the Wet Mountains, the federal
Bureau of Prisons seeks to modify violent prisoners by entombing
them in isolation cells for up to 23 hours a day. ``After four and
half years of operation, the $60 million prison has proved
successful,'' says Blake R. Davis, executive assistant to the
warden. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) FLORENCE, Colo. -- June 12, 1999 -- SUPERMAX-PRISON-1,
6-12 -- Raymond Luc Levasseur, 52, an inmate at the Administrative
Maximum Facility, known locally as Super Max, in Florence.
Levasseur expects to move to a less-restrictive prison this year as
a part of the prison's ``step down'' program that is designed to
return cooperating prisoners back to normal prisons in three years.
``Prolonged isolation is the worst punishment you can put on a
human being,'' he says. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) KUKES, Albania -- June 12, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ALBANIA, 6-12
-- Kosovar refugees gather on Saturday near the wreckage of a C-130
British transport that crashed next to a camp near Kukes, late
Friday. All 12 people aboard survived and no one on the ground was
injured, a NATO spokesman said. The crash comes amid stepped-up
military activity, as NATO forces prepare to go into Kosovo from
the same southwestern route that some 450,000 ethnic Albanians used
to escape from their homes to Kukes. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
