<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3067 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-METS-REDSOX-NYT &LR;      06-12 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-REDSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO TROUBLE FOR LEITER AGAINST THE A.L. 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Al Leiter turned in his second consecutive strong
outing _ in his second consecutive start against an American League
team _ to lead the New York Mets to a 4-2 victory over the Boston
Red Sox on Saturday at Shea Stadium. The victory was the Mets'
fifth in six games since they dropped a season-high eight in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter had helped reverse the Mets' sinking fortunes last
Sunday, when he allowed one run in seven innings at Yankee Stadium,
in his strongest performance of the season. Saturday, before 43,519
fans at Shea on a beach towel giveaway day, Leiter nearly topped
himself.
</P>
<P>
   He tossed six shutout innings, then pitched his way out of a
major jam in the seventh to leave with a 3-2 lead. Leiter allowed
two runs on six hits in seven innings, with one walk and four
strikeouts. In the last week, Leiter has lowered his earned run
average from 6.39 to 5.57.
</P>
<P>
   And, thanks to solo home runs from Benny Agbayani, Robin Ventura
and John Olerud, Leiter was able to improve to 4-5. That isn't
quite the record befitting a $32 million pitcher, but there has
definitely been improvement since Leiter has had his left knee
taped differently to help protect an injury. Through six innings,
Leiter allowed only three base runners, all on singles, two of
which never left the infield.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, the 33-year-old left-hander fanned Damon Buford
for the 1,000th strikeout of his career. And in the sixth _ with
the Mets clinging to the 2-0 lead they had taken in the third on
Agbayani's ninth home run and a run-scoring Edgardo Alfonzo double
_ Leiter survived his own throwing error to keep the shutout
intact.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, who had left five runners stranded in extra innings
Friday night, gave the Mets a 3-0 lead in the bottom of the sixth
with his 10th home run. And that was fortunate for Leiter, too,
because after he quickly recorded the first two outs of the
seventh, the Red Sox rallied for a pair of runs.
</P>
<P>
   Buford began the rally with a two-out single to center and then
stole second. Troy O'Leary followed with a bloop double down the
left-field line on a 3-1 pitch to end Leiter's shutout bid. And,
after Creighton Gubanich delivered a full-count single through
short for another run, it was a 3-2 game.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Lewis was the next batter and he fouled off four
consecutive full-count pitches before drawing a walk on Leiter's
100th pitch of the game. And, with the tying run was in scoring
position at second base, the right-handed hitting Jason Varitek
stepped to the plate to pinch-hit for Pat Rapp. Bobby Valentine
stayed with Leiter, however, something the manager has done often
this season; something that has often hurt the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, Leiter rewarded Valentine's faith. He threw
two quick strikes past Varitek, then induced the catcher to meekly
pop out to first.
</P>
<P>
   And when Olerud homered in the bottom of the eighth _ after
Armando Benitez had tossed a scoreless inning in relief of Leiter _
the Mets were up by 4-2. A scoreless ninth gave Leiter his second
consecutive victory for the first time this year.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   _ With his second-inning single, MIKE PIAZZA extended his
hitting streak to 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   _ BOBBY BONILLA nodded when asked if his meeting on Friday, with
BOBBY VALENTINE and STEVE PHILLIPS had been productive, but the
outfielder was otherwise mum. The Mets expect to resolve Bonilla's
situation by Tuesday or Wednesday, one member of the organization
said Saturday. Presumably, Bonilla will be traded or released.
Scratch the Royals from the list of prospective suitors, however.
``We wouldn't have any interest in going in that direction,''
Kansas City general manager HERK ROBINSON said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Red Sox closer TOM GORDON traveled back to Boston on
Saturday for a magnetic resonance imaging test on his right elbow.
Gordon surrendered a game-tying two-run home run to Piazza in the
bottom of the ninth inning Friday night before the Red Sox rallied
to win, 3-2, in 12 innings. It was the first time in Gordon's
career he had blown two consecutive save opportunities, both coming
after he had set a major-league record by recording 54 saves in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   _ Before Saturday's game, the Red Sox announced that they had
placed BRET SABERHAGEN on the 15-day disabled list. The former Mets
pitcher cut his left foot stepping on a piece of glass during a
team party at his Long Island residence Thursday night. Mark
Portugal will start in Saberhagen's place Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
