<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-COLUMN-VALENTINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: VALENTINE HAS TURNED INTO A LEGEND IN HIS OWN MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There he goes again.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Valentine and the Mets haven't been immersed in enough
turmoil the past week, so the manager had to go and create yet
another issue Saturday. Practicing revisionist history at his best,
Valentine sat in his Shea Stadium office before the game against
the Boston Red Sox and talked about the great job he has done
considering what he found when he became the manager in August
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for two and a half years here we had as placid and as
peaceful a situation as there was in baseball,'' Valentine said.
``I took a terrible, disruptive situation and contained it,
straightened it and made it whole.''
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter asked him later if by the disruptive situation
he was referring to the past week, Valentine said, ``I was
referring to the abyss that was here two and a half years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps so much has happened the past week that the ceaseless
succession of events has clouded Valentine's 49-year-old mind, but
his recollection of an abyss isn't the way others who were there
remember that time.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Green was brought in to clean up the mess that was the
fallout from a disastrous, disappointing 1992 season, and he did
sweep out the refuse. Green's only failure was that the team didn't
win under him, and he was excused after three and a half years.
Valentine replaced him, and he has won. But there was no mess for
him to clean up.
</P>
<P>
   As for the placid existence the Mets have supposedly lived the
past couple of seasons, Pete Harnisch didn't find peace and
serenity in their clubhouse. Valentine saw to that. Todd Hundley
didn't live a life of serenity either. Valentine saw to that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He comes into a whole new situation and goes right after I
guess the most popular guy,'' Hundley, now with the Los Angeles
Dodgers, said of Valentine in spring training. And: ``You see him
coming from a mile away. He thinks he's working in the shadows, but
he's not. You can see right through him.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for placid and peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   The past week certainly wasn't. The Mets' effort to shed Bobby
Bonilla and Brian McRae via irrevocable waivers to clear up their
overcrowded outfield became known and roiled the clubhouse. Their
contemplation of the dismissal of pitching coach Bob Apodaca became
known June 5, and before the day was over, the Mets fired Apodaca
and two other members of Valentine's six-man coaching staff, over
his strenuous objections, of course.
</P>
<P>
   The loss to the Yankees that day was the team's eighth in a row.
Life with the Mets was rapidly spinning out of control.
</P>
<P>
   It would get better and worse. Worse when Bonilla refused to
pinch-hit in a game last Tuesday because Valentine had benched him
and disclosed the news to a reporter. Better when the Mets beat the
Yankees in the third game of their interleague series and went on a
four-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   But near the end of the fourth game of that winning streak,
Valentine created the most bizarre episode of the week and turned
what could have become a smooth sea into a choppy one. Ejected from
the game, he reappeared at the dugout entrance disguised in a fake
mustache and sunglasses. National League president Leonard Coleman
saw through the disguise and suspended him for two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an incident that occurred that I can't take back,''
Valentine said Saturday, managing because he has appealed the
suspension. ``It's one of those things that happened. If I had
known what the responses would be and how seriously the outside
world would take it, I never would have done it.''
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that what he did was stupid, he said: ``Let's not
kid anyone. I knew where the camera was. If I thought this was
punishable by death, the camera never would have seen me. I didn't
think it was that big a deal. But again I was incorrect.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said Coleman had offered to hear his appeal at 8:30
a.m. Saturday, but he said it would not be feasible because the
Mets had a 1:15 p.m. game. After his team's 4-2 victory behind Al
Leiter's strong pitching, Valentine said he was glad he had
managed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of tough decisions made in that game,'' he
said, noting his use of John Franco, his closer, who had thrown 32
pitches the night before, and his leaving Leiter in to get the last
out in the seventh inning with the bases loaded. ``I'm glad the
guys whose job isn't to make those tough decisions didn't have to
make them. I'd rather have them do those &QC; 8-0 games we have planned
later.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Valentine said the conflagrations had abated. He said
he wasn't aware that before the game Rickey Henderson expressed his
displeasure at not playing regularly.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, Valentine said, were not in a fragile state. ``I think
the foundation is laid here, and it's a strong foundation,'' he
said. ``It's built around the players in the clubhouse. There might
have been a couple windows broken, but the structure is still
there.''
</P>
<P>
   He just better watch out for those leaks in the basement. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
