<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNCONTROL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN PROPOSAL TAKES A TURN AS DEMOCRATS SHOW DIVISIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FRANK BRUNI  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A proposal for mandatory background checks of
buyers at gun shows that has the blessing of House Republican
leaders and reflects the preferences of the National Rifle
Association is being sponsored by a group of Democrats, including
the most senior Democrat in the House.
</P>
<P>
   That twist underscores a sharp division on gun control among
House Democrats and could provide valuable political cover for
House Republicans, many of whom would like to vote for softer
gun-control measures than the Senate has approved without having
their party tarred as indifferent to gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be clear until the middle of this week precisely what
rival gun-control measures the House Rules Committee allows to go
to the floor as amendments to a juvenile crime bill that is
scheduled for debate beginning on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But several Republican and Democratic aides said Saturday that
the most lenient of several gun-show options that House members
ultimately vote on could be one put forward by Rep. John Dingell,
D-Mich., a four-decade veteran of the House, and several Democrats
generally opposed to significant new restrictions on firearms.
</P>
<P>
   That is the scenario that Republican leaders, who hold sway over
the Rules Committee, are encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want it to be very clear that both parties are divided on
this issue,'' said Michelle Davis, a spokeswoman for House Majority
Leader Dick Armey.
</P>
<P>
   It is no surprise to House Democrats that Dingell, a former NRA
board member, opposes the Senate bill, or that some House Democrats
share his position. Nor does it change the fact that Democrats are
generally fiercer advocates of gun control than Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, some Democrats pleaded with Dingell and his
Democratic allies last week not to do anything to potentially
dilute the party's claim to a popular issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It blunts it a little bit,'' said one senior Democratic aide.
``But I think the media and the public will still know where our
party stands.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nita Lowey, D-N.Y., who strongly favors new restrictions on
firearms, said that the decision of Dingell and a few other
Democrats probably reflected their lingering convictions about the
extent to which advocacy of gun control factored into the party's
loss of its majority in Congress five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their interpretation of 1994 is that this issue had an
important effect,'' Ms. Lowey said.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone calls late Saturday afternoon to Dingell's offices in
Washington and in Michigan were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Democratic and Republican aides said Saturday that they
were not sure which Democrats in addition to Dingell had their
names on his amendment.
</P>
<P>
   After a fight that split Republicans and Democrats, the Senate
narrowly approved a gun-show measure that defined the events
broadly and gave vendors up to three business days to complete
background checks. Most Democrats are promoting a similar measure
in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Early last week, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., who heads the House
Judiciary Committee, unveiled a less strict alternative. His
proposal shortened the maximum time allowed for background checks
to three calendar days and provided a much narrower definition for
what sorts of gatherings qualified as gun shows and subjected
vendors to the obligation of conducting background checks.
</P>
<P>
   But many Republicans found Hyde's measure too strict, and the
NRA continued to lobby for an alternative that limited to 24 hours
the time that gun-show vendors had to conduct background checks.
Senior Republican and Democratic aides said today that Dingell's
proposal contained that limit.
</P>
</TEXT>
