<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3072 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-ART-NYT &LR;      06-12 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DANCING FROM THE GARDEN RAFTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They are now one of the great teams of the Garden,
one of the epic teams of New York. The Eastern Conference banner
will hang from the beams, but what really matters is the sound, the
emotion of that Friday night in June, forever trapped under the
rafters.
</P>
<P>
   Forget, for the moment, what may transpire against San Antonio
if Larry Johnson cannot play. That may be pure epilogue, sheer
aftermath, like Blutarsky growing up to be senator, downhill all
the way, baby, from the raging intensity of that Animal House night
against the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   On that Friday night in June, when their last remaining big
fella went down, the Knicks defended their property with a savage
sense of entitlement, the kind of energy that allows mothers to
lift automobiles off their children. They would not let anything
bad happen, not that night.
</P>
<P>
   These words were written, by the way, in the calm daylight of
Saturday morning, not in the first crazed minutes after the Knicks'
90-82 victory that put them in the finals of the National
Basketball Association playoffs. They play in San Antonio on
Wednesday, much too far away to think about at this moment.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, consider what this eighth-seeded Knicks team
accomplished Friday night, and why the crowd chanted ``Jeff Van
Gun-Dee!'' in a chilling acknowledgment of the little terrier of a
coach, and why Latrell Sprewell bounced up and down on a victory
lap of the court, the pride and the relief momentarily wiping away
his glowering game face. Oh, what a night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me ask you something,'' Spike Lee said before the game.
``When did the term the `Monster of the Garden' begin?''
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I think of it as the Beast of the Garden, but
whichever, it goes back a decade or two, to when people began to
perceive the collective roar of ancient crowds (maybe even the
ghost of classic Penn Station, destroyed to build this impractical
Garden), the will of millions of New Yorkers fused into one ghastly
sound, like Scottish war bagpipes or steel subway wheels grating
against steel rails. The Monster or the Beast, it was loose on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Spike danced at the edge of the court, letting out the joy of
his inner child. Donald Trump even watched a few random bounces of
the ball rather than his normal sporting routine of scoping out the
crowd for potential condo buyers. And, one can be sure, Hillary
Clinton will be wearing an orange-and-blue Knicks cap as soon as
somebody whispers the words ``downstate vote.''
</P>
<P>
   It is irrelevant how many of these guys, aside from the wounded
Patrick Ewing, will ever get their numbers hung from the beams,
along with the No. 24 of Bill Bradley, who was there, in the crowd.
What is relevant is what they accomplished from the moment Larry
Johnson went down near the end of the first half, his right knee
sprained by an inadvertent football clip.
</P>
<P>
   If they had won with Johnson firing 4-pointers, as he does
whenever they need one, that would have been sheer basketball
momentum. Rather, they won without Johnson, and that is a tribute
to them, and also a tribute to the man who wasn't there, Ernie
Grunfeld, the general manager who was sacked when the team was
mired at 21-21.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish Ernie was in the building,'' said Chris Childs, who ran
the team when Van Gundy had finally seen enough of Charlie Ward.
``I wish he could see what he's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Grunfeld was not in the building, unless he was using Bobby
Valentine's ludicrous disguise kit. But his players were, Sprewell
and Marcus Camby, their pogo-stick space walks turning a respected
Indiana franchise into an instant dinosaur.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Childs, the backup point guard who has emerged to
play the quality minutes. He conceded later that if anybody, two
months ago, had proposed to him that the Knicks would be in the
championship round, ``I'd have said, `Go into rehab,''' quipped the
man who is an openly recovering alcoholic.
</P>
<P>
   Childs has bonded with the ferocious, often surly, Johnson. They
sometimes counsel the mild-mannered Allan Houston to shoot his
shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Allan's mother and father,'' Childs recalled
later. ``I asked, `Why doesn't he shoot more?' I told Allan,
`You've got to be more aggressive.'''
</P>
<P>
   They all tell him that. Brendan Malone, the assistant coach,
told Houston before the game, ``This is the kind of game you dream
about,'' and Houston shot with selective aggression, making 12 of
17, and 8 of 10 fouls, for 32 points.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of his game was coldly going after the Pacers who
were in foul trouble, like in the third period when Mark Jackson
picked up his fourth personal. Before the clock stopped to allow a
sub for Jackson, Houston drove right at Jackson for an essentially
undefended layup that tied the game at 53-53. The Knicks were never
behind again.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the fourth period, Childs hit a 3-pointer to put
the Knicks ahead, 62-59. As he ran down the court, Childs stuck his
left hand in the crook of his right elbow, demonstrating the Big L,
as in Larry.
</P>
<P>
   In Bensonhurst and Little Italy (and Naples and Genoa and other
tough places), this gesture can cause your elbow to be wrenched in
the opposite direction, but in the Garden it becomes Johnson's
narcissistic tribute to himself.
</P>
<P>
   Now Childs gave the Big L as a salute to his fallen comrade. It
was Animal House in the Garden, another tableau, along with Willis'
walk and Messier's glare, a few more frightful noises to live
forever with the Monster, with the Beast, up there in the rafters. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
