<HEADER>
A3073 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BB0-BASESTEALER-COX     06-12 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB0-BASESTEALER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Macon Braves' Furcal aiming for 100 steals
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACON, Ga. _ Just as it once did for Vince Coleman, 73-year-old
Luther Williams Field begins to buzz with anticipation every time
Rafael Furcal reaches first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows he's going to try to steal,'' longtime Macon
fan Joe Jones, 75, said. ``I really think he's even faster than
Coleman was back then. Of course, your mind can play tricks on you
when you're my age. It's hard to imagine anyone stealing 145
bases.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's what Coleman did for Macon in 1983, setting an
organized baseball record that might never be challenged. Not even
by the fleet Furcal, who could be the Atlanta Braves' leadoff man
and shortstop of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oooooh!'' Furcal said when told what Coleman accomplished on
the same red-clay basepaths he now uses as his personal dragstrip.
``I knew about Vince Coleman. But I didn't know he played here or
stole all those bases. I don't think I can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the powerfully built 18-year-old Dominican thinks he can
become the first player this decade to steal 100 bases in a minor-
or major-league season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my goal,'' said Furcal, who had 52 steals in 60 games
and the Class A South Atlantic League season of 142 games not half
over. Caught 12 times this season, he stole 31 bases in May _
including a record-tying five in one game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of us will be shocked if Raffy doesn't steal
100,'' Macon teammate Junior Brignac said.
</P>
<P>
   Furcal stole an Appalachian League record 60 bases in 66 games
last season _ a pace for 147 steals over a 162-game major-league
season. He also batted .328 and was voted the best prospect in the
rookie league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raffy is special,'' Macon manager Jeff Treadway said. ``If
there is a better prospect in this league, I haven't seen him.''
</P>
<P>
   Furcal, who signed with Atlanta at 16, has been clocked as fast
as 6.2 seconds for the 60-yard dash. That makes him even a little
faster than prized Braves prospect George Lombard.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Furcal's explosive first step and ability to read
pitchers _ not just speed _ that sets him apart from most young
base stealers. Given the green light to run on his own, Furcal
takes a lead with one foot past the first-base cutout, but he is
almost impossible to pick off because of his quickness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some teams have almost given up trying to stop him,''
Macon coach Tommy Gregg said. ``He usually picks the right pitch to
run on, but he even steals on pitchouts.''
</P>
<P>
   Stolen bases, however, are just part of Furcal's game. Converted
to a switch-hitter after signing, Furcal also impresses scouts with
his bat control at the plate, and with his range and strong arm in
the field.
</P>
<P>
   Furcal is hitting a team-high .321 and leads Macon in
walk-strikeout ratio. Playing shortstop for the first time after
moving from second base, Furcal also leads the M-Braves with 25
errors. But Treadway, a former infielder with the Braves and four
other major-league teams, downplays the miscues.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a few years, people aren't going to remember the errors he
made here,'' said Treadway, who took a leave of absense from the
team Saturday. ``He's going to be a good major league shortstop.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman was 21 _ three years older than Furcal _ when he played
at Macon in 1983, and reached the majors with a splash after just
one more minor league season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raffy won't get there that fast, but he's certainly the kind
of player who has the talent to skip a level and move up quickly,''
Treadway said. ``He has good baseball instincts and puts in the
work to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman was the National League Rookie of the Year with St.
Louis in 1985 and stole more than 100 bases in each of his first
three big-league seasons. He led the NL in steals a record three
more seasons, then went into decline because of injuries and
off-the-field problems. He finished his major league career ranked
No. 6 in stolen bases with 752.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman calls his 145-steal season at Macon a
``once-in-a-lifetime thing.'' He batted a league-best .350 and set
the record despite missing 32 games with a broken hand. Playing at
Lodi of the California League, Donnell Nixon _ Otis Nixon's younger
brother _ led the minors most of the season. But Coleman stole
eight bases in the last three games, including three the last day,
to edge Nixon 145-144.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lee Thomas was the farm director at St. Louis at the time, and
he wanted to see me do it,'' Coleman said of the record. ``That's
probably the only reason he kept me at Macon for the whole year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it does seem like it might be a record that's never
broken. At the time, though, I believed it was something I could do
again, even in the major leagues. I guess I was pretty ambitious.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Furcal. ``I don't know what year, but I know I'll get to
the big leagues,'' he said. ``In the Dominican, baseball was always
my dream. I want to get there as fast as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
