<HEADER>
A3074 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-NOTES13-COX     06-12 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-NOTES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American League notebook
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AL EAST
</P>
<P>
   Honor thy uniform
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay left-hander Wilson Alvarez still is hearing about it
after flinging his hat and glove into the stands at Turner Field on
Tuesday night and ripping off his jersey. Now 8-19 with a 4.82 ERA,
Alvarez offered apologies to the team, manager Larry Rothschild and
owner Vince Naimoli after seeing a replay of his act on TV, but it
rang hollow.
</P>
<P>
   Rothschild said that Alvarez, in the middle of a five-year, $35
million contract, is out of shape and will have his weight
monitored. Alvarez flipped after the Braves nicked him for nine
hits and seven runs in 2 2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never, as long as I'm managing here, let a player throw
this uniform on the ground,'' Rothschild said. ...
</P>
<P>
   Like father like son: Yankees pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre
took off just one night after being struck in the forehead by a
Tino Martinez line drive during batting practice. The hit opened an
11-stitch gash. Earlier in the week in Arizona, son Todd
Stottlemyre vowed, ``Nothing will stop me from returning before the
year's out.'' He continues rehab exercises to help a partially torn
right rotator cuff.
</P>
<P>
   AL CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   Tigers `one year behind'
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Tigers are through fooling themselves. The additions
of catcher Brad Ausmus, third baseman Dean Palmer, DH Gregg
Jefferies, right-hander Dave Mlicki and right-hander Willie Blair _
plus a $10.8 million increase in payroll _ created false hope. The
Tigers haven't been better than .500 all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're one year behind where we thought we were,''
manager Larry Parrish said. ``Everyone thought we were ready to put
it together this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly owner Mike Ilitch, who has reiterated his desire
for the club to be improved by next spring, when it moves into new
Comerica Park. The Tigers have taken series from New York, Boston
and Cleveland, but have won just two of their other 16 series.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys either have to find a way within themselves to
learn how to win,'' general manager Randy Smith said, ``or we have
to go out and get somebody to show us how to win.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Will pitching ever be the same after Kansas City's I-70 Series
with St. Louis? The two staffs gave up 63 runs in three games and
needed 24 relief appearances. ... AL player of the week Frank
Thomas, who hit .555 with four doubles, just recorded his 1,000th
career RBI but hears nothing in Chicago about his home-run
production. He entered the weekend with just five home runs. ``I've
always prided myself on consistency,'' Thomas said. ``Lately, it's
just been fun to hit the ball hard.''
</P>
<P>
   AL WEST
</P>
<P>
   Keep on knucklin'
</P>
<P>
   Old knuckleballers never die. They just get released. Tom
Candiotti said goodbye to his fifth organization when Oakland axed
him, a painful decision for the A's. Candiotti was 3-5 with a 6.35
ERA when manager Art Howe called him in. ``It was real emotional on
my part,'' Howe said. ``I know how Tom must feel. I went through
it. It's not an easy thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Life immediately resumed. Rookie Tim Hudson took Candiotti's
spot in the rotation and struck out 11 in his debut Tuesday. And
Candiotti's name immediately was linked with Cleveland, where he
once led the Tribe in victories in 1987 _ with seven wins. ...
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's Ken Griffey and left-hander Jeff Fassero are running
neck and neck _ Griffey with 23 home runs hit and Fassero with 23
homers allowed. The Mariners discussed with San Diego the
availability of relievers Donne Wall and Dan Micelli. ... Texas'
bullpen was 17-1 entering the weekend and on a 14-game winning
streak. Rangers starters were 19-22.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
