<SLUG> BC-GLF-BIG-PUTTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIG ONES THAT DIDN'T GET AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's the most important putt you ever made? Some prominent PGA
Tour players give their answers.
</P>
<P>
   DAVIS LOVE III: ``At the '93 Ryder Cup, I made a putt at No. 18
to beat Costantino Rocca to help win the cup. It was only a
6-footer, but it gets longer every time I tell the story. I was
scared to death. The whole team was looking at me. The Ryder Cup
was riding on it. I got so nervous, I had to back off. I went
through my whole routine again and made it. After that, I figured
if I could make that putt, I could make any.''
</P>
<P>
   TOM LEHMAN: ``An 8-footer I made for par on No. 15 at Royal
Lytham in '96 on the way to winning the British Open. Another big
one was at the '95 Ryder Cup, a 5-footer when it was raining
sideways, to clinch the victory for me and Corey Pavin against
Colin Montgomerie and Nick Faldo. But at the 1990 qualifying
school, I made a 3-footer for birdie on the 72d hole to make the
Hogan Tour. That putt, at that time of my career, gave me the
confidence to go on. In many ways, that was the turning point of my
career.''
</P>
<P>
   SCOTT SIMPSON: ``When I won the U.S. Open in 1987, I one-putted
Nos. 14, 15, 16 and 17 at the Olympic Club to beat Tom Watson by
one stroke. You can probably pick any of those putts. But the one
at No. 15 was the best. I made a 20-footer.''
</P>
<P>
   BILLY MAYFAIR: ``I still say the biggest putt of my life, I
missed. It was at the World Series in '95. Had an 8-footer, not
only to win the tournament but to get a 10-year exemption on tour.
It lipped out. Then I lost to Greg Norman in a playoff. There's no
way that ball could've come out, but it did.''
</P>
<P>
   FRED COUPLES: ``The most fun putt was a 40-footer to beat Vijay
Singh to win the 1996 Presidents Cup. But the biggest was probably
a 4-footer at No. 17 at Augusta in 1992 when I won the Masters.''
</P>
<P>
   DAVID DUVAL: ``My first victory, a 12-footer at Kingsmill during
a playoff in 1997. That wasn't the hardest I've ever made, but it
was the most important for my confidence. The hardest putt was the
6-footer at the Bob Hope this year when I shot a 59.''
</P>
<P>
   PAYNE STEWART: ``When I won the U.S. Open in 1991 at Hazeltine,
I made a 20-footer for birdie at No. 16 that was the turning point,
because without that, I don't get into a playoff with Scott
Simpson.''
</P>
<P>
   LEN MATTIACE: ``In 1996, I made a 5-foot putt to win the Compaq
world putting championship. I won $250,000. Second place was worth
$50,000 That's a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   TIGER WOODS: ``I've got to give you two. When I was 12, I made a
15-footer to win the 11- and 12-year-old junior worlds. I wanted to
win the junior worlds in every age group, and I had already lost
when I was 11, so that was my last chance to win the 11 and 12. I
eventually won the junior worlds at every level. The other biggest
putt was on the 17th hole at Sawgrass in 1994, to win my first U.S.
Amateur championship, over Trip Kuehne. Without that one, maybe I
don't win three straight amateur championships.''
</P>
<P>
   GREG NORMAN: ``This decade, it would be a 10-footer for par on
the 15th hole at Royal St. George's, when I won my second British
Open.''
</P>
<P>
   JUSTIN LEONARD: ``The 17th hole at the British Open when I was
tied for the lead. I made a 30-footer. That was the key to winning
it.''
</P>
<P>
   JACK NICKLAUS: ``I'm not sure I can answer that. OK, on the 36th
hole of the 1959 U.S. Amateur championship against Charlie Coe, I
knocked in an 8-footer for birdie to win it. That was my first
major championship. From that point on, that one putt gave me the
confidence to say: `I can do it. I can do it.''' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
