<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Orioles again befuddle Braves
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the second day in a row, the Braves found
themselves dominated by one of the weakest pitching staffs in
baseball and subjugated at home by the game's losingest road club.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by four runs after 13 pitches, the Braves lost 5-0 to
Baltimore on Saturday afternoon, on a six-hitter by Juan Guzman
(3-4), who had been doing his best to flunk out of the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   That makes two losses in a row to the 24-36 Orioles, who
received back-to-back complete games for the first time since the
last week of the 1995 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interleague has nothing to do with it,'' left fielder Ryan
Klesko said. ``You don't play well, you don't win.''
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz will face Mike Mussina tonight, trying to avert just
the third three-game sweep of the Braves since Turner Field opened
in 1997. The O's that season were the first visitor to take three
in a row here, but that club was a division champion. These Orioles
are 12 games under .500.
</P>
<P>
   They have made the Braves look pathetic. The Braves are 0-for-6
with runners in scoring position this series, and their Nos. 3-6
hitters are 4-for-28 (.143). Guzman, who had given up 68 hits and
36 runs in his previous 62 innings, allowed no extra-base hits and
walked two while allowing only two men to get past first base.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko and Andruw Jones both committed base-running sins
Saturday. Klesko was thrown out in the second trying to make a
single into a double, and Jones was doubled off second base on a
fly ball in the eighth. Jones would have been safe if he hadn't
jogged back.
</P>
<P>
   But this one was lost in the first inning, when Kevin Millwood
gave up three home runs to the first five batters. Brady Anderson,
Mike Bordick and Will Clark opened a 4-0 lead that was not
challenged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been living on the outer-third (of the plate) and on the
inner third,'' said Millwood, who recovered to hold the Orioles to
one more run through the sixth. ``That first inning, I was right
down the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
