</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-FEATURE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dissension threatening Mets' season
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Mets worried about contending in a division
dominated for a decade by Atlanta. They worried about maintaining
steady gains at the turnstile. They worried about roster
continuity, with seven new players this year and 17 added since
1997.
</P>
<P>
   And with the sun blotted out by the cross-town New York Yankees,
the Mets worried so much about losing their personality in a city
where identity is everything. Turns out, the Mets' personality is
entirely functional. It's just that it formerly belonged to Cosmo
Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   In a year that began with the general manager being sued in a
sexual harassment case after he acknowledged an affair with a
front-office secretary, the Mets are seriously out of control,
their hopes for contention slipping away by the week.
</P>
<P>
   As the weekend began, manager Bobby Valentine was hit with a
$5,000 fine and two-game suspension by the National League for
failing to leave the Mets bench after being ejected in Wednesday's
extra-inning victory against Toronto. Well, he left, but he
returned with some eye black under his lip, wearing some geek
glasses and hoping no one would notice. He said later he was trying
to ``lighten the mood.'' Now he's appealing the fine and
suspension.
</P>
<P>
   There is no lightening Bobby Bonilla's case. The Mets are
expected to release the recalcitrant outfielder and eat what
remains of his $10 million contract. Forget a trade. The Mets ran
both Bonilla and center fielder Brian McRae through waivers last
week, and no one claimed either.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, after Valentine informed Bonilla that he was out of the
outfield rotation, Bonilla responded during the game by refusing to
pinch-hit. The two had to be separated Wednesday in a dugout
screaming match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have one of my coaches play the outfield,''
Valentine said later, and Mookie Wilson still could do it better
than Bonilla.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Steve Phillips, whose job security is apparently
Kevlar-treated, as he retained his post after disclosure of his
affair with a Florida-based Mets secretary, just fired pitching
coach Bob Apodaca and hitting coach Tom Robson without consulting
Valentine. At the time, the Mets were second in NL batting and
their bullpen was ranked third.
</P>
<P>
   The clubhouse has broken into random piques of temper. Shortstop
Rey Ordonez tossed some batting helmets when he was out of the
lineup one day against Cincinnati. McRae has lobbied hard against
Valentine's policy of withholding his lineups until the day of the
game, although it is universal practice.
</P>
<P>
   And at center stage sits Valentine, as self-centered as any
manager in recent years. Within the space of a few hours Wednesday,
he went on WFAN to dispute how he has been portrayed in the press,
got into a shouting match with a Newsday reporter who disputed
those remarks and then took on Bonilla.
</P>
<P>
   Through the fog, the Mets trudged into the weekend with a
four-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the team rule is the first rule,'' Valentine said, ``if
what people are thinking about first is the team, then everything
else falls into place. And I think at times, there's some confusion
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
