<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An issue of scar tissue
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The San Francisco Giants were three games over .500 the day
Barry Bonds underwent elbow surgery and were seven games over .500
when he returned Wednesday. The club did surrender first place to
Arizona, but it did not suffer as deeply as Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Faced in mid-May with the possibility of season-ending surgery
to remove scar tissue, Bonds went to the training room with
physical therapist Steve Conte, who manipulated Bonds' left elbow
so severely that the three-time MVP was crying in pain. But Conte
cracked the scar tissue, and Bonds was able to return 20 days ahead
of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something one human being should do to another human
being,'' Conte said. ``I pushed it to where he couldn't take it any
longer, and then I pushed it some more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had plateaued with his range of motion,'' Conte said. ``If
we didn't get more range, (doctors) would have put him back in the
operating room, given him an anesthesia and then bent and broken
the scar tissue.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Dusty Baker already thinks Bonds is throwing harder than
before, coming straight over the top more than from the side.
</P>
<P>
   TRIBE ON A RAMPAGE
</P>
<P>
   The numbers coming out of Cleveland continue to boggle the mind.
The Indians are not just leading the majors in offensive
production. They lead the galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   After completing one-third of the schedule, the Tribe was on
pace to score 1,092 runs, 25 more than the record-setting 1931 New
York Yankees. The club was hitting a major-league high .300,
leading the AL in stolen bases and ranking second in homers, a
vicious pairing of speed and power. Roberto Alomar, Travis Fryman
and Manny Ramirez are heading for 100-RBI/100-run seasons.
</P>
<P>
   And Ramirez has been simply frightening. He is hitting .424 with
runners in scoring position, hitting an absurd .727 (8-for-11) with
the bases loaded and is on pace to drive in 196 runs, six more than
Hack Wilson's record 190, which has stood since 1930.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he has 100 or more at the All-Star break, he can definitely
make a run at it,'' hitting coach Charlie Manuel said. ``The key
will be our first three hitters (Kenny Lofton, Omar Vizquel and
Alomar). If they keep hitting and getting on base like they are
now, Manny has a very good chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Those first three have a combined .426 on-base percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
