<HEADER>
A3081 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES13-C     06-12 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES13-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anderson extension unlikely before Falcons' camp
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Falcons begin ``passing camp'' Monday, and
although attendance is not mandatory, coach Dan Reeves has made it
clear he regards it as important. For running back Jamal Anderson,
it could mean more than that.
</P>
<P>
   As contract extension talks continue with AndersonJim Sims, team
officials are looking for a sign that he regards the Falcons'
efforts as earnest. It wouldn't hurt if the 26-year-old All-Pro
would take a flight from his offseason home in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Agent Jim Sims said the goal is for Anderson to be one of the
three highest-paid backs in the NFL. The best offer the Falcons
have made averaged $5.2 million a year, which would place him in
the top five, depending on whose contrace interpretation is used.
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation Anderson is waiting on a signing
bonus of $10 million, which would far surpass the franchise-record
$6 million bonus quarterback Chris Chandler got with his four-year
extension last fall, with $2 million deferred until this spring.
Sims isn't confirming the $10 million figure.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson led the NFC and was second in the NFL last season with
a franchise-record 1,846 rushing yards on a league-record 410
carries. But Reeves points out that Anderson's breakout season was
just that. He had 1,002 yards in 1997, with a 3.5-yard average, and
1,055 yards in '96.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas' Emmitt Smith, Denver's Terrell Davis and Detroit's Barry
Sanders have nine rushing titles, five Super Bowl titles and three
league MVP awards among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a player who has had one outstanding
season,'' Reeves said. ``We don't have to be doing anything. We're
talking about a player who has a contract this year. Still, we want
to extend Jamal. At the same time, we've got to do what's best for
our team (financially).''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sims offered a counterproposal Wednesday, and said,
``We're making progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Sims would not say whether Anderson will be here Monday, and
Anderson could not be reached last week.
</P>
<P>
   Sims hasn't forgotten that the Falcons called the Patriots on
draft day to see if New England was interested in acquiring
Anderson in a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to know (Anderson) is going to be a Falcon,'' Sims
said. ``We don't want him to be used as trade bait again next
year.''
</P>
<P>
   What's next?
</P>
<P>
   Passing camp will barely resemble training camp, but there is
on-field skill work as players work in shorts, shirts, cleats and
helmets. Players will focus on basic offensive and defensive sets
for 30-45 minutes a day _ Monday, Tuesday, Thursday and Friday _
for four of the next five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks, but no thanks
</P>
<P>
   The agent for recently released Rams strong safety Toby Wright
called his former head coach, Atlanta defensive coordinator Rich
Brooks, to see if the Falcons might be interested. Atlanta already
has seven safeties, though, and probably will keep five, perhaps
four. ... Atlanta will not pursue recently waived Dallas wide
receiver Billy Davis, and probably will not pursue recently waived
Patriots cornerback Chris Canty.
</P>
<P>
   Working hard
</P>
<P>
   Strength and conditioning coach Al Miller said free safety
Eugene Robinson and defensive end Chuck Smith are in great shape.
``I don't think there's any comparative analysis that would show
how much further along they are,'' Miller said. ``Chuck's in the
best shape in my three years, and Eugene is light years ahead of
last summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Among rookies, first-round draft choice Patrick Kerney, a
defensive end, has been impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Moving parts
</P>
<P>
   Reserve linebacker Craig Sauer, who moved from the weak side to
the strong side last season, probably will move back to the weak
side, where Keith Brooking is expected to start. ... The plan is
for Ronnie Bradford to get some work at free safety, but Bradford
will begin training camp as the starter at right cornerback, ahead
of '97 first-rounder Michael Booker.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
