<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3082 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS13-COX     06-12 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons' rise brings training site crunch
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Falcons moved their headquarters from
downtown to suburban Suwanee more than two decades ago, but senior
equipment manager Horace Daniel has not forgotten the joy of
moving.
</P>
<P>
   The team went from cramped offices in Atlanta-Fulton County
Stadium into a a new 28,000-square-foot building off 1-85 in
Gwinnett County. The Falcons facility was the ``kingpin of all
kingpins,'' said Daniel, who has been with the team since 1967.
``It was big, and ... we could do everything right here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were about the only team that had our own place. When other
teams were ready to build, they'd look at our place for ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Falcons are gathering ideas for another new home. The
team has signed a nonbinding letter of intent to move next summer
into a two-story, 70,000-square-foot structure at Stone Mountain
Park.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal goes through, the Falcons will be kingpins once
again. It can't happen too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the media relations and marketing departments moved
into trailers 300 yards from the main building. Team and group
meetings are held in other trailers, some workout equipment is in
another trailer, and news conferences are held in still another
trailer.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons didn't have such problems two decades ago, before
NFL rosters grew from 45 players to the current 53, plus five
players on the practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   The league's increased public presence has required additional
personnel, as well. The number of nonplaying personnel has doubled,
from 31 in 1978 to 63 last season. The Falcons have added a
four-person marketing staff and two community-relations employees,
and the public-relations department has grown from one to four. The
team has gone from seven assistant coaches to 14 and from four
scouts to 11. Strength and conditioning coach Al Miller and his
assistant, Rocky Colburn, are good examples how times have changed.
Teams were starting to hire strength coaches in the late '70s.
</P>
<P>
   The current weight room, about 2,000 square feet and undersized
by NFL standards, has dozens of bench, squat and clean racks and
hundreds of weight plates.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed facility at Stone Mountain will have a weight room
more than twice that size. It will also have an auditorium that
will seat 150 to 200 people.
</P>
<P>
   John Russell, vice president of Partners &AMP; Associates, the
Knoxville-based developer in charge of the project, said the
facility will offter many other improvements, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be multiple whirlpools (in contrast to one now), a
more spacious locker room,'' Russell said. ``There will be 200
spaces in a gated parking facility for the team and about 800
spaces for the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be reasonable to say it will cost about $15 million
to $20 million, although that number could be revised,'' he said.
``The Falcons' intent is to take care of everybody involved and
have them all under one roof. ''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Falcons will have three outdoor practice fields
and an indoor practice field under a roof 225 foot by 395 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Partners and Associates was hired by Silver Dollar City, the
Branson, Mo., theme-park management company that runs Stone
Mountain Park.
</P>
<P>
   The developers have checked out several other NFL facilities,
including the one under construction in Nashville, but most of
their input is coming from the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Equipment manager Brian Boigner, who stores quite a bit of gear
in an adjacent health club that was closed years ago, has put in
several requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know in New Orleans their (storage) cabinets are like track
lighting,'' he said. ``They can be suspended or on tracks in the
floor, and they can roll them when they're not using them.
Jacksonville, Cleveland and the Saints have it. It's a great
space-saver.
</P>
<P>
   ``And in the locker room, where we now have (three) aisles, the
big thing is to get the perimeter lockers so the middle of the room
is open (like the Braves' clubhouse). And we want to have a loading
dock right off the back of the equipment room, which we don't have
now. A laundry facility that is its own separate entity would be
nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks also has been consulted. When he was coach of the Rams in
1995-96, St. Louis was building a new headquarters in Earth City,
Mo. He liked much of what he saw and has offered Partners some
advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need separate rooms for offensive and defensive staff
meetings,'' he said. ``Right now, my office doubles as the
defensive meeting room, and staff meetings typically are in the
draft room, which is where the scouting staff does much of its
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks was one of several coaches to say that each of their
offices needs a video setup. ``Sometimes, it's hard for coaches to
break down film without interrupting someone else,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   The annual lease for such a facility would approach $2 million,
but the Falcons want to reduce the payment to $200,000-$300,000 a
year, Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   That will take a lot of corporate sponsorship; the balance
likely would have to be paid for by the issuance of construction
bonds which would increase the team's lease payments.
</P>
<P>
   Partners has about eight weeks to prove it can gather enough
corporate sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, talks are starting on the exterior appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will probably be a fair amount of brick,'' Russell said.
``We don't anticipate a modern, high-tech building with a lot of
glass; that wouldn't be in keeping with the park. But right now,
we're still focusing mostly on the floor plan, the way traffic will
flow through the building.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
