A3084 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PINEHURST-COX     06-12 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PINEHURST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. Opeourse's splendor in its grass
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   So how did Pinehurst No. 2, the elegant Donald Ross masterpiece
in the Sandhills, get the 1999 U.S. Open?
</P>
<P>
   A better question: Why did it take this long?
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, folks, there's no great controversy here. There were no
Salt Lake City-type payments to the United States Golf Association.
There's nothing that would get Mike Wallace on a flight to
Raleigh-Durham.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, we're just talking grass.
</P>
<P>
   Pinehurst No. 2 being one of the great tracks on the planet, it
had all but one ingredient to have secured a U.S. Open decades ago.
The USGA likes firm, fast greens in summer heat, and until a few
years ago it wasn't possible at No. 2 or many other courses in the
South.
</P>
<P>
   But a strain of bentgrass known as Penn G-2, installed in 1996
on the Donald Ross greens during a refurbishment headed by Rees
Jones, changed everything. They had proved successful at the newest
Pinehurst course, No. 8. Resistant to heat and humidity and able to
hold its smoothness and firmness, the putting surfaces, in the
opinion of the Pinehurst director of golf course maintenance Brad
Kocher, can be kept as firm and fast as any greens anywhere in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main concern,'' No. 2 superintendent Paul Jett said, ``is
the greens could potentially become too fast. We may have to raise
the mowing height for the Open.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This grass is so good,'' said Tim Moraghan, the USGA's
championship agronomist, ``if you don't play a shot correctly, that
shot will get away from you real fast. Players will have to be
extremely accurate with their approach shots and very careful about
the spin they use.... (For putting) this stuff has virtually no
grain. It rolls really true.''
</P>
<P>
   With perfect grass, Pinehurst emerges as a perfect U.S. Open
venue for the first such championship in the South since the
Atlanta Athletic Club hosted in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's obvious that the fairways and approaches in the
South are as good as anywhere, but the putting surfaces are
normally the best during the early spring and late fall,'' said Don
Padgett, Pinehurst's director of golf. ``We had to convince them
that we could get firm and fast greens in June before they ever
thought about coming here.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears to have worked. Players on spy missions in advance of
the tournament report shaved areas around the crowned greens that
will make par a very good score. Instead of brute strength often
being the tiebreaker in a U.S. Open, finesse will be foremost this
year.
</P>
<P>
   As for the area itself being able to withstand U.S. Open masses,
the USGA felt it adequate after the often congested Long Island,
N.Y., area so capably handled the 1996 U.S. Open at Shinnecock
Hills. Pinehurst is a village of only 8,000 residents, and to house
U.S. Open masses every hotel and rentable house within a 50-mile
area was needed. But it is a place that just exudes golf in every
aspect. Although Pinehurst will be too crowded this week to
appreciate in its usually charming state, the setting nonetheless
will be superb.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicklaus, who does not readily praise course architecture
that does not bear his own handiwork, calls Pinehurst No. 2 ``my
favorite course in the country, from a design standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, the course will escape any periods of heavy rain this
week. If No. 2 plays firm and fast, playing for the flagstick will
be about as common as Tiger Woods in plaid pants. With balls likely
to scoot off the bowl-shaped greens and down tricky slopes,
creativity will be tested. If No. 2 softens, too many birdies
definitely could ruin a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
