<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3085 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-TIGER13-COX     06-12 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TIGER13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tiger Woods' next hurdle
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since 1995 at Shinnecock Hills, when Tiger Woods started
flailing in U.S. Opens, we have seen too many:
</P>
<P>
   _ Replays that required an ``R'' rating for anger, some
occasionally for language.
</P>
<P>
   _ Drives that found the thick, unyielding rough and too many
attempted recovery shots that discovered even more of it.
</P>
<P>
   _ First rounds, averaging 74.5, that separated the game's most
dynamic player from serious contention.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, all of 23 years old entering this week's 1999 U.S. Open
at Pinehurst No. 2, freely admits as much. ``I understand the U.S.
Open is a difficult tournament and I'm not always going to play
well,'' he said, eager for his fifth installment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though people think you have all the talent in the world
and all the mental skills, you still have to have some good
breaks,'' Woods said. ``You still have to have some balls end up in
the rough with good lies, knock them on the green and have
no-brainers. ... Unfortunately, I haven't played as (well) as I've
liked in a U.S. Open, but you could also say the same for a lot of
other people, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods has shot in the 60s only two of 13 rounds, and his best
finish has been last year's tie for 18th. But timing being
everything in golf, he quite possibly has positioned himself for
his finest challenge at a U.S. Open. He has won his last two starts
_ the Deutsche Bank Open on the European Tour and last week's
Memorial, one of the most important nonmajors on the PGA Tour. And
he brings a more controlled game, featuring a rounded swing plane
less prone to errors and new evidence that he's been cracking the
books on course management.
</P>
<P>
   At the Memorial, Woods displayed his genius in the short game,
flopping out of trouble with uncanny regularity when he wasn't able
to fire successfully to the flagsticks. He also has learned to use
another 300-yard club, his 3-wood, a la Jack Nicklaus in his prime,
for landing the ball softly in firm fairways to avoid scooting into
the rough.
</P>
<P>
   Which bring us to the P-word. Patience. Woods finally is
starting to play like someone able to display it. And while Woods
has spoken before about par being acceptable in a U.S. Open, he has
not demonstrated as much when Thursdays arrived. But this time, his
more mature approach seems to be sincere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. Open is one of those tournaments where your patience
is tested to the utmost,'' he said. ``You just have to hang in
there and make sure you limit the mental mistakes. You're going to
put the ball in the rough. You're going to have some tough putts.
But you just have to hang in there. Sometimes, you can fire at the
pin. Sometimes, you can put the driver down there and make birdie.
Other times, you just have to put it in play. If you can get to the
pin, OK. If not, take your par and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not a new philosophy; it's just new for Tiger.
</P>
<P>
   ``You play the U.S. Open differently,'' Fred Couples said. ``You
know par is a great score. ... Every year it's like that. You're
not trying to go out there and be a hero and shoot 8-under for the
week. First of all, it's probably not going to happen. Second of
all, if it does happen, you'll win by six shots and play the four
best rounds of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinehurst No. 2's requirements will be different from most other
U.S. Opens. From tee to green, it doesn't appear to be so penal.
The trees are more decorative than punitive. The Bermuda rough
isn't unreasonably deep. The scary part is the crowned greens,
rebuilt in 1996 with speedy G-2 bentgrass. When Donald Ross built
them, drainage systems weren't as sophisticated as for today's
courses, and the putting surfaces became inverted bowls to allow
water run-off. However, golf balls fall off just as easily. Finding
safe spots for approach shots will require an exact number from the
fairway. Chipping or putting up slopes to the green will put
players such as Jose Maria Olazabal, Phil Mickelson, Lee Janzen or
Davis Love III in prominent roles. Or Woods, if he maintains his
controlled attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have gotten frustrated in tournaments,'' Woods conceded.
``Unfortunately, you look at some of the spots I've put myself in.
I've put myself in bushes and trees and water, and I don't know too
many people that are going to be very happy with that. I know I
wasn't. ... But I think with the evolution of my game, just because
I'm hitting it better, you're going to be more patient. ... I've
learned, through my own mistakes, of handling my emotions, of
handling disappointments, as well as handling the highs a lot
better. ... That's one of the reasons my game has been very
consistent, why I don't miss a whole lof of cuts, why I finish in
the top 10 a lot, why I gave myself a lot of chances and why I'm
starting to win again.''
</P>
<P>
   The performance at Muirfield Village, as Woods flopped and
flipped his way to an amazing series of up-and-downs, definitely
has improved his short-game confidence for Pinehurst. At No. 2, you
will see Woods using his 3-wood from the fringes, putting or
settling his 60-degree wedge onto the crowned greens.
</P>
<P>
   In a No. 2 practice round before the Memorial, Woods said, ``I
tried almost every club in my bag around the greens.''
</P>
<P>
   If Woods slips into his old habits, he has the brawn to wrestle
the Pinehurst rough, which is not as thick as in some Opens. Woods
said he has put on nearly 20 pounds of muscle since turning pro at
a wiry 160 and has reduced his body fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing a lot of lifting, and it's starting to pay
off,'' he said. ``I've been able to hit shots I've never been able
to hit, because of strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever low-percentage shots have not worked out in previous
U.S. Opens, Woods has no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I may get in my own way,'' he said, ``but I'd rather
do that than someday have to say, `I wish I would have tried
harder.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Open
</P>
<P>
   When: Thursday-Sunday, June 20.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Pinehurst Resort and Country Club, Pinehurst, N.C.,
Course No. 2, 7,175 yards, par 70.
</P>
<P>
   Purse: $3 million ($625,000 to winner).
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion: Lee Janzen.
</P>
<P>
   TV (all times Eastern): Thursday and Friday _ ESPN 11 a.m.-3
p.m., NBC 3-5 p.m., ESPN 5-6:30 p.m.; Saturday and Sunday _ NBC
12:30-7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
