<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA BECOMING BASEBALL'S HOTTEST SPOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Here is all you need to know about the
early-season success of the Arizona Diamondbacks. Actually, there
are three things that will impress even the most ardent fans, who
insist expansion teams must take their lumps.
</P>
<P>
   1. The second-year Diamondbacks scored eight or more runs in
seven straight games before being held to four by the Rangers last
Sunday. STATS Inc. researched back to 1951 and found no other team
to score eight or more in that many consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   2. Of the 73 fastballs Randy Johnson threw last Friday to end
Texas' nine-game winning streak, 44 were 98 mph or harder according
to the club's radar gun (16 at 98 mph, 23 at 99 and 5 at 100). His
96th pitch hit 99 mph. And catcher Damian Miller said Johnson, who
took a no-hitter into the seventh, had his best slider of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   3. Arizona already has had four National League Players of the
Week and none of them are Luis Gonzalez, who already has had a
30-game hitting streak and entered the weekend series against the
Angels with a .381 average. The others: Johnson, Matt Williams, Jay
Bell and Steve Finley, who received the honor last week.
</P>
<P>
   Add it up and the Diamondbacks suddenly are the bullies of the
National League, interleague and any other league that wants to
challenge their credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is real,'' said Bell, who already has 18 home runs, just
three short of his career high. ``I mean the team is real. I don't
know how long I'll keep it up, but I'm enjoying the winning a lot.
The whole team is.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not the whole team. The Diamondbacks, who entered
the weekend two games ahead of San Francisco in the West, are
struggling with their relief pitching. With the free-agent money
spent on Johnson, Finley and Todd Stottlemyre (now injured), they
should be there all season. But championships are not won in June.
And they usually are won in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Closer Gregg Olson has six blown saves (in 14 chances) and is
tied with Baltimore's Mike Timlin for the major-league lead. The
Diamondbacks have dropped five games they led entering the ninth
inning and have seen their opponents win 10 games in their final
at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Olson has allowed four homers, matching his total from last
year. But the four this year have all been with two out and two on
and have all tied or won the game (one in the eighth inning, three
in the ninth).
</P>
<P>
   There has been a call for a new closer, either Byung-Hyun Kim
(the youngest player in the big leagues) or someone else. But
manager Buck Showalter usually stays with veterans.
</P>
<P>
   What happens from here in the West is uncertain. The Giants lost
just three games to Arizona during the seven weeks Barry Bonds
missed following surgery. The Dodgers have not really been heard
from yet.
</P>
<P>
   But if you want excitement, Arizona is your team. And it won't
get any better than July 18-20 when the Diamondback travel to
Seattle to face Johnson's former team in its new ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   You remember the Mariners didn't think they could afford to keep
Johnson and pay pending big contracts to Ken Griffey, Jr. and Alex
Rodriguez. The Diamondbacks spent big money in the winter and now
are making everyone else pay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-99 1941EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3087 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMERY-INVESTIGATION-C     06-12 2271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMERY-INVESTIGATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FAA investigating Emery Worldwide over hazardous materials
 &HT;    (Moving in national (a) and financial (f) categories.)
 &HT;    By Wes Hills, Timothy R. Gaffney and Steve Bennish
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The Federal Aviation Administration is
investigating allegations that Emery Worldwide shipped hazardous
materials without adequate documentation, failed to notify pilots
of hazardous cargo on board their aircraft and concealed problems
from FAA inspectors, the Dayton Daily News has learned.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA began the investigation more than a month ago, said Bill
Wilkening, manager of the FAA's Dangerous Goods/Cargo Security
Division in Washington, D.C. Wilkening would say only that the FAA
is conducting a nationwide investigation and that the alleged
violations involve the shipment of hazardous materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly we do have a national compliance inspection'' under
way, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two employees who worked at Emery's Dayton hub also told the
Daily News that they have been interviewed by an investigator from
the U.S. Department of Transportation Inspector General's Office. A
spokeswoman in the office's Washington, D.C., headquarters would
not confirm an IG investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Emery spokesman Rocco Sacci acknowledged that FAA inspectors
have been auditing Emery Worldwide's operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that they have been to 15 of our some 200 locations,
and they have done various types of auditing, as they do . . .
checking our security procedures, and our Hazmat procedures and so
forth.''
</P>
<P>
   Sacci said the ``audits'' have found, ``At the worst, maybe some
minor administrative violations . . . maybe mistagging, or
mislabeling, something like that there. But there have been no
penalties or fines or anything like that nature.''
</P>
<P>
   The FAA probe is focused on Emery's North American freight hub
at Dayton International Airport because much of the company's cargo
_ including hazardous materials _ flows through the hub. The Daily
News obtained copies of documents made available to the FAA that
show a hazardous materials supervisor at Emery's Dayton hub
repeatedly brought complaints of violations to her superiors but
she said little was done.
</P>
<P>
   Emery's Dayton hub processes about 5 million pounds of freight
daily, according to its 1998 annual report. Although only a small
percentage involve hazardous materials _ 3 percent, say company
officials _ Emery routinely ships explosives, flammable liquids,
toxic substances, radioactive materials and biomedical products,
documents show.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines are permitted to carry hazardous materials, but the
shipments are subject to strict federal regulations and require
special labeling, documentation, handling and loading.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkening said Emery personnel have been cooperating with
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   One Emery employee who said she has been interviewed extensively
by FAA investigators is Debbra O. Bullock, 40, who from July 1997
until October 1998 worked as a hazardous materials supervisor at
Emery's Dayton hub.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock agreed to speak to Dayton Daily News reporters in the
offices of her attorney, Lawrence J. Greger, after she was asked
about documents related to the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Those documents, including numerous memos from Bullock to her
superiors warning of dangerous practices, describe a pattern of
violation after violation of hazardous materials laws over a
two-year period.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious allegations include:
</P>
<P>
   _ A Sept. 26, 1998, memo by Bullock regarding the hiding from
FAA inspectors hazardous materials in an area ``way out past the
waste building in what used to be called the graveyard.'' The Daily
News could find no evidence that an Emery manager responded to the
memo.
</P>
<P>
   _ A lengthy and detailed memo of February 1998 alleging hundreds
of shipments of hazardous materials moving without paperwork or
pilot notification, a pattern one Emery manager described as
``alarming.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Shipping materials Emery supervisors acknowledge are not
permitted ``in our system.''
</P>
<P>
   _ An acknowledgement by a hub supervisor that the handling of
hazardous materials ``has always taken a back seat to other
priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Sacci said Emery would not respond to specific allegations
involved in the FAA investigation. But he called the company's
hazardous materials handling ``industry-leading.''
</P>
<P>
   Emery has ``spent hundreds of thousands of dollars and thousands
of hours in development and training to achieve what we believe to
be the finest program for the handling of Hazmat shipments that can
be found in the air industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock said during her tenure the company did improve its
compliance record. She said she succeeded in reducing the number of
compliance violations from 800 a month to about 100. However, she
said she asked to be removed from her position last fall because
she did not feel other supervisors shared her commitment to
complying with FAA regulations.
</P>
<P>
   In a Sept. 26, 1998, letter requesting a transfer, Bullock
stated, ``I love my job, I care about the company I work for, and I
see a large liability I feel has never been addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullock said she first discovered that FAA rules were being
repeatedly ignored shortly after becoming hazardous materials
supervisor in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed there was a large number of hazardous materials that
were traveling out of compliance,'' Bullock said. ``Materials were
traveling through our process without being loaded correctly (and
without) pilot notification. The paperwork was not going with the
hazardous material, so therefore no one even knew the hazardous
material was on the aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   Federally-mandated paperwork that tracks and documents hazardous
shipments is a key component of safe transportation, Bullock said,
because pilots and ground crews must know the location and content
of hazardous freight aboard aircraft in the event of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA should have been notified when Emery violated federal
rules, but to Bullock's knowledge, federal authorities weren't
contacted.
</P>
<P>
   Her frustration and stress over conditions at the company boiled
over, Bullock said, when Emery passed an FAA inspection with flying
colors in September 1998 despite what she said were deeply
entrenched problems.
</P>
<P>
   Because Emery had prior knowledge of FAA visits, workers
successfully avoided problems by holding up hazardous materials
shipments for the period of the inspection, Bullock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't set well with me,'' she said. ``I couldn't hardly
stomach it...I had people standing around everywhere because we
just hardly got any freight at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The FAA acknowledged that it often informs companies like Emery
in advance when annual inspections occur so the people responsible
for hazardous materials will be available to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock also alleged that forms certifying that Emery planes
were loaded in accordance with FAA regulations carried a mechanical
signature of her name, even when she was not at work and had no
idea what was aboard a particular aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which means if your name's on there and there's a problem, the
FAA is going to call you and you're going to be the one held
accountable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock continues to work at Emery in another supervisory job.
She said the FAA has not offered her any job protection in exchange
for her cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was my obligation to continue to not lie to the FAA.
I felt I needed to answer their questions and answer them
honestly,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Carriers such as Emery have come under increasing scrutiny from
the FAA since the May 11, 1996, crash of ValuJet Flight 592 in the
Everglades that killed all 110 people aboard. Investigators blamed
the crash on a fire caused by oxygen generators that had been
improperly packaged, labeled and loaded into the plane's belly.
Following the crash, the FAA increased its hazardous materials
inspection staff from 12 to more than 130.
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen generators use chemical reactions to produce oxygen.
Airlines use them in their emergency oxygen systems, but the FAA
banned passenger airlines from carrying them as freight after the
Valujet crash. Freight airliners may haul oxygen generators if they
follow strict packaging and loading rules. But Emery memos describe
errors that worried the company's hazardous materials supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998, Bullock wrote a memo that said an audit by the
hazardous materials department found hundreds of hazardous
materials shipments being moved without required documentation.
Noting one that contained oxygen generators, she wrote, ``This is
what brought down ValuJet.''
</P>
<P>
   An October 1998 memo by another hazardous materials supervisor
described how a shipment of oxygen generators got loaded into a
cargo container next to part of a shipment of paint. The oxygen
generator was classified as an oxidizer and the paint as a
flammable liquid, which the supervisor called ``incompatible
materials'' that should not have been loaded side-by-side in the
same container.
</P>
<P>
   That cargo container and another one containing the rest of the
paint shipment were loaded onto a plane bound for John F. Kennedy
International Airport in New York. The improper loading was
discovered after some of the paint in the other cargo container was
spilled as it was being loaded, requiring both cargo containers to
be pulled from the flight.
</P>
<P>
   Had the spill happened in the cargo container containing the
oxygen generator, the supervisor rote, ``the oxidizer could have
reacted with the paint causing a serious fire.''
</P>
<P>
   The documents show numerous Emery supervisors were aware of the
alleged violations.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1998, Bullock was urged by a supervisor to ship a
package of methanol even though Emery's policy prohibits it on
airplanes. The shipment had already been flown to the Dayton hub
from Oklahoma City, according to the documents.
</P>
<P>
   The shipment ``was in fact not allowed in our system and should
not have been accepted,'' the supervisor wrote, ``but since it will
be flying only on Emery aircraft to the destination, we can move
this shipment, this once, on our aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   The documents also, at times, reflect concerns of Emery
supervisors to comply with FAA regulations.
</P>
<P>
   In a Sept. 2, 1998, memo, Mike A. Massie, director of
environmental affairs/dangerous goods, states, ``We expect 100
percent compliance for all shipments accepted and offered for air
transport.''
</P>
<P>
   And in another, dated March 28, 1998, Tom R. Olson, Emery's
director of primetime hub operations, said, ``We've got to close
the gap on these non-compliance shipments yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   Emery Worldwide operates one of the biggest U.S. airlines
specializing in freight, serving customers from small retail
shippers to auto companies and the Department of Defense. Based in
Redwood City, Calif., Emery Worldwide has more than 75 cargo
aircraft, 2,000 trucks and vans, and 560 service centers in 229
countries.
</P>
<P>
   It's also an important part of the Dayton area's economy.
Emery's Dayton freight hub employs about 4,200 workers _ 60 percent
of them part-time _ and expansion plans here call for an additional
6,100 jobs. In April, the company and Dayton airport officials
announced a proposal to spend $1.2 billion in three phases over 20
years on runways, infrastructure and road construction in and
around the airport, mainly to support Emery's growth.
</P>
<P>
   But the freight business is also highly competitive, and company
documents suggest that Emery personnel can be under great pressure
to move hazardous materials to retain important customers.
</P>
<P>
   In a May 1, 1998, memo describing a partially damaged shipment,
an Emery manager warned that if the items weren't moved promptly,
``there could be a plant shutdown.''
</P>
<P>
   After examining portions of Emery's internal documents regarding
the alleged violations, Mary Schiavo, former Inspector General of
the U.S. Department of Transportation, said Emery is running the
risk of being grounded by the FAA.
</P>
<P>
   Schiavo is the author of Flying Blind, Flying Safe , which is
critical of the FAA and warns the public about the most dangerous
planes and flying conditions. Schiavo is also a pilot, former
assistant U.S. attorney, and a professor of public policy at the
Ohio State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``My initial reaction is it's pretty serious stuff and if it's
still going on they could be in for some big fines, and if they're
endangering passengers they could be in for worse action,'' Schiavo
said. ``The FAA hates to ground carriers, but if they won't shape
up, I suspect if it persists they might even have to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Michael Maya Charles, a professional pilot for over 25
years and expert aviation witness and safety consultant, also
reviewed portions of the Emery documents.
</P>
<P>
   Charles, of Erie, Colo., said it is vital that pilots know
what's aboard their aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is any problem with the shipment in flight, including
a fire, odors, or smoke (or) fumes, that listing of Hazmat is vital
to the health or lives of the crew,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles said pilots have little tolerance for hazardous
materials being loaded aboard their aircraft without their
knowledge, but he said the penalties for such violations do little
to discourage the practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, the penalties for Hazmat violations amount to
little more than hand slaps and fines,'' he said, ``which only
encourages the bold and the reckless to try shipping the high
tariff dangerous goods without telling the shipper.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-99 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
