<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3089 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     06-12 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHANGE OF PHIL-OSOPHY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the Los Angeles Lakers were recently eliminated from the
NBA playoffs by the San Antonio Spurs, Jerry West had a lengthy
conversation with Jerry Buss.
</P>
<P>
   They talked about a variety of subjects, foremost of which who
would be coaching the Lakers next fall in their inaugural season at
the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson's name was mentioned, but Buss shook his head in
dissent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of my price range,'' said the Laker owner.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that Buss was set to retain Kurt Rambis, much to the
displeasure of most Laker fans, most members of the Southern
California media and Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   But then a few weeks later, West had another powwow with Buss at
his home near San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   And this time Buss, perhaps chastened by the withering criticism
he had been enduring for his desire to bring back the inexperienced
Rambis, was singing a different tune.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would it take to get Phil Jackson?'' Buss asked a
startled West.
</P>
<P>
   West threw out a number.
</P>
<P>
   Buss didn't blink.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then go get him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And so Jerry West the past week has been in serious negotiations
with Jackson's agent, Todd Musberger, in a development stunning to
those who had been led to believe that Buss would be unwilling to
spend the kind of money necessary to lure the former coach of the
Chicago Bulls to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not made a deal yet,'' said West Saturday. ``Phil
Jackson has not signed anything. I think we're close. I think it
can be done. The offer is out there. But you never know for sure
until all parties sign the contract.''
</P>
<P>
   It is believed the Lakers have offered Jackson a five-year
contract worth in the vicinity of $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   West said he still hasn't spoken to Jackson, but figures to
sometime this week. Jackson is scheduled to be in L.A. on Wednesday
to lend campaign support to his ex New York Knick teammate, Bill
Bradley, a Democratic presidential candidate. It won't be
surprising if Jackson arrives here earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Why did Jerry Buss suddenly change his mind and decide to open
up his bank vault for Phil Jackson, who coached the Michael
Jordan-fueled Bulls to six NBA titles.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I'm sure the Lakers' playoff failures in recent seasons
have something to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   The team hasn't won a world championship since 1988, hasn't been
in the finals since 1991, and has been swept in four games during
the past two post-season competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Such erratic deportment has to be grating to Buss, a man who had
come to savor all the national publicity he received when the
Lakers won five NBA crowns during his first nine seasons as their
owner.
</P>
<P>
   The last three coaches that Buss hired, Randy Pfund, Magic
Johnson and Rambis, have been huge disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the aging Buss didn't want to risk blowing another
Laker season with the unproven Rambis, who proved only during his
brief incumbency that he was far closer to being another Randy
Pfund than another Pat Riley.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure the fact that Buss also has been absorbing his share of
media attacks in recent times---a new experience for him---might
have played a vital role in his deciding that Phil Jackson wasn't
too expensive for his tastes, after all.
</P>
<P>
   As you might known, Buss was denounced for nixing a 1997 trade
Jerry West had made for Mitch Richmond, was condemned for
conducting hardball contract negotiations with West, and had been
roundly ridiculed in recent weeks for choosing to ignore Jackson
because of financial considerations.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if Buss were losing money on the Lakers, such fiscal
restraint on his part would have been quite understandable.
</P>
<P>
   But since it's known the Lakers are a lucrative enterprise and
that Buss earns anywhere between $25 and $35 million a year from
the team, Buss' posture toward Jackson wasn't exactly tenable.
</P>
<P>
   It became obvious to anyone who had only the barest knowledge of
basketball that the undisciplined, disoriented Lakers, with two
players of exceptional athletic skills in Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe
Bryant who have been unable to play effectively together, were in
desperate need of a strong leader with established credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Who better than Phil Jackson, who pushed all the right buttons
with the Bulls including even the ones geared toward Dennis Rodman?
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil's really a good guy,'' said West, who played against
Jackson when Jackson was a reserve forward with the Knicks. ``The
players he's coached liked him, but he can be quite tough. He's
also an extremely hard worker.''
</P>
<P>
   Securing Jackson's services will take a chunk out of Buss'
private profits, but Buss figures to make up for such lost revenue
if Jackson is able to get the Lakers to the same level that he did
the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson was the beneficiary in Chicago of coaching the
greatest player in all the seasons of basketball in Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   He won't have such a divine force in Los Angeles, but the wily
Jackson knows the Lakers aren't exactly undermanned with the
presence of O'Neal, Bryant and Glen Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been all very interesting,'' said West, who seems
genuinely excited by the imminent arrival of Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike others in recent years, this is one Jerry Buss decision
that Jerry West clearly endorses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
