<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3090 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE13-COX     06-12 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While Texas Gov. George W. Bush was making his Iowa
debut Saturday, Vice President Al Gore sketched a Democratic
presidential campaign that he said will be grounded in family and
children's issues _ and PG-rated in its approach to his Republican
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to bring about revolutionary improvements in our public
schools and give families a chance to be strong and live in safe
and liveable communities,'' Gore said in a roundtable discussion
with political writers in the vice president's residence at the
Naval Observatory.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he would push for ``full access to high-quality
pre-school for every child in America,'' and smaller class sizes
all the way through 12th grade.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing Bush and Elizabeth Dole in early polls, Gore has moved
up his campaign kickoff in his home of Carthage, Tenn., to
Wednesday. It's a political launch in which he faces the tricky
task of identifying himself with the economic good times the nation
is enjoying, while setting a course independent of President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I represent is continuity where the prosperity is
concerned, but dramatic change where our approach to solving social
problems is concerned,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Bush's advisers have predicted the Gore strategy will be
to wear down their candidate over what promises to be a very long
general election campaign, one that will grow increasingly nasty
and personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' Gore said, repeating a pledge by his
campaign chairman, Tony Coelho, that anyone engaging in ``that kind
of activity'' will be fired, with ``no appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore was also asked about his choice of Coelho, who is
considered to have pioneered many of the fund-raising practices
which have been a source of political trouble for the vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been friends for more than 20 years and I don't think
there's anybody more capable of being a national campaign
chairman,'' Gore replied tersely.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president said he'd not seen the televised coverage of
Bush's speech earlier Saturday in Cedar Rapids and declined to
comment directly on some of the Texas governor's tax-reduction
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   But he had a reply, nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the keys to keeping our prosperity going is
steadfastness in rejecting risky tax schemes based on political
appeals to the extreme right that threaten to drive the economy
straight into the ditch,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The balance of the discussion with the vice president dealt with
domestic matters.
</P>
<P>
   However, Gore said he'd had an hour-and-15-minute telephone call
earlier in the day with Sergei Stepashin, the new Russian prime
minister, about the situation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Russian troops that moved into Pristina was ``not a
militarily significant force'' and expressed confidence that
frictions with the Russians could be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   He credited Russian emissary Victor Chernomyrdin with ``the key
role in bringing about an end to the conflict and said he had done
``a spectacular job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When the full story is told, people will realize how much
courage he showed,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
