<HEADER>
A3091 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN     06-12 1337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZEN AND JERRYS IN A KOAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a season in detox, the NBA will wave the white flag at its
addiction to Zen and Jerrys.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Zen and Jerrys will be served in a koan.
</P>
<P>
   This timing is better than swell. As the next millennium grinds
to within walking distance, the Phil-osophy of the East is poised
to collide with the protocol of the West ... Jerry West.
</P>
<P>
   Rolling into Laker Acres behind the wheel of luxury karma is
Phil Jackson, Zen Master P, the coach/spirit guide who coaxed six
championships out of Michael Jordan and the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the rings, Jackson's Windy City flavor had been
reduced to a bitter strain of wavy gravy. His stream of higher
consciousness was rippled by a celebrated power struggle between
himself and personnel serpent Jerry Krause, who wore the blessing
of Bulls owner Jerry Reinsdorf.
</P>
<P>
   Now on the cusp of becoming warlord of the Lakers, Jackson will
be under the scrutiny of two more big-time Jerrys, West and Buss.
</P>
<P>
   Did either side really have a choice?
</P>
<P>
   If he never coached again, the perception of Jackson's legacy
would be limited to his uncanny knack for putting Jordan in the
starting lineup. Oh, he wasn't about to validate his genius by
hauling the triangle offense to a risky site such as Vancouver. But
the Lakers just happen to satisfy the league-championship recipe
for Hall of Fame-caliber talent.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence suggests that hiring Jackson could bring the type
of immediate results you might achieve by assigning Dirty Harry to
direct traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, over in Inglewoodstock, a franchise that has
Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant on the payroll is riding the crest
of two consecutive season-ending playoff sweeps. It had begun to
look like the only Jackson who could handle this crisis was Jesse.
</P>
<P>
   Short of Pat Riley, Zen Master P may be the only coach in
captivity with the historical chutzpah to stand up to this Laker
cast.
</P>
<P>
   So, with Phil on the bench, the next order of business will be
selecting a championship parade route. Right? Well, for reality's
sake, let's send the clue bus on that first victory lap.
</P>
<P>
   The only guarantees Jackson brings are greater expectation and
relentless drama.
</P>
<P>
   OK, he did weave a convincing psyche job through the fabric of
his Bulls teams. But the Lakers and their management team (don't
forget Earvin Johnson) suit up more ego per square inch than roll
call at the Academy Awards show.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls weren't starving for ego either, but they ran behind
the lead of one alpha dog ... Jordan. The Lakers, on the other
hand, have two many pups barking at the same time. Jackson, who has
a couple of books on his resume, will be challenged to steer Shaq
and Kobe onto the same page.
</P>
<P>
   West's duty will be selecting the proper supporting mutts to
fill in around them.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been interesting if this week's rumored
acquisition of Scottie Pippen was more than a rumor. A source close
to West said it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   With Pippen in the lineup, Jackson may have convinced the Lakers
to embrace his concept of Zen defense.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of defense: While major league baseball is under siege
by purists who believe it's suffering from too much offense, the
NBA has been accused of screaming in the other direction.
</P>
<P>
   Not enough scoring, eh?
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry ... a few league sharpies are attempting to concoct
remedies. One such notion - fueled by frequent sightings of
low-post sluggos burning 15 seconds while backing toward the hoop -
is to outlaw the illegal defense.
</P>
<P>
   That would allow the illogical defense ... the zone.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, striving to improve point production by allowing a zone
would be as strategically absurd as promoting population control by
passing out Barry White CDs.
</P>
<P>
   But sources close to the NBA's competition committee doubt that
any wild changes in defensive freedom or shot-clock duration will
occur. One change that could happen is altering the lane to conform
with the triangular shape used in international play.
</P>
<P>
   Boo. That would cripple low-post activity. Think ``A Rik Smits
in every garage.''
</P>
<P>
   The best move would be resurrecting the ol' five-second count
for a closely guarded ballhandler. That would discourage backing in
and send Charles Barkley to NBC.
</P>
<P>
   And if the league insists on stirring up more offense, it should
encourage its referees to call fouls.
</P>
<P>
   Still pitching Penny: Yeah, it's June, a month for kids to be
released into the wild, and a time for reporters to hurl a few
trade rumors against the wall.
</P>
<P>
   One that won't stick is this week's fictional tale concerning
Penny Hardaway and the Clippers. According to a popular New York
news sharpie, the Clips were prepared to package their first-round
pick (No. 4 overall) with two re-signed free agents (Lamond Murray
and Rodney Rogers) and send this gift to Orlando in exchange for
Penny.
</P>
<P>
   The talk-radio bandwagon was crowded in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   However, according to sources for both teams, that deal hasn't
been discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Well, the Clippers, who reporters think are to the baggage
of other teams as Mikey is to Life cereal, don't need to deal the
pick for a big-ticket free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Come July 1, they will experience something wonderful ...
serious cap room. If Penny wanted to play for them (doubtful) in
the first place - and they wouldn't make a trade without such an
agreement - the Clippers could buy him and keep their draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   What they don't seem to have is an owner who will commit to the
85 million scoots Hardaway is seeking and the $70 million-plus tab
to re-sign Maurice Taylor in the same summer.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway as a Clipper is not impossible, but in a climate of
pinch, don't expect Penny.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-draft campfire: According to snitches reporting from the
NBA's Pre-Draft Camp at Moody Bible Institute in Chicago, the
action has been as promising as an airport bar at 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the draft's expected heavyweights didn't participate,
but Corey Maggette, the lottery's X-factor, did provide something
to chatter about. Maggette, who's from Chicago, did (with the help
of an eager agent) stage a one-man workout for representatives of
13 teams in an attempt to prove leaving Duke after his freshman
year is not a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Including the water breaks, said one scout, the Maggette show
lasted about 20 minutes. All the 6-foot-6 helicopter did was miss
an inordinate amount of unguarded, mid-range jump shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it won't matter,'' the scout said. ``Some team will look
at him and see (1999 rookie of the year) Vince Carter. They'll be
too scared not to take him. But Carter has much better skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Maggette will be in L.A. on Friday to put his skills to the test
of the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Shot-clock violations: If you're shocked by the playoff
performance of the Knicks' Marcus Camby, you probably didn't see
him outplay Tim Duncan when UConn defeated Wake Forest during their
junior season. Camby finished the season as the national Player of
the Year. ... Two players who have worked out for the Lakers are
Arizona point guard Jason Terry and Duke sniper Trajan Langdon. ...
Isiah Thomas remains the grapevine favorite to coach the Wasington
Wizards, but don't be surprised if he after putting together a
group of investors buys the CBA. He then would attempt to make the
CBA a true minor league for the NBA. ... Next month, an arbitrator
will decide if the league's new collective bargaining agreement
allows Jalen Rose to become a free agent or keeps him on the
Indiana roster for one more season. Rose would be a hot free-agent
commodity, but don't forget that his agent is L.A.-based and
Clipper-friendly Norm Nixon, and a close friend is Clip star Mo
Taylor, like Rose an ex-Michigan Wolverine. ... Dennis Rodman took
a verbal shot or two at Jerry West this week, proving that it's
much easier to put your foot in your mouth when you can't find your
shoes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
