<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3093 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-ENTRY-BOS &LR;      06-12 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-ENTRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US ATTEMPTS TO SMOOTH OVER DIFFERENCES WITH RUSSIA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN AND ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Their thunder stolen by the Russians and
their progress slowed by thunderstorms, NATO troops rolled into
Kosovo Saturday, beginning the peacekeeping operation aimed at
getting 850,000 refugees to return home.
</P>
<P>
   Led by an advance party of British troops that disarmed some
Kosovo Liberation Army rebels and Serb police officers, the first
NATO forces to enter Kosovo proceeded slowly and cautiously,
fearing land mines and booby traps in the eight tunnels and 50
miles between the Macedonian border and the Kosovar capital. But
the tedious trek from Macedonia, where British and other NATO
troops have been waiting for months, went without major incident.
</P>
<P>
   The deployment coincided with the effort by US officials to
smooth diplomatic relations with Russia, negotiating with Moscow
over the terms of the peacekeeping mission after the unexpected
arrival of Russian troops in Kosovo earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian movement remained a mystery Saturday. Defense
Secretary William S. Cohen said he did ``not know what the
motivation was,'' although he and other US officials insisted the
200-member Russian convoy was militarily insignificant and a minor
glitch in an overall triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look forward to working with Russia and others who may not
have agreed with our military campaign, but do agree with the
proposition that all the people of that tiny land, Serb and
Albanian alike, should be able to live in peace and freedom,''
President Clinton said in a commencement speech at the University
of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the dispute is who will command Russian troops _
NATO or Russia. Russian leaders say they will not be a part of a
NATO-led Kosovo-Force (K-FOR) peacekeeping unit; NATO has said it
will not accept a separate Russian patrolling zone, for fear it
would lead to the partitioning of Kosovo. Cohen reiterated that
demand Saturday, saying ``there must be NATO forces throughout the
region and NATO in every sector, and they will be under a unified
command.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, as Russian and NATO soldiers faced each other
for the first time in Pristina, it was still unclear how the matter
would be resolved, despite a day of talks in Moscow between Deputy
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott and the Russian national security
chief, Vladimir Putin, Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev, and Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov. Vice President Al Gore also phoned Russian
Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin and had a ``very constructive,''
hourlong conversation, an aide said.
</P>
<P>
   But a Russian participant in the talks said the United States
had taken a ``rigid'' position and indicated that the sides were
still far apart.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs within Kosovo took delight in the early arrival of the
Russians, because it upstaged NATO and because they consider
Russians, their fellow Orthodox Christian Slavs, an important
counterweight to the Western allies. The Russians proceeded to the
airport, where there was a brief but tense standoff between
British, Russian and Yugoslav forces late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The British forces had spent the day journeying into Pristina,
becoming the first Western presence in Kosovo in nearly three
months. They were greeted along the road by a mixture of cheers
from scattered local Albanians and jeers from Serbs, many of whom
continued to flee the province.
</P>
<P>
   Lieutenant James Blount of the British Army's Household Cavalry
Regiment, who surveyed the journey into Kosovo from the top of a
Scimitar light tank, described the landscape of burned-out homes as
eerie. His firsthand glimpse of ethnic cleansing underscored the
necessity of the mission, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't seen a single civilian yet,'' said Blount, as the
convoy of the first NATO troops stopped about 20 miles within
Kosovo. ``Everybody's gone. It's incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, bursts of automatic gunfire sounded around Pristina
frequently Saturday and into Saturday night, a not so subtle
reminder to occupying forces that they are surrounded by a heavily
armed, hostile local population, albeit one that grows smaller by
the day as Serbs continue to leave Kosovo in droves.
</P>
<P>
   Serb humiliation was evident on the face of a police officer,
one of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's feared Interior
Ministry police, blamed for most of the atrocities during the
conflict, who was disarmed just south of Urosevac. Another police
officer who had his sidearm taken away covered his empty holster
with his right hand as photographers arrived.
</P>
<P>
   British Army Captain Frasier Rea, leading the first NATO troops
into Kosovo, a dozen members of the Royal Gurkha Rifles Regiment,
took a submachine gun from the officer, who said he needed it for
protection from the Kosovo Liberation Army as he drove south.
</P>
<P>
   Rea, who was in the first NATO vehicle, a Land Rover, to drive
into Kosovo, insisted there were no hard feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked them very politely,'' he said. ``We've had very
little trouble. We've met VJ forces, KLA, everyone's been friendly.
Everyone understands the terms of the military-technical
agreement.'' VJ is an acronym for the Yugoslav army.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement calls for all Serb forces to withdraw from Kosovo
within the next eight days.
</P>
<P>
   The first NATO troops on the ground inside Kosovo were the
Gurkhas, a British regiment recruited from Nepal. NATO's
multicultural troops provided a contrast to the forces representing
Serbia, which has provoked four wars in 10 years in a policy aimed
at creating a Serb-dominated nation.
</P>
<P>
   Gurkha Corporal Chet Gurung, 30, said he was not concerned that
the Russians had beat them into Kosovo. ``Not a worry,'' Gurung
said, his machine gun at the ready. ``Peace already dawned.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet officials in the United States and Russia were far less
certain of how those roles would be carved up. Saturday night, no
one seemed to know if the Russian deployment was intentional, or if
it indicated the Russian military was wildly out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov, the foreign minister, said early Saturday that the
Russian troops had entered Kosovo by mistake and that they had been
ordered to leave the province. But late Saturday, the Russian
troops were still in Pristina and Russian news agencies reported
that reinforcements were ready to leave for Kosovo. At the same
time, Russian President Boris Yeltsin promoted the general who led
the unit, Viktor Zavarzin, to the rank of three-star general,
indicating approval at the highest levels. Clinton and Yeltsin are
scheduled to have a conference call Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Cullen reported from Pristina; Kornblut from Washington. Also
contributing were Globe staff members David Filipov from Moscow,
Susan Milligan from Kukes, Albania, and Globe Correspondent Kurt
Pitzer from southeastern Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-99 1952EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
