<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO TOWNSPEOPLE BLAME OUTSIDERS FOR BRUTAL ACTS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GNJILANE, Yugoslavia _ When the men in masks moved through this
Kosovo town a couple of months ago, they spoke in accents that led
ethnic Albanians to conclude they were not local men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the trouble here comes from outsiders,'' one man said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the term ``outsider'' is about to get a whole new meaning.
With its 60,000 people split between 70 percent ethnic Albanians
and the rest Serbs, Gnjilane could be just any other town in
Kosovo, where Serbs and Albanians have lived in periods of awkward
tolerance and open hatred.
</P>
<P>
   But it is different, because this town is about to be
transformed into the headquarters of some 7,000 American troops,
part of the peacekeeping force here known as K-FOR.
</P>
<P>
   Some Serbs see the arrival of the Americans as a humiliation,
the latest in a string for the Serbs, who have lost wars in
Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia and now Kosovo, seat of their religious
and national identity.
</P>
<P>
   But Rela Nesic sees nothing but dollar signs, or more precisely
dinar signs. Nesic runs the Hotel Europe, a 50-room hostelry that
has seen better days. Nesic smiles when he thinks about the
prospect of GIs and the flood of United Nations personnel about to
arrive in Kosovo filling his cavernous restaurant, which
 &UR; yesterday &LR;   &UR; afternoon &LR;  had only one table of diners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why shouldn't I be hospitable to the American soldiers?'' he
asked. ``I have no problems with Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Nesic's politics, or lack of them, may explain his views toward
Americans. Most Serbs in Kosovo are hard-line nationalists, seeing
their very existence threatened by the Kosovo independence movement
led by the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   But Nesic insists that Gnjilane was always a more tolerant
place, where Albanians and Serbs got along. Outside, Yugoslav
soldiers on convoys passing through town as they withdraw from
Kosovo fired gunshots defiantly into the air.
</P>
<P>
   Nesic shrugs, saying, ``Nobody here approves of that. I'm a
Serb, what can I do?''
</P>
<P>
   Nesic claims that Serbs here protected Albanians during the war.
Around the corner, an Albanian man who declined to give his name
challenged Nesic's rosy view of community relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only a few cases of Serbs protecting Albanians
here,'' he said. And he disputed the notion that only Serb
paramilitary police from outside Gnjilane caused the trouble here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a saying,'' he said. ``You are who your friends are.''
</P>
<P>
   But that man, and other Albanians interviewed  &UR; yesterday &LR; , said
there will not be reprisals against local Serbs when the Albanian
refugees return.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been through bad things, and we wouldn't do it to
anybody else,'' said one man, carring eggs and lettuce from a
three-week-old Albanian market that was frequented  &UR; yesterday &LR;  by
Serb police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Melici Ramadan, who was selling vegetables  &UR; yesterday &LR;  at the
market off the main square, moved here from Malisevo, a Kosovo
Liberation Army stronghold that has been punished repeatedly by
Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   He said 20 masked Serb police officers entered Malisevo two
weeks after the war began and summarily executed four men and
expelled the rest of the residents. Ten members of his family,
including his 90-year-old mother, joined more than 800,000 refugees
and left Kosovo. He decided to move here and stick it out.
</P>
<P>
   Ramadan agreed with Nesic about the violence in this town,
saying that ``most people who made a mess here were not from here,
they were from Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   His relations with Serbs have been mostly positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born with them here. I had a good life and we worked
together for a long time. We never had a problem, but now we do,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, during the air raids of the last 2 1/2 months, Ramadan
took shelter in a Serb's basement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people are good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nesic agreed with that, and wants to put the war behind him
quickly. ``This was a stupid war. Why would anyone go to war with
NATO?'' he asked. ``I wasn't responsible for this. Let's bury the
war. This war didn't produce any heroes. So let's just bury it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nesic agreed with most local Albanians, saying he thought the
Albanians who fled will return to their homes. ``There was one
group here who were bad to Albanians. They could not be controlled.
Even the police here and the (Yugoslav Army) didn't like what
happened here. Who brought them here? Why? I don't know. They
should be held responsible for what they did, burning houses,
robbing places. Honest Serbs chased them out.
</P>
<P>
   That might not be entirely true, but even if it isn't the
Albanians don't seem to be waiting to even the score. While
Gnjilane has its share of problems, this is hardly the tensest town
in Kosovo. For that, the arriving Americans can be thankful. They
will have enough problems everywhere else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
