<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BREAKDOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON TRIES COOL RESPONSE TO RUSSIA'S SURPRISING MOVE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There it was on CNN, the startling sight of Russian
tanks rolling through the streets of downtown Pristina against US
wishes, and well ahead of NATO peacekeeping forces. Even so, White
House officials at first refused to believe it, rushing into
meetings late Friday night and dodging questions about why their
assurances of cooperation by Russian peacekeepers had been so
terribly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   By Saturday, the same officials were clearly playing cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, President Clinton glossed over the event, welcoming
Russian participation in tending to the peace. General Hugh
Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, dismissed the
Russian move as part of the normal confusion of sending troops.
Defense Secretary William S. Cohen chalked it up to a Russian state
of mind, saying that while he was not certain of the motivation, it
might have been ``simply overanxiousness on the part of the
military commanders.''
</P>
<P>
   Ignored throughout was a simple question: How were NATO and the
United States once again caught so unaware, despite the massive
intelligence capacities officials are usually so quick to promote?
Wasn't it just five weeks ago that NATO warplanes had accidentally
bombed the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, prompting the idea of using
extra caution in future military affairs?
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the details behind the Russian advance were still
unclear. National Security Council spokesman David Leavy declined
to go into specifics, saying US officials had not been aware of the
Russian tank movement because the Russians ``gave us assurances
that wasn't going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   And anyway, Leavy added late Saturday afternoon: Russian Foreign
Minister Igor ``Ivanov told us it was a mistake. They told us
privately and publicly they regretted what had taken place.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea that US officials simply took Russian leaders at their
word _ and then cheerfully accepted an apology _ struck several
intelligence analysts as ludicrous. Also, said defense analyst John
Pike of the Federation of American Scientists, signs abounded that
the Russian deployment was not a mistake, including the fact that
Yeltsin Saturday promoted the commander who led in the troops.
Another reason: the reality that the troops disobeyed Ivanov's
retreat order by remaining in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew the convoy was on the way from Bosnia to Yugoslavia.
What we didn't know was what was going to happen at the border,''
Pike said. ``National technical means are very good for assessing
capabilities, but not so good for assessing intentions.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems, according to analysts, were probably twofold: US
officials mishandled Russia diplomatically, reading incorrectly the
promises of Ivanov and failing to sense the dissatisfaction of the
military and the Russian Parliament with Russia's back-seat role in
the peacekeeping mission.
</P>
<P>
   That diplomatic miscalculation could easily have led to a
military one, with US officials failing to order close surveillance
of the Russian convoy after it appeared to stop outside the border
of Kosovo. Hours after the tanks appeared to have settled in for
the night, they suddenly showed up in Pristina, and on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Galen Carpenter, the vice president for defense and foreign
policy studies at the CATO Institute, a conservative think tank,
said it was ``certainly embarrassing to have that kind of
intelligence failure again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sloppy diplomacy that no one would realize this was a
possibility,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If they had, military officials could have ordered unmanned
surveillance planes, known as drones or UAVs, to follow the convoy.
Those are the same planes that have been monitoring Serb troop
withdrawal from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   According to retired Colonel Bill Taylor, now an analyst at the
Center for Strategic and International Studies, the State
Department should have at least considered history. After World War
II, it was the Russians who ``moved en masse into Berlin before we
did,'' he pointed out, carving out extra space for the Soviet bloc
and defining the geography of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who knows anything about history should have thought
of this as one of a dozen scenarios,'' he said. ``It's laughable.
It's one of a long series of screwups. Somebody goofed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
