<SLUG> BC-BBN-NL-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE RAIN FOR MARLINS PARADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Florida Marlins had an unlikely seven-game
winning streak end this past week. But there was another stat that
might be more critical to their future in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Entering their weekend series with the New York Yankees, the
Marlins had experienced seven rain delays in their previous 12 home
games. Rain is part of life in the summer there, but for fans faced
with watching bad baseball it is another reason to stay home.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance, well over 3 million in the club's first season
(1993), was 1.75 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   New ownership is meeting resistance in attempts for a domed
stadium and it would still be years away if the measure was
approved. That might not be enough time to keep the club from
moving, however. &QL; 
JUST A THOUGHT
</P>
<P>
   Braves manager Bobby Cox admits the thought of shifting Chipper
Jones!off back to his natural position at shortstop crosses his
mind every time Walt Weiss is injured, which is often.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, he plans to make no changes, keeping Jones at
third base and playing veteran Ozzie Guillen at shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always think about that,'' Cox said of moving Jones. Guillen
played 83 games last year in place of Weiss. Jones, who came though
the Braves system as a shortstop, played 38 games there in 1996,
but none since. &QL; 
TAKING AIM
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa drew criticism from some fans for not playing in last
year's All-Star Game, instead resting his sore left elbow. But he's
looking forward to both the game and the home run hitting contest
at Fenway Park this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's going to be some fireworks show out there,'' he said. &QL; 
ROAD WARRIORS
</P>
<P>
   The Reds finished a four-city, 12-game road trip with a 9-3
record, the most wins they've had on a trip since going 11-2 in
September 1981. Their 19-10 road record is second only to
Cleveland's 19-7.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Reds, they are playing the high-powered
Indians this weekend in Cincinnati. Reds first baseman Sean Casey
entered the weekend batting an NL-best .388, but it will be
difficult to make the All-Star team with Mark McGwire, Jeff Bagwell
and John Olerud around. &QL; 
HOME BOY
</P>
<P>
   Dante Bichette ended the Rockies' last homestand with a
game-winning homer off Arizona's Gregg Olson. Then he proceeded to
go 2 for 34 on a 10-game road trip. In his first game back at Coors
Field, Bichette went 4 for 6 with three RBI, including the
game-winner on a 10th-inning single. &QL; 
WHO'S MORE VALUABLE?
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell hit three homers Wednesday night at Comiskey Park,
the third time in his career he has hit three homers and the second
time this season he has hit three in a game. But he might not be
the most important player on the Astros. From May 18 through June
4, Craig Biggio batted .193 and Houston's lead in the NL Central
shrank from 5{ games to one. &QL; 
MORE METS MADNESS
</P>
<P>
   How did GM Steve Phillips convince Mets owner Fred Wilpon that
he needed to fire three trusted members of embattled manager Bobby
Valentine's coaching staff? By promising to promote former Dodgers
pitching coach Dave Wallace, the organizational pitching guru, who
just happens to be close to Sandy Koufax, who just happens to be
Brooklyn high school buddies with Wilpon. &QL; 
GOIN' SOUTH
</P>
<P>
   Since Curt Schilling ripped Phillies ownership for a lack of
commitment to winning, his season has soured. In his nine starts
before making those comments, he was 7-1 with a 2.58 ERA. In four
starts since, he is 1-2 with a 4.40 ERA. Schilling, who pitches
today despite a recent flareup of gout, has blown a four-run
ninth-inning lead against the Mets and a three-run seventh-inning
lead against the Giants, and lost both games. &QL; 
MOON SHOT
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh's Brant Brown was batting .164 in his previous 30
games when he went 5 for 5 against Detroit and hit just the 35th
homer to clear the roof at Tiger Stadium. He hadn't driven in a run
since May 9, when he hit his only other homer of the season, an
inside-the-park shot at Busch Stadium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
