</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-S.AFRICA-BUTHELEZI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUTHELEZI LIKELY TO BE TAPPED FOR HIGH SOUTH AFRICAN POST
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ Barring a last-minute shift, a man regarded as a
leading fomenter of ethnic violence during the closing years of
apartheid will step into South Africa's second-most powerful job
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to newly elected President Thabo Mbeki said the
successor to Nelson Mandela will tap as his deputy Mangosuthu
Buthelezi, leader of the Zulu-based Inkatha Freedom Party and until
recently an arch-foe of the ruling African National Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement is expected to come Monday shortly after a
special session of Parliament formally elects Mbeki to the
presidency. The new leaders will be inaugurated Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of Buthelezi marks a strategic attempt by Mbeki to
stabilize the troubled KwaZulu-Natal Province, where more than
12,000 people have been killed in factional fighting between the
ANC and Inkatha over the past decade. A partnership between the two
parties could also effectively give the ANC a 75 percent majority
in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is better to have Buthelezi inside than outside,'' said a
senior adviser to Mbeki. ``If we don't take that route, the
situation in KwaZulu could degenerate into the kind of experience
we see in many African countries today, where leaders fail to rise
above petty politics and ethnic differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Other moves by Mbeki to consolidate his power may mean that
Buthelezi will play little more than a ceremonial role in the
nation's second-highest office. That would mark a sharp contrast
with Mbeki's own role as Mandela's deputy. He ran the Cabinet and
played a primary role in foreign policy, essentially crafting
Mandela's doctrine abroad. He also ran, with Vice President Al
Gore, the US-South Africa Binational Commission, the most important
trade body linking the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   Organizational moves announced by Mbeki's office last week
indicate that the incoming president is likely to reserve those
roles for himself. The new organizational chart structure places
the deputy president's staff under the president's
director-general. Mbeki also plans to form a secretariat, a
powerful coordinating organ within the president's office that will
oversee policy and planning.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Buthelezi's power is carefully checked, his
proximity to the presidency raises troubling questions for many
South Africans.
</P>
<P>
   Buthelezi's party was deeply infiltrated by the apartheid
security forces during the late 1980s and early 1990s, and Inkatha
was linked to a third of the atrocities examined by the Truth and
Reconciliation Commission, the panel charged with investigating the
human-rights abuses of South Africa's racist past.
</P>
<P>
   The commission concluded that, as Inkatha's leader, chief
minister of the KwaZulu government, and minister of police of the
now-defunct black homeland, Buthelezi was accountable ``where these
three agencies are found to have been responsible'' for gross human
rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   ANC officials scoff at the notion that Buthelezi's past should
disqualify him from holding office. They note that former president
F. W. de Klerk served as Mandela's second deputy president for two
years without coming clean about his apartheid-era actions.
</P>
<P>
   But past violations are not the only issue. More than 1,000
people have died in political violence in KwaZulu-Natal each year
since 1994, according to two independent analyses. At least half a
dozen have been killed since last week's elections.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, in an attempt to win immunity from prosecution, a
senior Inkatha leader disclosed to police the location of the
largest secret arms cache yet found in South Africa. The payload,
seven tons of explosives, amounted to a fraction of the weapons
known to have been brought into KwaZulu-Natal by apartheid police
ahead of the 1994 elections and delivered to Inkatha. The party
leader, Phillip Powell, faces possible charges of treason. There
are thought to be other such arms stockpiles whose locations remain
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Buthelezi has not come clean about his knowledge of the arms
caches, but the find last month indicates the importance of
rapprochement between the ANC and Inkatha.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thabo Mbeki is concerned about national unity,'' said Themba
Sono, president of the South African Institute on Race Relations.
``He doesn't want to see Buthelezi's followers become loose cannons
and go on a spree. So bringing Buthelezi on board is a price he is
willing to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Granting the Inkatha leader a high-profile seat in government
isn't a new move. Buthelezi served as minister of home affairs for
the past five years and often filled in as acting president when
Mandela was traveling outside the country. Those gestures paved the
way for ongoing peace talks between the ANC and Inkatha.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki's move follows a similar strategy, but takes it further.
Earlier last week, three minor opposition parties joined together
to form a coalition government in the Western Cape, thereby
excluding ANC from power in the province. By bringing Buthelezi
into Mbeki's government, the ANC hopes to form a close partnership
with Inkatha and expand its power base at both the national level
and in KwaZulu-Natal.
</P>
<P>
   But Mary de Haas, an anthropologist at the University of Natal
who has studied the two parties' conflicts, is not sure the move
will end the ongoing violence in KwaZulu-Natal. Buthelezi may
happily trade his cooperation for higher office, she notes, but he
might not be able to swing the traditional Zulu leaders and rogue
warlords still stirring much of the strife.
</P>
<P>
   The ANC and Inkatha ``have been talking peace at the leadership
level, but it hasn't filtered down,'' De Haas said. ``For those
maintaining fiefdoms it means little. The violence will continue
unless the leaders go together throughout the region, talking peace
and reprimanding'' those won't toe the line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
