<HEADER>
A3115 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-1STLD-WRI     06-12 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-975&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TRIES TO SORT OUT RUSSIAN MOVE IN KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: TOPS with new information; UPDATES throughout) 
(ATTN: Ill.)  (rk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Defense Secretary William Cohen said Saturday that
President Boris Yeltsin had authorized the early entry of Russian
troops into Kosovo, a deployment that surprised American officials
and possibly senior members of his own government.
</P>
<P>
   At a Pentagon briefing Saturday, Cohen declined to characterize
the presence of Russian troops in Pristina, Kosovo's capital, as a
mistake, a term widely used in the last 24 hours by various
administration, NATO and Moscow officials as they played down a
Russian move that stole the spotlight from NATO's entry into
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also rejected the possibility that the Russian deployment
was a case of crossed signals between Moscow and military
commanders in the Balkans, and he insisted that the Russian troops
would have to come under NATO command.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unclear whether it's a mistake or not,'' Cohen said of
the continuing presence of Russian forces at the airport in
Pristina. ``It certainly was a precipitous action leading to some
confusion. It was surprising to the foreign minister, who had
indicated privately to Secretary Albright and others that there
would be no action taken going into Pristina last evening.'' He was
referring to the Russian foreign minister, Igor Ivanov, and
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said Yeltsin had apparently given orders to his commanders
in Bosnia to prepare to move into Kosovo to take part in the
unfolding international peacekeeping operation there, even though
their specific role had not yet been agreed upon in talks between
American and Russian officials.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin left it to his generals to decide when and where to
deploy their troops, Cohen said. They did so late Friday evening,
to the surprise and consternation of NATO officials who were
planning the movement of their own troops into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the motivation was,'' Cohen said. ``It may
have been simply over-anxiousness on the part of military
commanders. It may have been some confusion in terms of what the
direction was.''
</P>
<P>
   To try to sort out the muddle, Vice President Al Gore spoke by
telephone for an hour Saturday morning with Sergei Stepashin, the
Russian prime minister, according to an aide to Gore. The aide said
both sides had agreed not to disclose details of the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is scheduled to speak to Yeltsin on Sunday,
White House officials said. In a late addition to a commencement
speech he was giving at the University of Chicago Saturday, the
president alluded to the need for cooperation, saying, ``We look
forward to working with Russia and others who may not have agreed
with our military campaign but do agree with the proposition that
all the people of that tiny land _ Serb and Albanian alike _ should
be able to live in peace and freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the presence of the Russian troops continued to bedevil
the start of the mission.
</P>
<P>
   American and Russian diplomats and generals were meeting
Saturday in Moscow and in Macedonia to try to clarify Russia's role
in the peacekeeping force. Moscow has so far balked at putting its
troops under direct NATO command, but allied officials insist that
there will be no exclusive Russian sector and no independent
Russian military command.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they will work out an acceptable arrangement whereby
we can have our strict requirements met,'' Cohen said, ``namely
that we have a unified command structure, that there is not a
separate sector as such that is only Russian, as has been
requested, that there must be NATO forces throughout the region and
NATO in every sector. And they will be under a unified command.''
</P>
<P>
   The province has been divided into five zones, with the United
States, France, Britain, Germany and Italy each controlling one
sector.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official said Moscow appeared to be
sending simultaneous and ambiguous signals to NATO, to the restive
Russian parliament and to the Serbian people.
</P>
<P>
   He said the uncertainty about Moscow's motives has cast at least
a temporary pall over the entry of American and European troops
into the shattered Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think our military people are all that worked up about
it,'' the official said. ``They don't like the idea they were lied
to by the Russians. But on the other hand, there's a lot going on
in the Russian government, so who the hell knows what they're up
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, administration officials said that security
surrounding the Russian force's deployment was good enough on
Friday to prevent American intelligence agencies from intercepting
any communications ordering the troops into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   American officials say they are not sure whether the order
moving the troops was issued by Russian senior commanders at the
last minute because they have no intercepts to study. It is
possible, they said, that the Russian order was issued earlier to
avoid interception by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say they do not believe that all the
Russian troops that are planned for deployment to Kosovo will come
from the contingent in Bosnia, but officials interviewed Saturday
morning could not say how many Russian troops are expected.
</P>
<P>
   The confusion over the timing and location of the deployment of
Russian troops in Kosovo arose from the unexpectedly abrupt end of
the NATO air war and the vague terms under which the conflict
ended. NATO and the Russians had not yet agreed on Moscow's role in
the peacekeeping operation or on the complex issues of command and
control of forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow might have been trying to settle some of those questions
pre-emptively by sending its troops to Pristina, an administration
official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know ultimately where the Russians will be,'' a
senior official here said. ``All the sectors will have
participation by a number of countries.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But this official emphasized that wherever the Russian forces
are stationed, they will be under NATO command, even if the
alliance has to devise some sort of fig leaf to disguise the fact
that Russian troops are reporting to a NATO officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a unified command structure, I can assure you,''
the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Another senior administration aide said the sense in Washington
Saturday was that the perplexing Russian move was at worst a
temporary hurdle at the outset of a long military and relief
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow never approved of the NATO bombing of Serbia, a
historical ally of Russia, and might feel the need to assert its
independence from the alliance for domestic political reasons and
to signal its sympathy to the Serbian populace, this official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not clear whether this is a stunt or something serious,''
the official said. ``But we're trying not to get distracted by
something that in the long run won't be important. We hope it's
just a blip.''
</P>
</TEXT>
