<SLUG> BC-BOAT-FOSSETT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF THERE'S A CHALLENGE, FOSSETT WILL BE UP TO IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ Steve Fossett can't understand why yacht racers
enjoy sailing America's Cup sloops. But show him a multihull with a
deck made of netting and a cockpit the size of a bathtub, and
you'll find a man with his sea boots on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sailing is a racing sport,'' the 55-year-old Fossett said
during a recent interview here. ``But in every other sport, a great
deal of attention is paid to who is the fastest. In most sailing,
how you do is based on handicap racing against other boats in other
classes, not on speed itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between buoy racing and speed exploits has drawn
Fossett into a five-year whirlwind of long-distance record
attempts. Going fast, after all, is what speed is all about _ 10
ocean records so far for Fossett. They include four Pacific Ocean
passages, on either single-handed or crewed voyages. Other records
are on traditional race courses such as the Chicago-Mackinac Race
along Lake Michigan. In 1998, he was first to finish there in 18
hours 50 minutes, a record.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Fossett set an astonishing standard for the
635-mile route from Newport to Bermuda. Sailing solo, he shaved 13
hours off the 53-hour time set in 1996 by Jean-Pierre Mouligne, the
French solo sailor.
</P>
<P>
   Fossett, who entered yachting in 1993 as a neophyte, is a quick
learner. His first victory was in the 1994 Round Britain Race, a
1,700-mile hair-raiser at sea aboard Lakota, the 60-foot trimaran
that Fossett used as his training wheels in boating.
</P>
<P>
   Fossett competed with David Scully, an around-the-world sailor
who finished fifth in the 1994-95 BOC Challenge yacht race around
the world. Scully, who was 10 years younger than Fossett, came to
the race with a younger body and more experience, but the same
inscrutable passion for speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wild,'' Fossett said. ``There was a lot of wind around
the British Isles. We were tearing sails, but did some fast sailing
_ up to 30 knots at times.''
</P>
<P>
   Fossett subsequently bought the three-hulled boat from Scully,
and has used it to cut his swath through long-distance sailing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know very much then,'' he said. ``I had sailed
recreational dinghies basically. But David Scully was teaching me
at the same time I was sailing for records. I associated with good
sailors who carried the ball for me early on. Now I like to sail
single-handed to let people know that I'm doing much of it
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   His boating accomplishments are impressive. But layer them with
a history of other offbeat exploits, and the result is multifaceted
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   He swam the English Channel in 22 hours in 1985, and finished
47th in the Iditarod dog-sled race in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   He has climbed the highest peaks in six of seven continents (he
has yet to reach the top of Mt. Everest) and competed in the
Paris-Dakar auto race and the 24 hours of Le Mans race, both in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, he competed in the Ironman in Hawaii, the
mother of all triathlons that includes a 2.4-mile swim, a 112-mile
bike ride, and a 26.2-mile marathon. And since 1994, he has set a
series of ballooning records, which included two unscheduled dumps
into open ocean. In one, Fossett's capsule dropped from an altitude
of 30,000 feet at a rate of about 1,500 feet per minute. He landed
in the Coral Sea off the northeast coast of Australia, shaken but
undaunted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Steve Fossett that fascinates me,'' said Bob
Rice, a meteorologist in Wolfeboro, N.H., who has guided Fossett's
ballooning and boating forays, ``is that he gets an idea and just
jumps right into it. He bought a balloon when he had no idea what
he was going to do with it. Then he went out and got a license and
flew it across the Atlantic. He has done the same thing with
boats.''
</P>
<P>
   Fossett is no obvious jock. He dresses conservatively, white
shirt and khakis at a recent interview, and with a receding
hairline and oval face, he looks more like a businessman than a
scruffy risk-taker. It is less surprising that he owns a successful
securities marketing company in Chicago than that he owns the
world's fastest sailboat. His new $4.5 million catamaran, the
105-foot Play Station, set a 24-hour speed record of 580 miles off
New Zealand in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things I do are things that a lot of people would like to
do,'' Fossett said. ``So I go out and take on an interesting
project, like driving a race car or swimming the English Channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's unusual is that I actually go out and do them.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
