<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HOUSTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON, THE SCORER, RISES TO THE OCCASION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky.)   (bl)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The game was glowing on the tube in the living room, but Alice
Houston was searching for things to tidy up in the basement of her
family's Louisville, Ky., home. Her son, Allan, was on the court
creating rainbows that splashed into the net, but she was scouring
the kitchen for another dish to wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on all three floors of the house,'' Alice Houston said
Saturday. ``I've been around this so long. My father was a coach.
Allan's father was a coach. They tease me because I've missed so
many great moments over the years, because I can't look. It's too
much.''
</P>
<P>
   But near midnight on the East Coast, Alice Houston crept into
the living room and stole a glance at the glorious finish of the
Knicks' victory in Game 6 against the Indiana Pacers, and the
moment when her son and his coach, Jeff Van Gundy, found each other
amid the mayhem and embraced beneath the pinwheel ceiling of
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they were going to the National Basketball Association
finals to meet the San Antonio Spurs. Together, they had made it
through a tumultuous season when Houston had to find his game next
to Latrell Sprewell and Van Gundy was nearly fired. The latter
might have taken place three weeks ago if Houston hadn't sent up a
spellbinding runner that kicked off the rim, kissed the backboard
and landed softly in the net to win the Knicks' first-round series
in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   And now, just maybe, Houston's 32-point effort in Game 6 Friday
night _ a game the Knicks played against Indiana without the
injured Larry Johnson for the last 30 minutes on the clock _ will
make it that much harder for the Garden president, Dave Checketts,
to nudge Van Gundy away.
</P>
<P>
   Unassuming by nature, Houston would never admit to any impact he
has had on Van Gundy's future. Team game. Team victories. That's
his response. But beneath that veneer, there is a player who
genuinely cares about his coach and understands the pressures he
has been under. His father, Wade Houston, went through a similar
situation when he was the coach at the University of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allan went through the rumors with his own father, and it was
hard for him,'' Alice said. ``Allan's close to Jeff, and his wife,
Kim, and the whole Van Gundy family. He knows how hard and draining
the job of coaching can be.''
</P>
<P>
   But as a coach's son, Houston has often looked to get his
teammates involved in the game before himself throughout the
playoffs. But not Friday night, not when circumstances demanded
that he assert himself as the dominant player. With six minutes
left in the second quarter, Johnson was found curled up on the
baseline of Madison Square Garden, writhing in pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think about when Larry went down,'' Houston said. ``I
just wanted to do what I could do the whole game, because if you
think about those things, you kind of put more pressure on
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   He played as carefree as a playground star. Whenever Indiana's
Reggie Miller tried to slap his spindly but prickly frame on him,
Houston simply faded away and lofted up a feathery jumper. Whenever
Miller attempted to cut him off, Houston ignored his presence and
barged to the basket. After beginning the night 2 for 6, Houston
finished 12 for 17 in an uncanny night of shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allan just carried us,'' center Chris Dudley said. ``He put us
on his back and carried us there for a while. He just came through
huge for us.''
</P>
<P>
   He came through just when the night looked bleak with the image
of Johnson being helped off the floor. He popped up as a star while
Latrell Sprewell was struggling to find his rhythm and played a
tireless 47 minutes that included a few cat-and-mouse chases with
Miller. After lurking in the background for most of the series,
Houston shed his wallflower status and became the life of the party
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something I've been waiting for all series from
Allan,'' said Chris Childs, who took over guarding Miller in the
fourth quarter to help Houston preserve his energy down the
stretch. ``Allan did it in the Miami game, and he did it in a game
in Atlanta. I talked to Allan's father after a couple of games and
I told his mother also, `He's got to shoot.' She even said: `Why
doesn't he just shoot? I mean, that's what he's there for.' Allan's
not here to lead us, he's here to score. I told his mother, `He's
got to be aggressive.' I mean, take nothing from Indiana, they're a
great team, but there's nobody in this league that can go on Allan
one-on-one. He has to believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, his laid-back demeanor conceals that belief. But it's
there, as quiet as an ember. It may not have hit him consciously,
but Johnson's injury seemed to stoke Houston into a shooting
exhibition that wowed everyone who watched.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like being a fan sitting there,'' Sprewell said.
``I was going on the weak side just watching him do his thing.
Every shot he was putting up, there was nothing but net.''
</P>
<P>
   About 2 a.m., Alice Houston had a chance to see it for herself.
Knowing the outcome, she put the tape in the v.c.r. and opened her
eyes to what her son _ and the entire Knicks team, she will remind
you _ had done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to Allan's wife, Tammy, and she said she knew it
was going to be a great June,'' Alice said.
</P>
<P>
   What could be more amazing than an NBA final series? A first
child. Tammy Houston is due any day now. Tammy's voice was the
first Alice heard from the site of the celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, just about five minutes after the game ended, I got
a call from Tammy, and she was still in her seats at the game,''
said Alice, who attended the road games during the Eastern
Conference finals. ``She was like, `Can you believe this?'''
</P>
<P>
   See it for yourself, Alice.
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   _ PATRICK EWING was in a suit, but he was still on the floor
with the rest of the team when the Game 6 buzzer went off. ``When I
got hurt, I told them to go get me my ring,'' Ewing said. ``We're
right there knocking on the door. All we have to do is kick it
open.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The end of Game 6, and the chance to play in the finals,
marked a memorable moment for in the year of LATRELL SPREWELL, who
watched last year's playoff from home because of his suspension.
``To be at the bottom of the barrel and somehow climb your way out
and have the type of success that I've personally had and we've had
as a team, it's just a blessing from God,'' he said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
