<SLUG> BC-CANADA-ROBBER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBBER TURNED WRITER SAID TO ROB AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ For much of his life, Stephen Reid, who in the 1970s
led the notorious ``Stopwatch Gang'' on scores of precisely timed
bank heists across the United States and Canada, walked as crooked
a line as can be.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after winning parole in 1987, Canada's noted
robber-turned-wordsmith stuck to the straight and narrow for a
dozen years _ redeemed, he liked to say, by the job of writing, by
marriage to one of Canada's foremost poets, and by love for their
two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   As modestly acclaimed author, teacher of creative writing,
organizer of literary festivals and technical adviser on crime
movies, he became a high-profile figure in British Columbia's
lively arts scene _ and living, breathing testimony to the
possibilities of rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My criminal career ended on the day I took up writing,'' the
mustachioed, soft-spoken 49-year-old ex-desperado liked to tell
interviewers.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, in what appears to have been a reversion to the
reckless ways of his past, Reid chucked aside the pen allegedly
once again to snatch up a pistol and a pump-action shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, after a botched bank robbery, a gun battle with
police in a tourist-filled park, and a six-hour armed standoff in
Victoria, he was arrested and charged with 10 criminal counts,
including armed robbery, hostage taking, and attempted murder. An
accomplice was also arrested.
</P>
<P>
   To Reid's loved ones and friends, it was a stunning and
inexplicable twist. ``He's obviously gone off the deep end to a
private hell,'' Susan Musgrave, his wife of 13 years and one of
Canada's most renowned poets, told the Vancouver Sun. ``He lived a
larger-than-life life, but we never expected this. . . . I am
completely in a state of shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Said fellow writer and friend Brian Brett: ``This is an odd,
strange, terrible tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Police, however, were far less appalled by Reid's apparent fall
from grace than by the violent episode that rattled British
Columbia's picturesque and famously peaceful harborside capital.
The drama marked the first shootout between police and suspects in
Victoria in at least two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just amazing no one was killed or hurt,'' said Constable
Michael Yeager, one of the officers who traded shots with the bank
robbers during a wild car-and-foot chase through Victoria's Beacon
Hill Park and residential streets just a few blocks from the
provincial Legislature. ``It had all the elements of a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were also elements of extraordinary luck for law
enforcement. By coincidence, police were en route to the Royal Bank
of Canada to handle a routine complaint about a panhandler just as
two masked men armed with pistols and long guns burst out the back
door and into a getaway car _ their robbery attempt thwarted by a
sudden approach of the patrol vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   As the robbers and a growing cavalcade of pursuers careened
through Beacon Hill Park, one of the robbers fired on police, the
shot shattering the windshield of a van whose driver escaped
injury.
</P>
<P>
   More shots were fired before the two men abandoned their vehicle
and fled on foot. One man, identified as Allan McCallum, 30, was
quickly apprehended while the other _ reportedly wearing a jacket
marked ``Police'' _ charged into a retirement home and bluffed his
way into the apartment of 64-year-old Catherine Toupalik.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was extremely polite, but obviously very scared,'' Toupalik
said. ``He said his life was over, but he had a wife and daughters
that he loved.''
</P>
<P>
   After a long standoff, Reid surrendered to police. He is being
held for psychiatric assessment pending a June 24 court hearing.
Police say the two men were armed with a .22 caliber pistol, a .357
magnum revolver, a pump shotgun, and bolt-action hunting rifle.
</P>
<P>
   Those who knew Reid, meanwhile, were left to wonder why it was
that he would apparently succumb to the call of his old ways.
``This comes as a brutal surprise,'' said William Deverell, a
novelist who lives near Victoria. ``In the dozen years I've known
him, he's been an exemplary character. He'd become a pillar of the
community, one of the most gentlemanly figures in all Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   Born and raised in northern Ontario, Reid was a bright student
who turned to drugs and petty crime at an early age, quitting 10th
grade to hitchhike west to British Columbia. He soon was involved
in serious felonies, showing a special penchant for banks. Caught
and convicted of robbery, he was sentenced to prison outside
Kingston, Ontario _ escaping in 1973, the first of three breaks
from high-security penitentiaries across Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next six years, he made criminal history.
</P>
<P>
   Reid and two cronies, Paddy Mitchell and Lionel Wright, teamed
up to form the Stopwatch Gang, a nickname invented by the press
after security cameras showed Reid wearing a stopwatch in bank hits
whose hallmark was split-second timing.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1970s, the gang is believed to have committed more
than a hundred armed robberies netting an estimated $11 million in
Canada and the United States, earning longtime spots on the FBI and
Royal Canadian Mounted Police most-wanted lists. The gang's most
successful holdup was a 1974 grab of gold bars worth $785,000 from
Ottawa's Uplands Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Although always heavily armed, the gang carried off its
robberies without violence, although Reid once shot himself in the
leg. Even today, the Stopwatch Gang boasts a loyal following among
aficionados of crime, with a Web site on which fans swap details of
gang history and lore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Stopwatch Gang may very well be the last of North
America's legendary bank-robbing gangs,'' wrote author Greg Weston
in a 1992 book on the bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Captured by the FBI in 1980, Reid served 38 months in the Marion
penitentiary in Illinois before being returned north under a
US-Canada prisoner exchange treaty. He escaped twice, committed
more robberies, and seemed to define ``incorrigible'' until he
turned his energies to writing his life story.
</P>
<P>
   The book that would eventually become the Canadian bestseller
``Jackrabbit Parole'' was read in manuscript by Musgrave, then a
writer-in-residence at Ontario's University of Waterloo.
</P>
<P>
   Musgrave, best known for her poetry but also a novelist and past
president of the Writers Union of Canada _ and a woman with an
acknowledged proclivity for dangerous men _ mailed Reid a literary
critique accompanied by a passionate love letter. The two were
married in a 1986 prison ceremony after which Musgrave flung her
garter on to the barbed wire coils surrounding the yard. Their
honeymoon was spent in a trailer on the compound.
</P>
<P>
   Reid was paroled from prison in 1987, and they settled into what
he would describe as a life of happy domesticity. He adopted her
daughter by an earlier relationship and they had another daughter
of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life now is Susan,'' he told the Toronto Star several years
ago. ``We lead quiet, work-filled lives. . . . I would never put
that at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid taught writing at a British Columbia college and to prison
inmates, rose to local prominence as an organizer of literary
festivals, and wrote book reviews for major Canadian newspapers and
magazines. In addition to serving as a technical adviser on several
movies, last year he performed a bit part _ as a bank guard _ in
the film ``Four Days,'' shot in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the robbers today are addicts or there is a lot of
violence,'' he told the London (Ontario) Free Press. ``We were an
old-fashioned gang. . . . We tried not to hurt people.''
</P>
<P>
   He also became a handyman, boasting of his renovations to the
home he shared with Musgrave and the two girls. Most recently, said
friends, he was building a family summer cottage in British
Columbia's Queen Charlotte Islands.
</P>
<P>
   But there were also signs that Reid missed his desperado past.
He spoke regularly to journalists, and in an interview in January
sounded almost wistful when recalling the ``exhilaration'' of
pulling off bank heists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next to being a rock star,'' he said, ``being a bank robber is
the most chaotic and fun ride you can take.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
