<HEADLINE>
A DISCREDITED PRESIDENT RETURNS TO MEXICO ON A VISIT  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Interrupting a four-year exile, former President
Carlos Salinas de Gortari visited Mexico on Saturday for the first
time since his tumultuous departure in 1995, when he left behind a
brother accused of murder, a country in economic crisis, and a
presidential legacy under seige.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas' return provoked scattered demonstrations, hundreds of
angry calls to radio talk shows, and accusations by political
opponents that the visit had been timed to influence Mexico's
presidential campaign for next spring's elections.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas told reporters he had returned for a two-day visit to
attend to his ailing father and to other family matters. But the
visit appeared to follow a carefully written political script.
</P>
<P>
   In television interviews and other encounters with the news
media that were choreographed hour by hour, Salinas defended his
presidency, which ran from 1988 to 1994, and especially his efforts
to modernize the Mexican economy. He also acknowledged mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pioneers,'' Salinas said. ``And pioneers often make
errors.''
</P>
<P>
   He especially lamented what he said was his failure to more
closely oversee his older brother, Raul, who amassed an illicit
fortune of at least $120 million during Salinas' presidency and who
was convicted last year of killing a political rival.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas has passed his exile in Ireland, with frequent visits to
Europe, Cuba and occasionally the United States. He arrived in
Mexico City Saturday morning on a private jet after a flight from
London via Nassau, he said, and intends to leave Mexico on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   His visit roiled political currents in Mexico that have already
been whipped up by an unprecedented public struggle for the
presidential nomination of the governing party, a growing
controversy over the finances of President Ernesto Zedillo's 1994
campaign, and a continuing investigation into a $65 billion banking
bailout.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo, who succeeded Salinas, kept on many senior officials
from the previous administration and continued with similar
policies. Yet Zedillo enjoys considerable popularity, and Salinas
is currently one of Mexico's most reviled figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ruined my lunch!'' shouted one enraged caller to TV Azteca
minutes after an interview with Salinas was broadcast live
nationwide. ``That man is not a true Mexican! How can he be allowed
to move around freely here?''
</P>
<P>
   Even in Mexico's political system _ where presidents are exalted
with king-like powers and then immediately blamed for all the
country's ills when they leave office _ Salinas' fall from grace
was one of the bitterest.
</P>
<P>
   This is so largely because Salinas brought broad and painful
changes to the Mexican economy, including the sale of state
industries that left millions of workers unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks after he left office on December 1, 1994, speculators
began to attack the peso, which had become overvalued and which
Zedillo was forced to devalue. That immediate crisis threw at least
500,000 Mexicans out of work and plunged banks and debtors into a
crisis that continues to a degree to this day.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, the police arrested Raul Salinas on murder
charges. The former president tried to defend his brother by
announcing a hunger strike, abandoned it days later, and after a
secret meeting with Zedillo flew to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, aides to Zedillo who spoke anonymously to reporters
said that Salinas had been forced into exile. Publicly, Zedillo and
Salinas have always denied that Salinas' departure was forced.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Zedillo repeated those denials Saturday in portraying
Salinas' return as a strictly personal decision by the
ex-president.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was absolutely nothing to prevent him from returning,''
an aide to Zedillo said. ``He's not been charged with any crime,
there's no lawsuit, no investigation. His absence until now has
been his own free choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Salinas' visit appeared carefully planned. A female secretary
called scores of foreign and Mexican reporters Saturday morning,
inviting them to what was portrayed as an intimate encounter with
the ex-president but turned out to news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carlos Salinas de Gortari would like to have coffee with you
this afternoon,'' she said, giving the address of Salinas'
colonial-style boyhood home along a cobbled street in the Coyoacan
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   As reporters gathered outside the home, Salinas was already
being interviewed live on TV Azteca, the first of several
television appearances Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In that interview, conducted by Sergio Sarmiento, Salinas said
that during his presidency he had no knowledge that his brother
Raul was systematically moving at least $120 million into foreign
bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see it is difficult for people to understand how a president
who was as well-informed as they thought I was could not have
known,'' Salinas said. ``But I was focused on aspects of Mexican
life that I considered important for the country's development.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes into the televised interview, TV Azteca's switchboard
lit up with incoming calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's such a controversial figure that when I was interviewing
him on television, irate telephone calls started coming in,''
Sarmiento said in an interview later. ``His visit is going to
arouse a political scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   Callers were so belligerent that several attacked Sarmiento, one
of Mexico's most admired broadcast journalists and newspaper
columnists, for his respectful treatment of Salinas, and the
interviewer himself felt obliged to defend the interview.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Salinas' Coyoacan home, several protesters appeared.
``Salinas Get Out! Criminal!'' read one placard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
