<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. 71 THROUGH MISSOURI MAKES YOUR JAVA JUMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can pull onto U.S. 71 at the town of International Falls,
Minn., on the Canadian border, point your car south, and about
1,600 miles later -- three reasonable days or two brutal ones --
you'll wind up in Baton Rouge, La., almost in sight of the Gulf of
Mexico. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At one time or other I have driven every bit of that road,
except possibly the hour or so between Texarkana, Texas, and
Shreveport, La. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of that travel was years ago, so I can't claim my
information is current. But if there is any bumpier stretch of U.S.
71 than the piece between Kansas City, Mo., and the turnoff toward
my cabin in the Osage hills, I wouldn't know where to look for it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Listen, I am no stranger to bumpy roads. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I have ridden on highways in Africa where the last maintenance
was done from the air, with explosives. Once, in Khartoum, Sudan, I
saw a Volkswagen stuck in a pothole so deep that only the top of
the windshield was visible. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I've been on back roads in Siberia, where melting permafrost
turns the surface to porridge, and peasants pray for the blessing
of a 70-degree-below cold snap to solidify the goo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   U.S. 71 is not as bad as those. Not yet, anyway. But if you have
to drive it, be prepared to do without any amenities or
indulgences. Extravagant luxuries such as, for instance, coffee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I was headed toward the cabin the other day, lulled and
half-hypnotized by the chattering vibration set up by the washboard
texture of the pavement, when suddenly I noticed that my coffee had
risen from the holder in the arm rest to nearly shoulder level. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just the coffee, that is. The cup itself had remained in place,
but the actual fluid had been propelled upward by the bouncing, and
hung suspended there for a moment -- still in the shape of the cup
-- before gravity had its way. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some fell on me. But some, enough to be worth saving, fell back
into the cup. So I lifted the cup from the holder, determined to
hold it until the drink was finished. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had I taken it in hand than the bouncing began again.
At first, there were only little droplets arcing up singly above
the rim of the cup. Then all the rest -- or what was left of it --
shot out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, these several circulations through the air had
cooled my coffee to a point where it was useless even to consider a
lawsuit against the convenience store where I'd bought it, the
contractor who built the highway or the manufacturer of the car I
was driving. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So there I was -- mad as hops, wet to the hide, with nothing to
drink and nobody to sue, undone by the product (as the signs say)
of my highway dollars and yours at work. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are, I suppose, a good many ways to get from International
Falls to Baton Rouge. For example, one could get on Interstate 94
south of International Falls and head west to Butte, Mont., then
Interstate 15 south to San Bernardino, Calif., where you'd pick up
Interstate 10 and stay on it all the way across California,
Arizona, New Mexico and Texas, right straight into Baton Rouge. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You could drink coffee any time it pleased you, save a lot on
your laundry bill, and never once have to lay a tire on U.S. 71. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However, to get to my cabin in anything like reasonable time you
about have to go at least part of the way on U.S. 71. Every trip's
a trial. But just when I've about decided to give up and sell the
place, I come to my turnoff to the east. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Right there at the junction there's a restaurant with good
coffee to go. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From that point on, the traffic is light. The state road is
asphalt, laid by people who knew what they were doing. And those
last 27 miles are like riding on air. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
