u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-SALINAS-0613-C     06-12 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-SALINAS-0613-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DISGRACED EX-PRESIDENT SALINAS RETURNS BRIEFLY TO MEXICO FROM
SELF-EXILE
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Carlos Salinas de Gortari, one of the most
despised ex-presidents in Mexican history, returned here Saturday
for a one-day visit for the first time since he went into
self-exile in Ireland four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas was once hailed as a free-market reformer and
Harvard-educated golden boy who would lead Mexico into new
prosperity after he took office in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   But after he left office in 1994 the Mexican peso was devalued
-- a devastating economic blow -- and revelations of alleged links
between his brother, Raul, and drug cartels began to trickle out.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas' legacy took a 180-degree turn and he is now widely
blamed for reckless policies that worsened poverty, and for
allowing drug traffickers to infiltrate the highest circles of
power in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   At a Saturday press conference Salinas, 51, downplayed his
administration's responsibility for Mexico's economic woes. He said
he had been ``reflecting'' on his administration and that an
``objective evaluation'' could reveal his good and bad policies.
</P>
<P>
   But he suggested that he was the victim of a smear campaign that
had incited hatred toward him.
</P>
<P>
   ``After four years of a tenacious campaign with distorted facts
. . . and a smoke-screen over the deeds that occurred when I was
carrying out my responsibilities as president,'' Salinas said,
``who couldn't understand that kind of manifestation (of hatred)?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I also recognize the difficulties that the Mexican family has
lived through,'' Salinas added in a contrite manner.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he could identify who was leading the campaign against
him, Salinas suggested the press would probably know more than he.
</P>
<P>
   During the conference, Salinas didn't forcefully defend his
brother, Raul, from allegations that he accepted $500 million in
bribes to protect drug traffickers. Swiss authorities say $114
million is in Swiss and British bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas said he had no knowledge of the funds, but suggested
that the allegations raise questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say that my brother's behavior hurt me and hurt
Mexicans. I think it requires a clear, precise explanation,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas vigorously defended Raul on other charges, however.
</P>
<P>
   Raul, who Salinas said he spoke to Saturday, is serving a
50-year sentence in Mexico for ordering the 1994 murder of Jose
Francisco Ruiz Massieu, the Salinas' ex-brother-in-law and former
secretary general of the Revolutionary Institutional Party (PRI).
</P>
<P>
   Salinas told reporters he thought Raul -- who is appealing his
sentence -- was wrongfully convicted on hearsay and testimony by
paid witnesses and witnesses who received reduced sentences in
exchange for testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas also bristled when reporters asked him about drug
traffickers who have implicated him in smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many years later there are those who remember things thanks to
reduced sentences offered to them. They don't deserve to be
considered credible,'' Salinas said. ``My administration acted with
full severity'' against traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas said he returned to Mexico for personal reasons, mostly
to visit his ailing father and attend his son's university
graduation.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived in Mexico Saturday on a private airplane via London
and Nassau.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas said he planned to leave early Sunday to return to
Europe. He said he didn't know when he'd return again, but said
Mexico ``will always be my permanent residence.''
</P>
<P>
   During the press conference with Mexican and foreign reporters,
protesters gathered outside a Salinas family compound in Mexico
City's exclusive Coyoacan neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Jesusa Rodriguez, a Mexico City actress, said, ``I think Salinas
is a psychopath'' who represents ``the face of impunity in our
country.''
</P>
<P>
   During the press conference, photographers climbed over a fence
to get a glimpse of the ex-president as he spoke on a porch.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in an impeccable blue suit, Salinas waved and smiled and
said, ``Let them pass.''
</P>
<P>
   When Salinas was asked to comment on Mexico's upcoming
presidential race, he stuck to the long tradition of ``no comment''
from Mexican ex-presidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not participate nor comment on anything to do with the
electoral process,'' Salinas said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
