<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURDERS-DECADE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEN YEARS LATER, FATES OF MURDERER'S THREE VICTIMS REMAIN A
MYSTERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY RIZZO  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Theresa Brown. Joan Butler. Christine Rusch.
</P>
<P>
   It was 10 years ago this month that the three young Johnson
County, Kan., women vanished, never to be seen or heard from again.
</P>
<P>
   The secret of their fates remains locked away in a Kansas prison
cell, along with the man who has kept it to himself for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   His prediction to police, ``You'll dig them up,'' remains
unfulfilled.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of bodies, Richard Grissom Jr. was convicted of
murdering all three. His first chance at parole will be in 2071,
when he would be 110 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Each family continues to remember their daughters in their own
way, but the hope they have shared of finding their bodies has been
tempered with the realization that they probably never will.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, some members of the families would even prefer
that they're not found.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like a long time ago, yet the memories you have of
your daughter are pretty vivid,'' said Christine's father, David
Rusch. ``Sometimes not knowing everything is better than knowing.''
</P>
<P>
   For the dozens of police officers and prosecutors who caught and
convicted Grissom, it remains their biggest case, and the biggest
mystery of their careers. To a person, finding the women's bodies
remains a consuming quest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody involved in that case is ever going to
give up until those bodies are found,'' said Johnson County
District Attorney Paul Morrison.
</P>
<P>
   Overland Park Police Detective Bill Batt estimates that he has
spent 5,000 hours on the case. He still fields about two calls a
month concerning the whereabouts of the women.
</P>
<P>
   He and other detectives have checked countless cases of human
remains found throughout Kansas and Missouri and as far away as
California and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought we would find them someday,'' Batt said.
``For me, it's not over yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Lenexa Police Sgt. Pat Hinkle, who with Batt was one of the lead
detectives in the case, says he thinks Grissom keeps the secret as
a way to maintain a sense of power and control.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has that one last card to hold,'' Hinkle said. ``The
families of these three victims deserve better. They deserve an
opportunity to bury their loved ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Butler says he won't celebrate Father's Day this year. On
that day in 1989 he was looking forward to a phone call from his
oldest daughter, Joan Marie. It was a call that never came.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess my luck's running out, Dad,'' she told him in their
last conversation on June 11, 1989. She had been in a car wreck.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Butler was 24. She lived alone in Overland Park and was a
buyer at a Kansas City advertising agency.
</P>
<P>
   On June 18 she disappeared. The $900 in her bank account was
withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   On June 26, Lenexa roommates Theresa Brown and Christine Rusch
vanished. They were both 22, born on the same day. Money was
withdrawn from their bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In what would become the biggest investigation-manhunt ever
mounted in Johnson County, Grissom, a 28-year-old parolee, emerged
as the prime suspect.
</P>
<P>
   He was almost arrested the night before Brown and Rusch
disappeared. A police officer stopped him in the parking lot of a
Lawrence apartment complex as he opened the trunk of Butler's
rental car.
</P>
<P>
   But Grissom bolted and escaped. A friend later testified that he
gave Grissom a ride from Lawrence that night and last saw him at a
motel about half a mile from the complex where Brown and Rusch
lived.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Grissom's car, packed with his belongings, was
found parked outside a Grandview apartment after a maintenance man
saw him lurking under a stairwell.
</P>
<P>
   The manhunt ended July 7, when detectives and FBI agents
arrested Grissom at the airport in Dallas. But the investigation
was only beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives spent thousands of man-hours collecting mountains of
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most haunting item uncovered in the investigation
was a security camera photograph of Rusch standing in front of an
automatic teller machine on the night of June 26.
</P>
<P>
   Oversized sunglasses cover her eyes, but what appears to be a
large bruise is visible on her forehead.
</P>
<P>
   It is the last photograph of any of the women.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives also learned that Grissom had killed before.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 16, he beat and fatally stabbed an elderly neighbor
woman near his family's home in Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   Court records are sealed because he was a juvenile, but two
years later he was on parole.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison said the case was a good example of why people mistrust
the legal system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had all the earmarks of somebody who is extremely
disturbed,'' Morrison said. ``If the system had worked right, four
young women would be alive today.''
</P>
<P>
   The fourth woman Morrison referred to is Terri Maness. She was
found dead in her Wichita apartment 11 days before Butler
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Like the woman in Lansing, her body was mutilated after she was
dead. Wichita detectives joined their colleagues from Lenexa and
Overland Park in the Grissom investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Although Grissom was named as a suspect in the Maness killing,
charges have never been filed.
</P>
<P>
   Grissom's trial in October 1990 was the biggest Johnson County
has ever seen. About 600 people were summoned for jury duty. Jurors
were sequestered for more than two weeks of testimony. It is
thought to be the only time a Johnson County jury has been
sequestered.
</P>
<P>
   Spectators waited for hours in long lines for a seat to open up
in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers Kevin Moriarty and Tom Erker were appointed to represent
Grissom. They received threats at their homes and office. The rest
of their law practice came to a halt for the 3 1/2 months they had
to prepare Grissom's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most labor-intensive and emotionally and
psychologically taxing case I've ever worked on,'' Erker said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors called more than 100 witnesses and linked Grissom to
Butler's rental car through fingerprints. A drop of her blood was
found in the car's trunk, and Grissom's wallet was found inside.
</P>
<P>
   Credit cards and jewelry belonging to Rusch and Brown were found
in Grissom's abandoned car, along with keys to the apartments of
the roommates and Butler.
</P>
<P>
   Grissom operated a painting company and had master keys to
apartment complexes across the area.
</P>
<P>
   A young woman who lived in a Kansas City apartment described her
escape from an attacker who tried to abduct her a week before
Butler vanished. The attacker drove a car like Grissom's, and
Grissom had keys to that complex as well.
</P>
<P>
   The jury deliberated for 12 hours before finding Grissom guilty
of 11 felonies, including murder and kidnapping. District Judge
William Gray sentenced him to four consecutive life sentences plus
an additional 90 to 360 years.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Grissom is at the El Dorado Correctional Work Facility.
He gets out of his cell one hour a day, five days a week, for a
shower and recreation. The rest of the time he is locked down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he lives to be very, very old so he has a lot of years
to suffer and think about what he's done,'' Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   On Father's Day, Ralph Butler will go to Mass and say a rosary
for his daughter. It is an almost daily ritual he started when she
first disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started, I was hoping that she would be found,'' he
said. ``Now I hope that she's in heaven and God is giving her soul
rest and peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The Butlers, who live in Wichita, don't see the other families
very often.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns and Ruschs, who live in the Kansas City, Mo., area,
still get together once a year on the birthday their daughters
shared _ Oct. 12.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns have donated money to their church in Belton, Mo.,
for an outside prayer garden in memory of Theresa. They also have a
Mass said on the anniversary date of her disappearance every year.
</P>
<P>
   The Ruschs use money from an insurance settlement to make a
charitable donation in Christine's name every year.
</P>
<P>
   None of them thinks Grissom will reveal the truth, and none of
them has any interest in asking him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't give (him) ... the time of day,'' said Theresa's
father, Harold Brown. ``I wouldn't give him the satisfaction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
