<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3134 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHARTER-SCHOOLS-KAN &LR;      06-12 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARTER-SCHOOLS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THEIR INAUGURAL YEAR, MUCH RIDES ON SUCCESS OF KC CHARTER
SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Kansas City's new charter schools experiment
is among the more aggressive in the nation. That has parents and
educators both excited and worried. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This summer and fall, 15 of the independently operated schools
will open in the city. According to the Center for Education
Reform, a nonprofit group that advocates school choice, no other
district in the country has opened that many schools so soon after
they were authorized by state law. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the plunge into charter schools comes with questions: Are
too many of the schools opening too fast? Is the new law too
loosely written? Does the law lack proper safeguards for students
and the state money the schools will spend? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Education Commissioner Robert Bartman sent letters last
week to the charter school sponsors encouraging caution. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``With the academic success and physical safety of students as
its top priority, the state board asks that you encourage schools
that are not completely ready to receive students to delay opening
until the 2000-2001 school year,'' Bartman wrote. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charter schools typically receive the same amount of state money
per student as any public school but are free of a district's
central office and much of the state's regulatory control. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By law, the schools must operate under a contract with a
sponsor, be able to measure student achievement and be responsible
for the school's finances. In exchange, they are free from
traditional school rules and regulations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bartman said he and the state Board of Education were worried
that some of the new charter schools would fail. With less than
three months to go before classes start, several schools have yet
to identify a site or hire a staff. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Families and kids have to know that once they sign up for a
particular charter there's going to be a program for them that
lasts at least one year,'' Bartman said. ``Obviously the schools
which are just getting into business, there's no guarantee.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bartman wondered whether charter sponsors could oversee both the
academics and finances of charter schools. State law excludes the
Department of Education from conducting such oversight. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bartman said the charter sponsors -- Central Missouri State
University, the University of Missouri-Kansas City and the Kansas
City School District -- have limited ability to check school
performances. Some sponsors, he said, seem reluctant to hire the
people it would take to monitor the schools. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``At least the public schools have local boards of education
that can be held responsible,'' Bartman said. ``My concern is that
the law was written to clearly leave out the establishment from
oversight of these charters. We think there are some holes in the
laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Thomas, a CMSU professor and chairman of the school's
charter oversight committee, agreed that the law is vague on
charter school supervision. For example, sponsors are not required
to review a school's academic performance until the end of the
second year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If no one is paying attention, these schools could fall flat
on their faces,'' Thomas said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He also agreed that some sponsors are reluctant to hire more
administrators, saying it would create the very bureaucracies they
are seeking to avoid, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas expects that, to ensure the schools' success, sponsors
will work closer with the schools than state law requires. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is these are schools of choice,'' Thomas said.
``If they're not performing, parents won't put their children in
them.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Oliver, dean of UMKC's School of Education, was
unavailable for comment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other charter proponents contend Bartman overstates the
problems. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Judy Akers is associate director of the Della Lamb Center, which
will operate an elementary charter school. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She said charter schools must follow state accounting
procedures. And they must routinely produce attendance records to
receive state funding. She said the schools will also face
tremendous internal pressure to show academic results. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The charter is a legal binding document,'' she said. ``If we
don't show accountability, we're subject to losing the very tool
that allows us to exist.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first charter school opened in 1992 in St. Paul, Minn. As of
April, more than 1,205 operating charters were serving 300,000
students in 36 states and the District of Columbia, according to
the Center for Education Reform. The schools cannot charge tuition,
must observe all federal anti-discrimination laws and meet health,
safety and accessibility regulations. All students must have an
equal opportunity to attend. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dave DeSchryver, a policy analyst for the Center for Education
Reform, agreed that if Kansas City opened a lot of charter schools,
it could lead to problems. But a recent report by the center showed
that less than 3 percent of all charter schools that opened before
January closed for poor performance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DeSchryver also said Kansas City will benefit from the
experience of other charters across the country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big number,'' DeSchryver said, ``but it's not
unmanageable.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The impact of charters divides Kansas City School District
officials. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Board member Sandy Mayer sees them as the district's salvation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the charter movement as comparable to deregulation,''
Mayer said. ``All the monopolies have broken up. Education is the
last to go. We're seeing a consumer-driven society affecting the
public school system.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mayer said charter schools will speed up district reforms for
greater accountability among students, teachers and
administrators. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``All kids will benefit once the district starts changing,
transforming and competing,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet others worry that the charters could drain students from the
district and steal its top students and most involved parents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charter school officials said they were being swamped with
applications. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 9,000 students, or a fourth of the district's enrollment,
already have enrolled in charter schools. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not all charter students will come from district schools. Alta
Vista and Genesis, for example, already operate as alternative
schools and won't draw students from the district. And most expect
the free education in charter schools to lure private school
students. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Zsa Zsa Addison, office manager at Hogan Preparatory Academy,
said students from Catholic grade schools and other area high
schools were flocking to the new charter program. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We are like full,'' Addison said. The school has room for 250
students. ``The only spots we have left is for seniors.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   District officials say the uncertainty of how many district
students attend charters and how much money the district will lose
as a result makes it difficult to plan and budget. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be an interesting experiment,'' Bartman said.
``We've got to hope for the best because we've got kids involved in
this thing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
