<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-IOWA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH LAUNCHES CAMPAIGN IN IOWA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMANA, Iowa _ So far, so good for Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Trailed by 200 reporters, Bush formally launched his
presidential bid Saturday with an energetic defense of his
``compassionate conservative'' philosophy and a bold proclamation
that suggested the hype surrounding his candidacy was justified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to be the next president of the United States,'' Bush
said early in his speech inside a farm building. ``There's no
turning back.''
</P>
<P>
   Underlying Bush's maiden campaign trip was the question of how
he would respond to the media frenzy surrounding him. And Bush,
though his blue dress shirt became soaked with sweat during his
25-minute speech, appeared to make a favorable impression and
avoided committing any gaffes.
</P>
<P>
   Commentators generally praised the address, and the crowd
responded warmly, interrupting the governor frequently with
applause. Several audience members said afterward that Bush not
only met expectations, but also exceeded them.
</P>
<P>
   Although the speech lacked specifics and was delivered with a
sometimes clunky style, Republicans said they appreciated Bush's
energy and seeming sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was great,'' said Mark Erceg of Iowa City, who
decided to back Bush after hearing him speak. ``He did a nice job
of connecting with the average voter.''
</P>
<P>
   Marge Ziskovsky of Toledo, Iowa, agreed: ``I liked his emphasis
on compassion and wanting something better for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the trick for Bush will be to continue to show Iowans and
the rest of the nation that he's not merely riding into the Oval
Office on the wings of his famous name or on the passionate desire
among many Republicans to finally back a winner, no matter who that
candidate is.
</P>
<P>
   The going could get tougher. Last week, Bush's fellow
Republicans began taking shots at him, questioning his credentials
and emphasizing the untested nature of his candidacy. He is, some
say, merely a one-term governor riding the wave of a good economy.
Others equate him to a soap bubble yet to pop.
</P>
<P>
   There's something to that, suggested Peverill Squire, a
University of Iowa political scientist.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, it's inevitable that some people are going to
feel disappointed by some positions he's taken,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But whether Bush ever will feel pressure to get more specific is
an open question, Squire added. He is so far ahead that he may be
inclined to coast and not risk alienating potential backers.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of rivals, Elizabeth Dole and Lamar Alexander, did their
best Saturday to push Bush. They stressed the fact that Bush has
not taken firm stands on many issues.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, the former transportation secretary, unveiled a detailed,
10-point farm program aimed at contrasting herself with Bush's
nonspecific rhetoric. In a speech, Dole emphasized her support for
ethanol-blended fuels, a popular issue in Iowa because ethanol is
distilled from corn and offers a new market for farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has yet to take a stand and, as an oil-state governor, will
be hard-pressed to offer similar support.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander dispatched a top aide, Brian Kennedy, to the event. He
termed Bush's speech a ``solid performance,'' but knocked the
governor for being vague.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to have to be more specific than that,'' Kennedy
said.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the crowd dismissed the concern, saying it is still
early in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush began his first trip to Iowa with a quick stop in Cedar
Rapids before moving on to the Amana Colonies for a $30-a-head
fund-raiser for Rep. Jim Nussle. Then he was off to Des Moines and,
late Saturday, to New Hampshire, the state that has the first
primary.
</P>
<P>
   In Amana, the $30 bought Republicans a pork chop dinner. As they
ate, many seemed amused by the dozens of reporters fluttering
around the building waiting for Bush to arrive. Flash bulbs popped
when Cokie Roberts of ABC News entered the room.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush did not address farm policy, his speech was
delivered in an agricultural setting. The makeshift stage was
surrounded by bales of hay. On stage right was a gleaming red
tractor hoisting still another bale.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech full of sound bites, the governor emphasized his
intent to knock down trade barriers, strengthen Social Security and
cut taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that after we meet priorities, if we have money left
over it must be passed back to taxpayers so it is not spent in
Washington, D.C.,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He drew some of his most sustained applause when he said he
would not make decisions based on polls, a direct jab at the
current administration, which has been criticized for doing
precisely that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be a president who sets a tone, a direction and an
agenda,'' he said. ``I will be an activist president who sets goals
worthy of a great nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would emphasize the need to teach children proper
values and the difference between good choices and wrong choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message must be loud and clear: It is not the definition
of a man to father a child out of wedlock and say, `They're not my
problem, they're yours,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He offered a stalwart defense of his ``compassionate
conservative'' approach to government, which critics have derided
as ambiguous and code language for a liberal style of governing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this approach has been criticized, but why?'' Bush
said. ``Is compassion beneath us? Should our party be led by
someone who boasts of a hard heart?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
