<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3136 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPUBS-IOWA-NYT &LR;      06-12 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-IOWA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH RIVALS TACKLE HOG-SIZED PROBLEMS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1995 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Iowans demonstrated their passion for
candidates on the hoof Saturday, vying at the Pork Expo auction for
prize swine like Red Ace and Duncan, then gathering across the
state fairgrounds to amiably hear three Republican presidential
contenders try to buck the media whirlwind of Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush touched down with great fanfare in the state and in the
presidential nomination race, one of his rivals, former Gov. Lamar
Alexander of Tennessee, quickly criticized him, asking why Bush was
laying out broad campaign themes to the east in Cedar Rapids when
he could have been here tackling the deepening problems of hog
farmers face to face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of using slogans in another city he could be at the
Pork Expo at the fairgrounds saying exactly what we have to do to
open markets up,'' Alexander declared. His campaign aides searched
among a mere trickle of media representatives so that he might get
a piece of a political day dominated by Bush's arrival and maiden
speech before a traveling press corps of more than 100
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The odd psychological effect here at the fairgrounds, where pigs
squealed and farm families leisurely snacked amid clouds of
barbecue smoke, was of an offering of thoughtful political speeches
by a gathering of instant presumed also-rans, a feeling that
annoyed some listeners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't exactly know why he gets this big buildup,'' Linda
Hicks, a housewife from nearby Clive said of Bush's being favored
by waves of organizational Republicans and of his prodigious lead
on the pack in preliminary opinion polls. ``His name, I guess, and
he has enough money to talk with people who have the big campaign
money,'' she said. ``I'm thinking of working for Alexander,'' she
added in the typical spirit of Iowans who like competitiveness in
their caucus season, which culminates in precinct preference voting
next February.
</P>
<P>
   Two other candidates who addressed the Pork Expo fairgoers,
Elizabeth Dole, former Red Cross president, and Rep. John R. Kasich
of Ohio, chose to take the day's focus on Bush in stride and speak
in detail of their farm proposals. Alexander, who has been running
for five years, also offered a list of ideas to help pig farmers.
But he took care to draw a political bead on Bush as the
beneficiary more of hyperbole, he complained, than of hard work
among the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too important to be inherited,'' he said of the
nomination in an allusion to former President George Bush, the
governor's father. ``It ought to be earned,'' he told an audience
of more than 200 people. ``I am here today and not somewhere else
in order to earn it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole, who brandished the most detailed program of all for
her highly knowledgeable audience, drew repeated applause as she
praised American farmers and sympathized with their problems in the
global market. In a demonstration of political adaptability, she
said the new peace in Kososvo should be used as an opportunity for
American farmers to sell exports to ``people in the mountains and
the forests who desperately need food.''
</P>
<P>
   All three Republicans stressed the need for more open marketing
information for farmers anxious about falling prices, for an end to
farm inheritance taxes, and, above all, for a rapid expansion of
free world trade as the salvation of American agriculture. They
criticized China only sparingly in the areas of human rights abuses
and nuclear espionage charges, calling for acceptance of Beijing in
the World Trade Organization to open its markets to American
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's do it quickly,'' said Mrs. Dole, adding that at the same
time ``we can be very, very tough on the human rights front.''
</P>
<P>
   The fairgrounds, with prize boars promenading for the auctioneer
just down the trail from the importuning candidates, presented an
early tableau of summer Americana. Listeners slaked their thirst
with fresh lemonade in the sweltering sunshine, while entire
families wielded big grilled pork chops for lunch in the
grandstand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen so much pork since the highway bill passed in
Congress a year ago,'' Kasich of Ohio began his stump speech,
surveying a vast campus devoted to the products, achievements and
problems of America's hog farmers.
</P>
<P>
   There were computerized high-tech management programs (``Swine
Finish'') and giant mechanical paraphernalia resembling space
rocket vents used in the odoriferous hog megafarms that have been
eliminating Iowa's traditional family homesteads. There was also
the ``PigCasso'' show over in the art tent where the lucrative
creature groomed for the abattoir was sentimentally
anthropomorphized after the styles of Modigliani, Grant Wood, and
even George Grosz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of a populist at heart,'' said Kasich as he spoke
emotionally of the family farm as the repository of moral values
that ``need to transcend time.'' ``Those old fashioned God-fearing
values that dominate the small town in rural America,'' he said,
matching his rivals in their bucolic enthusiasms. All three paid
homage to two Iowan political icons _ ethanol, the subsidized
automobile fuel produced here from corn, and the state's senior
senator, Charles E. Grassley. He listened in blue jeans off to the
side and kept his counsel about whom he might eventually endorse.
</P>
<P>
   Grassley did not fault Bush for not using the Pork Expo as a
campaign stop, saying that in multiple campaign visits across the
year he expected Bush and his rivals must all offer detailed farm
programs in order to be taken seriously in the caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three candidates stumping the Pork Expo, only Alexander,
who party professionals say needs a strong early showing to
continue beyond Iowa, allowed his frustration to show at the
pre-emption of so much early attention by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give him credit for winning the pre-season,'' he said. ``His
strategy is to make sure that the contest never gets to the
people,'' Alexander contended. ``Mine is to make sure it does.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasich gently observed of Bush, ``A guy so far ahead in the race
doesn't need my advice.'' Then he turned back to listening to a hog
farmer.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole hurried from the Pork Expo to her next stop, beaming,
``I'm just enjoying my day in Iowa.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
