<SLUG> BC-FOOD-FESTIVAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMOUS FOR ITS FESCUE, TOWN ALSO HAS A FESTIVAL WITH A FUNNY NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLEAN, Mo. -- What did Missourians do last weekend? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom might be that Show-Me residents,
seemingly in lockstep, mowed yards, attended baseball games, fired
up the barbecue and hauled large boats to lakes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But they also went to fishing tournaments (Maryville); rodeos
(Tarkio and Kennett); quilt shows (Kirksville and Carrollton);
homecomings (Lee's Summit and Union were among several);
wool-growing exhibitions (Butler); dart tournaments (Noel);
concerts (Weston, Columbia, Independence); and horse shows, craft
gatherings, 10K runs and even chautauquas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, they attended festivals, those oversized block
parties that little towns throw and that feature food, soft drinks,
beer, games, booths and music -- usually loud. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That latter category fit Olean, population 106 and renowned,
Monday through Friday, for the processing of millions of pounds of
high-quality fescue grass seed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A week ago Saturday, Olean's numbers jumped to 6,000 as throngs
of people jammed this village for its festival. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Main Street was wall-to-wall crowds; the local watering hole,
The Hut, was packed; Zeravica Park was teeming, and there were
enough motorcycles to make Olean resemble Sturgis, S.D., the
legendary rendezvous for Harley-Davidson bikers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was also the smell of cooking -- which organizers freely
admitted was aimed at snagging as many visitors as possible. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the deep fryers were turkey fries and bull fries -- what some
call mountain oysters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In short, the main course here was that part of poultry and
livestock rarely mentioned but which some find -- golden brown and
heaped in a red- checkered cardboard basket -- a culinary
delicacy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, some came just to say they've been to Olean's
festival, one whose official name adorned caps, T-shirts, beverage
cups and more. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And suffice to say that the anatomical word preceding
``festival'' almost rhymes with it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Allen Groves came up with the name. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea was to grab people's attention, hit 'em right
between the eyes,'' he said. ``With a corny name -- you know, peach
or strawberry or ones like those -- people are going to go ho-hum
and forget it,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our festival you can't forget. People see the name and they
tell themselves, `I got to go and see what's going on.' '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Groves said the festival's name had drawn one or two letters in
the newspaper in nearby Eldon. No problem, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't heard a single complaint around here,'' he said.
``But then, we're not politically correct out here yet.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But they are charitable. Sponsored by the Olean Jaycees, the
festival raised in excess of $14,000 for Camp Wonderland for
disabled children; Mission Inn, a group of 13 residences around the
country for kids with AIDS; and Access Day at the Missouri State
Fair, which gives disabled people a chance to go to the Sedalia
event in August. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our sixth year,'' said Dave Gooch, president of the
Jaycees. ``That first year people thought we'd lost our minds. Part
of it was what we were offering as food. Who'd drive out to the
middle of Missouri for that? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``But Olean's perfect. Small. Good people. Traffic's not really
a problem, although parking close in can be a bear.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gooch is the first to admit there's absolutely nothing profound
about Olean's festival. But then that's the whole point, he said.
That and helping kids and the disabled. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing could get a whole lot bigger,'' he said. ``We could
get a pasture outside town, mow it, and I'll bet we could bring in
$100,000. But that's way in the future. Right now we're just having
a good time with people who want to kick back, come to a small town
and have some fun.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While a tiny and random sample of those attending said they'd
heard about the festival through fliers or word of mouth, a few
told Gooch they'd seen Olean listed on the Missouri Division of
Tourism Web site, www.missouritourism.org. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be frank. When Olean's listing came in, we had a little
meeting about it,'' said Marta Newman, who works for the division
and runs the site. ``You know, the name. But then, it was a
festival and it does draw a lot of people. So we listed it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The division's Web pages currently are getting about 500,000
hits a month. And while that number sounds impressive, said Newman,
a more revealing figure is that a tenth of those _ roughly 50,000
people a month _ are spending from three to five minutes visiting
various parts of the site. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the ones who are really interested,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The site, added Newman, offers Missouri an opportunity to cut
the spending for making and mailing high-cost, four-color printed
brochures and ads. Plus, she said, it may mean that spur-of-the
moment travelers with access to the Internet can just head out to a
rodeo in Tarkio, a concert in Columbia, even a dart tournament in
Noel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking at our site today,'' Newman said. ``There's
something going on in Kansas City to do with alligators. Well,
maybe somebody in eastern Missouri is really into alligators. It
probably won't be in their local paper. But we'll have it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even in little Olean, hardly a familiar place name to most
Missourians. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aileen Bishop, 77, also known hereabouts as ``Mrs. B.,'' sat on
her front porch on Olean's main drag and watched and listened as
the big Harleys passed by with their distinctive rumble. Time was,
she said, when not so long ago the road into Olean was just
gravel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a busy place then,'' she said, recalling there was a
barbershop, a truck line, a hatchery, a restaurant, a bank, an Odd
Fellows lodge, a milling company, a gas station, a garage, a
mercantile, a post office, several grocers, a lumberyard,
stockyards, and a high school and a grade school. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Now all that's left is a post office and a restaurant,'' she
said. ``The schools? Oh, they closed years ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. B was asked about the name of the festival. She said it
didn't faze her a whit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what they call it. Doesn't matter. What does
matter is that this town comes back to life, even if for only a
day.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
