<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3138 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH13-COX     06-12 1542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush mBy Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMANA, Iowa _ The trip had been billed as ``exploratory,'' but
at a barbecue lunch fund-raiser for an Iowa congressman, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush on Saturday made official what everybody has known
for months: He wants to move to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come here today to tell you this: I'm running for
president of the United States,'' he told a crowd of several
hundred cheering people gathered for a fund-raiser for Rep. Jim
Nussle at a historic German community called the Amana Colonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no turning back _ and I intend to be the next
president of the United States,'' Bush said in a surprise
announcement on the same day that his father turned 75.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's head-first entry into the White House race marked a
decided change in strategy in recent weeks. In mid-May, Karl Rove,
Bush's top political adviser, said the governor was planning to
assume a tone of ``I'm exploring it'' during this first foray. This
trip, Rove said last month, was to be ``an introductory thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's Saturday comments came amid rumblings of dissatisfaction
from Iowa and New Hampshire Republicans who are used to seeing
candidates early and often. Where, they asked in recent weeks, was
Bush, who was working behind the scenes on a presidential race
while the Texas Legislature moved toward its May 31 conclusion?
</P>
<P>
   On a spring Saturday in Iowa, where the presidential season
unofficially begins with an August straw poll and officially starts
with its February caucuses, Bush showed up to begin filling in the
blanks for voters who know him only as an as-seen-on-TV candidate.
He arrived during the busiest week in Iowa so far this year for
presidential aspirants. GOP challengers Elizabeth Dole, Lamar
Alexander and John Kasich were also in the state. And earlier in
the week, Dan Quayle, Pat Buchanan and Gary Bauer visited.
</P>
<P>
   While his GOP opponents slammed Bush on issues ranging from
abortion to trying to inherit the nomination, they were noticeably
silent about Bush after his Saturday declaration.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the Democratic National Committee, with months to
prepare for Bush's entry into the race, was ready with a
full-frontal assault on the GOP front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' goal was to link Bush with a fallen GOP leader
and the party's far-right reaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we know that George Bush's `compassionate conservatism' is
really just Newt Gingrich's `Contract with America,''' said
Democratic National Committee Chairman Joe Andrew in releasing a
document that asks ``Is Bush really any different from Newt
Gingrich, Pat Robertson or any other old-fashioned right-wing
conservative?''
</P>
<P>
   After months of pretended indecision, Bush put himself solidly
on the starting line here Saturday with a speech that was quickly
posted on his web site and listed as ``The Speech.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am running for president of the United States. Full
throttle. Pedal to the floor. No turning back,'' his posted speech
said. Although he deviated slightly when he spoke to the Iowa
crowd, Bush left no doubt that he's in.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the front-runner in the polls long before he asked for a
single vote, headed out from Austin Saturday morning on a campaign
jet his staff has dubbed ``Great Expectations.'' In Iowa, Bush and
his wife, Laura, were greeted by a boisterous crowd that filled a
hangar at the Cedar Rapids airport. They waved signs reading,
``Iowa is Bush Country,'' ``Iowa Loves Laura,'' and ``Viva Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   One woman handed Bush her cell phone so he could say hello to
her sister. Hours before his official announcement, the governor
shattered all pretense of the trip as an ``exploratory'' mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want your vote in the caucuses,'' he said into the phone as
he smiled for the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa hosts the February caucuses that are viewed as the
traditional kick-off of the presidential campaign season. The
contests actually will begin when Louisiana holds its caucuses
prior to Iowa's, but many top contenders skipped Louisiana in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's entry into the race will make it difficult for Bush
to skip Iowa's August straw poll, generally regarded as the first
major test of strength. As an undeclared candidate, Bush, perhaps
seeking to avoid an early stumble, might have been able to skip the
August event. With what he said here Saturday, it now would be
difficult for him to beg off.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Bush will head to Maine for a quiet day with his parents
in Kennebunkport. He'll hit the campaign trail again Monday and
Tuesday in New Hampshire, which hosts the nation's first primary,
and then he goes to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first out-of-state foray for Bush, who stuck to his
pledge not to leave Texas before the Legislature adjourned. Without
actively campaigning or appearing at an out-of-state fund-raiser
until this past Friday, he has built a large lead over his rivals.
He has secured so many major GOP endorsements and raised so much
money _ an expected $20 million by month's end _ that many have all
but crowned him the winner.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush aides who chose the name for his airplane were poking
fun at those high expectations. The candidate did the same thing
when he greeted the roughly 100 reporters who flew with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please store your expectations securely in the overhead bins,
as they may shift during the trip and hurt someone _ especially
me,'' Bush said over the intercom as the plane _ and his campaign _
prepared for take-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please understand that while you are traveling with a
well-trained crew, for many of us this is our first solo flight.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, wearing ostrich skin cowboy boots and a state of Texas
belt buckle embossed with his name, appeared to be a little
apprehensive as he wandered back with a cup of coffee to talk to
reporters. But he was buoyed by the enthusiasm of the crowd at the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready, I'm ready,'' he said, as if to steel himself for
the journey ahead. ``I intend to earn this nomination and I intend
to win this nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   This trip marks Bush's official introduction to a national
audience. But, as promised, he didn't offer much in the way of
specific policy proposals. In his speech at the barbecue, the
prelude to a ``formal'' announcement in the fall, Bush focused
mostly on the broad themes that would guide him as president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be a president who sets a tone, a direction, an agenda.
I will be an activist president, who sets goals worthy of a great
nation. I will not use my office as a mirror to reflect public
opinion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be guided by conservative principles, that government
should do a few things, and do them well. Government should not try
to be all things to all people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush repeated many of the themes he's ridden to two
gubernatorial victories in Texas. He talked about personal
responsibility, limiting government regulation, and rallying
``armies of compassion,'' such as the faith-based organizations he
has empowered in Texas, to provide many social services in a
nongovernmental way. He also defended his self-styled
``compassionate conservatism,'' which some of his Republican
opponents have ridiculed as meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this approach has been criticized, but why? Is
compassion beneath us? Is mercy below us? Should our party be led
by someone who boasts of a hard heart?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush did touch on some specifics, saying he'd support allowing
people to invest part of their Social Security contributions in
private accounts, and that he'd increase defense spending. With
little detail, he also said he'd cut taxes without hurting
``struggling families on the outskirts of poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who attended the luncheon weren't bothered by the dearth
of specific proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he came up with a plan,'' said 22-year-old Randy
Foreman of Waterloo.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Edwards, a retired farmer from Marengo, said Bush was smart
to avoid hot-button issues so early in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He left the abortion issue totally alone, which I think may be
just as well for the present,'' said Edwards, who is anti-abortion
rights. ``But he's going to have to make a stand sometime.''
</P>
<P>
   The Washington-based National Abortion and Reproductive Rights
Action League (NARAL) prepared for Bush's trip by publicizing his
anti-abortion rights views on bill boards and on radio commercials
in Iowa. But those hoping to pin Bush down were disappointed:
Nearly all of the people who attended Saturday's events already are
Bush supporters, and there wasn't a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Some say Bush's late arrival here could hurt him, but an early
start doesn't guarantee success: Texas Sen. Phil Gramm, who began
organizing here long before the 1996 campaign was in high gear,
finished a dismal fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa Bush chairman Joe Gunderson insists that ``Iowans don't
think that a shortened presidential election cycle is a bad
thing,'' and Bush supporters here have worked hard to put a
positive spin on the governor's promise to remain in Texas until
after the legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberger is an American-Statesman writer. His colleague Ken
Herman contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
