<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3140 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRIVATE-CITY-KAN &LR;      06-12 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVATE-CITY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME, CITY MIGHT NOT BE ABLE TO RESIST THE LURE OF
PRIVATIZATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN HORSLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (NOTE-With four sidebars: PRIVATE-WATER, PRIVATE-ARENA,
PRIVATE-GOLF, PRIVATE-PORT)
KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- The blossoming debate in Kansas City over
privatization -- allowing private companies to deliver city
services -- is about money. Your money, as a taxpayer; city
employees' money, as wage-earners; and private enterprises' money,
as for-profit businesses.
</P>
<P>
   As with most issues governmental, this one has produced two
views:
</P>
<P>
   Advocates see bloated payrolls slashed; city services improved;
and more money for the city from its arenas, airports and golf
courses.
</P>
<P>
   Critics see city workers laid off, taxpayer-supported public
buildings handed over to private corporations, and a profit motive
subverting and supplanting public service.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, the debate raging over privatizing has become
politicized since Mayor Kay Barnes' chief campaign consultant, Pat
Gray, was linked to a private company's efforts to manage or buy
the Water Services Department.
</P>
<P>
   But privatizing is really nothing new. It has been studied off
and on for the past quarter-century at City Hall and is growing in
popularity nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some Kansas City government services already are
performed by private companies, such as garbage collection,
boulevard maintenance and street resurfacing.
</P>
<P>
   But the concept has gained resonance in recent months, prompted
by a mayoral campaign that focused on better basic services and the
need to shrink a $15 million gap between city revenue and expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Areas ripe for consideration in Kansas City are the convention
and sports facilities, drinking water services, Kansas City
International Airport and the city golf courses. Combined, they
have a payroll of about $43 million and more than 1,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   But some are urging caution, aware of the concerns by city
employees over jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have indicated I am not for privatization just for
privatization's sake,'' said City Manager Bob Collins. ``What the
mayor is asking for is that we have a reasoned approach for
providing services, looking at public/private partnerships as a way
to improve services.''
</P>
<P>
   Privatizing can take several forms, but in general, it means
shifting some or all of the responsibility for service delivery to
private companies, or to some type of partnership between the
government and private sector, with the goal of saving money and
boosting performance.
</P>
<P>
   It can run the gamut: sale of a city asset, in which the city
gives up all control; long-term leasing of a facility, with private
management and private or city employees; or short-term contracts
with greater city control.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another approach, which the city auditor endorses, involves
``managed competition,'' in which city employees can bid against
private vendors to provide a city service. They often win the bid,
reducing costs and increasing efficiency along the way.
</P>
<P>
   National League of Cities officials say they know the concept
has increased in popularity since the early 1970s, when cities
confronted shrinking budgets and the public's demands for greater
accountability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I challenge someone to come up with a service that I can't
find at least one city that's privatized it, including police and
fire,'' said Adrian Moore of the Reason Public Policy Institute, a
market-oriented think tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overarching lesson is that, if done right, it works well.
The trick is to learn how to do it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Definitive data on how well privatization has worked in other
cities are difficult to find and, because each city has different
problems, comparing data also is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   But cities have privatized everything from trash collection to
adoption services. Usually, the private sector can perform the same
task with lower utility costs, lower purchasing costs and
two-thirds the number of employees.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix, for example, saved $27 million in 13 services between
1979 and 1994. It awarded 22 competitively bid contracts to city
workers and 34 to private contractors.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest opposition to privatizing usually comes from unions.
Moore said cities must involve employees in the planning and avoid
any hint of special-interest favoritism.
</P>
<P>
   Local 500 President Nate Byas, who represents Kansas City's
2,200 blue-collar and clerical workers, said his union was
concerned that the city might use privatization to skirt
affirmative-action rules. He said his members, two-thirds of whom
are minorities, feared privatization would be ``devastating to the
minority community.''
</P>
<P>
   But Moore said the practice shouldn't be perceived as a threat
to minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The techniques for doing privatization without large-scale
layoffs and without putting the burden on the back of public
employees have gotten far more refined,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cities such as Atlanta and Milwaukee have written into their
contracts that the private contractor must hire every city employee
in the area to be privatized. Other cities require contractors to
give right of first refusal to public employees, using attrition
and buyouts to cut the work force.
</P>
<P>
   In one example cited by the National League of Cities,
Charlotte, N.C., adopted a no-layoff policy, but still managed to
reduce the work force by 272 positions.
</P>
<P>
   Byas said he wasn't opposed to managed competition between
Kansas City employees and the private sector, but he wants to make
sure the mayor isn't showing favoritism or cutting deals for her
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   He also is skeptical that privatization can save money, because
many city employees already are paid less than private-sector
workers. Byas wonders what would happen if a private company
reneged on an agreement when profits didn't meet expectations:
``Then who will be the ones who make sure the job gets done?''
</P>
<P>
   Other city officials said talk of privatization hurt employee
morale and made it difficult to recruit employees and department
managers.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, a report on public/private partnerships is
expected from the city manager by July 8. Assistant City Manager
Rich Noll said he was looking at how other cities did it.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis, Noll said, created a committee of civic leaders,
city staff members and union members who recommend privatizing
opportunities. Noll thinks that's a good idea because he doesn't
want privatizing to be threatening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will put on an entirely neutral process that favors no
one,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
