r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRIVATE-WATER-KAN &LR;      06-12 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVATE-WATER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME, TALK OVER PRIVATIZING WATER SERVICES MIGHT NOT GO AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (NOTE-Sidebar to PRIVATE-CITY)
KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- More than four years ago, City Auditor Mark
Funkhouser recommended that Kansas City's water system be sold,
leased or turned over to private management.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing came of it. Today, city officials still run a
moneymaking drinking water operation with about 500 employees and a
$22.4 million payroll that sells water to the city's residents as
well as more than two dozen neighboring suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   But talk about privatizing the Water Services Department, which
also handles storm drainage and wastewater management, is back. And
this time, it might not go away.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City isn't alone. Pick almost any city, and its water
department is likely to be at the center of a flourishing debate
about whether it would fare best in private or public hands.
</P>
<P>
   If Kansas City were to take its water department private, it
would become the largest water utility -- based on its
240-million-gallon daily capacity -- to be privatized in the United
States so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly this is going to continue to be a hot topic,'' said
Jack Hoffbuhr, executive director of the American Water Works
Association, a Denver trade group representing 4,000 water
utilities in North America.
</P>
<P>
   Privatization of something so fundamental as water is an
emotional topic.
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham, Ala., found that out last year when voters rejected
a plan by city officials to sell their department. Larger water
utilities in cities such as Oklahoma City and Jersey City, N.J.,
have retained private management.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's water utility earlier this year hired private managers
for its water department, becoming the largest to do so. Atlanta's
water utility, which produces 200 million gallons per day, expects
to save $400 million over the next 20 years in labor costs, energy
savings and operating efficiencies. It will use the money for
repairs and to expand the water system.
</P>
<P>
   United Water Services, a Harrington Park, N.J., company, won the
bid for the Atlanta system. Lou Ann Baker, a company spokeswoman,
said that the company took over in January and that savings were
already accruing.
</P>
<P>
   On the other end of the privatization debate is Chattanooga,
Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   It's been more than 130 years since the city was in such bad
shape that it couldn't afford to purchase a drinking water system
built on orders of Gen. Ulysses S. Grant during the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to water, old times there are not forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Chattanooga now wants to buy the utility, which has always been
privately owned. The utility's owner, however, is resisting, and
the city is trying to force a sale through condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want it back,'' said Ken Hays, chief of staff for
Chattanooga's mayor.
</P>
<P>
   City officials say public ownership would save $100 million over
10 years and reduce water bills for consumers by 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Loftin, a spokesman for Tennessee-American Water Co.,
the owner of the Chattanooga water utility, said that the savings
figures were bogus and that its existing rates were competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Chattanooga would retain private management if successful in
buying the utility. But Hays said that Chattanooga needed better
control of its future and that owning the water department was key.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're crazy not to own our most precious resource,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In privatizing water departments, the fate of employees has
become the most sensitive issue.
</P>
<P>
   United Water has recognized the union that represents about half
of the Atlanta water department's workers. The company also agreed
to offer benefits equal to or better than offered by the city.
United Water pledged no layoffs, and any staff reductions would be
through attrition.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there has been uneasiness among employees. There
were 430 workers in the department last year. There were 417
employees when United took over in January. Today, the employment
number is 402.
</P>
<P>
   One grievance is that water department employees can stay in the
city's pension plan, but only their service with the city will
count. No additional contributions will be made to the city system.
</P>
<P>
   Some employees say they will be harmed by the move. Atlanta
employees have filed a lawsuit against the city over their
pensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still problems,'' said Marie Robinson, executive
director of Local 1644 of the American Federation of State, County
and Municipal Employees, which represents 2,200 of Kansas City's
6,900 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Robinson said water department workers under private
management had received higher pay raises than city workers
received.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-99 2134EDT &QL; 
