<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3142 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TRADE-NYT &LR;      06-12 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ASKS CONGRESS TO SUPPORT NEW INTERNATIONAL TRADE DEALS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ President Clinton urged Congress Saturday to help him
forge new international trade agreements that would create a more
open marketplace while making a stronger commitment to improving
labor conditions around the world.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wanted Congress to give him the authority to
negotiate trade agreements based not only on the notion of
protecting interests in things like food safety and intellectual
property, but to protect the environment and the rights of workers
in other regions as well.
</P>
<P>
   By publicly endorsing labor and environmental rights as part of
trade accords, Clinton is trying to close a huge breach in the
Democratic Party that has stymied his trade efforts for years.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, he was forced to withdraw a bill that would have
given him broader authority to negotiate after more than half of
his own party rebelled, led by the House minority leader, Rep. Dick
Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is bound to come up again in coming months. Some
Democrats are already threatening to make labor and human rights
provisions a part of any deal to get China into the World Trade
Organization, a step the Chinese have already ruled out.
</P>
<P>
   It is a particularly difficult issue for Vice President Al Gore
because he is seeking to mollify the unions, which oppose both the
trade authority and any China agreement, without seeming to differ
from Clinton's approach.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that in many countries children work ``in conditions that
shock the conscience,'' the president announced that he had signed
an executive order directing all federal agencies to take steps to
ban the purchase of goods manufactured by companies that use forced
or indentured child labor.
</P>
<P>
   The order requires federal agencies to make a list of any
products that they suspect were made with the use of forced child
labor, and any federal contractor found to be in violation of the
ban on selling those goods to federal agencies could be barred from
doing business with the government.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made the announcement in a commencement address at the
University of Chicago, amid a cluster of Gothic spires on the south
side of Chicago, where he personally greeted nearly every one of
the 800 graduates who rose to accept a diploma.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would step up his efforts to negotiate a new
international agreement that would seek to combat the worst forms
of child labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to figure out how to build a system that is both free
and fair, and not just to workers in the United States, but in
other countries of the world,'' he said to applause from the more
than 6,000 people who gathered on the Harper quadrangle here. ``The
only way to do that is to have trade agreements that lift everybody
up, not pull everybody down. They shouldn't undermine labor rights
or environmental standards.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
