<SLUG> BC-PRIVATE-ARENA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVATE COMPANIES ARE DEVELOPING TRACK RECORD MANAGING CITY
ARENAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (NOTE-Sidebar to PRIVATE-CITY)
KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Private management of convention halls and
public arenas is hardly a new concept -- in Kansas City or
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   In many states, private management of public arenas is the rule
rather than the exception. The notion has been bandied about in
Kansas City Council chambers for years, and Mayor Kay Barnes has
made no secret that she favors looking at privatization of some
city services.
</P>
<P>
   But the disclosure last week that Pat Gray, a Kansas City
consultant and Barnes' key political adviser, worked for one of the
nation's largest arena-management firms has agitated the Convention
and Entertainment Center Department's 223 workers.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Philadelphia-based SMG, operates dozens of public
and privately owned arenas. SMG executives say they would love to
add Kansas City's Bartle Hall and Kemper Arena to their portfolio,
and they acknowledge they already have been meeting privately with
city officials -- but not yet with Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   Bartle, Kemper, Municipal Auditorium, the American Royal
complex, Barney Allis Plaza and several city parking facilities
collectively generate less annual revenue than it takes to operate
them. They manage to break even through a generous subsidy from the
city's hotel and motel room tax collections.
</P>
<P>
   The Convention and Entertainment Center Department this year is
budgeted to spend $20.8 million, including $7.7 million for
salaries, while taking in around $13.2 million from rentals and
other operations.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City is not unique in that regard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to make a profit'' with any convention, sports or
concert arena, said Keith Curry, a consultant with
Philadelphia-based Public Financial Management.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Eckerman, an executive with SFX Entertainment Inc.,
agrees. New York-based SFX operates about 70 U.S. arenas and
similar buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our facilities are definitely in what I call the
popcorn-and-peanut business,'' he said, plus the occasional parking
lot, because those are about the only profit centers left after the
entertainers are paid.
</P>
<P>
   Top-name performers command fees up to 85 percent of ticket
revenue, and even lesser stars can grab 60 percent or more,
Eckerman said.
</P>
<P>
   It takes $11.3 million a year to run Bartle and Municipal, and
even though those buildings are rented virtually every day of the
year, they are projected this year to bring in only $5.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same story in Topeka, Kan., where SMG operates the
12-year-old Kansas Expocentre.
</P>
<P>
   The company came on board in 1993, five years after the center
was built and opened by the Shawnee County Commission -- whose
members gladly contracted operational control to people with
industry and marketing savvy the county staff admittedly lacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was stagnant,'' said Winnie Kingman, a former county
commissioner closest to the civic auditorium project.
</P>
<P>
   Privatization, she said, ``was the best thing for that facility
... and the reason for its success today.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling Expocentre a success, however, may be a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   SMG General Manager Gary Desjardin said Expocentre was running
an average $1.2 million annual deficit under county control.
</P>
<P>
   He said SMG cut the annual loss to less that $800,000 until last
year, when the red ink dipped around $400,000 -- thanks largely to
the addition of the Topeka Scarecrows minor-league hockey team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still running in the red, but we've saved the county
money,'' Desjardin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
