<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves slumps contagious
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Slumps have been passing through the Braves clubhouse
like the flu. Next case: Bret Boone.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Cox started Keith Lockhart at second base
Saturday, he said, to ``get Keith some at-bats.'' Another factor
may have been to give Boone time to collect himself. He goes into
tonight's series finale on a 0-for-13 skid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go through it every year at some point. It happens,'' said
Boone, who had started 57 of the first 60 games. ``It's just in the
last four or five games, my swing's just got long on me for some
reason. I've got to shorten it up and get back.It's going to end.
It's going to end soon. It's just not any fun going through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Boone hit .302 in May, third highest on the club, but is
5-for-36 in June with nine strikeouts. He has lost 33 points off
his season average to .266 in the last 16 games. His last
extra-base hit came May 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seeing the ball fall,'' he said. ``I'm getting my pitch to
hit and fouling it off. I'm not swinging and missing and flailing
around.''
</P>
<P>
   KC calling
</P>
<P>
   Braves general manager reserved comment on a Kansas City report
that Royals GM Herk Robinson had inquired about the availability of
Atlanta first basemen. Robinson, who has been in touch with ``six
or seven'' teams, was said to be particularly interested in Randall
Simon, though the Braves are not interested in dealing,
particularly now the rookie has just begun platooning on a regular
basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some oars in the water,'' Robinson said. ``We've got
to have somebody who is going to catch the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Royals have been playing converted catcher Mike Sweeney and
converted outfielder Jeremy Giambi at first, with regular Larry
Sutton on the DL. The club earlier dealt away Jeff Conine and Jeff
King retired, leaving the organization stripped at the position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll let Herk talk about his search for a first baseman,''
John Schuerholz said.
</P>
<P>
   Cure 59
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz is no longer wearing the energy band he wore around
his wrist for while.
</P>
<P>
   ``Threw it away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Add that to the body magnets he tried in spring camp and the
other treatments, workouts and gimmicks Smoltz has experimented
with to find a comfort zone for his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if encouraged is the right word,'' said Smoltz,
who tonight will make his third start since coming off the disabled
list. ``I'm more positive. I'm not going to be consumed with
whether it feels good or whether it doesn't. I'm more concerned
with how to win that particular game.''
</P>
<P>
   Jethroe meets Jones
</P>
<P>
   Sam Jethroe, the first African-American to play for the Braves
when he was the 1950 NL rookie of the year, made his first visit to
Turner Field Saturday. Jethroe came from Erie, Pa., for the
dedication of a baseball field in his name at Welcome All Park in
the Ben Hill section of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Jethroe was interested in meeting Andruw Jones, who last season
tied the record of 413 putouts by a Braves outfielder that Jethroe
set in 1952.
</P>
</TEXT>
