<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-N0TES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National League notebook
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NL EAST
</P>
<P>
   Counsell, Marlins break up
</P>
<P>
   If you can't find playing time in Florida, someone is sending a
message, which second baseman Craig Counsell has received loud and
clear. After being lifted Tuesday for defensive substitute Luis
Castillo, Counsell, a hero of the 1997 world champion Marlins,
requested a meeting with manager John Boles and asked to be traded.
Friday, he was designated for assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can handle being a utility player, and I can handle losing
my job in spring training,'' said Counsell, who lost the starting
job to Castillo during camp. ``But now they're telling me I can't
play defense?'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   Phillies right-hander Carlton Loewer had felt a ``dull ache'' in
his arm most of the season, but it was not until team physician
Phillip Marone ordered an MRI that an incomplete stress fracture
was found above the elbow. Marone's discovery saved Loewer from
possibly snapping his arm, as Tampa Bay's Tony Saunders did two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   NL CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   A vote against interleague
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire took his last look at the site of his first career
homer when the St. Louis Cardinals visited Detroit. As an Oakland
rookie in 1986, McGwire cracked a shot past the 440-foot sign at
Tigers Stadium, which will be vacated after this season.
</P>
<P>
   With the old park jammed with 20,000 just to watch batting
practice, McGwire marveled, ``If I hit a home run, they cheer for
me. And if I strike out, they cheer for me again.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, interleague play has lost its interest for the
Cardinals, who urge that it should be revamped on a rotating
divisional basis or scrapped. Growing familiarity and the imbalance
between divisions mar the current arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some divisions have more talent than others,'' former Braves
left- hander Kent Mercker said. ``Would you rather face Mercker or
would you rather face (Greg) Maddux?'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates are pushing second baseman Warren Morris, acquired
from Texas last year in the Esteban Loaiza trade, for rookie of the
year. He leads first-year NL players with 29 RBIs and 25 walks. The
Pirates never have had a rookie of the year.
</P>
<P>
   NL WEST
</P>
<P>
   Throwing in the towel
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Olson is officially out as Arizona's closer, following his
sixth blown save Tuesday against the Cubs. Olson gave up a two-run
homer to Tyler Houston in a 5-3 loss, after which manager Buck
Showalter nominated rookies Vladimir Nunzez and Byung-Hyun Kim for
the job.
</P>
<P>
   Kim spiced the new arrangement the following night, when a
liniment-laced bandage he was wearing on his shoulder flew out from
under his jersey at mid-inning. Cubs first baseman Mark Grace
handed it to plate umpire Ed Montague during the changeover, and
Kim was promptly ejected for using a foreign substance. Showalter
maintained that the goo was just balm for a sore shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Grace laughed at that one. ``You have to give (Kim) credit,'' he
said. ``Most guys don't start cheating until later in their
career.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' proposed move to a new spring training home has
become a mess, after the Fort McDowell Indian Community of Arizona
disclosed that their baseball facility would include no housing for
the team. While the Dodgers say that makes staying in Vero Beach,
Fla., a more attractive option, the state of Florida has scaled
back tax-related offers to keep the team in their only spring home
since 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
