<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Packers gear for rebound
 &HT;    (Resending to fix garble.)
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pundits in Las Vegas currently rate Green Bay as no better
than the No. 3 favorite, behind Minnesota and Atlanta, in the NFC
for 1999. Quarterback Brett Favre, however, thinks the Packers can
return to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened last year stung us,'' Favre said about the
team's second-place finish in the NFC Central and last-minute loss
to San Francisco in the wild-card round. ``Maybe we'll have the
luxury of sneaking up on folks.''
</P>
<P>
   Under first-year coach Ray Rhodes, the practices are longer and
more physical than the no-pads workouts of Mike Holmgren. But even
without Reggie White, general manager Ron Wolf has worked hard to
improve the depth. Look for the team to pursue tailback Lawrence
Phillips as a backup to Dorsey Levens and to sign a veteran
linebacker. There is optimism that fourth-year wideout Derrick
Mayes finally is ready to make an impact. And though the offensive
line is the deepest it has been in years, offensive coordinator
Sherm Lewis has Favre working from the shotgun for the first time
in his career.
</P>
<P>
   The Pack used its first three draft choices on defensive backs _
Antuan Edwards of Clemson (No. 1), Vanderbilt's Fred Vinson (No. 2)
and Mike McKenzie of Memphis (No. 3) _ in an attempt to get bigger
and quicker in the secondary. But it is the return to health of
corner Craig Newsome and additional experience of free safety
Darren Sharper that defensive coordinator Emmitt Thomas will count
on for improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say we were complacent last year,'' strong
safety LeRoy Butler said. ``I just know we're better now than we
were this time a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Saints getting busy
</P>
<P>
   At the league owners meetings, New Orleans GM Bill Kuharich
vowed the Saints would be active in the free-ageny market after
June 1. Two weeks later, he seems to be intent on fulfilling that
promise. Within a three-day stretch last week, New Orleans met with
offensive tackle Andy Heck; linebackers Dixon Edwards, Anthony
Davis and Greg Lloyd; fullback Tim Lester; cornerbacks Ashley
Ambrose and Ryan McNeil and punter Tommy Barnhardt. With $2.38
million in cap room and one-man draft class Ricky Williams under
contract, the Saints could make some noise. They were working hard
during the weekend to get a deal with Ambrose.
</P>
<P>
   Tip sheet
</P>
<P>
   With free safety Mark Carrier requesting a contract extension,
Detroit officials have inquired about the availability of New
England's Willie Clay. The former Georgia Tech star has a base
salary of $1.5 million, and with the Patriots needing cap room so
they can re-sign corner Ty Law and strong safety Lawyer Milloy,
personnel director Bobby Grier might listen to offers. ...
Free-agent quarterback Neil O'Donnell is close to a contract with
Tennessee. ... At the Pittsburgh minicamp last week, former Georgia
star and second-year wideout Hines Ward was lining up with the
first-unit offense as coordinator Kevin Gilbride began installing a
more wide-open scheme he hopes will benefit quarterback Kordell
Stewart. ... It looks as if Dallas owner Jerry Jones will gamble
that Deion Sanders can be ready to play at least half the season.
Jones already lost one gamble this spring. He gave defensive tackle
Leon Lett a signing bonus to lower his base salary to $400,000. Now
he won't get much salary-cap relief while Lett serves his drug
suspension. ... Baltimore will restructure the contract of corner
Rod Woodson, who probably will move to safety this year. ... What
kind of shape is Ryan Leaf in? When the San Diego quarterback
finally showed up for a minicamp last week, he strained his
throwing arm in the third practice. ... Miami coach Jimmy Johnson
is incensed that rookie tailback Cecil Collins sprained his back
jumping on a trampoline at an event sanctioned by the NFL Players
Association. ... The league had to address a festering problem with
its Berlin franchise in the NFL Europe League last week. Some
citizens of Turkish background, upset by the fact that local white
women were dating minority players, were threatening players in
their hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Faulk juggles offers
</P>
<P>
   The Rams made two offers to tailback Marshall Faulk. The first
is four years, $19 million. The second is a seven-year deal worth
$38.5 million, but includes ``voidables'' that decrease its value.
</P>
<P>
   Money matters
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday, there was a total of just $60.45 million in
salary-cap room remaining in the league. But three teams _
Cleveland ($8.5 million), Philadelphia ($7.1 million) and
Cincinnati ($6.24 million) _ account for more than one-third of it.
Ten clubs each are under $1 million, and Oakland ($82,000), New
England ($33,000) and Carolina ($16,000) are under $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
