<HEADER>
A3151 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRIVATE-PORT-KAN &LR;      06-12 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVATE-PORT-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Airport turns profit, but that money doesn't leave the property  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE RICE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (NOTE-Sidebar to PRIVATE-CITY)
KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Some city officials think it's time to sell
Kansas City International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Others think hiring a private firm to manage the airport is the
answer.
</P>
<P>
   KCI, with 330 employees and a $12 million annual payroll, is a
moneymaking commodity. Last fiscal year, the Aviation Department --
the bulk of which is KCI's operations -- made a profit of $19.8
million.
</P>
<P>
   So why sell something that makes money?
</P>
<P>
   Because KCI's profit doesn't benefit the rest of the city, said
City Auditor Mark Funkhouser. Federal law prohibits airport revenue
from being used by a city's general fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't buy a police car or fix a bridge or pave a road with
the money it makes,'' Funkhouser said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Councilwoman Teresa Loar said privatization advocates
should be cautious.
</P>
<P>
   Because of safety issues, Loar said, government supervision of
departments such as aviation is beneficial to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Privatization is a real buzzword right now,'' she said. ``But
I'm not going to jump on a bandwagon just to jump on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City -- which has never tried to sell KCI -- might have
to move fast to make the most of a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the federal government launched a pilot program for
the first five cities that sell their airports.
</P>
<P>
   These pilot cities can put the profits from a sale directly into
a city's general fund. Usually, any money made on the sale of an
airport must go back into that city's aviation department.
</P>
<P>
   Funkhouser said there was another critical benefit to selling
KCI, which sits on 9,500 acres. ``If a private company comes in
there, it would be paying property taxes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Property taxes that Funkhouser estimated could amount to tens of
millions of dollars each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be as if we went out to recruit a big firm,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, almost two dozen U.S. airports are managed by private
firms.
</P>
<P>
   Cities and counties that have done some sort of privatization
with their airports or launched feasibility studies include San
Diego; San Antonio; Newark, N.J.; and Allegheny County, Pa., home
to Pittsburgh International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The poster child of airport privatization is the country's
largest privatized airport -- Indianapolis International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Since privatizing in 1995, Indianapolis International has become
one of the world's largest cargo airports. Its work force has
increased from 275 to 309, and its non-airlines revenue -- such as
food and retail sales -- has doubled.
</P>
<P>
   But Indianapolis Councilwoman Susan Williams said she feared
that a private company could make damaging moves to passengers more
quickly and quietly than government -- by raising parking prices,
for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice to other cities is that if privatization doesn't
show a definite upside potential, then don't do it,'' she said.
``You would be giving an asset away.''
</P>
<P>
   Talks about privatizing in Kansas City have sparked concern
among some blue-collar and minority workers. Some experts suggest
cities make contract stipulations for minority hirings and union
participation when selling their airports.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Paul Danaher, a vocal privatization supporter, said
workers might be better off with a private airport because there
would be a better chance for merit-pay increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the present system,'' he said, ``someone who is getting
Southwest Airlines to expand here is not able to get merit pay.''
</P>
<P>
   And there can be job creation, as has happened at the Pittsburgh
airport.
</P>
<P>
   BAA USA took over that airport's commercial area in 1992 and
converted it into a shopping center-style operation with new stores
such as The Gap, TGI Friday's, and a Discovery Channel store.
</P>
<P>
   That new retail and restaurant area has created more than 1,000
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Webber, a local transportation consultant who
supports privatization, said non-airline businesses might not reach
that type of potential at KCI because of its curved, three-terminal
configuration.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't get the critical mass that you would normally get
from 11 million passengers a year at KCI,'' Webber said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-99 2148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
