A3156 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRIVATE-GOLF-KAN &LR;      06-12 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVATE-GOLF-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CEDING CITY CONTROL OF GOLF COURSES WOULD BREAK 93-YEAR-OLD
TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN HORSLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (NOTE-Sidebar to PRIVATE-CITY)
KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Urged on by Mayor Kay Barnes and new park board
Chairman Bob Lewellen, the Kansas City Parks and Recreation
Department plans to seek a feasibility study on some type of
private partnership for the city's four golf courses.
</P>
<P>
   If recommended, it would be a big change in a city that has run
golf courses since it opened the metropolitan area's first, Swope
Park Golf Course, in 1906. Today, the department employs about 110
people on its courses during the summer, with a golf operations
budget of about $3.3 million and a $1.4 million payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Still, privatizing of municipal courses is catching on
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   About one-fourth of U.S. cities contracted for golf operations
by 1995, up 67 percent since 1987, according to the Reason Public
Policy Institute, which supports prudent privatizing efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, an avid golfer, wants the park board to explore what
other cities have done, the potential costs and benefits, and the
effect on city employees.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City's four courses include Minor Park, Hodge Park and
Blue River Golf Academy in Swope Park.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes and Lewellen said private involvement could range from
complete management of the courses, to management of the golf carts
and pro shop, to management of the food and beverage concessions,
or other combinations.
</P>
<P>
   Cities such as St. Louis and Indianapolis rave about
privatization, while Fort Worth, Texas, gave up on it in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, American Golf Corp. won a 20-year lease to run St.
Louis' two courses at Forest Park. The company provided $500,000 in
capital improvements, and the city now receives $125,000 per year
in revenue. Maintenance and use of the courses improved
significantly, said Dan Skillman, commissioner of parks.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis' 13 golf courses also privatized in 1993. The city
garners about $1 million a year in revenue and last year had a
$100,000 budget surplus. The courses also kept the lowest fees in
the state -- $15 for 18 holes.
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Worth, a company defaulted on its contract and the city
had to take back control of one of its two courses in January 1998.
The other company, American Golf, fulfilled its eight-year contract
on the second course, but the council opted not to renew.
</P>
<P>
   ``The City Council wanted to see how it worked. In our case, it
didn't work very well,'' said George Kruzick, golf operations
manager. ``We had a lot of complaints from the golfers about the
condition of the courses. ... The other city-run courses were
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City parks department officials say they are not opposed
to some type of private partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt you can always improve your maintenance,''
said parks director Terry Dopson. ``It's an open question whether
privatizing would make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   City audits in 1996 and 1997 were critical of the parks
department's course maintenance, inventory controls, and freebies
to marshals and VIPs that cut into profits.
</P>
<P>
   Dopson said maintenance improved in 1998, the marshals no longer
play for free, strict inventory controls are in place, and profits
last year were more than $450,000 -- up nearly $75,000. But those
profits don't account for depreciation or indirect costs. If
factored in, the city auditor argues, the courses actually lose
money.
</P>
<P>
   In many cities, municipal employees remain on the job at
competitive wages but work for a private company, such as American
Golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the vast majority of cases, we offer to come into and
assume all the existing staff,'' said Sheri Clark of American Golf,
the nation's largest municipal-course operator.
</P>
<P>
   The general manager usually is replaced by an American Golf
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis' courses are run by local businessmen or PGA pros.
City workers were moved to other jobs in the parks department and
the courses improved, said Lou Hurrle, city golf administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Some Kansas City golf experts are skeptical that privatizing
would be an improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Krakauer, a director of the Missouri Golf Association,
points out that Leawood, Kan., and Blue Springs, Mo., contracted
for management of their courses because they had small parks staffs
that lacked expertise. He said that was not the case in Kansas
City, which hires PGA professionals to run its courses and has
ample staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they would benefit by having a private
company,'' Krakauer said. ``I think the replacement would be very
difficult. It would be very difficult for a replacement to know as
much about it as these guys know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
