<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-PREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTH FINALISTS HAVE KARMA, BUT SPURS HAVE THE TOWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NBA Finals: New York's Destiny vs. San Antonio's Domination.
</P>
<P>
   After an irregular season in which both teams hit rock-bottom
lows and contemplated firing their coaches, followed by provocative
playoff runs in which their stars sacrificed starring roles, the
Spurs and Knicks match mojos in the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   While the favored Spurs own the home-court advantage and
dominant 7-footers Tim Duncan and David Robinson, the surprising
Knicks try to overcome key injuries by riding the unique talents
and unlikely chemistry of Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt we can beat them,'' said Camby, the human
jumper-cable reserve who has sparked the Knicks' shocking and
unprecedented rise to the Finals as the East's No. 8 seed.
``Nobody's given us a chance, but here we are. One more mountain to
climb. We've got a chance to do something really special.''
</P>
<P>
   With a simplistic plan based on the offense of Duncan and
defense of Robinson, the Spurs have been the league's best team
since March. They have won 42 of their past 48 games and are 11-1
in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the Knicks barely sneaked into the playoffs, then
needed a quirky last-second bounce to upset the Miami Heat in the
first round. Despite injuries to key players Patrick Ewing and
Larry Johnson, the Knicks knocked off the Indiana Pacers with
relentless passion and boundless energy provided from Sprewell and
Camby. The Knicks were 21-21 in late April, but 18-5 since firing
general manager Ernie Grunfeld.
</P>
<P>
   A preview of the intriguing strategic, social and silly matchups
that will provide NBA Finals storylines the next two weeks:
</P>
<P>
   Twin Peaks vs. Twin Freaks: Chris Dudley will never be mistaken
for Duncan's ``Mini-Me'' and the Spurs look like the Houston
Rockets during their repeat titles, only with two Hakeem Olajuwons.
The tattooed Camby and dreadlocked Sprewell will try to get San
Antonio's Twin Towers into a running game, but without Ewing and
Johnson, it could get ugly underneath. Advantage: Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Alamodome vs. Madison Square Garden: One has played host to a
Beatles concert, a Muhammad Ali fight and an NBA Championship Game
7. The other has pink splashed on its hardwood. Advantage: Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Rest vs. Rust: The Spurs haven't played since winning Game 4 of
the West finals in Portland on June 6. Their nine-day layoff will
be the second-longest for a Finals team, matching the Jazz's wait
last year and one short of the Lakers in '89. Both those team lost
the series, but the Knicks have to be physically and emotionally
drained. Advantage: Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   George Valle vs. Spike Lee: Valle, president of the Spurs'
Baseline Bums, has missed five games in 26 years. Lee wears a
bright orange towel on his head. Advantage: Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Texas vs. New York: See the NHL Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Popovich vs. Jeff Van Gundy: Spurs fans chanted ``Pop Must
Go!'' after a February loss that dropped their team to 6-8. Shortly
afterward, Popovich gave the ball to Duncan. With his team at .500
and on the playoff bubble, Van Gundy was given a playoffs-or-else
ultimatum. Shortly afterward, he started playing Sprewell and Camby
more minutes. Popovich could be mayor of San Antonio, but Van Gundy
now has job security and a $4 million bonus for just reaching the
Finals. Advantage: Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   26 years vs. 26 years: One team is Final-ly destined for a Susan
Lucci breakthrough. The Knicks won their most recent NBA title in
1973, same year the Spurs rose from the ashes of the Dallas
Chaparrals. Advantage: Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   One-horse Town vs. The City That Never Sleeps: The Big Apple is
the nation's No. 1 media market and home to nine major professional
sports teams. The town that invented jalapeno peppers is the 37th
largest market and home to the Spurs and the minor-league baseball
Missions. Advantage: Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Avery Johnson vs. Charlie Ward: Has there ever been a Finals
with such unassuming, unproductive point guards? Both score only
when wide open and are devout Christians who give credit for every
made jumper or victory to God. Considering their empowerment, can
either have an edge? Advantage: Even.
</P>
<P>
   River walk vs. Central Park: In San Antonio, you might see a
boat float by with a load of tourists. In New York, you might see a
mugger sprint by with someone's purse. Advantage: Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   The Alamo vs. The World Trade Center: Both still standing after
being bombed by angry foreigners. Advantage: Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Hindsight vs. Foresight: Take the vote now _ after Duncan's
demolition of Shaquille O'Neal and the emergence of Grunfeld
acquisitions Camby and Sprewell _ and the most valuable player
award would go to Duncan and executive of the year to the fired
Knicks GM.
</P>
<P>
   $1,290,000 vs. $855,000: Winners' share of the Finals' pot
compared to the losers' take. New York has the league's largest
payroll and the world's highest cost-of-living. Advantage: Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Spurs vs. Knicks: Don't forget, the Knicks were one bounce away
from playoff elimination and the Spurs one game away from
postseason perfection. While the Knicks' enthusiasm has been
refreshing, and coach Jeff Van Gundy's tenacity undying, dealing
with Duncan is another world from defending Miami's Alonzo
Mourning, Atlanta's Dikembe Mutombo or Indiana's Rik Smits. And if
that's not enough to rip apart the Knicks' inferior interior,
there's always Robinson. For once, the nice guys who would be flops
on MTV won't finish last in the NBA. Advantage: Spurs. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
