<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA STATE RELIEVER STIFLES TEXAS A&AMP;M
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ Each time Chris Chavez is called to the mound to
pull off another desperate rescue of Florida State, Kay Chavez
rises from her seat and departs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aw, my mom, she's always done that,'' Chavez said. ``Whenever
I pitch, she'll walk off and get somebody to tell her what happened
... or maybe go underneath the grandstand and watch it on TV. It
makes her nervous to see me pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the afternoon yesterday, Texas A&AMP;M probably
considered joining her.
</P>
<P>
   Riding a withering relief performance from Chavez, the
second-seeded Seminoles (54-12) rolled to a 7-3 victory against
Texas A&AMP;M (52-17), dropping the Aggies into an elimination game at
6:30 p.m. tomorrow against the Stanford-Cal State Fullerton loser.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all honesty, you'd have to say this was a game that Chavez
just came in and took control of,'' Seminoles coach Mike Martin
said. ``Not forgetting, of course, what Matt Diaz \Rtwo home runs,
three runs batted in\S did, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   game.'']
</P>
<P>
   Chavez arrived in the fifth inning afterSeminoles ace Nick
Stocks walked the first three batters. A 4-3 Seminoles lead was
teetering, but not for long.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, who mixes a sidearm delivery with his normal pitching
motion, struck out the next three hitters, eventually retiring 12
in a row before Chad Hudson opened the ninth with single. By then,
Florida State had a four-run cushion, and Hudson was promptly
erased in a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez faced the minimum 15 batters, struck out six, and then
went off to find his mom and give her a hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just bases-loaded, no-outs, one-run game,'' Martin
said. ``Not really that tough of a situation.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M coach Mark Johnson said the Aggies had been mesmerized by
Chavez, who is 7-5 with five saves, a 2.35 earned-run average and
102 strikeouts in 78 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, if you look at the opponents batting average against him
\R.194\S, it's not that surprising,'' Johnson said. ``We'd never
seen him, and he has a unique motion that's hard to pick up. And he
can make the ball break both ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Shawn Schumacher, who homered off Stocks in the second,
expressed the Aggies' frustration with Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat there inning after inning trying to pick up some kind of
pattern,'' he said. ``He didn't have one; he threw anything he had
whenever he wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M's Casey Fossum pitched into the eighth and threw 144
pitches. His four strikeouts made him the school's career leader
with 404, passing Jeff Granger.
</P>
<P>
   Both Texas entries in the College World Series lost their
openers; Rice faces Oklahoma State in an elimination game tonight,
and the Aggies will try to survive tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this dropped us to our knees,'' Johnson said.
``We've been in this situation before.''
nn
</P>
