<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WWC GIVING SOCCER NEW KICK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Who are these girls of summer? You've probably
heard of Mia Hamm, but how about Nigeria's ``Marvelous'' Mercy
Akide? Or a Mexican named Laurie Hill?
</P>
<P>
   With the 1999 FIFA Women's World Cup less than a week away, its
theme _ ``If we build it they will come'' _ is looking more
dignified each day. This could actually become the breakthrough
event that WWC president Marla Messing has been talking about. The
tournament gets underway Saturday in New York and San Jose, with a
doubleheader scheduled for the Rose Bowl next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it has all the personalities of a big event, which is
being billed as the single largest women's sporting event ever in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   WWC and FIFA officials have sold more than 388,000 tickets for
the 10 venues throughout the country. WWC hopes to sell 400,000 to
500,000 tickets before the tournament ends.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers also believe they can put a half-million spectators
in the seats by selling out the 77,716-seat Giants Stadium for the
American and tournament opener Saturday and the 92,542-seat Rose
Bowl for the championship game July 10.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers easily exceed the total of 112,000 tickets sold
for the 1995 Women's World Cup in Sweden or any other single
women's event held here previously.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's well beyond what we expected it to be,'' said Messing.
``The demand is greater than we had projected. It's one of two
things: The people we thought would buy are buying a whole lot
earlier, or a lot of people are interested in coming to the
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. midfielder Julie Foudy said they will prove wrong the
naysayers who believed a women's event such as this shouldn't be
held in large stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said when we started this World Cup, `You can't do it
on a big stage, you can't do it in big stadiums, you won't draw,'
'' said Foudy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell us what we can't do and we'll do it. We love these types
of obstacles. This is the opportunity for us to show the world our
sport and what we've done with it. Women's athletics needs to know
it can put on a big event and be successful. The hardest part is
they don't want to take the risk. We were fortunate enough that we
had great backing to take the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the (1984) Olympics and put the soccer final in the
Rose Bowl and sold it out,'' said Alan Rothenberg, president of the
1994 World Cup held in the United States. ``We had the (1994) World
Cup and put the soccer final there and sold it out. And now, with
the Women's World Cup, we've put the final there again. What we're
going for is the soccer hat trick.''
</P>
<P>
   So it's on. Sixteen countries will play a total of 32 games
during the tournament, which will be aired nationally by ABC, ESPN
or ESPN2, in addition to overseas television. The U.S., China,
Norway and Germany are the top seeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many iffy teams capable of having a tremendous
tournament that the chance of upsets are tremendous,'' said U.S.
coach Tony DiCicco. ``Even those lower tier of teams are emerging
as dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. dominated the inaugural Women's World Cup in 1991 by
outscoring its opponents 25-5. U.S. defender Brandi Chastain says
that won't happen again because other counties have continued to
get stronger.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, defending World Cup champion Norway defeated the U.S.
1-0 in the semifinals of the 1995 Women's World Cup in Sweden; but
the U.S. avenged that defeat by capturing the 1996 Gold Medal in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are a lot more teams like Norway that can defeat
the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is not the U.S. getting worse or people
catching up,'' said Chastain. ``It's other countries becoming more
involved with women's soccer. These countries always had the
potential to have good teams, it was just a matter of their
federations getting behind them and letting them play. The battle
was never could they play soccer, it was always about who would
allow them to play soccer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
