<HEADER>
A3256 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-DAVID-DUVAL-TEX     06-12 1936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DAVID-DUVAL-TEX </SLUG>
 
David Duval: Free and easy and on top of the golf world 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The wraparound sunglasses are off, allowing an unobstructed view
of blue eyes that have seen generous helpings of triumph and
tragedy through 27 years.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, this simple act serves as the perfect metaphor for
a 1999 season that has seen David Duval climb to the top of the
world golf rankings and willingly embrace the distractions that
come with it.
</P>
<P>
   As he made final preparations for the U.S. Open, which begins
Thursday at Pinehurst (N.C.) Resort and Country Club, Duval
acknowledged he finds the fuss that surrounds him puzzling. In his
mind, Duval is little more than a homebody who likes to read books,
catch fish and break par.
</P>
<P>
   Others, including his parents, view him as a survivor of two
childhood ordeals that steeled his resolve and narrowed his focus,
two traits that ultimately benefited his golf game. But friends and
family members believe mental scars resulting from his brother's
death and the breakup of his parents' marriage made Duval leery of
outsiders until the past couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   The truth, said Duval, probably rests somewhere in between. Yes,
Duval said, he still thinks occasionally of Brent, the older
brother who died in 1981 when bone marrow donated by 9-year-old
David was rejected by Brent's body. He would have preferred that
his parents, Bob and Diane, stay together, rather than separating
and eventually divorcing, in the wake of the profound grief that
accompanied Brent's death.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, those events helped shape Duval's lone-wolf
personality that others, including former college teammates at
Georgia Tech, have interpreted as arrogant and aloof.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Duval shows none of those traits on this day, which begins
with a practical joke orchestrated by playing partner Fred Funk. As
Duval waited to begin the second round of the Houston Open in late
April, Funk sneaked behind him carrying a life-size, cardboard
cutout of the PGA Tour's lone four-event winner this season.
</P>
<P>
   Printed at the top of the cardboard image were the phrases ``If
life were better, I'd be twins'' and ``I want to be like David.''
Funk donned a pair of Oakley shades, the signature piece of Duval's
golfing ensemble because they protect eyes sensitive to sunlight
and allergies. He wrapped his arm around the cardboard Duval and
smiled as fans began chuckling.
</P>
<P>
   Duval turned, roared with laughter and urged Funk to keep the
cutout ``in your house, behind the night stand.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Duval drowned a pair of approach shots and
ballooned to a 78, his worst score of the season. Instead of
grousing, he left the course in good spirits and spent several
minutes signing autographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get the biggest kick out of days like this,'' Duval said.
``I don't enjoy playing bad. But a day like this makes you
appreciate it more when things go well. You need one of these every
once in a while to maintain your perspective.''
DROPPING HIS GUARD
</P>
<P>
   Perspective is something Duval will tell you he has gained since
turning professional in 1993. First, by spending a couple of
humbling seasons on the Nike Tour and later by finding religion
(he's a practicing Christian) and establishing a long-term
relationship with Julie McArthur, his live-in girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Those have been key ingredients, Duval said, in a recent surge
that has seen him win 11 times in his past 38 PGA Tour events after
failing to post a victory in his first 86 career starts. They have
made him more willing to drop his guard, as well as his Oakleys,
and welcome interaction with outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I want to be to be known as a great player, want to achieve
great things in the game, then I have to be ready for the things
that come with it,'' said Duval, whose 1999 earnings total
($2,861,350) already stands as a single-season tour record. ``Image
is not something terribly important to me, but I must have done
stuff to achieve that \Raloof\S label. It did annoy me. What it
was, I don't know. I don't think it's really fair to draw
conclusions about someone when they're 21 and they haven't matured
into what their personality's going to be like.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see myself that way at all. I'm not a reluctant
participant in people getting to know me. I'm eager, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, Duval has shown a greater willingness to talk
about his brother's death, his once-strained relationship with his
father and other personal topics since making himself the odds-on
favorite to win player of the year honors by virtue of his
blistering start to the 1999 season. Just don't ask him to try to
connect today's great play with personal tragedies that surfaced 18
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's not relevant to what I'm doing out here. That
seems like a lifetime ago,'' said Duval, who leads the PGA Tour in
five statistical categories, including scoring average (69.01) and
greens in regulation (70.8 percent). ``I think people are well
aware of my brother's death and my parents' divorce. But I can't
grasp how \RBrent's death\S might have affected me. I was too
young.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, said Duval, he is puzzled _ and a bit
uncomfortable _ by the attention his past tribulations have
received since he became the world's top-ranked player after
winning The Players Championship on March 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I don't understand the fascination with me,'' said
Duval, who skipped both the GTE Byron Nelson Classic and the
MasterCard Colonial because he felt ``burned out'' by mounting
demands on his time. ``Other people have been through more. I
wouldn't use the word `trying' to describe my life ... because I
don't want it to sound like I need sympathy. It's not comfortable
stuff to hear about for a lot of people. It's not comfortable for
me to talk about, either. But those are the facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like it's a fact that, the longer you live, the more
you're going to run into some people who don't like you. We all
know we can't please everybody. I'm going to step on some toes. Not
intentionally, but I'm sure I will. I've done it before.''
KEEPING A LOW-KEY APPROACH
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent toe belonged to his father, Bob, the man who
chased a distraught David for several blocks through the streets of
Cleveland after he paid a last visit to his dying brother in a
children's hospital on May 17, 1981. Bob Duval said David, because
he had been a marrow donor in an unsuccessful transplant, ``blamed
himself'' for Brent's death and lapsed into a sullen fog that
seemed to lift only when his son retreated to the sanctuary of a
golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brent's death triggered a lot of things, none of them good,''
Bob Duval said.
</P>
<P>
   The first was a one-year separation of Duval's parents, shortly
after Brent's death. Although the couple reconciled, they
eventually divorced in 1993. By then, David had pounded enough
practice balls in lieu of an active social life that he'd earned a
spot on the Nike Tour.
</P>
<P>
   He responded to the divorce by avoiding contact with his father,
which Bob Duval considered ``perfectly understandable ... because
no one wants to see their family disrupted.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, their chilly relationship thawed to the point that
David served as his father's caddie during his Senior Tour debut in
1996. In March, when they became the first father-son tandem to win
PGA Tour and Senior Tour events on the same day, both were overcome
with emotion in discussing the significance of their shared feat.
</P>
<P>
   For Bob Duval, it marked his first career victory. For David, it
was his 10th in 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Asked who was proudest of the other, David Duval said: ``I think
I would win that award as the most proud. This is a special day.
We've been through a lot together.''
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, one significant piece of advice has been passed
down from generation to generation in the Duval family: Never fear
failure on the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the hardest things to learn out here,'' Duval
said. ``But it's the greatest golf gift I've ever received. Because
of my dad, I learned not to be afraid of shooting low scores.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval put that into practice Jan. 24, firing a closing round of
59 at the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic in which his 11 birdie putts
and one eagle putt traveled a combined 54 feet. Not only did he
pick up a victory and tie the PGA Tour record for lowest round in
history, several peers believe Duval might have turned in the
greatest ball-striking round the game has seen that afternoon in La
Quinta, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain. Duval's hot streak, unlike the early surge
by Tiger Woods that triggered ``Tigermania'' in 1997, has been
greeted with open arms by veteran players. Witness the willingness
of Funk, 42, to tease him on the tee box in Houston. Listen to Joey
Sindelar, 41, contrast the hot young player of 1999 with the rising
star of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their personalities are a lot different,'' Sindelar said.
``With David, there's no cockiness. In the past year, Tiger's come
a long way in that department. But in the beginning, he wasn't able
to be one of the guys for a while. David always was. He's had his
struggles, and he's paid his dues. Guys respect that about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players like David's low-key approach to what he does. It took
an eagle putt at the end for him to even pump his fist when he shot
his 59. We all realize he's an awesome player who's having a great
run, and we're happy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Lickliter, 29, said Duval showed who he really is in
Houston while shooting that 78 _ nine strokes above his season
average.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never acted frustrated or upset. We spent the whole day
talking about fishing,'' said Lickliter, who shot a 69 as Duval's
playing partner. ``David's so cool. Success hasn't changed him at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   But it has changed the way Lickliter views his former Nike Tour
peer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandkids,'' he said, ``will hear about this round. You can
bank on that.''
RATING HIS SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   Duval, in turn, will bank on a rare blend of power and finesse _
he's the only player ranked among the tour's top 10 in driving
distance (seventh), putting (second) and greens in regulation
(first) _ to continue building the star power that he craves. For
the moment, however, he considers himself unworthy of such acclaim
because he has no major championships on his resume.
</P>
<P>
   Others have compared his recent dominance of the golf world with
the success enjoyed by NASCAR driver Jeff Gordon or retired NBA
legend Michael Jordan. Duval disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's really inappropriate to compare me to Michael
Jordan or Jeff Gordon,'' Duval said. ``I don't think I've done it
long enough. That'd be a disservice to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, however, Duval envisions a place for himself in such
rarefied company.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's most certainly a desire. And I think I've shown that I
might have that potential,'' Duval said. ``But defining a great
golfer is a lot harder now than it was a generation ago. The level
of competition is higher and deeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, do you have to win eight majors, like Tom Watson did, to
be one of the great players? Is six enough, like Nick Faldo has?
I'm not sure how much the standard for greatness has changed over
the years. But whatever it is, I'd like to look back when it's over
and think that I got there.''
</P>
<P>
   When the time comes for reflecting, David Duval still figures to
be viewing the world through his wraparound sunglasses. But recent
indications show that he'll take time to drop his guard, as well as
his Oakleys, and sniff the flowers along the way.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
