<HEADLINE>
PEREZ MIGHT BE PULLED AS STARTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ After getting wracked in another start, Los Angeles
Dodgers manager Davey Johnson may be ready to pull lefty Carlos
Perez from the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he'll talk to Perez in the next few days and make a
decision. Perez's next start would be Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never do anything unless I put a lot of thought into it,''
Johnson said. ``I've been thinking about it for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson opts to go with another starter _ perhaps righty
Jamie Arnold _ the breaking point was easily Friday's loss to
Oakland. Perez allowed eight earned runs in 21/3 innings. He's 2-8
with a National League-worst 7.18 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had the utmost confidence in Carlos to start doing the
things to make him successful,'' Johnson said. ``He can't be out
there trying to paint the corners.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the latest debacle the Dodgers thought Perez was making
progress _ no matter how minute it seemed. However, Johnson said he
didn't see any type of progress against the A's. He also wasn't too
happy about Perez, who signed a three-year, $15.5 million contract
during the offseason, throwing 79 pitches and walking four batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to happen early (in the count),'' Johnson said. ``When
he's right, it doesn't take 130 pitches. It takes 100.''
</P>
<P>
   Catfish honored: Before the game the Athletics held a ceremony
to honor Hall of Famer Jim ``Catfish'' Hunter, and to raise money
and bring awareness to amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, also known as
Lou Gehrig's disease, from which Hunter is suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Emotion was strong as Hunter told the crowd about a saying he
once had over his locker: Winning isn't everything, but wanting to
is.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want something bad enough, you have to work for it,''
Hunter said. ``And that's what I'm going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter's presence also triggered emotions for Dodgers hitting
coach Rick Down, who met Hunter during spring training in 1989.
Down was the Yankees' roving hitting instructor and Hunter was a
special instructor at the Yankees' camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first year as a Yankee, Dallas Green was the manager and
the whole mystique of the Yankees and the lure, it can really take
you back,'' Down said. ``I didn't know where the ballpark was and I
was in the hotel and Catfish came up to me and offered to take me
to breakfast and he took me to the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have to. It was an awful nice gesture to extend a
hand like that. That's the kind of guy he is. He didn't have to
help me but he did just because he was that kind of guy. He won't
remember it, probably, but I don't forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   FYI: Dodgers center fielder Devon White returned to the lineup
after missing three games with a groin strain.... Brent Cookson
started in left field and Gary Sheffield was the Dodgers'
designated hitter.... Eric Young and Raul Mondesi each stole a base
off A's starter Kenny Rogers, the second and third stolen bases
he's allowed this season.... Rogers is 4-0 at home this season, has
won 16 straight at Oakland and is 14-0 with a 2.33 ERA here since
joining the A's.... Oakland's top draft pick, USC pitcher Barry
Zito, threw a bullpen session on the side wearing No.43, last worn
by Dennis Eckersley. Zito will report to Single-A Visalia on
Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
