<DOCNO> NYT19990612.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3325 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     06-12 1910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM STARS TO STALKED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shannon Miller felt sorry for the man who was
stalking her until police showed her a drawing they had discovered
in his apartment. The man had sketched Miller with her head hacked
off.
</P>
<P>
   More than a year after her fall from guilelessness, the most
decorated Olympic gymnast in U.S. history is still trying to regain
her emotional equilibrium. On the first anniversary of her
stalker's Feb., 1998 arrest, Miller had a bad dream. Somebody was
watching her, and hard as she tried, she couldn't escape his prying
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   She awoke cold and confused.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just feel claustrophobic,'' Miller says.
</P>
<P>
   Only since she started sharing her story has Miller come to
appreciate that she wasn't living the nightmare alone. People
approach her all the time, she says, with similar stories. It's
little wonder why. An estimated 1.4 million people are being
stalked in the U.S. In three of four reported cases, the objects of
obsession are women.
</P>
<P>
   An increasing number are athletes.
</P>
<P>
   From Temple University in Philadelphia to UCLA, alarmed college
administrators are forming focus groups to study the hot-button
issue, the way they once did binge drinking and fraternity hazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a phenomenon that across the board has gotten
really scary,'' said Sparks guard Jamila Wideman.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers, daughters, CEOs. Amateurs, collegians, pros. No one is
outside a stalker's range. Miller, the amateur, Wideman, the pro,
and Kyra Elzy, the collegian, found that out the horrible way. They
are part of a sickening sorority. All three have been pinned by
obsessed fans.
</P>
<P>
   Stalkers, 90 percent of whom suffer from mental disorders, take
the natural yearning to connect with another person to perverse
extremes. The more visible female athletes become, the more
vulnerable they are to obsessed fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question female athletes are at a higher risk,'' says
Dr. Park Dietz, a Southern California-based forensic psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
   Dietz has been studying stalking behavior for the past 20 years.
What he has found in his cases involving athletes is the high
profiles that launch a thousand press clippings are meat and
potatoes to a person starved to make a connection.
</P>
<P>
   The mundane details of an athlete's life that become a matter of
public record _ her dog's name, her favorite foods, her best
friend, her schedule, for example _ can whet an unstable fan's
appetite for contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``The personal information produced by the press on an athlete
can enhance the illusion of a personal relationship,'' Dietz says.
</P>
<P>
   Female athletes can reinforce the illusion without realizing it.
They are instructed, after all, to play by the Golden Rule. They
know to treat the public well.
</P>
<P>
   There are fans to be cultivated, one hello and handshake at a
time. Sportswomen are constantly reminded they are also saleswomen,
duty-bound to pitch their sport, to dive into crowds and do
backflips for the public. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Temple sports psychologist Carole Oglesby says, ``Female
athletes are more likely to extend themselves to fans beyond what
(their male counterparts) normally would. They'll reach out for
approval and a favorable response because they're aware of the fact
public attention generally is lacking and they want to encourage
some type of fan base.''
</P>
<P>
   The public knows it can count on female athletes to be polite.
They're usually much more than that, never comprehending anybody
could mean them harm. Their fans, secure in the knowledge they
won't be rejected, are thus emboldened.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general attitude of fans is that we are somehow available
to give ourselves to people,'' said the Sparks' Wideman. ``The
great majority of people are extremely supportive. I'm really glad
people see me as approachable. But it's very unsettling to know
that your accessibility opens you up to the possibility (of being
targeted) by people who don't understand clearly what boundaries
are.''
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA has its eyes wide open to the obsessive-fan phenomenon.
League representatives meet with each team and one of the things
they address is the dangers that potentially lurk behind a fan's
smiling face. The league also pays for plainclothes police to
patrol the area around both benches in its arenas on game nights.
</P>
<P>
   Even with precautions in place, an obsessed male fan stalked
Wideman her first two seasons with the Sparks. The deviant behavior
started the usual way, with a game-day encounter. From there it
escalated to phone calls and physical confrontations until Wideman
finally sought and obtained a restraining order against the man
last year.
</P>
<P>
   She is hesitant to divulge any more details because she doesn't
want to imbue her tormentor with more power (through publicity)
than he already has brandished over her. She does say she hasn't
seen him since.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be a little scary,'' Wideman says.
</P>
<P>
   She believes her background makes her an easier target for
obsessed fans. The daughter of Pulitzer Prize-winning author John
Edgar Wideman, she has been the subject of stories since she made
the varsity team at Amherst (Mass.) High as a seventh-grader. The
1993 season at Amherst _ her senior year _ was chronicled in a
book, ``In These Girls, Hope is a Muscle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What a lot of people look for is people who have been
humanized,'' Wideman says. ``From an emotional standpoint, I'm much
more real to people.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The torment of Elzy, a guard on the exalted Tennessee basketball
team, began with a tender note sent in the fall of her freshman
year in Knoxville, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you,'' it read. ``You're my sweet cake. You're the one
for me. I see you on TV and you're pretty as candy.''
</P>
<P>
   Elzy, a rising senior, giggled and her roommates laughed along
with her. It didn't seem so funny a few months later when the
letters were arriving daily, filled with marriage proposals and
love songs and a log of her comings and goings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting kind of scared,'' Elzy says. ``But I kept
blowing it off, being the naive person I am.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa man, who was in his late 30s, had been writing her for
more than a year before Elzy mentioned him to anyone on the
Tennessee coaching staff. The man became more bold in early 1998,
showing up at a game at Tennessee and slipping a note to Elzy
through an usher.
</P>
<P>
   Soon he was appearing like an apparition at the Vols' road
games. The university responded by placing extra security behind
the bench during home games and assigning someone to walk Elzy to
her car afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The man continued to pester Elzy until he was confronted after a
game by Vols coach Pat Summitt and Elzy's mother Sheryl, who is a
prison guard in Kentucky. Elzy didn't hear from him for three
months. Then one day in May of 1998 she was walking on campus and
there he was, not 50 yards away, waving at her like they were old
friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart dropped,'' Elzy says.
</P>
<P>
   When she couldn't ditch him, Elzy contacted an assistant coach
who called police. The man was arrested on campus and hauled into
court on charges of stalking and criminal trespassing. He was
sentenced to two years' probation and ordered not to attend any
more Tennessee basketball games. Elzy hasn't seen him since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously he has some kind of problem,'' she says. ``I was
lucky he was just in love with me and wasn't dangerous.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Miller, too, knows she was fortunate to escape the clutches of
her stalker with no physical scars. The man who would have Miller
running in fear for a couple of years before being convicted last
fall of misdemeanor stalking began his pursuit of the gymnast by
jogging past her family's house.
</P>
<P>
   When he began filling her answering machine with telephone
messages, Miller grew anxious. She went out of her way to spurn his
attentions, which only made the man, who was in his early 20s, more
aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   He moved into her apartment complex and enrolled at the
University of Oklahoma, where Miller was a student. Somehow he
wound up in the same meteorology class as Miller. A fitting bit of
irony, that, for he had become the tenebrous cloud in Miller's
otherwise sunny life.
</P>
<P>
   It got so bad, Miller says, she saw him out her apartment window
and in her sleep. Miller got ``really worried,'' as she puts it,
yet she told no one outside her family for fear of seeming panicky
and/or paranoid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt embarrassed to go to the police,'' Miller says. ``I
felt sorry for him because it was obvious something wasn't right
with him.''
</P>
<P>
   He proved Miller right about that when, in a fit of jealous
rage, he rear-ended a pickup truck driven by Chris Phillips in
February of last year. Phillips married Miller on Saturday but at
the time they only had just begun dating.
</P>
<P>
   After the accident, investigators combing the man's apartment
found 115 clippings that made mention of Miller and 16 videotapes
of her performances. And of course, the dismembered drawings.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw those drawings, it honestly made me sick,'' Miller
says. ``I had to leave the room, I was so ill. You're thinking to
yourself, this can't be happening to me, this isn't real. It's hard
to accept there could be someone out there who wants to hurt you.
It's almost like you try to remain naive about it and hope it just
goes away.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, Elzy and Wideman are wiser _ and warier _ now. When it
comes to protecting themselves against stalkers, they know
vigilance is the better part of valor. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SOMEBODY'S WATCHING ME
</P>
<P>
   A list of female athletes who have been hunted like prey by
obsessed fans reads like a Who's Who in the Wide World of Sports.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to gymnast Shannon Miller and basketball players
Jamila Wideman and Kyra Elzy, other stalking victims include tennis
players Monica Seles (the poster girl for fans' crazed behavior)
and Steffi Graf; basketball player/coach/commentator Cheryl Miller;
swimmers Janet Evans and Summer Sanders; golfers Annika Sorenstam
and Laura Davies; volleyball players Gabrielle Reece, Elaine Roque
and Laurie Jones and figure skater Katarina Witt.
</P>
<P>
   In conversations with many of them, familiar refrains rang out.
We've blended their voices into a chorus of Dos and Don'ts to
Safeguard Yourself Against Stalkers:
</P>
<P>
   _Do be vague when it comes to divulging personal information to
people you don't know well.
</P>
<P>
   _Don't, as a rule of thumb, give out your phone number or
address.
</P>
<P>
   _Do filter all requests for contact through a third party (a
coach, a team liaison, a parent, an agent).
</P>
<P>
   _Don't list your telephone number or address in the phone book.
</P>
<P>
   _Do invest in a post office box rather than have correspondence
sent to your home address.
</P>
<P>
   _Don't assume you can reason with a person who is bothering you.
When a stranger is stalking you, in the vast majority of cases it
is someone who suffers from a mental disorder that precludes him or
her from developing normal personal relationships through
conventional and socially acceptable means.
</P>
<P>
   _Do act swiftly to nip unwanted advances, no matter how
seemingly innocent, in the bud. Dispassionately let the person know
at the outset that you have no interest in developing a
relationship with him or her.
</P>
<P>
   _Don't put off contacting law enforcement officials if the
person persists in pestering you. At the very least, you'll
establish a paper trail.
</P>
</TEXT>
