<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-PLEASAC-DEAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLESAC ACQUIRED TO FILL BULLPEN HOLE  
 BATISTA, FRASCATORE GO TO TORONTO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The Diamondbacks have been searching for quite some
time for an experienced pitcher, preferably a left-hander, to add
to their bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   They finally made a deal for one Saturday, acquiring 37-year-old
Dan Plesac, a 13-year veteran with 153 career saves, from the
Toronto Blue Jays for infielder Tony Batista and right-handed
middle reliever John Frascatore.
</P>
<P>
   Plesac is scheduled to join the club today in time for the
finale of a three-game interleague series with the Anaheim Angels.
To fill Batista's spot on the roster, the Diamondbacks called up
infielder Edwin Diaz from their Triple-A Tucson affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   The question remains: How much does Plesac have left?
</P>
<P>
   He was 0-3 with an 8.34 ERA in 30 games for the Blue Jays. He
had a career-high 78 appearances in 1998, his third season with 70
or more.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter said the team wanted a
second left-hander in the bullpen to supplement Greg Swindell, who
signed as a free agent during the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have more flexibility,'' Showalter said. ``If you
brought in Greg in the sixth or seventh innings, you would lose
your match-ups (with left-handed hitters) later. Now we have
another guy. He's good against left-handers, but he can get
right-handers out, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Telling Batista and Frascatore) was pretty emotional. They
both did some good things for us, but we feel we got in return a
player who can make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter said Plesac throws a good fastball and change-up. His
best pitch may be his slider. Plesac has given up only nine hits in
44 at-bats (.205) against left-handers this season. He has 778
career appearances, 25th on the all-time list, including 774 in
relief. He began his career with Milwaukee in 1986 and pitched for
the Chicago Cubs and Pittsburgh before going to Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's another veteran guy who's been in the big leagues for 13
years and been in a lot of pressure situations,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Didier, senior assistant to General Manager Joe Garagiola
Jr., has been following Plesac, as have Ron Hassey, a special
assistant to Garagiola, and scout Ed Durkin.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've given us good reports,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Plesac's arrival also gives Showalter another option in the
closer's spot. Veteran right-hander Gregg Olson had a lock on the
role last season with 30 saves but has struggled this season. He
has eight saves but has blown six other opportunities.
Right-handers Byung-Hyun Kim, Vladimir Nunez and Darren Holmes also
are capable of filling the closer's role.
</P>
<P>
   Plesac will make $1.5 million this season, and the team will
have an option for next season.
</P>
<P>
   Frascatore, acquired from St. Louis for right-hander Clint
Sodowsky on March 30, was disappointed that he had been dealt a
second time. He was second on the club in appearances (26 to
Swindell's 27), with a 1-4 record and 4.09 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to leave a good team and a good bunch of guys. There's
a lot of uncertainty, especially going up into Canada,'' he said.
``I felt I did a good job. I knew they (Diamondbacks) were trying
to do something, but I didn't think I would be involved. I
understand what they're trying to do. I've been on teams with only
one lefty in the bullpen, and it doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter hedged on saying it, but Batista's departure means
that Andy Fox will be the starter at shortstop most of the time.
Batista began the season as the starter but struggled, and the two
had been in a platoon situation, the right-handed-hitting Batista
against left-handed pitchers and the left-handed-hitting Fox
against right-handers. Hanley Frias, a switch-hitter, started
Saturday night against the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has 73 career games at shortstop, 23 for the Diamondbacks
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a big surprise. I didn't see this coming at all,''
Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Fox didn't play shortstop last season after being
acquired in a spring trade with the New York Yankees, he did start
in 122 games at six positions. He hit .277 with nine homers and 44
RBIs in 502 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``With that many at-bats, I think I showed that I'm capable of
playing every day,'' Fox said. ``But I just go out and play. I
never think about, `Hey, I'm the guy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It is uncertain how long Diaz will be with the big club. Danny
Klassen, the organization's top middle-infield prospect, could be
called up soon, perhaps by next weekend's home series against the
Atlanta Braves. Klassen has had a sore left knee and recently had a
magnetic resonance imaging test as a precaution, but his status
does not appear to be in jeopardy. He was with the big club for a
month in 1998, playing in 29 games and starting 28 at second base.
</P>
<P>
   Batista was taken from the Oakland Athletics in the expansion
draft and played mostly at second base in 1998, hitting 18 home
runs. He moved to shortstop this season and veteran Jay Bell moved
to second. Batista started 38 games at short and hit .257 with five
homers and 21 RBIs. He is expected to give Toronto Manager Jim
Fregosi a boost at shortstop because Alex Gonzalez is out because
of an injury. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
