<HEADER>
A3332 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-MARLINS-NYT     06-12 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES BEAT MARLINS, 5-4  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1995 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Roger Clemens is the only five-time winner of the Cy
Young Award, but he is not a Cy Young Award candidate this year. So
far, he has been less than overwhelming and has been forced to
navigate through games with his experience, like a pilot working
without a computer or compass.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens struggled against the Florida Marlins Saturday night,
allowing seven hits, five walks and four runs in six innings, but
that was good enough, in the Yankees' 5-4 victory. Bernie Williams,
Paul O'Neill and Scott Brosius all hit home runs, as the Yankees
(35-24) won for the third straight game and moved one and a half
games ahead of Boston in the American League East.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill and Manager Joe Torre were ejected by the first-base
umpire, Brian Gibbons, in the eighth inning, after O'Neill was
called out on a pickoff play at first base. After being called out
_ the replay would indicate that Gibbons's call was incorrect _
O'Neill turned in disgust, pulled off his helmet and bounced it off
the ground. Gibbons immediately ejected O'Neill, spurring Torre
from his dugout seat, and after Torre informed Gibbons what he
thought of his umpiring and his call, Torre was tossed, for the
first time in the 23 games he has managed this year.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens practices self-analysis more than anyone other than
Woody Allen, and in spring training, Clemens mentioned how
important it is for him to command his adrenaline early in the
game; even after his first exhibition appearance for the Yankees,
he talked about this.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been games when Clemens has seemed unable to rein
in his emotions, Saturday night's game being only the latest
example. In his 10 starts, he has allowed 18 runs in innings 1 and
2, for an earned run average of 8.10; after the first two innings,
his e.r.a. is 3.63.
</P>
<P>
   After Williams bombed a two-run homer in the Yankees' first
inning, the Marlins quickly jumped on Clemens: Alex Gonzalez dumped
a double down the right-field line, Cliff Floyd singled, Bruce Aven
swung at a pitch on three balls and no strikes and bounced a single
through the right side of the infield. After Tim Hyers fell behind
no balls and two strikes, he pulled a hit to the right side. When
Preston Wilson grounded into a fielder's choice, Aven scored to
move the Marlins ahead, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is throwing hard, his fastball consistently clocking
anywhere from 92 to 95 miles an hour. But Saturday night, he had
trouble developing a secondary pitch with which to finish off the
Marlins' hitters after getting ahead in the count _ a splitter in
the dirt, a slider or a curveball.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens often seemed to battle the Marlins with only his
fastball, and as the conventional wisdom goes, major league hitters
will eventually hurt you if you throw only fastballs, no matter how
hard you throw. Clemens reached two-strike counts on 11 occasions
in the first five innings, and 7 of those 11 batters reached base
with a hit or a walk.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees resorted to the long ball to regain the lead
against Livan Hernandez, who constantly placed himself in
compromising situations: He threw a ball on the first pitch to 14
of the first 24 batters he faced, and in one stretch of 10 batters,
he threw at least four pitches to each hitter.
</P>
<P>
   And Hernandez's breaking ball was not fine. He tried to spin a
slider to Paul O'Neill leading off the fourth, and O'Neill waited
and waited for it and stretched his body and swung, his back foot
lifting off the ground just after contact. For some hitters, the
imbalance would mean a groundout to second, but O'Neill blasted a
tremendous home run to right-center field, tying the score, 3-3.
O'Neill has seven home runs this season.
</P>
<P>
   Three batters later, Hernandez hung a slider to Brosius, the
pitch heart-high, and Brosius crushed it, far and long and high
over the left-field wall; Yankees 4, Marlins 3.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the theme, Kevin Orie led off the bottom of the
same inning for Florida by bashing Clemens's first pitch _ a
split-fingered fastball that didn't drop _ for a game-tying home
run.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees moved ahead once more in the fifth inning. Chuck
Knoblauch worked a walk and when Derek Jeter singled to right,
Knoblauch sped around second and pulled into third. The Marlins'
infield played back, rather than moving in and trying to cut off
the run at the plate, and when Williams grounded to second base and
the Marlins tried unsuccessfully to turn a double play, Knoblauch
crossed the plate to push the Yankees ahead, 5-4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
