</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FILM-AUCTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUCTIONING OFF THE TREASURES OF RALPH KRAMDEN AND SCARLETT  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What price memory? How much of today's cash does it
take to own a vestige of yesterday's passion?
</P>
<P>
   For someone else's Oscar, Michael Jackson paid $1,542,500 at
Sotheby's Saturday. The singer's winning bid, for the gold-plated
Best Picture statuette awarded in 1939 to the producer David O.
Selznick for ``Gone with the Wind,'' dwarfed the previous Oscar
auction record of $607,500 paid in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson, whose own doo-dads have occassionally gone on the
auction block and who has been known to bid on such esoteric items
as an obscure Sinclair Lewis novel, was not alone in taking
nostalgia to inflationary heights.
</P>
<P>
   For a slate blue wool jacket and matching pants worn about 45
years ago by the overweight (49 1/2-inch waist, 49 3/4-inch chest)
Brooklyn bus driver Ralph Kramden, aka Jackie Gleason, an
unidentified but obviously devoted fan of the ``The Honeymooners''
television shows paid $64,100.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, as he banged his gavel, the Sotheby's auctioneer
murmured, ``How sweet it is!''
</P>
<P>
   For a pink percale dress with ruffled sleeves and lace collar
worn by Vivien Leigh as Atlanta burned in ``Gone with the Wind,'' a
darkly beautiful Brazilian woman in a black fishnet veil and prim
black gloves paid $90,500.
</P>
<P>
   She would identify herself only as Elizabeth, the proud owner of
trunkloads of Ms. Leigh's hats and clothing and a Sao Paolo
restaurant named, not surprisingly, ``Scarlett's.''
</P>
<P>
   Deepening the mystery with hyperbole, her 11-year-old son,
Rodrigo, said his mother is famous back home not only for greeting
her customers in full Southern Belle gloved-and-petticoated
regalia, but for having seen ``Gone with the Wind'' upwards of
8,000 times since her first fateful encounter with the movie 31
years ago, as an impressionable 8-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, although perhaps on a slightly different scale, a
Manhattan psychologist recaptured a bit of his childhood for
$1,035, buying a wooden mural of a clown and a dashing bejeweled
couple riding a carpet through the clouds that once adorned the
Magic Carpet ride at Coney Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more thrilling than any rollercoaster,'' said Barry S.
Lubetkin, recalling how the whole chair of the ride collapsed and
left its screeching occupant involuntarily recumbent. ``It's one of
my strongest memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Lubetkin, now 55, said he intends to hang his newly acquired
amusement park memorabilia above the couch in his office. ``I'm a
shrink,'' he joked. ``I use magic carpets in therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   Other pieces of Coney Island rides and attractions also were
sold at prices ranging up to a high of $10,350, for the garish
7-foot-tall bubble-blowing clown face that used to delight children
at the Brooklyn park. But perhaps Coney Island's most famous lady,
the mechanical Fat Lady called Minnie Ha Ha, did not draw a bid
high enough to be sold.
</P>
<P>
   Its owner, Leonard Goodstein, said he would put it on display at
the Brooklyn Historical Society museum. ``It's time,'' he said,
``to let my childhood go.''
</P>
<P>
   The price paid for Selznick's Oscar was vastly higher than the
$200,000 to $300,000 estimate made by Sotheby's in advance of the
auction, which also sold the final shooting script belonging to the
producer's script assistant on ``Gone With the Wind'' for $33,350.
</P>
<P>
   Cinema flotsam, especially from the classics, has fetched
increasingly high prices over the past decade, but the interests
and passion of film buffs and collectors can be wildly
unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   Clark Gable's leather-bound script from ``Gone With the Wind''
brought $77,000 in 1994. But in 1996, the director, Steven
Spielberg, bought Gable's Oscar for his role as a reporter in ``It
Happened One Night'' for $607,500 and then presented it as a gift
to the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Television and rock aficianados, at least those at Sotheby's
Saturday, do not appear to have the same deep pockets.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of John Lennon's wire-rimmed prescription glasses sold
for $25,875 and a copy of ``Sgt. Peppers Lonely Hearts Club Band''
signed by all four Beatles brought $57,500.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen suite _ a battered table and chairs, a dresser and
icebox _ from ``The Honeymooners'' show during the 1960s, when
Gleason and friends filmed it in Miami, was bought for $63,000 by
the TV Land cable network.
</P>
<P>
   Larry W. Jones, the general manager, said he plans to take the
furniture from Ralph Kramden's fictional cold-water flat on the
road to promote his company's airing of reruns from the show,
starting in January.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's officials said they could not identify the buyer of
the oversized blue bus driver's outfit worn, around the mid-1950s,
by Gleason. The bid was received by telephone. But Peter Crescenti,
one of the two remaining members of RALPH, the Royal Association
for the Longevity and Preservation of the Honeymooners, said the
outfit is one of very very many produced over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gleason was notorious for having his weight go up and down,''
said Crescenti, who put the Gleason memorabilia up for sale. ``So
there were a lot on hand.'' The one sold was from one of the star's
heavier periods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
