<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPT-BICKLEY-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIM, BELLE, PERDUE: IT'S ALL SO GREASY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith has taken a little break
from a drawn-out coaching search and was rumored to be spending a
little time in San Diego, where, apparently, he is interviewing
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Let me get this straight: Sammy Sosa takes a bow and triggers
beanball warfare. Byung-Hyun Kim takes a bow and is hailed for good
manners.
</P>
<P>
   If Kim is found guilty of cheating, the question is this: Did an
unassuming kid bring these habits to America? Or did he learn such
trickery inside the locker room at BOB? And if that's the case,
someone pass the petroleum jelly to Gregg Olson.
</P>
<P>
   If hitting a baseball is really the toughest thing in sports,
isn't it odd that pitchers feel the need to doctor baseballs, scuff
baseballs and throw them at a hitter's head?
</P>
<P>
   The Suns held a workout Saturday for Israeli star Oded Katash, a
small kid with a great shot who might be playing for the Knicks if
not for the NBA lockout. In fact, Israeli newspapers say that Tom
Chambers wants Katash in a Suns uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Before you laugh at the notion of Albert Belle giving financial
advice on his Web site, understand that he makes $19,000 every trip
to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Proof that arrogance has not died at Bank One Ballpark:
</P>
<P>
   ``My chest swells out every time I see Jay Bell and Matt
Williams and Luis Gonzalez and Steve Finley _ and I could go on and
on _ run around the bases after a home run,'' Diamondbacks Manager
Buck Showalter said. ``It's not a look-at-me mentality. We have so
many guys here whose substance is their style instead of their
style being their substance. I know things have changed in our
society, but a lot of guys here are easy to be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   As always, air sickness bags are located underneath your tray
tables.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing wrong with San Antonio in the NBA Finals, except for the
prospect of Will Perdue winning his fourth championship ring.
</P>
<P>
   The Dead Presidents Cup: Aside from offering what could be the
most entertaining NHL finale in years, Dallas and Buffalo are two
cities where a U.S. president was assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing against David Duval, but suffering second-degree burns
while lifting a teapot is merely the perfect metaphor ever for a
country club sport.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Marcus Camby is no longer tagged as Marcus Gumby (or
Cotton Camby), now that the eighth-seeded Knicks are headed to the
Finals, Ernie Grunfeld should be General Manager of the Year. And
the first to be fired during midseason.
</P>
<P>
   Good-natured jab delivered at Diamondbacks pitcher Brian
Anderson following a short stint against the Cubs:
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian, I hate to tell you this, but you're not going to win
the ERA title this year,'' Andy Benes said.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Jeff Van Gundy has reached the Finals and is guaranteed
$3.3 million next season, could he do us a favor and buy himself
some sleep?
</P>
<P>
   The lollipop kids: Olympic gymnast Shannon Miller got married on
Saturday and stood exactly one inch taller than her five-foot-high,
butter-cream wedding cake.
</P>
<P>
   Good stuff: After a diet of tutoring sessions and night classes,
ASU basketball recruit Donnell Knight posted the highest SAT score
of any Sun Devils hoopster in the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA is floating the notion of ineligibility for freshmen in
basketball, an asinine concept that would only encourage high
school kids to opt for the NBA. So how about this: Have the NBA
fund a developmental league and any kid who goes to college can't
be drafted for three years. And don't tell me it would open a
floodgate of lawsuits. It works in baseball, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   The ``Chicago Tribune'' reported that the Blackhawks, through
tamperproof channels, have contacted Jeremy Roenick and asked how
he'd feel about a return to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly what Roenick had in mind when he decided to play
Game 7 with a broken jaw.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Tocchet, on marital bliss: ``My wife wants me to play
another five years, minimum. And when I look at my American Express
bill, I know why.'' &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
