<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release on Sunday, June 20) 
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending June 5, at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. SUMMER SISTERS, by Judy Blume. (Dell, $7.50.) Two
</P>
<P>
   young women from very different backgrounds come of
</P>
<P>
   age on Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   2. BAG OF BONES, by Stephen King. (Pocket, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A series of terrifying events besets a best-
</P>
<P>
   selling novelist four years after his wife's death.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE PILOT'S WIFE, by Anita Shreve. (Back Bay/Little, Brown,
</P>
<P>
   $13.95.) After learning that a plane flown by her husband
</P>
<P>
   has exploded, a woman tries to unravel the secret life
</P>
<P>
   he led.
</P>
<P>
   4. THE BLESSING, by Jude Deveraux. (Pocket, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A corporate executive and his physician brother fall
</P>
<P>
   in love with the same young widow.
</P>
<P>
   5. SECRET PREY, by John Sandford. (Berkley, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Lucas Davenport pursues the killer of a corporate
</P>
<P>
   chairman who was on a hunting trip.
</P>
<P>
   6. THE MIDNIGHT CLUB, by James Patterson. (Warner
</P>
<P>
   Vision, $6.99.) A New York journalist finds herself
</P>
<P>
   threatened by a psychopathic killer.
</P>
<P>
   7. SERPENT, by Clive Cussler with Paul Kemprecos.
</P>
<P>
   (Pocket, $16.) The Andrea Doria's remains yield
</P>
<P>
   treasures that point to a deadly conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   8. MEMOIRS OF A GEISHA, by Arthur Golden. (Vintage, $14.)
</P>
<P>
   The life of a young woman growing up in Kyoto who has
</P>
<P>
   to reinvent herself after World War II begins.
</P>
<P>
   9. GENUINE LIES, by Nora Roberts. (Bantam, $7.50)
</P>
<P>
   A biographer has a problem: to reveal or conceal the
</P>
<P>
   secrets of a glamorous film actress.
</P>
<P>
   10. THE FACE OF DECEPTION, by Iris Johansen. (Bantam,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) A woman who helps identify the dead from their
</P>
<P>
   skulls is enmeshed in danger.
</P>
<P>
   11. LOW COUNTRY, by Anne Rivers Siddons. (Harper Paperbacks,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) The husband of a South Carolina woman considers
</P>
<P>
   turning the island she inherited into a resort.
</P>
<P>
   12.(x) YOU BELONG TO ME, by Mary Higgins Clark. (Pocket,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) A radio talk-show host attempts to expose a
</P>
<P>
   killer who targets lonely women.
</P>
<P>
   13. I KNOW THIS MUCH IS TRUE, by Wally Lamb. (Regan Books/
</P>
<P>
   Harper Perennial, $16.) A troubled man must care for his
</P>
<P>
   schizophrenic twin brother.
</P>
<P>
   14.(x) THE READER, by Bernhard Schlink. (Vintage, $11.)
</P>
<P>
   A German high school student falls in love with a
</P>
<P>
   former Auschwitz employee.
</P>
<P>
   15. THE GENERAL'S DAUGHTER, by Nelson DeMille. (Warner,
</P>
<P>
   $7.50.) The investigation of the murder of an officer,
</P>
<P>
   a general's daughter, unearths scandals in the military.
</P>
