<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 23:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3350 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     06-12 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 20)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; DREAMLAND: TRAVELS INSIDE THE SECRET WORLD OF ROSWELL AND AREA
51 &LR;  By Phil Patton. Villard, $12.95. This offbeat history explores
the once top-secret military base in Nevada where experimental
aircraft were tested, and the flying-saucer subculture and
conspiracy theories that have flourished around it. The author ``is
keenly interested in the origins of UFO lore and in all things
aeronautical,'' Glyn Vincent wrote in The New York Times Book
Review in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE NEWTON LETTER &LR;  By John Banville. Godine, $10.95. After
renting a cottage in rural Ireland to work on a biography of Isaac
Newton, a historian becomes obsessed with an eccentric family whose
members echo characters from an 1809 Goethe novel. In 1987 the
reviewer Molly Hite called this a ``powerful novella'' with much to
say about literary history and the history of science.
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has reissued another novel by Banville,
 &UR; MEFISTO &LR;  ($13.95), a modern version of the Faust legend in which a
math prodigy is seduced by a trio that includes a portly engineer,
a deaf woman and a winking master of ceremonies named Felix.
```Mefisto' is a novel of virtuosic scope, written in a style as
pristine as the rarefied mountain air atop the Brocken, the
witches' gathering place on Walpurgisnacht,'' Amy Boaz wrote in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO: A SHORT HISTORY &LR;  By Noel Malcolm. Harper Perennial,
$16. This carefully researched account by a British journalist,
published last year before the conflict in Kosovo but updated with
a new preface, reveals how much history matters in the Balkans and
how much of today's strife is linked to a mythologized past. The
result is a ``painfully useful ... well-written, readable book,''
the reviewer Anna Husarska wrote.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LAST RESORT &LR;  By Alison Lurie. Owl/Holt, $13. This
bittersweet story features men and women who move to Key West for
desperate, misguided and even sensible reasons and find themselves
baking in the hothouse at the nation's southern tip. ``The novel
and its readers ... have great fun with what these people expect
from their southward migration, and what they wind up getting,''
Francine Prose wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY MAN &LR;  By Calvin Trillin. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $11.
The curmudgeonly author turns to family life _ his own _ in this
collection of low-key humorous essays devoted to his domestic
adventures with his wife and two daughters. ``It's hard to think of
another writer who so consistently manages to be acerbic without
being mean, a literary Houdini act that has won Trillin legions of
readers,'' Suzanne Berne wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has reissued  &UR; WANTING A CHILD &LR; , edited by
Jill Bialosky and Helen Schulman ($13), in which 22 writers recount
their difficult, often painful struggles to conceive or adopt
children. ``Each story in this moving anthology reiterates the
universal need to be a parent,'' Leslie Chess Feller wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAVEDWELLER &LR;  By Dorothy Allison. Plume, $13.95. In the second
novel by the author of ``Bastard Out of Carolina,'' a rock 'n' roll
singer returns to her roots in rural Georgia and the two daughters
she abandoned when she fled her first marriage. This ``unabashedly
emotional'' story ``pays close attention to the way women get by,
the way they come to forgive one another, the way they choose who
they will be,'' Valerie Sayers wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SOLIBO MAGNIFICENT &LR;  By Patrick Chamoiseau. Vintage
International, $12. This novel, originally published in French in
1988, revolves around a storyteller whose death from strangulation
by words is emblematic of the destruction of Creole in the French
Caribbean and the author's attempt to supplant it with a home-grown
hybrid of his own. The book ``wonderfully illustrates the moment
when oral literature reluctantly leaves the stage clear for the
written word,'' Caryl Phillips wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITIZEN LORD: THE LIFE OF EDWARD FITZGERALD, IRISH
REVOLUTIONARY &LR;  By Stella Tillyard. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $15.
Lord Edward Fitzgerald was a handsome, high-spirited aristocrat who
abandoned a promising career in the British army and wound up
taking part in the 1798 Irish rebellion. Last year the reviewer
Thomas Flanagan called this a persuasive portrait of ``a committed
revolutionary, more radical in his politics than the other Irish
leaders, more resolute and reckless in action.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IRISH REBEL: JOHN DEVOY AND AMERICA'S FIGHT FOR IRELAND'S
FREEDOM &LR; , by Terry Golway (St. Martin's Griffin, $15.95),
chronicles the life and times of an ardent nationalist who fled his
country in 1871 and spent the next 57 years trying to raise
American support for Irish independence. ``Golway ... has produced
a well-researched biography of a man whose life has hitherto been
given too little attention,'' the reviewer David Murray wrote in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIKE A HOLE IN THE HEAD &LR;  By Jen Banbury. Mysterious
Press/Warner, $12. The heroine of this raucous first novel, who
spends much of her time tossing wisecracks at crazed hoodlums as
she hunts down a missing book in Los Angeles, ``is just as
hard-boiled as ... Sam Spade, and she's a lot funnier,'' Brian
Morton wrote in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
