<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3352 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     06-12 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF JACKSON'S IN, COUNT ON HARPER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Playing 58 games in 108 days took a toll on Derek
Harper's 37-year-old body. The bitterness of a playoff sweep took
its toll on his resolve, and it all left the Los Angeles Lakers
veteran considering retirement when the season came to a crashing
halt last month.
</P>
<P>
   But it took just two words to get Harper jazzed for a 17th NBA
season.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking by phone from his home in Dallas on Saturday, Harper
enthusiastically became the first Lakers player to publicly endorse
Jackson, who is close to signing a deal to become coach. An
announcement could come in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a dream come true for the Lakers to get Phil
Jackson. I would come back in a heartbeat if Phil Jackson is
coach,'' said Harper, who has one year left on his contract. ``I
would cherish the opportunity just to be around a guy like that.
I've played for a lot of great coaches, from Pat Riley (in New
York) to Dick Motta (Dallas) to Chuck Daly (Orlando). Adding him to
my portfolio, so to speak, would do nothing but help my career, at
the end of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   And might help Harper win the elusive NBA championship ring he's
coveted since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson won six rings as head coach of the Chicago Bulls, and
while Michael Jordan deservedly gets much of the credit, Jackson
played a vital role, Harper said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust me, Phil Jackson orchestrated a lot of Chicago's
success,'' he said. ``The guy's a winner, he's a proven winner. He
was on a championship team in New York (as a player in 1972-73),
and he's just a respected person, a respected coach, a coach that
obviously is a no-nonsense coach....
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to some of the Chicago players. He's a good guy,
but he also finds a way to motivate players and hold them
accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, Harper said, might be what the young Lakers _ built
around 27-year-old Shaquille O'Neal and 20-year-old Kobe Bryant _
need most. Harper didn't say it, but the Lakers' problems might
have been too much for rookie coach Kurt Rambis to handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Kurt did as good as he could being in a new
situation,'' Harper said. ``Phil's experience would definitely help
our young team.... Phil adds a lot of stability.''
</P>
<P>
   And Jackson's presence might help distill the locker-room
chemistry problems that plagued the Lakers this season. Competing
egos and agendas contributed to a subpar season for the
star-studded roster.
</P>
<P>
   But in guiding the Bulls to six championships in eight years,
Jackson managed to corral the Goliath egos of Michael Jordan and
Scottie Pippen and the unpredictability of Dennis Rodman while
maximizing role players like Steve Kerr and John Paxson.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at Chicago's situation, Dennis (Rodman) was
there, and they had a lot of different personalities there, too,''
Harper said. ``Phil, he's as good as anybody at getting it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper spent much of his first season with the Lakers preaching
sacrifice and teamwork, but those messages only occasionally got
through. So the Lakers found themselves watching the conference
finals on TV, while teams with less talent but more selfless play
and willing role players competed for bids to the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy like Phil would definitely be able to get guys to play
those roles,'' Harper said. ``Take a guy like Ron Harper (no
relation), who was an All-Star once or twice in his career and a
big-time scorer (with Cleveland and the Clippers). (Jackson) got
him to play a defensive role. That's what it's all about, man. It's
about accepting a role and being committed and willing to
sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Lakers, Jackson would have to find a way to mesh the
talents of O'Neal, Bryant and Glen Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel in my heart that all three of those guys can play
on the same court, but it's gonna take sacrifices for the good of
the team,'' Harper said. ``You look at (Robert) Horry, (Rick) Fox,
(Derek) Fisher, all of our little guys are willing to sacrifice.
Without a doubt, Shaq, Kobe, Glen _ our stars _ they're gonna have
to sacrifice too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
