<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-12 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3356 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-SWANN-AZR &LR;      06-12 1513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-SWANN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWANN STAYING MUM ABOUT KNEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - One can envision Eric Swann firing out of his
three-point stance, striking with his trademark fierce charge, and
taking down all his frustration in a big bear-hug tackle 6 yards
behind the line. If he were right.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, perhaps as early as September, Swann might once again
be able to do that to an opposing quarterback. Returning to the
dominating level of play that caused him to be regarded as one of
the premier defensive left tackles in the business would soothe the
riled waters of his mind, one would suspect.
</P>
<P>
   For now, one can only suspect because Swann continues under a
shroud of secrecy his rehabilitation on his arthritic right knee on
which two more surgeries were performed in the closing 10 weeks of
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Where he is in the process and how he feels about the public
reaction to his decision to have the second surgical procedure at
the height of the Cardinals' playoff run remain his private domain.
</P>
<P>
   Swann is not talking. His latest surgeon, Dr. Richard Steadman,
is not talking. Until Friday, after the latest bizarre rumor
regarding Swann had taken on a life of its own, Swann's agent,
Steve Zucker, was not talking. Earl Edwards, the Cardinals player
programs coordinator, who has served as a mentor to Swann, did not
return phone calls Friday.
</P>
<P>
   His coaches say that Swann, who can disrupt an opposing blocking
scheme as few others in the game can, is on schedule. They say they
base that on reports relayed to them from team medical personnel,
who in turn are getting information from Swann's caregivers.
</P>
<P>
   Swann did not get results that satisfied him from a procedure
performed by team medical personnel last Oct. 28. Swann, who at 28
has had four surgeries on his right knee and two on his left,
sought outside advice. He turned to Steadman of Vail, Colo.,
orthopedic surgeon of the U.S. Olympic Ski team. Steadman convinced
Swann to have a microfracture performed on Dec. 7. It would end
Swann's season but perhaps prolong his career.
</P>
<P>
   That subjected Swann to widespread criticism from inside and
outside the organization, to which he did not take kindly, hence
the information vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a player's perspective, regardless of what amount of
money you've been paid, you're still human and you still have
feelings,'' said Joe Greene, the Cardinals defensive line coach and
a member of the Pro Football Hall of Fame. ``And when you put
yourself on the line game in and game out, and then you're being
questioned about your manhood and your toughness from someone
that's never walked the walk, if he gives a damn what people say,
then it bothers him. Some of us understand that we can't change how
people think, and don't try.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding more mystique to Swann's situation are reports such as
this innocuous one in a Valley newspaper last week that Swann ``had
an unspecified internal procedure done recently, possibly for
stomach-related problems.'' From that grew reports on Internet
sites that Swann faced life-threatening or career-ending surgery.
That only fueled further speculation on talk radio.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder that Swann won't talk?
</P>
<P>
   But Zucker finally did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where these rumors get started,'' Zucker said
Friday, ``but it's absolutely not true.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is almost certain to further enrage a private man who now
might have more reason than ever to feel burned by fans, the media,
and perhaps even the Cardinals, who did not hide their displeasure
with Swann's decision to step outside their medical network. Club
officials were incensed when Swann informed them Thanksgiving
morning that he was going to do it.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches are hopeful that Swann comes back and takes it out
on a schedule of opponents that is among the toughest they ever
have faced, as they hope for a return trip to the playoffs, where
they won a game for the first time in 51 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't talked to him in a while but the report I get
through our medical people is he's on time and on line to return
once the season starts, that's all I know,'' said defensive
coordinator Dave McGinnis. ``Mentally, he feels like he really
missed out on something last year, the special feelings. He was
here every day and in meetings but he wasn't on the field. He
missed out on a big happening that went on here. He knows this
football team is on the upswing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, the first couple of days in minicamp (in May) we had
to take him out and slow him down because we knew this was not what
he was supposed to be doing. He's wanting to get out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Swann refused interview requests during minicamp last month.
</P>
<P>
   He recently flew to Pennsylvania to take part in a golf outing
organized by center Mike Devlin to raise money in the name of
Devlin's late father for a scholarship. Cardinals players who were
there said Swann looked great and seemed fine. Swann played in the
group that finished third.
</P>
<P>
   One who has been unwavering in support of Swann is Greene, who
knows what an arthritic knee feels like.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had mine for 25 years,'' Greene said. ``Arthritis does
hurt and there's no way you can get rid of that, and that's the
line that he's been given. But he thought it was something more
than arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how Eric felt, or what made other people say what
they said. But having walked in Eric's shoes before, the most
important thing a guy thinks about is taking care of his team and
his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   His health comes somewhere second or third. Eric felt that he
wasn't holding up his end of the bargain based on the way things
were going. He got an opportunity, a small opportunity, to improve
it, and he took it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals wanted to hustle Swann back into action six weeks
after his first surgery. They saw a chance to have a winning record
and get to the playoffs, goals they ultimately would accomplish
anyway without Swann.
</P>
<P>
   Swann continued to complain of pain four weeks into the first
rehab. Steadman convinced Swann that without Steadman's
microfracture procedure, Swann risked seriously injuring the knee
if he came back.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Swann's teammates were irked that he would elect to have
the season-ending procedure. With Swann, the Cardinals were among
the best in the league at stopping the run. Without him, they
quickly plummeted to the lower echelon. In seven games, Swann made
33 tackles, four sacks, had seven quarterback hurries, five tackles
for loss, four pass deflections, and two forced fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers attest to Swann being among the premier defensive
tackles, something the Cardinals also believed when they rewarded
him with a five-year, $25 million contract before the 1998 season.
It included what then was a team-record $7.5 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Five games into the season, Swann felt his knee flaring up. He
played two more games, practicing very little during the weeks
leading up to them, hoping to coax enough out of the knee to get
him through the season. He agreed to the October surgery by Russell
Chick, team orthopedic surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very difficult thing having gone out and set a standard
for yourself like Eric had, being a dominating player, then not
being able to deliver on that game in and game out,'' Greene said.
``Not only is it physically draining but it's mentally draining.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthritis is damage to surface cartilage that covers the bone at
a joint. It starts as a softening of firm cartilage, then becomes
rough and fissured, then eventually disappearing so the underlying
bone is exposed. If there is lost meniscal pad, it can lead to an
aggressive form of arthritis at a relatively young age. It is not
uncommon among linemen who are carrying a lot of weight. Swann (6
feet 5, 315 pounds), who had meniscus cartilage removed from the
right knee in 1995, is an example.
</P>
<P>
   Swann couldn't get into a football stance or push off on his
right leg when Steadman examined him just over a month after the
surgery by Chick. Swann agreed to let Steadman do it again his way,
refusing requests by the team to get an outside third opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The Steadman procedure ended Swann's season. That set off the
old-timers and the self-proclaimed experts harkening to players
from an era in which if they could walk he could play.
</P>
<P>
   Swann was on crutches for more than two months after Steadman's
procedure, which involves drilling a series of holes around the
joint causing a cartilage cap to be recreated. The initial
prognosis was for a six- or seven-month rehab. He was doing
minicamp walkthroughs at six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Eric understands that it's always going to be painful,
that arthritis is that way,'' Greene said. ``But he didn't think
this particular thing was just arthritis. That's what he told me.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all hope he's ready for the opener. . . . Eric is a force
in there. He is powerful. He does things you don't coach. When he's
right nobody can handle him. That's what we want.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-99 2341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
