r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-OPEN-LEHMAN-AZR &LR;      06-12 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-LEHMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
4-TIME OPEN BRIDESMAID  
 LEHMAN AIMS TO END NEAR-MISSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They say that nothing is fair at a U.S. Open. The rough is too
deep, the fairways too tight, the greens like lightning and the
pins untouchable.
</P>
<P>
   Patience seems to be the prevailing virtue, because the U.S.
Open reserves the right to be fickle.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lehman knows how it goes only too well. For the past four
national championships, the Scottsdale pro has been paired in the
final group on Sunday, a distinction he shares with the legendary
Bobby Jones (1927-30). But unlike ``The Greatest,'' who captured
four Opens and was the runner-up in four others, Lehman has yet to
solve this intricate equation for victory in the U.S. Golf
Association's most prestigious event.
</P>
<P>
   Two opportunities were especially painful:
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, at Oakland Hills in Michigan, Lehman was tied with
Steve Jones as they walked to the final tee. Jones selected a
3-wood, while Lehman opted to go with a driver. It was a costly
mistake, as Lehman's ball raced through the fairway and
parallel-parked against the lip of a bunker. The resulting bogey
left him in a tie for second place, as Jones went on to make par
and win by a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, at Congressional Country Club outside of Washington,
Lehman was chasing Ernie Els down the stretch when he tried to go
for the pin at No. 17 with a 7-iron. The shot was pulled slightly,
and the ball took one hop and disappeared in the water, dunking
Lehman into third place behind Els and runner-up Colin Montgomerie.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman also had near-misses in the '95 Open at Shinnecock
(N.Y.), and last year at the Olympic Club near San Francisco. Both
times he was paired with the leader before ending up tied for third
and tied for fifth, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Lehman's failures are grounded in reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything, I beat myself by being too aggressive,
trying to make too much happen, which led to bogeys,'' explained
Lehman, 40, whose only major in his four career victories was the
1996 British Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, I wouldn't trade the experience for
anything. It was very enjoyable being part of the drama in an Open.
I think you have to look at the bright side, pat yourself on the
back and learn from your mistakes. Those near-misses hurt, but I'm
looking forward to the future.'' &QL; 
Late start &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lehman only hopes he can be in the final twosome at Pinehurst
No. 2 when the 99th U.S. Open unfolds Thursday through Sunday in
the big pines of North Carolina's most storied golf community. He
certainly will be among the favorites, based on his track record
and his improved play as the 1999 season wears on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, things are beginning to come around,'' Lehman said
Friday just before a flu bug attacked him midway through the second
round of the FedEx/St. Jude Classic in Memphis, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a grind, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shoulder took longer (to rehabilitate) than I expected,''
Lehman said of an injury that dates to last year's British Open.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Lehman did not start his '99 campaign until late
February. In 10 tournaments, his best finishes are a runner-up in
the Bay Hill Invitational and a fifth place at Greater Greensboro.
His 70.36 scoring average ranks him 25th among his peers. He enters
today's final round of the St. Jude Classic in a four-way tie for
the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the U.S. Open hardly equates with play on the PGA
Tour. For whatever reason, guys like Lehman tend to take it up a
notch in the major championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the reasons I play better in the Open is that
par is a good score, and I seem to make a lot of them,'' he said.
``Plus, I usually have had at least one great round during the
tournament, where I've lapped the field. A great score goes a long
way in an Open.''
</P>
<P>
   A quick glance reveals that Lehman has six scores in the 60s
during the past four Opens. By comparison, Tiger Woods and David
Duval each have two sub-70 scores during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman also has another key ingredient to his game that bodes
well for Open-style courses. Even though his percentage is off
slightly this year (64.1 percent), he has been a virtual machine
when it comes to hitting greens in regulation, finishing ninth in
that tour category in 1995, fourth in '96, first in '97 and second
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman also cites his low-key demeanor for helping him rise
above the madness of an Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played under a lot of heat in Ryder Cups, Presidents
Cups, as well as the U.S. and British opens,'' he said. ``I've got
that ability to be calm when I get there.'' &QL; 
No changes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there is no reason to think he won't do more of the
same this week. Pinehurst No. 2, despite new and slicker greens, is
a venue that matches up well with his game. He even has some
insider's knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the 1992 Tour Championship held at Pinehurst, I learned the
better I played, the worse I scored, mostly because the better my
game got, the more I attacked the pins,'' he said. ``During the
first two rounds, I just hit it to the middle of the green and made
pars.''
</P>
<P>
   A strategy, Lehman said, he'll stick with this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I have to do,'' he said, noting there is a sense
of urgency to winning the Open, given his advancing age.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the one tournament I want to win more than any other. The
British Open was great, but this is our national championship.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
