<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-MCMANAMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTMAN CONFIRMS TEAMS LOSING MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   During his annual state-of-the-league meeting last week in
Dallas, NHL Commissioner  &UR; Gary Bettman would neither confirm nor
deny reports by Boston Bruins President and General Manager  &UR; Harry
Sinden that at least 20 of the league's 27 teams lost money this
past season. Or that 70 percent of NHL revenues are going directly
to pay player salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Sinden) is dead right,'' one NHL owner said. ``Actually, I'd
find it hard to believe if any more than three teams are making
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the actual numbers are, Bettman does admit there is a
problem in the NHL and that the league will address it. At the same
time, however, he also calls it nothing more than a ``four- to
five-year phenomenon'' that will begin to correct itself on its
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make it a practice not to get too specific in the numbers,''
said Bettman, who does just that in most meetings with the media,
constantly rattling off stats and trends like a math wizard.
``Suffice is to say, the percentage is higher than it should be and
more teams are losing money than they should.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I am not going to indulge in a public debate as to what
the percentages are. We have too many clubs losing money and we are
paying too much out on the expense side, and that is something we
are going to do something about.''
</P>
<P>
   The solution?
</P>
<P>
   Two words: Salary cap. The NHL's collective bargaining agreement
doesn't expire until 2004, and rest assured, a set salary ceiling
will be the major item on the owner's agenda when negotiations
commence. The Players Association will never go for it, of course,
but it might be the only way to save the sport as we know it.
</P>
<P>
   There are concerns that some teams might try to fight escalating
salaries by refusing to re-sign free agents or low-ball them on
offers and perhaps stay away from the unrestricted free-agent
market altogether. Though unlikely, that's a dangerous step that is
spelled C-O-L-L-U-S-I-O-N, and that's worse than 20-something clubs
operating in the red. &QL; 
Keen on Mike &QL; 
 &UR; Mike Keenan, the vagabond former NHL head coach and general
manager, hasn't been up for any job openings since being canned at
the All-Star break by the Vancouver Canucks. Not that he's worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be back,'' Keenan said Saturday. ``I don't have any
doubts about that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   It will have to be the right situation, of course. Some believe
only an established, self-confident GM would take a chance on
``Iron Mike,'' who also has made stops in Philadelphia, Chicago,
New York and St. Louis. And if Keenan were to somehow return to an
NHL front office, the head coach would have to be strong yet
willing to let Keenan run most of the controls.
</P>
<P>
   Keenan, never contacted about the Coyotes' head coaching job,
was asked what he'd tell all the critics who continue to say he's
done and won't coach again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd tell them they'd be wrong,'' he said, ``because they've
been wrong before, haven't they?''
</P>
<P>
   Call me Cup Crazy, but Keenan deserves another shot. &QL; 
Gretzky back in LA &QL; 
Recently retired superstar  &UR; Wayne Gretzky has moved his family back
to Thousand Oaks, Calif., from New York and apparently has no
active plans to re-enter the hockey business just yet. Gretzky has
said he might be interested in someday owning an NHL franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayne is going to take the summer off and spend time with his
kids,'' Gretzky's agent,  &UR; Mike Barnett, told the ``Los Angeles
Times.'' ``But I'm sure he'll be open to opportunities at the turn
of the calender year. He's an athlete, and at some point I'm sure
he'll want to compete with a suit on.'' &QL; 
Slap shots &QL; 
An informal survey with various NHL executives has revealed some
good news about the state of the troubled Pittsburgh Penguins. The
general consensus is the team will remain in Pittsburgh, that
 &UR; Mario Lemieux's ownership plan will be granted formal approval,
and thankfully, there will be no dispersal draft or dissolving of
the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's looking good,'' one official said. ``I have no doubts
that the Penguins will stay where they are and become healthy again
for quite some time.''
</P>
<P>
   A Pittsburgh Bankruptcy Court has set a June 24 deadline for
accepting Lemieux's plan.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of deadlines, the NHL has until Sept. 15 to notify the
International Hockey Federation of its intentions to participate in
the 2002 Winter Olympics in Salt Lake City. All signs look like a
go.
</P>
<P>
   So who will the Coyotes name as their new head coach? Well,
reports continue to circulate that General Manager  &UR; Bobby
 &UR; Smith might still have interest in former Edmonton Oilers Coach
 &UR; Ron
 &UR; Low and may have actually interviewed Low on Saturday in San Diego.
But don't bet on it. This is assistant coach  &UR; John Tortorella's job
to lose. The longer Smith drags it out, though, makes you wonder.
</P>
<P>
   How serious is former NHL star  &UR; Bryan Trottier, now an assistant
coach with the Colorado Avalanche, about becoming a head coach?
Very serious. His name has been linked to openings in both Phoenix
and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful compliment to have my name brought up,''
Trottier told the ``Denver Rocky Mountain News.'' ``I've been real
happy in Colorado, but . . . when there's an opportunity to be a
head coach, you want to give yourself a chance for advancement.''
</P>
<P>
   A possible dark horse in the Coyotes' coaching search:  &UR; Stan
Smyl, a longtime assistant coach with the Vancouver Canucks. Said
Canucks GM  &UR; Brian Burke, ``Stan's done a fine job. If he gets the
opportunity to move on, fine. If not, we've got a place for him
here. . .'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
