<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUTTING CENTERS WOULD BE DEPLORABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fullback  &UR; Larry Centers should retire in a Cardinals uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Centers, the team's career leading receiver, deserves that. So
do the 35,000 fans who for years had little to cheer about except
the NFL's best pass-catching back.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter that the team was getting blown out. There
always was the chance Centers would catch a pass in the flat, vault
six feet in the air over a defender and return from the
stratosphere amid cheers of ``Larry, Larry.''
</P>
<P>
   That chant was heard often late last season when the Cardinals
finally exorcised their Morgan Athletic Club/Racine/Chicago/St.
Louis/Phoenix Cardinals demons. They broke an 0-for-Arizona
non-winning streak and had their first playoff victory in 51 years.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody on the team deserved the success more than Centers, who
had endured nine frustrating years.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Centers, scheduled to earn $2.5 million next season, could
become a salary cap casualty as the team tries to trim $3 million
to sign their 11 draft picks. One of the running backs almost has
to go. It's the one position where the team can afford to make a
move.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not a done deal. General Manager  &UR; Bob Ferguson,
Assistant to the President  &UR; Rod Graves and Vice President  &UR; Bill
Bidwill
 &UR; Jr., the salary cap guru, are looking at every contract to see
which could be reduced, restructured or extended to get the
Cardinals under the $57.3 million cap.
</P>
<P>
   Centers, in the final year of a three-year, $7.5 million
contract, isn't opposed to having his deal reworked. He understands
his situation: He's a pass-catching specialist on the down side of
his career.
</P>
<P>
   Never an outstanding blocker, Centers has become, in some eyes,
a luxury the team cannot afford. Sure, he's still an offensive
weapon. But is he standing in the way of second-year running back
Michael Pittman, who has excellent hands, and rookie fullbacks Joel
Makovicka and Dennis McKinley?
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals officials should exhaust every possibility before
parting with Centers, their second-most-popular player behind
quarterback Jake Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   Centers, a survivor of `` &UR; Buddy (Ryan) ball'' and the
``Legitimate Tough Guy'' regime of  &UR; Joe Bugel, has earned that. The
fans have, too.
</P>
<P>
   Loyalty should matter. &QL; 
Sign of the times &QL; 
Even if Centers does return, he will be playing on the last year of
his contract unless it's extended.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are going to have to spend much of next season
reworking contracts or they are going to be in a worse dilemma in
February than they are this year.
</P>
<P>
   Others scheduled to become unrestricted free agents at the end
of the 1999 season include offensive lineman  &UR; James Dexter and
 &UR; Aaron
 &UR; Graham, running backs  &UR; Adrian Murrell and  &UR; Mario Bates, tight end
 &UR; Johnny
 &UR; McWilliams, defensive end  &UR; Simeon Rice, linebackers  &UR; Ronald
McKinnon and
 &UR; Patrick Sapp and strong safety  &UR; Tommy Bennett. All are starters. &QL; 
Ready and able &QL; 
Packers quarterback  &UR; Brett Favre, the league's Most Valuable Player
in 1996 and '97, appears determined to make up for a subpar season
a year ago, when he was intercepted 23 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be the best player in this league again,'' said
Favre, who said earlier that he was giving up alcohol and cutting
back on his personal appearances. ``I think I can be. The day that
I wake up and don't feel that way, I'll retire.'' &QL; 
In demand &QL; 
 &UR; Lawrence Phillips already had piqued the interest of NFL teams
before he ran for a 73-yard touchdown last weekend to help
Barcelona to the greatest comeback in NFL Europe history.
</P>
<P>
   Now, teams are lining up to try to get him, ignoring the fact he
could face a league suspension if he has any more legal problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers and Bengals are interested in Phillips, who earlier
was waived by the Rams after being arrested three times in 19
months. He then was signed by the Dolphins, who cut him because he
wasn't in shape. He also was accused of hitting a woman in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't follow him around,'' Barcelona Coach  &UR; Jack Bicknell
said. ``I don't know where he is all the time, and I haven't had a
problem with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bicknell, who coached quarterback  &UR; Doug Flutie at Boston
College, calls Phillips and Flutie ``the two best players I've been
around.''
</P>
<P>
   In eight games going into this weekend, Phillips had set NFL
Europe records for carries (160), yards (893) and touchdowns (12).
He had 177 yards rushing a week ago. &QL; 
Double trouble &QL; 
While teams are trying to decide whether Phillips is worth the
risk, the New England Patriots gave up on cornerback  &UR; Chris Canty,
their first-round pick two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Canty, who started the first nine games in '98, was waived last
week because of problems on and off the field, some bordering on
the bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   He rarely showed up at the team's off-season program, but he
almost always had an excuse for being absent. His latest was that
he suffered a rash caused by a reaction to the team's laundry.
</P>
<P>
   None of his teammates had complained that the soap powder the
Patriots were using made them itch.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Canty was arrested last season after police found
him asleep in his Mercedes at a gas station at 6 a.m. with a
container of an alcoholic beverage in his vehicle. &QL; 
Risky business &QL; 
In January, the Patriots lost starting running back  &UR; Robert Edwards
to a knee injury in a beach flag football game at the Pro Bowl in
Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Dolphins rookie running back  &UR; Cecil Collins has hurt his
back in a photo shoot sponsored by the NFL Players Association.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, a fifth-round pick, suffered a bruised back while
jumping off a trampoline at last month's NFL rookie premier show in
Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a guy who could be a real key for us, and he gets hurt
in something stupid,'' a Dolphins official said. ``You know guys
can get hurt walking across the street, but you live with that. We
thought this was going to be a few photos taken, and all of a
sudden they are jumping off trampolines. You get guys like that
together, and it becomes a competition thing and then it really
gets stupid.'' &QL; 
Short shots &QL; 
The five-year, $10 million deal signed by Rams first-rounder
 &UR; Torry &UR; Holt last week was lower than many teams expected, which is
good news for those clubs picking near Holt, taken sixth overall.
The Cardinals chose Ohio State wide receiver  &UR; David Boston eighth
overall.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for  &UR; John Kent Cooke, the outgoing Redskins
president, to get out of town. Cooke, who received $60 million from
the team's sale to  &UR; Daniel Snyder, is retiring to Bermuda, where
he'll save nearly $6 million in income taxes. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld can
be reached at (602) 444-8334 or at steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
