<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-ATHLETICS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN A'S BAFFLED BY DODGERS' EFFORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ The pained, perplexed expressions of manager Davey
Johnson tells the story of how the Los Angeles Dodgers' season has
been going. And, quite possibly, where it's going.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers hit into four double plays, botched a ball in the
outfield and on a cutoff on the same play and again sleepwalked
through a 4-3 loss to the Oakland Athletics on Saturday at the
Oakland Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (29-31) have lost two straight and five of six.
They're 3-7 and in the makings of a June swoon, they're two games
below .500 for the first time, and, after the loss, trailed
front-running Arizona by 6{ games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in their clubhouse so I don't know what's going on
over there, but they look like we did about a week ago,'' A's first
baseman Jason Giambi said. ``They're just playing the game,
unemotional about it. It seems like they're just there. There's no
emotion from them over there and the amazing thing is they have a
lot of (gutsy) players.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you know that's not the problem. They just seem flat out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a crepe.
</P>
<P>
   It's to the point where the patient Johnson is searching for
answers as to why the Dodgers aren't scoring more runs and why
mental mistakes are happening.
</P>
<P>
   This was also another wasted effort by right-hander Ismael
Valdes. Even though he hasn't allowed more than three earned runs
in any of his past three starts, he's lost each of them.
</P>
<P>
   Against the A's, Valdes (5-5) allowed three earned runs in 61/3
innings, including home runs to Olmedo Saenz and Tony Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't get him any run support,'' Johnson said. ``Not
real heads-up stuff out there. That just chews at you when you're
losing.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt the gnawing went on through the night, especially on a
pivotal play in the sixth inning when the A's scored twice.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Chavez singled with the bases loaded. Ben Grieve scored and
John Jaha was initially held at third. Dodgers right fielder Raul
Mondesi bobbled the ball, and Jaha went toward home. But the
ensuing play at the plate was interrupted when first baseman Eric
Karros cut the ball off. Karros then spun and fired wide as the A's
took a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cut the ball because I saw Jaha stop,'' said Karros, who hit
a solo homer in the top of the inning. ``I'm picking up the
third-base coach. I saw he was stopping (Jaha) at third. I already
had in mind I was going to cut the ball and I did. We had three
double plays. That's where the issue is.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, much of this loss was because of wasted opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had a hit in each inning yet scored in only three of
them. Their leadoff runner reached base four times (all in the
first six innings) but none of them scored.
</P>
<P>
   The woes were best illustrated in the second inning when the
double plays began. The Dodgers had the bases loaded with none out,
but rookie Brent Cookson struck out and Angel Pena grounded to
shortstop for what turned into a telling double play.
</P>
<P>
   A's second baseman Tony Phillips said he had no intention of
throwing to first to get Pena, but Pena was ruled out because
Adrian Beltre slid hard and late into second to break up the double
play.
</P>
<P>
   Second-base umpire John Shulock, citing rule 6.2, said Beltre
left his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know why he called that,'' Beltre said. ``You get
called out because you go off the base line, not because you
overslide the base. With the way we're struggling, anything can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The last double play ended the eighth inning. Mondesi singled
for the third straight at-bat and Karros walked, but Devon White
hit a soft liner to second. Mondesi was doubled off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just in a funk,'' said Eric Young, who's ninth-inning
sacrifice fly made it 4-3. ``We're not getting any breaks. It's
just not going our way right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
